{"title_page": "Political positions of Herman Cain", "text_new": "[[File:Herman Cain by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Cain in Washington, DC on October 7, 2011]]\n[[Herman Cain]] is a businessman, radio talk show host, and author who ran in the United States for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2012|presidential nomination]] in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]].  Cain suspended his campaign on December 3, 2011.\n{{Herman Cain series}}\n\n==Economic issues==\n\n===Bank bailouts, and \"too big to fail\"===\nCain supports the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP) bank bailouts as a way to revive the economy, viewing it as an investment opportunity for the taxpayers. In a 2008 editorial, Cain wrote, \"Owning a part of the major banks in America is not a bad thing. We could make a profit while solving a problem.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc133.htm |title=Far from Nationalization, Purchase of Bank Stocks Is a Win-Win for Taxpayers |first=Herman |last=Cain |date=October 20, 2008 |publisher=North Star Writers Group |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110619202228/http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc133.htm |archive-date=2011-06-19 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011 regarding his TARP support, Cain said, \"I don't have any regrets ... I studied the situation. I didn't have trouble with the idea; I had trouble with its implementation, picking winners and losers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/267029/introducing-herman-cain-robert-costa?page=7 |title=Introducing Herman Cain |first=Robert |last=Costa |date=May 12, 2011 |publisher=[[National Review]] |page=7 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515054238/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/267029/introducing-herman-cain-robert-costa?page=7 |archive-date=2011-05-15 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011 Cain said he does not believe in the concept of \"[[too big to fail]]\" and has stated that he did not agree with the bailouts of \"[[JP Morgan]] and the big banks on Wall Street\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Interview with Herman Cain |newspaper=International Wire |publisher=FDCH/eMedia |date=Oct 24, 2011 |quote=MORGAN: But I bet if I sat down with your family members that you're talking about now and said, how do you feel that nobody in the banking community of America has ever been properly held to account for what they did? Right? They would say it's outrageous? CAIN: Well, Piers, I did reel against it because the problem is multilevel. First of all, I didn't agree with the government bailing out JPMorgan and the big banks on Wall Streets. I don't believe in too big to fail. ... }}</ref>\n\n===Debt ceiling===\nCain opposes increases in the [[debt limit]] for the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]].<ref name=\"ceiling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60058.html |title='Cut, Cap, and Balance' rally cuts Herman Cain |publisher=Politico.com |date=July 27, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813074930/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60058.html |archive-date=2011-08-13 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  He was quoted in a July 27, 2011, ''Politico'' article that: \"I don't believe the debt ceiling should be raised. I don't believe the debt ceiling has to be raised ... Those are scare tactics. Those are simply exaggerated scare tactics.\"<ref name=\"ceiling\" />\n\n===Federal Reserve===\nCain believes that there was no need for an audit of the Federal Reserve.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/blogs/beltway-confidential/2011/05/flashback-2008-herman-cain-praised-tarp-chided-free-market-purist |title=FLASHBACK: In 2008, Herman Cain praised TARP, chided \"free market\" purists |publisher=Washington Examiner |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Cain also commented that while such an audit is not a high priority for him, he does not object to it.  He has stated that he finds it highly unlikely that anything would be found in such an audit, as the internal controls of the Fed are extensive, and that the Fed's problems stem from a politicization of the bank, rather than a failure to exercise due care for those internal controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoNIjGU5fbY |title=Glenn Beck Interviews Herman Cain \u2013 5/24/11 |publisher=iamcitizencain.com |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013074346/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoNIjGU5fbY |archive-date=2011-10-13 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Gold standard===\nCain supports the [[Gold standard]], saying that abandoning it \"allowed Congress to inflate our currency whenever they overspent. Now look at the mess that we have.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2010/12/28/herman_cain_return_to_the_gold_standard.html |title=Video \u2013 Herman Cain: Return To The Gold Standard |publisher=RealClearPolitics |date=December 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828080849/http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2010/12/28/herman_cain_return_to_the_gold_standard.html |archive-date=2011-08-28 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Social Security===\nCain has criticized the current implementation of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], describing it as a \"scam.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc14.htm |title=North Star Writers Group |publisher=004eeb5.netsolhost.com |date=May 17, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810124727/http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc14.htm |archive-date=2011-08-10 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He favors reforming the current system \"through free market solutions.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174238 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Social Security |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811192437/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174238 |archive-date=2011-08-11 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nSeveral times Cain has referenced the [[Chile pension system|Chilean model]] of redoing social security.  He supports the \"Chilean model\" for younger citizens while retaining the current system for current beneficiaries.\n\n===Taxes===\nCain has supported shifting the tax burden from [[investment]] on to [[Consumption tax|consumption]].  Cain has called for the elimination of taxes on capital gains, and suspending taxes on repatriated foreign profits.<ref name=aiken>{{cite web |url=http://www.aikenstandard.com/Local/0519-herman-cain |title=Cain draws record crowd |publisher=Aiken Standard |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718063610/http://www.aikenstandard.com/Local/0519-herman-cain |archivedate=July 18, 2012 |df= }}</ref>  He also supports elimination of the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]];<ref name=\"estate\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nodeathtax.org/resources/testimonies/cain |title=\"Federal Estate Tax: Uncertainty in Planning Under the Current Law\" Nov 14, 2007 |publisher=Nodeathtax.org |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20081202061710/http://www.nodeathtax.org/resources/testimonies/cain |archivedate=December 2, 2008 |df= }}</ref> and in 2007<ref>on November 14, 2007</ref> in testimony before the [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]] called for the permanent repeal of that tax.<ref name=\"estate\" />  Prior to his presidential campaign, Cain supported lowering the [[Corporate tax in the United States|corporate tax]] rate from 35 to 25 percent.<ref name=aiken/>\n\nCain testified in front of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] on May 9, 2002, in support of [https://web.archive.org/web/20160202054845/http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c107:H.R.2525: HR 2525], which would institute a national retail sales tax.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salestax.org/library/cain_5-9-02.html |title=Testimony Before the Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures of the House Committee on Ways and Means Hearing on the Extraterritorial Income Regime |publisher=Salestax.org |date=May 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930083618/http://www.salestax.org/library/cain_5-9-02.html |archivedate=September 30, 2011 |df= }}</ref>  According to the [[Washington Times]], Cain has been known as a supporter of the broad national consumption tax on retail sales called the [[FairTax]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/may/10/gop-field-has-own-change-ideas/ |title=GOP field has own 'change' ideas |date=May 10, 2011 |first=Seth |last=McLaughlin |publisher=Washington Times |accessdate=May 23, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514151139/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/may/10/gop-field-has-own-change-ideas/ |archive-date=2011-05-14 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  During his presidential campaign in 2011, Cain introduced his signature \"9\u20139\u20139\" plan for a 9% tax on individuals, sales, and businesses.\n\n====9\u20139\u20139 Plan====\n{{Main|9\u20139\u20139 Plan}}\n\nThe \"centerpiece\"<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2011/1012/Does-the-Herman-Cain-9-9-9-tax-plan-have-a-fatal-flaw Does the Herman Cain 9\u20139\u20139 tax plan have a fatal flaw?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012193238/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2011/1012/Does-the-Herman-Cain-9-9-9-tax-plan-have-a-fatal-flaw |date=2011-10-12 }} By Peter Grier, csmonitor.com October 12, 2011</ref> of Cain's presidential campaign introduced in August 2011 has been the \"9\u20139\u20139 plan\",<ref>{{citation|publisher = HermanCain.com|title = 999 Plan|url = http://www.hermancain.com/999plan|accessdate = October 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan|archivedate = September 26, 2011|df = }}</ref> which would replace all current taxes (including the [[payroll tax]], [[capital gains tax]], and the [[inheritance tax|estate tax]]) with 9% business transaction tax; 9% [[personal income tax]] rate, and a 9% federal [[sales tax]]. According to Cain, corporations would be able to deduct costs of goods sold (provided the inputs were made in America) and capital expenditures, but not wages, salaries and benefits to employees.<ref>[https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/a-bit-more-about-cain/ A Bit More About Cain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906230143/https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/a-bit-more-about-cain/ |date=2017-09-06 }}. Paul Krugman. October 15, 2011</ref> Deductions, except charitable giving, would be eliminated. The federal sales tax would not apply to used goods. Cain also said that the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan would lift a $430 billion dead-weight burden on the economy.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} the 999 plan</ref>\n\nCain stated the following summary about the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan:\n\n<blockquote>Our current economic crisis calls for bold action to truly stimulate the economy and Renew America back to its greatness. The 9\u20139\u20139 Plan gets Washington D.C. out of the business of picking winners and losers, using the tax code to dole out favors, and dividing the country with class warfare. It is fair, simple, transparent and efficient. It taxes everything once and nothing twice. It taxes the broadest possible base at the lowest possible rates. It is neutral with respect to savings and consumption, capital and labor, imports and exports and whether companies pay dividends or retain earnings.<ref name=autogenerated3 /></blockquote>\n\nAccording to the analysis of Howard Gleckman the [[Tax Policy Center]],\n\n<blockquote>When you get right down to it, Cain's [9\u20139\u20139] plan is a 25 percent flat-rate consumption tax \u2014 not all that different from the FAIR tax that he says is his ultimate goal. This tax would be paid three times: first on wage income, again at the cash register as a sales tax, and yet again by businesses on their sales minus their cost of goods and services. For tax junkies, the first is a [[flat tax]]. The second is a retail sales tax and the third a business transfer tax.  But they are all consumption taxes.<ref>Howard Gleckman, [http://taxvox.taxpolicycenter.org/2011/10/18/cain\u2019s-9-9-9-plan-would-cut-taxes-for-the-rich-raise-taxes-for-almost-everyone-else Cain\u2019s 9\u20139\u20139 Plan Would Cut Taxes for the Rich, Raise Taxes for Almost Everyone Else] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305154717/http://taxvox.taxpolicycenter.org/2011/10/18/cain%E2%80%99s-9-9-9-plan-would-cut-taxes-for-the-rich-raise-taxes-for-almost-everyone-else/ |date=2016-03-05 }} ''[[Tax Policy Center]]'' October 18, 2011</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough Cain has spoken about having designated 'empowerment zones'<ref>{{cite news | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1110/13/ebo.01.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com | access-date=2011-10-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017071601/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1110/13/ebo.01.html | archive-date=2011-10-17 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref> wherein a lower percentage, such as 3%, is paid instead, apart from this consideration, some have called Cain's plan more [[Regressive tax|regressive]] than current policy, thinking it would raise taxes for most households, but cut them for those with the highest income.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/10/18/news/economy/cain_999_plan/?source=cnn_bin | work=CNN | first=Jeanne | last=Sahadi | title=84% would pay more under Cain's 9-9-9 plan | date=October 18, 2011 | access-date=2011-10-19 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205105815/http://money.cnn.com/2011/10/18/news/economy/cain_999_plan/?source=cnn_bin | archive-date=2015-02-05 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref><ref>[https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/tpc-does-herman-cain/ TPC Does Herman Cain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005122509/http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/tpc-does-herman-cain/ |date=2015-10-05 }} October 18, 2011, The Tax Policy Center has the distributional analysis of 9\u20139\u20139.</ref>\n\nCain modified the plan for people under poverty level, reducing income tax for the poor to 0%, telling an audience in Detroit October 21 that the poorest Americans would get a \"9\u20130\u20139\" plan.<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/.../herman-cain-tweaks-9-9-9-tax-to-remove-flat-tax-f] 9\u20130\u20139, 0% income tax for the poor</ref>\n\nIn an October 18, 2011 debate several of the other contenders for the GOP nomination attacked the plan, with candidate [[Rick Santorum]] referencing the [[Tax Policy Center]]'s claim that 84%<ref>[http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/numbers/displayatab.cfm?Docid=3222&DocTypeID=2 T11-0375 \u2013 Herman Cain's \"9\u20139\u20139\" Tax Reform Plan; Baseline: Current Policy; Fully Phased in Distribution of Federal Tax Change by Cash Income Percentile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021043931/http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/numbers/displayatab.cfm?Docid=3222&DocTypeID=2 |date=2011-10-21 }} ''[[Tax Policy Center]]'' October 18, 2011</ref> of Americans would pay more and that the plan would entail \"major increases in taxes on people,\" a charge Cain has denied.<ref>David Lightman and Steven Thomm, [http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/132054608.html GOP presidential candidates clash in testy debate] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020122740/http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/132054608.html |date=2011-10-20 }} ''[[McClatchy News Service]]'' October 19, 2011</ref>\n\nSome economists support the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan. The former Reagan Treasury official Gary Robbins stated that the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan will expand the GDP by $2 trillion, create 6 million new jobs, increase business investment by 33%, and increase wages by 10%.<ref>[http://www.hermancain.com/999plan 9\u20139\u20139 Plan | Herman Cain for President<!-- Butt generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |date=2011-09-26 }}</ref>\nAlso, Art Laffer, a famous [[supply-side]] economist, told HUMAN EVENTS that \"Herman Cain's 9\u20139\u20139 plan would be a vast improvement over the current tax system and boom the U.S. economy.\".<ref>[http://www.westernfreepress.com/.../art-laffer-supports-cains-9-9-9-plan/] Art Laffer's quote</ref>\n\nConversely, other economists feel that the 9\u20139\u20139 plan would not stimulate the demand.<ref name=autogenerated2>Bartlett, Bruce. [https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/11/inside-the-cain-tax-plan/ \"Inside the Cain Tax Plan.\"] ''The New York Times'', October 11, 2011.</ref> [[Bruce Bartlett]] of the Reagan and George H.W. Bush administrations has written that Cain's plan \"would increase the budget deficit without doing anything to stimulate demand\".<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n[[The Economist]] criticized the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan stating that the Cain plan is not a reduction in the current corporate tax, but instead a new value added tax (VAT). The article also stated that Cain's final tax would be a 30% VAT, as compared to the 15% [[European Union value added tax]].<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2011/10/herman-cain \"Dial 9\u20139\u20139 for nonsense.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826071750/https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2011/10/herman-cain |date=2017-08-26 }} ''The Economist'', October 17, 2011.</ref> The Cain plan would change the 35% corporate tax to a 9% transaction tax, which would be flat except for payroll deductions for employees in [[empowerment zone]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} 9\u20139\u20139 Plan www.hermancain.com</ref>\n\nCain said the following about the 9% sales tax.\n\n<blockquote>Unlike a state sales tax, which is an add-on tax that increases the price of goods and services, this is a replacement tax. It replaces taxes that are already embedded in selling prices. By replacing higher marginal rates in the production process with lower marginal rates, marginal production costs actually decline, which will lead to prices being the same or lower, not higher.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} The 9\u20139\u20139 plan</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Welfare===\nCain has criticized [[Social programs in the United States|social welfare programs in the United States]], stating that, \"Programs today are designed to make people more dependent rather than less dependent.\"<ref>''Q & A: Herman Cain on Faith, Calling, and Presidential Aspirations'', ''Christianity Today'', Interview by Trevor Persaud</ref>\n\n==Social issues==\n\n===Abortion===\nCain identifies as [[pro-life]] and opposes [[abortion]] in all cases,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qXTBDDhDN1g |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-11-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723140024/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qXTBDDhDN1g |archive-date=2016-07-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> except where the mother's life is endangered.<ref>[http://new.accessnorthga.com/detail.php?n=172858 Three Republicans battling for spots in Georgia's likely Senate runoff | AccessNorthGa<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120529192838/http://new.accessnorthga.com/detail.php?n=172858 |date=2012-05-29 }}</ref> He believes that life begins at [[fertilization|conception]]. He favors defunding [[Planned Parenthood]], an organization he has referred to as \"Planned Genocide\" because he views it as guilty of [[Black genocide conspiracy theory|genocide against black Americans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144328 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Abortion |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009002808/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144328 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"genocide\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/10/30/planned-parenthood-rejects-cain-claim-abortion-clinics-are-aimed-at-black/|title=Planned Parenthood Rejects Cain Claim Abortion Clinics Are Aimed at Black 'Genocide'|work=Fox News|date=October 30, 2011|access-date=2011-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031175012/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/10/30/planned-parenthood-rejects-cain-claim-abortion-clinics-are-aimed-at-black/|archive-date=2011-10-31|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\nCain reaffirmed his position two days after a controversial interview during which many of his opponents believed he had changed his stance. In an email to supporters, he said the following:\n\n{{blockquote|The abortion issue is very serious.  I believe strongly that this is true, and I believe that you do too.\n\nBecause the news media loves to make mountains out of mole hills, I want to be very clear about where I stand on abortion:\n\nI am 100% pro-life, period.\n\nLet me explain.  In an interview yesterday with Piers Morgan on CNN, I was asked questions about abortion policy and the role of the President.\n\nIf you listen to the line of questioning, it is clear that Mr. Morgan was asking if I, as president, would simply \"order\" people to not seek an abortion.\n\nMy answer was focused on the role of the President.  The President has no constitutional authority to order any such action by anyone.  That was the point I was trying to convey.\n\nAs to my political view on abortion ... again, I am pro-life.  End of story.\n\nAs President, I will appoint judges who understand the original intent of the Constitution.  Judges who are committed to the rule of law know that the Constitution contains no right to take the life of unborn children.\n\nI will oppose government funding of abortion.  I will veto any legislation that contains funds for Planned Parenthood.  I will do everything that a President can do, consistent with his constitutional role, to advance the culture of life.<ref>Erickson, Eric (October 21, 2011). [http://www.redstate.com/erick/2011/10/21/herman-cain-clarifies-his-abortion-position-but-it-raises-more-questions/ Herman Cain clarifies his abortion position, but it raises more questions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022024847/http://www.redstate.com/erick/2011/10/21/herman-cain-clarifies-his-abortion-position-but-it-raises-more-questions/ |date=2011-10-22 }}. ''RedState''. Retrieved October 21, 2011.</ref>}}\n\n===Affirmative action===\nCain supports ensuring that [[minorities]] receive the same opportunities as non-minorities. He does not agree with a \"[[racial quota|quota]]\" style [[affirmative action]] system, which he believes gives an advantage to minorities simply because they are a minority.<ref>[http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2004/04/28/op_413767.shtml Herman Cain Letter to the Editor of the Augusta Chronicle, Affirmative action is a negative step] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922082226/http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2004/04/28/op_413767.shtml |date=2012-09-22 }}, April 28, 2004.</ref>\n\n===Homosexuality===\nCain is an opponent of the legalization of [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|marriage for same sex couples in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Atlanta |first=Project Q |url=http://www.projectqatlanta.com/news_articles/view/Start_worrying_about_Atlantas_Herman_Cain?gid=7118 |title=Gays: Start fretting over Atlanta's Herman Cain |publisher=Projectqatlanta.com |date=December 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> He supports the [[Defense of Marriage Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://equalitymatters.org/blog/201103290013 |title=Herman Cain: I'd Rather Defend DOMA Than Protect Religious Liberty |publisher=Equality Matters |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726034051/http://equalitymatters.org/blog/201103290013 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  He would seek to reinstate the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]] policy.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Islam===\nCain has made a number of comments regarding [[Islam in the United States|American Muslims]], and the hypothetical implementation of [[Sharia|sharia law]] in the United States.<ref name=mosques>[http://www.sacbee.com/2011/07/17/3775707/herman-cain-communities-have-right.html Herman Cain: Communities have right to ban mosques]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, July 17, 2011.</ref>\n\nSome comments made by Cain regarding Muslims have caused controversy. He said that he was \"uncomfortable\" when he found that the surgeon operating on his liver and colon cancer was a Muslim.  He later explained: \"based upon the little knowledge that I have of the Muslim religion, you know, they have an objective to convert all infidels or kill them\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2011/jun/08/herman-cain/cain-denies-claims-he-said-he-would-not-appoint-mu/ |title=Cain denies claims he said he would not appoint Muslims |access-date=2011-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127165310/http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2011/jun/08/herman-cain/cain-denies-claims-he-said-he-would-not-appoint-mu/ |archive-date=2011-11-27 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He has also spoken of his distrust of another Doctor when his name \"sounded ''too'' foreign\", telling the audience at a Biblically themed amusement park \"My mind immediately started thinking, wait a minute, maybe his religious persuasion is different than mine! She [the nurse] could see the look on my face and she said, 'Don't worry, Mr. Cain, he's a Christian from Lebanon'. Hallelujah! Thank God!\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/21/herman-cain-holy-land-experience_n_1105725.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Luke | last=Johnson | title=Herman Cain Says He Was Relieved When Doctor Who Treated Him Was A Christian | date=November 21, 2011 | access-date=2011-11-21 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123133838/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/21/herman-cain-holy-land-experience_n_1105725.html | archive-date=2011-11-23 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in March 2011, Cain stated that he would not feel comfortable appointing a Muslim to his administration, or as a judge <ref>{{citation |publisher=Politifact.com |date= }}</ref> saying:  \"No, I will not ... There's this creeping attempt, there's this attempt, to gradually ease Shariah Law, and the Muslim faith into our government. It does not belong in our government\"<ref name=\"foxnews1\">{{Cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/03/28/herman-cain-i-would-not-appoint-muslim-my-administration |title=Herman Cain: 'I Would Not' Appoint a Muslim in My Administration |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |publisher=Fox News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726104958/http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/03/28/herman-cain-i-would-not-appoint-muslim-my-administration |archive-date=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/26/gop-iowa-steve-king-2012_n_840956.html#6_herman-cain-says-he-wont-stay-on-democratic-plantation-raises-specter-of-sharia-law|title=Herman Cain Says He Won't Stay on Democratic 'Plantation,' Raises Specter of Sharia Law|date=March 27, 2011|last=Ward|first=Jon|work=Huffington Post|location=USA|accessdate=May 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110512020812/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/26/gop-iowa-steve-king-2012_n_840956.html#6_herman-cain-says-he-wont-stay-on-democratic-plantation-raises-specter-of-sharia-law|archive-date=2011-05-12|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/03/26/153625/herman-cain-muslims |title=Herman Cain Tells ThinkProgress \"I Will Not\" Appoint A Muslim In My Administration |author=Scott Keyes |date=March 26, 2011 |work=Think Progress |publisher=Center for American Progress Action Fund |accessdate=June 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605101625/http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/03/26/153625/herman-cain-muslims/ |archive-date=2011-06-05 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe explained that his view was in reaction to a lawsuit in which the [[Council on American-Islamic Relations]] (CAIR) sought to block the implementation of a 2008 Oklahoma law which would have denied the use of Sharia law in state courts,<ref name=\"mears1\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-29/us/oklahoma.sharia.law_1_sharia-law-state-courts-international-law?_s=PM:US |title=Judge issues permanent injunction on Oklahoma Sharia law ban |last=Mears |first=Bill |date=November 29, 2010 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=May 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718102246/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-29/us/oklahoma.sharia.law_1_sharia-law-state-courts-international-law?_s=PM:US |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a [[Florida]] judge's decision to use Sharia law to settle a dispute within a mosque,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/civil/article1158818.ece |title=Judge orders use of Islamic law in Tampa lawsuit over mosque leadership |work=St. Petersburg Times |date= |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |format=text |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830111655/http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/civil/article1158818.ece |archive-date=August 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> despite the Court's decision not to use ecclesiastical law in the past (see ''Kreshik v. St. Nicholas Cathedral''), and a case in New Jersey.<ref name=\"foxnews2\">{{cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/justice/2010/08/06/sharia-law-comes-new-jersey |title=Sharia Law Comes to New Jersey? |date=August 6, 2010 |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=May 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322101845/http://nation.foxnews.com/justice/2010/08/06/sharia-law-comes-new-jersey |archive-date=March 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Cain has described his position as being \"careful and cautious.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2011/06/201161405842986718.html |title=Republican 2012 hopefuls debate US issues |work=Al Jazeera |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=June 29, 2011 |format=embedded video |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617061510/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2011/06/201161405842986718.html |archive-date=2011-06-17 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe has also argued that Muslims should be prevented from building mosques in which to teach ''[[Jihad]]'' unless they have widespread approval from the local community. Cain campaigned for Muslims to be banned from building an Islamic Center at a site in Tennessee, claiming that it was \"an infringement and an abuse of our freedom of religion\" and \"just another way to try to gradually sneak Shariah law into our laws\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/herman-cain-islamic-center-of-murfreesboro-extremism_n_899499.html |title=Herman Cain: Islamic Center Of Murfreesboro Would Spread Extremism |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915102807/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/herman-cain-islamic-center-of-murfreesboro-extremism_n_899499.html |archive-date=2011-09-15 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Defending himself against the suggestion that this would be discrimination, during an interview he said: \"I'm willing to take a harder look at people who might be terrorists, that's what I'm saying\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/17/herman-cain-fox-mosques_n_900939.html |title=Herman Cain: Americans Have The Right To Ban Mosques In Their Communities |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=July 17, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |first=Alexander |last=Belenky |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920152212/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/17/herman-cain-fox-mosques_n_900939.html |archive-date=2011-09-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  On July 18, 2011, Cain declared that communities in the United States had the \"right\" to ban mosques. He justified his view by arguing that Muslims are trying to promote Shariah law within the U.S, and also that his position did not amount to \"religious discrimination\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/07/17/herman-cain-islam-combines-church-and-state |title=Herman Cain: Islam Combines Church and State |work=foxnews |date=July 17, 2011 |access-date=2011-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812105711/http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/07/17/herman-cain-islam-combines-church-and-state |archive-date=August 12, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> CAIR said that his comments were [[Constitution of the United States|unconstitutional]] and could give legitimacy to [[Islamophobia|anti-Muslim bigotry]].<ref name=mosques/>{{dead link|date=September 2011}} [[Southern Baptist Convention]] leader [[Richard Land]] also said that Cain had disregarded the constitutional rights of Muslims.<ref>Stephanie Samuel, [http://www.christianpost.com/news/southern-baptist-leader-chides-cain-for-mosque-ban-remarks-52448/ Southern Baptist Leader Chides Cain for Mosque Ban Remarks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921125254/https://www.christianpost.com/news/southern-baptist-leader-chides-cain-for-mosque-ban-remarks-52448/ |date=2018-09-21 }}, Jul. 18 2011.</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2011, Cain met with Muslim leaders at the All Dulles Area Muslim Society (ADAMS) in [[Sterling, Virginia]]. He also toured the ADAMS mosque. After the meeting, he reiterated his opposition to the use of sharia law in courts, but said, \"I am truly sorry for any comments that may have betrayed my commitment to the U.S. Constitution and the [[Freedom of religion in the United States|freedom of religion]] guaranteed by it. Muslims, like all Americans, have the right to practice their faith freely and peacefully.\"<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60100.html#ixzz1TOcJe7Z1 Herman Cain hosts meeting with Muslim leaders Herman Cain hosts meeting with Muslim leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929183437/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60100.html#ixzz1TOcJe7Z1 |date=2011-09-29 }}, July 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Foreign policy==\n\n===About foreign policy===\nCain defended his foreign policy knowledge. \"I'm not supposed to know anything about foreign policy. Just thought I'd throw that out,\" he said to a Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel reporter while on his campaign bus on Monday, the afternoon after his interview with the paper's editorial board. \"I want to talk to commanders on the ground. Because you run for president (people say) you need to have the answer. No, you don't! No, you don't! That's not good decision-making.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/herman-cain-libya-gaffe-foreign-policy_n_1097244.html |title=Herman Cain: 'I'm Not Supposed To Know Anything About Foreign Policy' |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119012223/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/herman-cain-libya-gaffe-foreign-policy_n_1097244.html |archive-date=2011-11-19 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-11-16 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuba===\nCain said he was not a fan of the \"[[Wet feet, dry feet policy]]\", in an interview with the television station WPLG.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/68576.html |title=Herman Cain ducks Cuba questions |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120011011/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/68576.html |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Prisoner Exchanges===\n{{See also|Gilad Shalit prisoner exchange}}\nCain said \"I could see myself\" freeing all Guantanamo detainees for one American hostage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2011/10/18/cain_i_could_see_myself_freeing_all_gitmo_detainees_for_one_american_hostage |title=Cain: \"I Could See Myself\" Freeing All Gitmo Detainees For One American Hostage |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120030145/http://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2011/10/18/cain_i_could_see_myself_freeing_all_gitmo_detainees_for_one_american_hostage |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe later abandoned this position.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/19/herman-cain-terrorist-negotiations_n_1020101.html |title=Herman Cain 'Misspoke' When He Said He Might Negotiate With Terrorists |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122090314/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/19/herman-cain-terrorist-negotiations_n_1020101.html |archive-date=2011-11-22 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-19 }}</ref>\n\n===Anwar al-Awlaki===\n\"I don't believe that the president of the United States should order the assassination of citizens of the United States,\" Cain said. \"That's why we have our court system, and that's why we have our laws.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/05/herman-cain-spying-on-americans-is-okay-but-not-assassinating-them/239400/ |title=Herman Cain: Spying on Americans Is Okay, But Not Assassinating Them |access-date=2017-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103184803/http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/05/herman-cain-spying-on-americans-is-okay-but-not-assassinating-them/239400/ |archive-date=2017-01-03 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-05-25 }}</ref>\n\nIn a brief Q&A with our panel after his speech, Cain told the crowd that he fully supported Barack Obama's decision to strike Anwar al-Awlaki.<ref>[http://pronast.com/blog/herman-cain-flip-flopped-on-the-killing-of-anwar-al-awlaki.html Herman Cain Flip-Flopped on the Killing of Anwar al-Awlaki]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Libya===\nWhen asked about U.S. foreign policy toward Libya, \"Cain repeated he would have 'assessed the [Libyan] opposition differently,' speaking in generalities about his problem-solving approach,\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/14/herman-cain-libya-question_n_1093425.html |title=Hermann Cain Stumbles on Libya Questions |newspaper=The Huffington Post |author=Luke Johnson |date=November 15, 2011 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124182416/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/14/herman-cain-libya-question_n_1093425.html |archive-date=2011-11-24 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> and expressing confusion regarding the issue.\n\n\"Cain suggested on [November 18, 2011] that the [[Taliban]] were playing a role in Libya's new government.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/11/18/herman-cain-suggests-taliban-is-running-libya/ |title=Herman Cain Suggests Taliban is Running Libya |work=foxnews.com |agency=Associated Press |date=November 18, 2011 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126231306/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/11/18/herman-cain-suggests-taliban-is-running-libya/ |archive-date=2011-11-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Afghanistan===\nCain has been supportive of a US presence in Afghanistan, and of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509170146 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The War in Afghanistan |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003519/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509170146 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Iraq===\nCain supported the [[Iraq War]], and opposed any timetable for [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]], arguing it to be equivalent to surrender.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110526130557 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The War in Iraq |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 14, 2007 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003513/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110526130557 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\nCain favors a \"diplomatic approach\" to nuclear disarmament, but that the United States should be wary of the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509171147 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Iran |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009002927/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509171147 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Israel and Palestine===\nCain supports Israel, and believes that the US should aid Israel in defending itself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509152655 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Israel |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003022/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509152655 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  After President Obama said that the starting point of negotiations for peace between the Israelis and the Palestinians should be based on the 1967 borders with mutually agreed-upon land swaps, Cain said:\n\n<blockquote>I was shocked at the president's position, and I was equally shocked that he would unilaterally suggest that Israel would move the borders back which they acquired 44 years ago.  This president threw Israel under the bus, there is no way around it. It demonstrates once again the arrogant disregard of this president for the opinion of the American people who like the relationship we have with Israel, and for Israel having the right to make its own decisions.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy7Zn-f2zg8 |title=Fox Interview of Herman Cain on Israel |publisher=Youtube.com |date=May 20, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106165006/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy7Zn-f2zg8 |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nCain supports the [[Palestinian right of return]] under Israeli conditions.<ref>{{cite web |last=James |first=Frank |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2011/05/23/136586652/herman-cain-wasnt-able-on-palestinian-right-of-return-question |title=Herman Cain Wasn't Able On Palestinian Right Of Return Question |publisher=NPR |date=May 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526024637/http://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2011/05/23/136586652/herman-cain-wasnt-able-on-palestinian-right-of-return-question |archive-date=2011-05-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He later commented that he had not understood the question while making his initial answer, but reiterated his support for it under Israeli conditions.<ref>{{cite web |author=Eric Kleefeld |url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2011/05/cain-i-didnt-understand-the-right-of-return-video.php |title=Cain: 'I Didn't Understand The Right Of Return' (VIDEO) |publisher=Tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806074533/http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2011/05/cain-i-didnt-understand-the-right-of-return-video.php |archive-date=2011-08-06 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  This led to criticism regarding his lack of foreign policy experience due to his admitted unfamiliarity with the issue and need for subsequent clarification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0511/55484.html |title=Herman Cain stumbles on Palestinian question |author=Juana Summers |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101200414/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0511/55484.html |archive-date=2011-11-01 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain was the only Republican presidential candidate at the former Fox News host [[Glenn Beck]]'s \"Restoring Courage\" rally in Israel.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/herman-cain-backs-israel-with-glenn-beck-in-jerusalem-54569/ |title=Herman Cain Backs Israel With Glenn Beck in Jerusalem, Christian News<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112010025/http://www.christianpost.com/news/herman-cain-backs-israel-with-glenn-beck-in-jerusalem-54569/ |archive-date=2011-11-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain pronounced, \"If you mess with Israel, you're messing with the USA.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2011/09/20/herman-cain-if-mess-with-israel-youre-messing-with-usa/#ixzz1ZJBJIE6n | work=Fox News | title=If You Mess With Israel, You're Messing With the USA | date=September 20, 2011 | access-date=2011-09-29 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929095725/http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2011/09/20/herman-cain-if-mess-with-israel-youre-messing-with-usa/#ixzz1ZJBJIE6n | archive-date=2011-09-29 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref>\n\nAfter Vice President [[Joe Biden]] said that the Obama administration would not release [[Jonathan Pollard]] \"over my dead body\", Cain publicly disagreed with Biden's stance and said that as a supporter of Israel, he personally sympathizes with Pollard. However, he said he would have to review Pollard's case fully before deciding to free him.<ref name=\"cain\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishvoiceandopinion.com/2011/10/herman-cain-and-the-%E2%80%9Ccain-doctrine%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%9Cif-you-mess-with-israel-you-are-messing-with-the-us%E2%80%9D/|title=Herman Cain and the \"Cain Doctrine\": \"If You Mess with Israel, You Are Messing with the US\"|access-date=2011-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012122328/http://jewishvoiceandopinion.com/2011/10/herman-cain-and-the-%E2%80%9Ccain-doctrine%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%9Cif-you-mess-with-israel-you-are-messing-with-the-us%E2%80%9D/|archive-date=2011-10-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn late October 2011, Cain said that President Obama's weakness on Middle East policies was emboldening what he referred to as the \"so-called Palestinian people\" to [[Palestine 194|seek statehood at the United Nations]].<ref name=\"socalled\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/190457-cain-push-by-so-called-palestinian-people-for-statehood-result-of-obama-weakness|title=Herman Cain: Obama's weakness emboldens 'so-called Palestinian people'|access-date=2011-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029143300/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/190457-cain-push-by-so-called-palestinian-people-for-statehood-result-of-obama-weakness|archive-date=2011-10-29|url-status=live|df=|date=2011-10-28}}</ref>\n\n===North Korea===\nCain opposes any form of negotiation with [[North Korea]], and has argued for maintaining \"peace through strength\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193955 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 North Korea |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724053832/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/President/US/Herman_Cain/Views/North_Korea/ |archive-date=2012-07-24 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nCain opposed the [[New START]] treaty, because he believes that the US should retain freedom to develop nuclear weapons systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509185820 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Nuclear Weapons |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=January 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003135/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509185820 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===China===\nYes, they're a military threat,\" Cain said on the PBS NewsHour, in response to a question from Judy Woodruff. \"They've indicated that they're trying to develop nuclear capability and they want to develop more aircraft carriers like we have. So yes, we have to consider them a military threat.\" \"We already have superiority in terms of our military capability, and I plan to get away from making cutting our defense a priority and make investing in our military capability a priority,\" he said.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20128920-503544/herman-cain-incorrectly-suggests-china-doesnt-have-nuclear-capability/ |title=Herman Cain incorrectly suggests China doesn't have nuclear capability |access-date=2011-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122124753/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20128920-503544/herman-cain-incorrectly-suggests-china-doesnt-have-nuclear-capability/ |archive-date=2011-11-22 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain addressed the gaffe in an interview with Ginni Thomas of The Daily Caller on Wednesday evening, and attempted to clarify his comments. \"Maybe I misspoke,\" he said. \"What I meant was China does not have the size of the nuclear capability that we have. They do have a nuclear capability. I was talking about their total nuclear capability.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/03/herman-cain-china-nuclear-weapons_n_1073477.html |title=Herman Cain On China Nuclear Capability: 'I Misspoke' |access-date=2011-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111206222635/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/03/herman-cain-china-nuclear-weapons_n_1073477.html |archive-date=2011-12-06 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-11-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\nCain continued, \"Knowing who is the head of some of these small insignificant states around the world, I don't think that is something that is critical to focusing on national security and getting this economy going. When I get ready to go visit that country, I'll know who it is, but until then, I want to focus on the big issues that we need to solve.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/opinion/herman-cain-thinks-uzbekistan-doesnt-matter-hes-wrong/11989/ |title=Herman Cain thinks Uzbekistan doesn't matter. He's wrong. |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715070525/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/opinion/herman-cain-thinks-uzbekistan-doesnt-matter-hes-wrong/11989/ |archive-date=2017-07-15 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-14 }}</ref>\n\n==Other issues==\n[[File:Herman-cain-ttu-2011-tn1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Cain in Tennessee on October 15, 2011]]\n\n===2008 presidential election===\nIn 2008, Cain initially praised Democratic candidate [[Barack Obama]], saying of Obama that \"His gift is the gift of oratory. That's not just the ability to speak, but the ability to connect with people.\" He also said that he would consider supporting Obama \"under the right circumstances\" but only if he made a serious attempt to \"reach across the aisle\". Cain instead endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] in the Republican primary, and eventually supported the GOP nominee, [[John McCain]].<ref name=\"cainobama\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8334-503544_162-20127194-503544/six-things-you-dont-know-about-herman-cain/?pageNum=2&tag=next|title=Cain at one point said he could envision himself supporting Barack Obama's candidacy \"under the right circumstances.\" | work=CBS News}}</ref>\n\n===Capital punishment===\nCain advocates the use of [[capital punishment in the United States]]. When asked if the death penalty should be thrown away when evidence comes into question, he replied \"No. If you do away with it, that will only brainwash people into thinking that they can do whatever they want and get away with it.\"<ref>Tolliver, Lafe. [http://www.thetoledojournal.com/news/Article/Article.asp?NewsID=111034&sID=16&ItemSource=L \"Cain\u2026.Raising Cain!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203145117/http://www.thetoledojournal.com/News/article/article.asp?NewsID=111034&sID=16&ItemSource=L |date=2012-02-03 }} ''The Toledo Journal'', October 14, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Education===\nCain opposes federal education schemes such as [[NCLB|No Child Left Behind]] and advocates \"unbundling\" education, weakening the [[United States Department of Education]] in favor of state control of education. He has argued for greater [[performance-related pay]] for teachers, as well as for vouchers and charter school systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508194027 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Education |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003145/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508194027 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Energy and the environment===\nCain favors [[offshore drilling]] and supports drilling in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] (ANWR). He favors allowing consumers to choose alternative energy sources such as solar and wind through the private market instead of the government providing funding and incentives to particular corporations and industries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174056 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Energy and the Environment |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712200528/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174056 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain's ideology on the climate represents what is termed [[climate change denial]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Evangelical Rejection of Reason |author=Karl W. Giberson and Randall J. Stephens |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 18, 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/opinion/the-evangelical-rejection-of-reason.html |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316044404/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/opinion/the-evangelical-rejection-of-reason.html |archive-date=2017-03-16 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He has made statements indicating a belief that anthropogenic global warming is a [[global warming conspiracy theory|hoax]], referring to it as \"poppycock\" and claiming that scientists were \"busted\" of having \"manipulated the data.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =Mark Levin interviews Herman Cain the day after the New Hampshire debate| url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p7YWwWF22gc&feature=player_embedded#!| date =June 16, 2011| work =[[The Mark Levin Show]]| publisher =(YouTube.com)| access-date =2016-11-30| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160427134101/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p7YWwWF22gc&feature=player_embedded#!| archive-date =2016-04-27| url-status=live| df =}}</ref>{{lopsided|date=November 2011}}\n\n===Health care===\nCain supports repeal of the 2010 [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (PPACA). Cain, a [[cancer survivor]], also has said that the PPACA would have killed him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/cancer-survivor-herman-cain-i-would-be-dead-on-obamacare/ |title=Cancer Survivor Herman Cain: \u2018I Would Be Dead\u2019 on Obamacare &#124; Video &#124; TheBlaze.com<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925193130/http://www.theblaze.com/stories/cancer-survivor-herman-cain-i-would-be-dead-on-obamacare/ |archive-date=2011-09-25 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain favors allowing the free market to play the largest role in health care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174531 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Health Care |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003249/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174531 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain supported the 2012 Ryan budget plan, which sought to privatize Medicare, describing it favorably as a \"voucher program.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-herman-cain-surge-20110526,0,3407916.story?track=rss | work=Los Angeles Times | first=James | last=Oliphant | title=Is Cain able? Herman Cain scores in latest presidential poll | date=May 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nCain believes illegal immigrants should be able to go through the traditional citizenship process but opposed what he has described as a sense of automatic \"entitlement\" by people here illegally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174404 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Immigration |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711024455/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174404 |archive-date=2011-07-11 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain was quoted as saying, \"America can be a nation with high fences and wide open doors.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/11/cain-gives-policy-points-gets-applause-and-high-reference-from-romney/ |title=Cain addresses controversial remarks, gets high reference from Romney &#124; Iowa Caucuses<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120709115605/http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/11/cain-gives-policy-points-gets-applause-and-high-reference-from-romney/ |archive-date=2012-07-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain has said he would favor erecting an [[electric fence]] on the [[Mexico \u2013 United States border|United States \u2013 Mexico border]], saying \"It's going to be 20 feet high. It's going to have barbed wire on the top. It's going to be electrified. And there's going to be a sign on the other side saying, 'It will kill you \u2014 Warning.'\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/cain-proposes-electrified-border-fence/ |title=Cain Proposes Electrified Border Fence \u2013 NY TIMES |access-date=2011-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016171208/http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/cain-proposes-electrified-border-fence/ |archive-date=2011-10-16 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-15 }}</ref>  He later indicated his statement was an exaggeration as a joke.\n\nCain supports a constitutional amendment stating that children born to illegal immigrants in the U.S. are not U.S. citizens.<ref name=ljohnson>{{cite news |title=Herman Cain On Sharon Bialek: 'I Don't Even Know Who This Lady Is' |first=Luke |last=Johnson |work=Huffington Post |date=November 8, 2011 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/08/herman-cain-sharon-bialek-sexual-harassment_n_1082348.html |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110065405/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/08/herman-cain-sharon-bialek-sexual-harassment_n_1082348.html |archive-date=2011-11-10 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Cain has also said he does not support changing the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]], which states that all persons born in the U.S. and subject to the jurisdiction thereof are citizens of the United States.<ref name=ljohnson/>\n\n===Occupy Wall Street===\nIn October 2011, Cain described the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement as \"un-American\".  He further stated, \"I don't have facts to back this up, but I happen to believe that these demonstrations are planned and orchestrated to distract from the failed policies of the Obama administration.  Don't blame Wall Street, don't blame the big banks, if you don't have a job and you're not rich, blame yourself.\" In response, fellow Republican candidate [[Buddy Roemer]] defended the protests.<ref>[http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2011/10/05/336423/her-cain-jobless-blame-yourself/ Herman Cain On Occupy Wall Street: \u2018If You Don\u2019t Have A Job And You\u2019re Not Rich, Blame Yourself!\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020125419/http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2011/10/05/336423/her-cain-jobless-blame-yourself/ |date=2011-10-20 }} By Alex Seitz-Wald on Oct 5, 2011</ref><ref name=\"roemer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65378.html|title=Buddy Roemer: The Occupy Wall Street candidate?|access-date=2011-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008112827/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65378.html|archive-date=2011-10-08|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Second Amendment===\nCain believes that any concealed carry law must be dealt with at the state level<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144427 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The Second Amendment |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003351/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144427 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> and that states have the right to control gun rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.outsidethebeltway.com/herman-cain-gun-control-a-states-issue-huh/ |title=Herman Cain: Gun Control A \"States Issue.\" |publisher=OutsideTheBeltway.com |date= 2011-06-08|accessdate=September 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007170710/http://www.outsidethebeltway.com/herman-cain-gun-control-a-states-issue-huh/ |archive-date=2011-10-07 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Supreme Court justices===\nCain has expressed support for Justices [[Antonin Scalia]] and [[Clarence Thomas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193709 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Supreme Court Justices |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=February 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003428/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193709 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment legislation===\n\nIn the early 1990s, following the Clarence Thomas hearings, Cain as the then-CEO of Godfather's Pizza expressed concern about laws making it easier for women to sue their supervisors for sexual harassment: \"This bill opens the door for opportunists who will use the legislation to make some money. ... I'm certainly for civil rights, but I don't know if this bill is fair because of what we'll have to spend to defend ourselves in unwarranted cases.\"<ref name=\"harassment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/67669.html#ixzz1cqvJdjHF|title=Under Herman Cain, NRA launched sex harassment fight|access-date=2011-11-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106115721/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/67669.html#ixzz1cqvJdjHF|archive-date=2011-11-06|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Herman Cain]]\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2012 United States presidential candidates|Cain, Herman]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Herman Cain by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Cain in Washington, DC on October 7, 2011]]\n[[Herman Cain]] is a businessman, radio talk show host, and author who ran in the United States for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2012|presidential nomination]] in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]].  Cain suspended his campaign on December 3, 2011.\n{{Herman Cain series}}\n\n==Economic issues==\n\n===Bank bailouts, and \"too big to fail\"===\nCain supports the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP) bank bailouts as a way to revive the economy, viewing it as an investment opportunity for the taxpayers. In a 2008 editorial, Cain wrote, \"Owning a part of the major banks in America is not a bad thing. We could make a profit while solving a problem.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc133.htm |title=Far from Nationalization, Purchase of Bank Stocks Is a Win-Win for Taxpayers |first=Herman |last=Cain |date=October 20, 2008 |publisher=North Star Writers Group |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110619202228/http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc133.htm |archive-date=2011-06-19 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011 regarding his TARP support, Cain said, \"I don't have any regrets ... I studied the situation. I didn't have trouble with the idea; I had trouble with its implementation, picking winners and losers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/267029/introducing-herman-cain-robert-costa?page=7 |title=Introducing Herman Cain |first=Robert |last=Costa |date=May 12, 2011 |publisher=[[National Review]] |page=7 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515054238/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/267029/introducing-herman-cain-robert-costa?page=7 |archive-date=2011-05-15 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011 Cain said he does not believe in the concept of \"[[too big to fail]]\" and has stated that he did not agree with the bailouts of \"[[JP Morgan]] and the big banks on Wall Street\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Interview with Herman Cain |newspaper=International Wire |publisher=FDCH/eMedia |date=Oct 24, 2011 |quote=MORGAN: But I bet if I sat down with your family members that you're talking about now and said, how do you feel that nobody in the banking community of America has ever been properly held to account for what they did? Right? They would say it's outrageous? CAIN: Well, Piers, I did reel against it because the problem is multilevel. First of all, I didn't agree with the government bailing out JPMorgan and the big banks on Wall Streets. I don't believe in too big to fail. ... }}</ref>\n\n===Debt ceiling===\nCain opposes increases in the [[debt limit]] for the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]].<ref name=\"ceiling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60058.html |title='Cut, Cap, and Balance' rally cuts Herman Cain |publisher=Politico.com |date=July 27, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813074930/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60058.html |archive-date=2011-08-13 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  He was quoted in a July 27, 2011, ''Politico'' article that: \"I don't believe the debt ceiling should be raised. I don't believe the debt ceiling has to be raised ... Those are scare tactics. Those are simply exaggerated scare tactics.\"<ref name=\"ceiling\" />\n\n===Federal Reserve===\nCain believes that there was no need for an audit of the Federal Reserve.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/blogs/beltway-confidential/2011/05/flashback-2008-herman-cain-praised-tarp-chided-free-market-purist |title=FLASHBACK: In 2008, Herman Cain praised TARP, chided \"free market\" purists |publisher=Washington Examiner |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Cain also commented that while such an audit is not a high priority for him, he does not object to it.  He has stated that he finds it highly unlikely that anything would be found in such an audit, as the internal controls of the Fed are extensive, and that the Fed's problems stem from a politicization of the bank, rather than a failure to exercise due care for those internal controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoNIjGU5fbY |title=Glenn Beck Interviews Herman Cain \u2013 5/24/11 |publisher=iamcitizencain.com |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013074346/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoNIjGU5fbY |archive-date=2011-10-13 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Gold standard===\nCain supports the [[Gold standard]], saying that abandoning it \"allowed Congress to inflate our currency whenever they overspent. Now look at the mess that we have.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2010/12/28/herman_cain_return_to_the_gold_standard.html |title=Video \u2013 Herman Cain: Return To The Gold Standard |publisher=RealClearPolitics |date=December 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828080849/http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2010/12/28/herman_cain_return_to_the_gold_standard.html |archive-date=2011-08-28 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Social Security===\nCain has criticized the current implementation of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], describing it as a \"scam.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc14.htm |title=North Star Writers Group |publisher=004eeb5.netsolhost.com |date=May 17, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810124727/http://004eeb5.netsolhost.com/hc14.htm |archive-date=2011-08-10 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He favors reforming the current system \"through free market solutions.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174238 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Social Security |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811192437/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174238 |archive-date=2011-08-11 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nSeveral times Cain has referenced the [[Chile pension system|Chilean model]] of redoing social security.  He supports the \"Chilean model\" for younger citizens while retaining the current system for current beneficiaries.\n\n===Taxes===\nCain has supported shifting the tax burden from [[investment]] on to [[Consumption tax|consumption]].  Cain has called for the elimination of taxes on capital gains, and suspending taxes on repatriated foreign profits.<ref name=aiken>{{cite web |url=http://www.aikenstandard.com/Local/0519-herman-cain |title=Cain draws record crowd |publisher=Aiken Standard |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718063610/http://www.aikenstandard.com/Local/0519-herman-cain |archivedate=July 18, 2012 |df= }}</ref>  He also supports elimination of the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]];<ref name=\"estate\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nodeathtax.org/resources/testimonies/cain |title=\"Federal Estate Tax: Uncertainty in Planning Under the Current Law\" Nov 14, 2007 |publisher=Nodeathtax.org |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20081202061710/http://www.nodeathtax.org/resources/testimonies/cain |archivedate=December 2, 2008 |df= }}</ref> and in 2007<ref>on November 14, 2007</ref> in testimony before the [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]] called for the permanent repeal of that tax.<ref name=\"estate\" />  Prior to his presidential campaign, Cain supported lowering the [[Corporate tax in the United States|corporate tax]] rate from 35 to 25 percent.<ref name=aiken/>\n\nCain testified in front of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] on May 9, 2002, in support of [https://web.archive.org/web/20160202054845/http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c107:H.R.2525: HR 2525], which would institute a national retail sales tax.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salestax.org/library/cain_5-9-02.html |title=Testimony Before the Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures of the House Committee on Ways and Means Hearing on the Extraterritorial Income Regime |publisher=Salestax.org |date=May 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930083618/http://www.salestax.org/library/cain_5-9-02.html |archivedate=September 30, 2011 |df= }}</ref>  According to the [[Washington Times]], Cain has been known as a supporter of the broad national consumption tax on retail sales called the [[FairTax]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/may/10/gop-field-has-own-change-ideas/ |title=GOP field has own 'change' ideas |date=May 10, 2011 |first=Seth |last=McLaughlin |publisher=Washington Times |accessdate=May 23, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514151139/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/may/10/gop-field-has-own-change-ideas/ |archive-date=2011-05-14 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  During his presidential campaign in 2011, Cain introduced his signature \"9\u20139\u20139\" plan for a 9% tax on individuals, sales, and businesses.\n\n====9\u20139\u20139 Plan====\n{{Main|9\u20139\u20139 Plan}}\n\nThe \"centerpiece\"<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2011/1012/Does-the-Herman-Cain-9-9-9-tax-plan-have-a-fatal-flaw Does the Herman Cain 9\u20139\u20139 tax plan have a fatal flaw?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012193238/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2011/1012/Does-the-Herman-Cain-9-9-9-tax-plan-have-a-fatal-flaw |date=2011-10-12 }} By Peter Grier, csmonitor.com October 12, 2011</ref> of Cain's presidential campaign introduced in August 2011 has been the \"9\u20139\u20139 plan\",<ref>{{citation|publisher = HermanCain.com|title = 999 Plan|url = http://www.hermancain.com/999plan|accessdate = October 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan|archivedate = September 26, 2011|df = }}</ref> which would replace all current taxes (including the [[payroll tax]], [[capital gains tax]], and the [[inheritance tax|estate tax]]) with 9% business transaction tax; 9% [[personal income tax]] rate, and a 9% federal [[sales tax]]. According to Cain, corporations would be able to deduct costs of goods sold (provided the inputs were made in America) and capital expenditures, but not wages, salaries and benefits to employees.<ref>[https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/a-bit-more-about-cain/ A Bit More About Cain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906230143/https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/a-bit-more-about-cain/ |date=2017-09-06 }}. Paul Krugman. October 15, 2011</ref> Deductions, except charitable giving, would be eliminated. The federal sales tax would not apply to used goods. Cain also said that the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan would lift a $430 billion dead-weight burden on the economy.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} the 999 plan</ref>\n\nCain stated the following summary about the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan:\n\n<blockquote>Our current economic crisis calls for bold action to truly stimulate the economy and Renew America back to its greatness. The 9\u20139\u20139 Plan gets Washington D.C. out of the business of picking winners and losers, using the tax code to dole out favors, and dividing the country with class warfare. It is fair, simple, transparent and efficient. It taxes everything once and nothing twice. It taxes the broadest possible base at the lowest possible rates. It is neutral with respect to savings and consumption, capital and labor, imports and exports and whether companies pay dividends or retain earnings.<ref name=autogenerated3 /></blockquote>\n\nAccording to the analysis of Howard Gleckman the [[Tax Policy Center]],\n\n<blockquote>When you get right down to it, Cain's [9\u20139\u20139] plan is a 25 percent flat-rate consumption tax \u2014 not all that different from the FAIR tax that he says is his ultimate goal. This tax would be paid three times: first on wage income, again at the cash register as a sales tax, and yet again by businesses on their sales minus their cost of goods and services. For tax junkies, the first is a [[flat tax]]. The second is a retail sales tax and the third a business transfer tax.  But they are all consumption taxes.<ref>Howard Gleckman, [http://taxvox.taxpolicycenter.org/2011/10/18/cain\u2019s-9-9-9-plan-would-cut-taxes-for-the-rich-raise-taxes-for-almost-everyone-else Cain\u2019s 9\u20139\u20139 Plan Would Cut Taxes for the Rich, Raise Taxes for Almost Everyone Else] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305154717/http://taxvox.taxpolicycenter.org/2011/10/18/cain%E2%80%99s-9-9-9-plan-would-cut-taxes-for-the-rich-raise-taxes-for-almost-everyone-else/ |date=2016-03-05 }} ''[[Tax Policy Center]]'' October 18, 2011</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough Cain has spoken about having designated 'empowerment zones'<ref>{{cite news | url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1110/13/ebo.01.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com | access-date=2011-10-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017071601/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1110/13/ebo.01.html | archive-date=2011-10-17 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref> wherein a lower percentage, such as 3%, is paid instead, apart from this consideration, some have called Cain's plan more [[Regressive tax|regressive]] than current policy, thinking it would raise taxes for most households, but cut them for those with the highest income.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/10/18/news/economy/cain_999_plan/?source=cnn_bin | work=CNN | first=Jeanne | last=Sahadi | title=84% would pay more under Cain's 9-9-9 plan | date=October 18, 2011 | access-date=2011-10-19 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205105815/http://money.cnn.com/2011/10/18/news/economy/cain_999_plan/?source=cnn_bin | archive-date=2015-02-05 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref><ref>[https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/tpc-does-herman-cain/ TPC Does Herman Cain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005122509/http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/tpc-does-herman-cain/ |date=2015-10-05 }} October 18, 2011, The Tax Policy Center has the distributional analysis of 9\u20139\u20139.</ref>\n\nCain modified the plan for people under poverty level, reducing income tax for the poor to 0%, telling an audience in Detroit October 21 that the poorest Americans would get a \"9\u20130\u20139\" plan.<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/.../herman-cain-tweaks-9-9-9-tax-to-remove-flat-tax-f] 9\u20130\u20139, 0% income tax for the poor</ref>\n\nIn an October 18, 2011 debate several of the other contenders for the GOP nomination attacked the plan, with candidate [[Rick Santorum]] referencing the [[Tax Policy Center]]'s claim that 84%<ref>[http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/numbers/displayatab.cfm?Docid=3222&DocTypeID=2 T11-0375 \u2013 Herman Cain's \"9\u20139\u20139\" Tax Reform Plan; Baseline: Current Policy; Fully Phased in Distribution of Federal Tax Change by Cash Income Percentile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021043931/http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/numbers/displayatab.cfm?Docid=3222&DocTypeID=2 |date=2011-10-21 }} ''[[Tax Policy Center]]'' October 18, 2011</ref> of Americans would pay more and that the plan would entail \"major increases in taxes on people,\" a charge Cain has denied.<ref>David Lightman and Steven Thomm, [http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/132054608.html GOP presidential candidates clash in testy debate] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020122740/http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/132054608.html |date=2011-10-20 }} ''[[McClatchy News Service]]'' October 19, 2011</ref>\n\nSome economists support the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan. The former Reagan Treasury official Gary Robbins stated that the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan will expand the GDP by $2 trillion, create 6 million new jobs, increase business investment by 33%, and increase wages by 10%.<ref>[http://www.hermancain.com/999plan 9\u20139\u20139 Plan | Herman Cain for President<!-- Butt generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |date=2011-09-26 }}</ref>\nAlso, Art Laffer, a famous [[supply-side]] economist, told HUMAN EVENTS that \"Herman Cain's 9\u20139\u20139 plan would be a vast improvement over the current tax system and boom the U.S. economy.\".<ref>[http://www.westernfreepress.com/.../art-laffer-supports-cains-9-9-9-plan/] Art Laffer's quote</ref>\n\nConversely, other economists feel that the 9\u20139\u20139 plan would not stimulate the demand.<ref name=autogenerated2>Bartlett, Bruce. [https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/11/inside-the-cain-tax-plan/ \"Inside the Cain Tax Plan.\"] ''The New York Times'', October 11, 2011.</ref> [[Bruce Bartlett]] of the Reagan and George H.W. Bush administrations has written that Cain's plan \"would increase the budget deficit without doing anything to stimulate demand\".<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n[[The Economist]] criticized the 9\u20139\u20139 Plan stating that the Cain plan is not a reduction in the current corporate tax, but instead a new value added tax (VAT). The article also stated that Cain's final tax would be a 30% VAT, as compared to the 15% [[European Union value added tax]].<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2011/10/herman-cain \"Dial 9\u20139\u20139 for nonsense.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826071750/https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2011/10/herman-cain |date=2017-08-26 }} ''The Economist'', October 17, 2011.</ref> The Cain plan would change the 35% corporate tax to a 9% transaction tax, which would be flat except for payroll deductions for employees in [[empowerment zone]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} 9\u20139\u20139 Plan www.hermancain.com</ref>\n\nCain said the following about the 9% sales tax.\n\n<blockquote>Unlike a state sales tax, which is an add-on tax that increases the price of goods and services, this is a replacement tax. It replaces taxes that are already embedded in selling prices. By replacing higher marginal rates in the production process with lower marginal rates, marginal production costs actually decline, which will lead to prices being the same or lower, not higher.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926051459/http://www.hermancain.com/999plan |archivedate=2011-09-26 |df= }} The 9\u20139\u20139 plan</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Welfare===\nCain has criticized [[Social programs in the United States|social welfare programs in the United States]], stating that, \"Programs today are designed to make people more dependent rather than less dependent.\"<ref>''Q & A: Herman Cain on Faith, Calling, and Presidential Aspirations'', ''Christianity Today'', Interview by Trevor Persaud</ref>\n\n==Social issues==\n\n===Abortion===\nCain identifies as [[pro-life]] and opposes [[abortion]] in all cases,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qXTBDDhDN1g |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-11-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723140024/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qXTBDDhDN1g |archive-date=2016-07-23 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> except where the mother's life is endangered.<ref>[http://new.accessnorthga.com/detail.php?n=172858 Three Republicans battling for spots in Georgia's likely Senate runoff | AccessNorthGa<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120529192838/http://new.accessnorthga.com/detail.php?n=172858 |date=2012-05-29 }}</ref> He believes that life begins at [[fertilization|conception]]. He favors defunding [[Planned Parenthood]], an organization he has referred to as \"Planned Genocide\" because he views it as guilty of [[Black genocide conspiracy theory|genocide against black Americans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144328 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Abortion |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009002808/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144328 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"genocide\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/10/30/planned-parenthood-rejects-cain-claim-abortion-clinics-are-aimed-at-black/|title=Planned Parenthood Rejects Cain Claim Abortion Clinics Are Aimed at Black 'Genocide'|work=Fox News|date=October 30, 2011|access-date=2011-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031175012/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/10/30/planned-parenthood-rejects-cain-claim-abortion-clinics-are-aimed-at-black/|archive-date=2011-10-31|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\nCain reaffirmed his position two days after a controversial interview during which many of his opponents believed he had changed his stance. In an email to supporters, he said the following:\n\n{{blockquote|The abortion issue is very serious.  I believe strongly that this is true, and I believe that you do too.\n\nBecause the news media loves to make mountains out of mole hills, I want to be very clear about where I stand on abortion:\n\nI am 100% pro-life, period.\n\nLet me explain.  In an interview yesterday with Piers Morgan on CNN, I was asked questions about abortion policy and the role of the President.\n\nIf you listen to the line of questioning, it is clear that Mr. Morgan was asking if I, as president, would simply \"order\" people to not seek an abortion.\n\nMy answer was focused on the role of the President.  The President has no constitutional authority to order any such action by anyone.  That was the point I was trying to convey.\n\nAs to my political view on abortion ... again, I am pro-life.  End of story.\n\nAs President, I will appoint judges who understand the original intent of the Constitution.  Judges who are committed to the rule of law know that the Constitution contains no right to take the life of unborn children.\n\nI will oppose government funding of abortion.  I will veto any legislation that contains funds for Planned Parenthood.  I will do everything that a President can do, consistent with his constitutional role, to advance the culture of life.<ref>Erickson, Eric (October 21, 2011). [http://www.redstate.com/erick/2011/10/21/herman-cain-clarifies-his-abortion-position-but-it-raises-more-questions/ Herman Cain clarifies his abortion position, but it raises more questions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022024847/http://www.redstate.com/erick/2011/10/21/herman-cain-clarifies-his-abortion-position-but-it-raises-more-questions/ |date=2011-10-22 }}. ''RedState''. Retrieved October 21, 2011.</ref>}}\n\n===Affirmative action===\nCain supports ensuring that [[minorities]] receive the same opportunities as non-minorities. He does not agree with a \"[[racial quota|quota]]\" style [[affirmative action]] system, which he believes gives an advantage to minorities simply because they are a minority.<ref>[http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2004/04/28/op_413767.shtml Herman Cain Letter to the Editor of the Augusta Chronicle, Affirmative action is a negative step] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922082226/http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2004/04/28/op_413767.shtml |date=2012-09-22 }}, April 28, 2004.</ref>\n\n===Homosexuality===\nCain is an opponent of the legalization of [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|marriage for same sex couples in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Atlanta |first=Project Q |url=http://www.projectqatlanta.com/news_articles/view/Start_worrying_about_Atlantas_Herman_Cain?gid=7118 |title=Gays: Start fretting over Atlanta's Herman Cain |publisher=Projectqatlanta.com |date=December 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> He supports the [[Defense of Marriage Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://equalitymatters.org/blog/201103290013 |title=Herman Cain: I'd Rather Defend DOMA Than Protect Religious Liberty |publisher=Equality Matters |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726034051/http://equalitymatters.org/blog/201103290013 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  He would seek to reinstate the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]] policy.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Islam===\nCain has made a number of comments regarding [[Islam in the United States|American Muslims]], and the hypothetical implementation of [[Sharia|sharia law]] in the United States.<ref name=mosques>[http://www.sacbee.com/2011/07/17/3775707/herman-cain-communities-have-right.html Herman Cain: Communities have right to ban mosques]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, July 17, 2011.</ref>\n\nSome comments made by Cain regarding Muslims have caused controversy. He said that he was \"uncomfortable\" when he found that the surgeon operating on his liver and colon cancer was a Muslim.  He later explained: \"based upon the little knowledge that I have of the Muslim religion, you know, they have an objective to convert all infidels or kill them\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2011/jun/08/herman-cain/cain-denies-claims-he-said-he-would-not-appoint-mu/ |title=Cain denies claims he said he would not appoint Muslims |access-date=2011-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127165310/http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2011/jun/08/herman-cain/cain-denies-claims-he-said-he-would-not-appoint-mu/ |archive-date=2011-11-27 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He has also spoken of his distrust of another Doctor when his name \"sounded ''too'' foreign\", telling the audience at a Biblically themed amusement park \"My mind immediately started thinking, wait a minute, maybe his religious persuasion is different than mine! She [the nurse] could see the look on my face and she said, 'Don't worry, Mr. Cain, he's a Christian from Lebanon'. Hallelujah! Thank God!\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/21/herman-cain-holy-land-experience_n_1105725.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Luke | last=Johnson | title=Herman Cain Says He Was Relieved When Doctor Who Treated Him Was A Christian | date=November 21, 2011 | access-date=2011-11-21 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123133838/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/21/herman-cain-holy-land-experience_n_1105725.html | archive-date=2011-11-23 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref>\n\nWhen asked in March 2011, Cain stated that he would not feel comfortable appointing a Muslim to his administration, or as a judge <ref>{{citation |publisher=Politifact.com |date= }}</ref> saying:  \"No, I will not ... There's this creeping attempt, there's this attempt, to gradually ease Shariah Law, and the Muslim faith into our government. It does not belong in our government\"<ref name=\"foxnews1\">{{Cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/03/28/herman-cain-i-would-not-appoint-muslim-my-administration |title=Herman Cain: 'I Would Not' Appoint a Muslim in My Administration |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=May 19, 2011 |publisher=Fox News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726104958/http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/03/28/herman-cain-i-would-not-appoint-muslim-my-administration |archive-date=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/26/gop-iowa-steve-king-2012_n_840956.html#6_herman-cain-says-he-wont-stay-on-democratic-plantation-raises-specter-of-sharia-law|title=Herman Cain Says He Won't Stay on Democratic 'Plantation,' Raises Specter of Sharia Law|date=March 27, 2011|last=Ward|first=Jon|work=Huffington Post|location=USA|accessdate=May 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110512020812/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/26/gop-iowa-steve-king-2012_n_840956.html#6_herman-cain-says-he-wont-stay-on-democratic-plantation-raises-specter-of-sharia-law|archive-date=2011-05-12|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/03/26/153625/herman-cain-muslims |title=Herman Cain Tells ThinkProgress \"I Will Not\" Appoint A Muslim In My Administration |author=Scott Keyes |date=March 26, 2011 |work=Think Progress |publisher=Center for American Progress Action Fund |accessdate=June 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605101625/http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/03/26/153625/herman-cain-muslims/ |archive-date=2011-06-05 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe explained that his view was in reaction to a lawsuit in which the [[Council on American-Islamic Relations]] (CAIR) sought to block the implementation of a 2008 Oklahoma law which would have denied the use of Sharia law in state courts,<ref name=\"mears1\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-29/us/oklahoma.sharia.law_1_sharia-law-state-courts-international-law?_s=PM:US |title=Judge issues permanent injunction on Oklahoma Sharia law ban |last=Mears |first=Bill |date=November 29, 2010 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=May 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718102246/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-29/us/oklahoma.sharia.law_1_sharia-law-state-courts-international-law?_s=PM:US |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a [[Florida]] judge's decision to use Sharia law to settle a dispute within a mosque,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/civil/article1158818.ece |title=Judge orders use of Islamic law in Tampa lawsuit over mosque leadership |work=St. Petersburg Times |date= |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |format=text |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830111655/http://www.tampabay.com/news/courts/civil/article1158818.ece |archive-date=August 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> despite the Court's decision not to use ecclesiastical law in the past (see ''Kreshik v. St. Nicholas Cathedral''), and a case in New Jersey.<ref name=\"foxnews2\">{{cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/justice/2010/08/06/sharia-law-comes-new-jersey |title=Sharia Law Comes to New Jersey? |date=August 6, 2010 |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=May 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322101845/http://nation.foxnews.com/justice/2010/08/06/sharia-law-comes-new-jersey |archive-date=March 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Cain has described his position as being \"careful and cautious.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2011/06/201161405842986718.html |title=Republican 2012 hopefuls debate US issues |work=Al Jazeera |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=June 29, 2011 |format=embedded video |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617061510/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/americas/2011/06/201161405842986718.html |archive-date=2011-06-17 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe has also argued that Muslims should be prevented from building mosques in which to teach ''[[Jihad]]'' unless they have widespread approval from the local community. Cain campaigned for Muslims to be banned from building an Islamic Center at a site in Tennessee, claiming that it was \"an infringement and an abuse of our freedom of religion\" and \"just another way to try to gradually sneak Shariah law into our laws\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/herman-cain-islamic-center-of-murfreesboro-extremism_n_899499.html |title=Herman Cain: Islamic Center Of Murfreesboro Would Spread Extremism |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915102807/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/14/herman-cain-islamic-center-of-murfreesboro-extremism_n_899499.html |archive-date=2011-09-15 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Defending himself against the suggestion that this would be discrimination, during an interview he said: \"I'm willing to take a harder look at people who might be terrorists, that's what I'm saying\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/17/herman-cain-fox-mosques_n_900939.html |title=Herman Cain: Americans Have The Right To Ban Mosques In Their Communities |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=July 17, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |first=Alexander |last=Belenky |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920152212/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/17/herman-cain-fox-mosques_n_900939.html |archive-date=2011-09-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  On July 18, 2011, Cain declared that communities in the United States had the \"right\" to ban mosques. He justified his view by arguing that Muslims are trying to promote Shariah law within the U.S, and also that his position did not amount to \"religious discrimination\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/07/17/herman-cain-islam-combines-church-and-state |title=Herman Cain: Islam Combines Church and State |work=foxnews |date=July 17, 2011 |access-date=2011-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812105711/http://nation.foxnews.com/herman-cain/2011/07/17/herman-cain-islam-combines-church-and-state |archive-date=August 12, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> CAIR said that his comments were [[Constitution of the United States|unconstitutional]] and could give legitimacy to [[Islamophobia|anti-Muslim bigotry]].<ref name=mosques/>{{dead link|date=September 2011}} [[Southern Baptist Convention]] leader [[Richard Land]] also said that Cain had disregarded the constitutional rights of Muslims.<ref>Stephanie Samuel, [http://www.christianpost.com/news/southern-baptist-leader-chides-cain-for-mosque-ban-remarks-52448/ Southern Baptist Leader Chides Cain for Mosque Ban Remarks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921125254/https://www.christianpost.com/news/southern-baptist-leader-chides-cain-for-mosque-ban-remarks-52448/ |date=2018-09-21 }}, Jul. 18 2011.</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2011, Cain met with Muslim leaders at the All Dulles Area Muslim Society (ADAMS) in [[Sterling, Virginia]]. He also toured the ADAMS mosque. After the meeting, he reiterated his opposition to the use of sharia law in courts, but said, \"I am truly sorry for any comments that may have betrayed my commitment to the U.S. Constitution and the [[Freedom of religion in the United States|freedom of religion]] guaranteed by it. Muslims, like all Americans, have the right to practice their faith freely and peacefully.\"<ref>[http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60100.html#ixzz1TOcJe7Z1 Herman Cain hosts meeting with Muslim leaders Herman Cain hosts meeting with Muslim leaders] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929183437/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/60100.html#ixzz1TOcJe7Z1 |date=2011-09-29 }}, July 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Foreign policy==\n\n===About foreign policy===\nCain defended his foreign policy knowledge. \"I'm not supposed to know anything about foreign policy. Just thought I'd throw that out,\" he said to a Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel reporter while on his campaign bus on Monday, the afternoon after his interview with the paper's editorial board. \"I want to talk to commanders on the ground. Because you run for president (people say) you need to have the answer. No, you don't! No, you don't! That's not good decision-making.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/herman-cain-libya-gaffe-foreign-policy_n_1097244.html |title=Herman Cain: 'I'm Not Supposed To Know Anything About Foreign Policy' |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119012223/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/herman-cain-libya-gaffe-foreign-policy_n_1097244.html |archive-date=2011-11-19 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-11-16 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuba===\nCain said he was not a fan of the \"[[Wet feet, dry feet policy]]\", in an interview with the television station WPLG.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/68576.html |title=Herman Cain ducks Cuba questions |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120011011/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/68576.html |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Prisoner Exchanges===\n{{See also|Gilad Shalit prisoner exchange}}\nCain said \"I could see myself\" freeing all Guantanamo detainees for one American hostage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2011/10/18/cain_i_could_see_myself_freeing_all_gitmo_detainees_for_one_american_hostage |title=Cain: \"I Could See Myself\" Freeing All Gitmo Detainees For One American Hostage |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120030145/http://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2011/10/18/cain_i_could_see_myself_freeing_all_gitmo_detainees_for_one_american_hostage |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe later abandoned this position.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/19/herman-cain-terrorist-negotiations_n_1020101.html |title=Herman Cain 'Misspoke' When He Said He Might Negotiate With Terrorists |access-date=2011-11-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122090314/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/19/herman-cain-terrorist-negotiations_n_1020101.html |archive-date=2011-11-22 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-19 }}</ref>\n\n===Anwar al-Awlaki===\n\"I don't believe that the president of the United States should order the assassination of citizens of the United States,\" Cain said. \"That's why we have our court system, and that's why we have our laws.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/05/herman-cain-spying-on-americans-is-okay-but-not-assassinating-them/239400/ |title=Herman Cain: Spying on Americans Is Okay, But Not Assassinating Them |access-date=2017-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103184803/http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/05/herman-cain-spying-on-americans-is-okay-but-not-assassinating-them/239400/ |archive-date=2017-01-03 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-05-25 }}</ref>\n\nIn a brief Q&A with our panel after his speech, Cain told the crowd that he fully supported Barack Obama's decision to strike Anwar al-Awlaki.<ref>[http://pronast.com/blog/herman-cain-flip-flopped-on-the-killing-of-anwar-al-awlaki.html Herman Cain Flip-Flopped on the Killing of Anwar al-Awlaki]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Libya===\nWhen asked about U.S. foreign policy toward Libya, \"Cain repeated he would have 'assessed the [Libyan] opposition differently,' speaking in generalities about his problem-solving approach,\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/14/herman-cain-libya-question_n_1093425.html |title=Hermann Cain Stumbles on Libya Questions |newspaper=The Huffington Post |author=Luke Johnson |date=November 15, 2011 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124182416/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/14/herman-cain-libya-question_n_1093425.html |archive-date=2011-11-24 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> and expressing confusion regarding the issue.\n\n\"Cain suggested on [November 18, 2011] that the [[Taliban]] were playing a role in Libya's new government.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/11/18/herman-cain-suggests-taliban-is-running-libya/ |title=Herman Cain Suggests Taliban is Running Libya |work=foxnews.com |agency=Associated Press |date=November 18, 2011 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126231306/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/11/18/herman-cain-suggests-taliban-is-running-libya/ |archive-date=2011-11-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Afghanistan===\nCain has been supportive of a US presence in Afghanistan, and of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509170146 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The War in Afghanistan |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003519/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509170146 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Iraq===\nCain supports the [[Iraq War]], and opposes any timetable for [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]], arguing it to be equivalent to surrender.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110526130557 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The War in Iraq |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 14, 2007 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003513/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110526130557 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\nCain favors a \"diplomatic approach\" to nuclear disarmament, but that the United States should be wary of the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509171147 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Iran |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009002927/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509171147 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Israel and Palestine===\nCain supports Israel, and believes that the US should aid Israel in defending itself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509152655 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Israel |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=May 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003022/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509152655 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  After President Obama said that the starting point of negotiations for peace between the Israelis and the Palestinians should be based on the 1967 borders with mutually agreed-upon land swaps, Cain said:\n\n<blockquote>I was shocked at the president's position, and I was equally shocked that he would unilaterally suggest that Israel would move the borders back which they acquired 44 years ago.  This president threw Israel under the bus, there is no way around it. It demonstrates once again the arrogant disregard of this president for the opinion of the American people who like the relationship we have with Israel, and for Israel having the right to make its own decisions.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy7Zn-f2zg8 |title=Fox Interview of Herman Cain on Israel |publisher=Youtube.com |date=May 20, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106165006/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zy7Zn-f2zg8 |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nCain supports the [[Palestinian right of return]] under Israeli conditions.<ref>{{cite web |last=James |first=Frank |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2011/05/23/136586652/herman-cain-wasnt-able-on-palestinian-right-of-return-question |title=Herman Cain Wasn't Able On Palestinian Right Of Return Question |publisher=NPR |date=May 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526024637/http://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2011/05/23/136586652/herman-cain-wasnt-able-on-palestinian-right-of-return-question |archive-date=2011-05-26 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He later commented that he had not understood the question while making his initial answer, but reiterated his support for it under Israeli conditions.<ref>{{cite web |author=Eric Kleefeld |url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2011/05/cain-i-didnt-understand-the-right-of-return-video.php |title=Cain: 'I Didn't Understand The Right Of Return' (VIDEO) |publisher=Tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806074533/http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2011/05/cain-i-didnt-understand-the-right-of-return-video.php |archive-date=2011-08-06 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  This led to criticism regarding his lack of foreign policy experience due to his admitted unfamiliarity with the issue and need for subsequent clarification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0511/55484.html |title=Herman Cain stumbles on Palestinian question |author=Juana Summers |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101200414/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0511/55484.html |archive-date=2011-11-01 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain was the only Republican presidential candidate at the former Fox News host [[Glenn Beck]]'s \"Restoring Courage\" rally in Israel.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/herman-cain-backs-israel-with-glenn-beck-in-jerusalem-54569/ |title=Herman Cain Backs Israel With Glenn Beck in Jerusalem, Christian News<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112010025/http://www.christianpost.com/news/herman-cain-backs-israel-with-glenn-beck-in-jerusalem-54569/ |archive-date=2011-11-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain pronounced, \"If you mess with Israel, you're messing with the USA.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2011/09/20/herman-cain-if-mess-with-israel-youre-messing-with-usa/#ixzz1ZJBJIE6n | work=Fox News | title=If You Mess With Israel, You're Messing With the USA | date=September 20, 2011 | access-date=2011-09-29 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929095725/http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2011/09/20/herman-cain-if-mess-with-israel-youre-messing-with-usa/#ixzz1ZJBJIE6n | archive-date=2011-09-29 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref>\n\nAfter Vice President [[Joe Biden]] said that the Obama administration would not release [[Jonathan Pollard]] \"over my dead body\", Cain publicly disagreed with Biden's stance and said that as a supporter of Israel, he personally sympathizes with Pollard. However, he said he would have to review Pollard's case fully before deciding to free him.<ref name=\"cain\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishvoiceandopinion.com/2011/10/herman-cain-and-the-%E2%80%9Ccain-doctrine%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%9Cif-you-mess-with-israel-you-are-messing-with-the-us%E2%80%9D/|title=Herman Cain and the \"Cain Doctrine\": \"If You Mess with Israel, You Are Messing with the US\"|access-date=2011-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012122328/http://jewishvoiceandopinion.com/2011/10/herman-cain-and-the-%E2%80%9Ccain-doctrine%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%9Cif-you-mess-with-israel-you-are-messing-with-the-us%E2%80%9D/|archive-date=2011-10-12|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn late October 2011, Cain said that President Obama's weakness on Middle East policies was emboldening what he referred to as the \"so-called Palestinian people\" to [[Palestine 194|seek statehood at the United Nations]].<ref name=\"socalled\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/190457-cain-push-by-so-called-palestinian-people-for-statehood-result-of-obama-weakness|title=Herman Cain: Obama's weakness emboldens 'so-called Palestinian people'|access-date=2011-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029143300/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/190457-cain-push-by-so-called-palestinian-people-for-statehood-result-of-obama-weakness|archive-date=2011-10-29|url-status=live|df=|date=2011-10-28}}</ref>\n\n===North Korea===\nCain opposes any form of negotiation with [[North Korea]], and has argued for maintaining \"peace through strength\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193955 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 North Korea |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724053832/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/President/US/Herman_Cain/Views/North_Korea/ |archive-date=2012-07-24 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nCain opposed the [[New START]] treaty, because he believes that the US should retain freedom to develop nuclear weapons systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509185820 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Nuclear Weapons |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=January 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003135/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509185820 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===China===\nYes, they're a military threat,\" Cain said on the PBS NewsHour, in response to a question from Judy Woodruff. \"They've indicated that they're trying to develop nuclear capability and they want to develop more aircraft carriers like we have. So yes, we have to consider them a military threat.\" \"We already have superiority in terms of our military capability, and I plan to get away from making cutting our defense a priority and make investing in our military capability a priority,\" he said.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20128920-503544/herman-cain-incorrectly-suggests-china-doesnt-have-nuclear-capability/ |title=Herman Cain incorrectly suggests China doesn't have nuclear capability |access-date=2011-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122124753/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20128920-503544/herman-cain-incorrectly-suggests-china-doesnt-have-nuclear-capability/ |archive-date=2011-11-22 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain addressed the gaffe in an interview with Ginni Thomas of The Daily Caller on Wednesday evening, and attempted to clarify his comments. \"Maybe I misspoke,\" he said. \"What I meant was China does not have the size of the nuclear capability that we have. They do have a nuclear capability. I was talking about their total nuclear capability.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/03/herman-cain-china-nuclear-weapons_n_1073477.html |title=Herman Cain On China Nuclear Capability: 'I Misspoke' |access-date=2011-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111206222635/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/03/herman-cain-china-nuclear-weapons_n_1073477.html |archive-date=2011-12-06 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-11-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\nCain continued, \"Knowing who is the head of some of these small insignificant states around the world, I don't think that is something that is critical to focusing on national security and getting this economy going. When I get ready to go visit that country, I'll know who it is, but until then, I want to focus on the big issues that we need to solve.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/opinion/herman-cain-thinks-uzbekistan-doesnt-matter-hes-wrong/11989/ |title=Herman Cain thinks Uzbekistan doesn't matter. He's wrong. |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715070525/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/opinion/herman-cain-thinks-uzbekistan-doesnt-matter-hes-wrong/11989/ |archive-date=2017-07-15 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-14 }}</ref>\n\n==Other issues==\n[[File:Herman-cain-ttu-2011-tn1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Cain in Tennessee on October 15, 2011]]\n\n===2008 presidential election===\nIn 2008, Cain initially praised Democratic candidate [[Barack Obama]], saying of Obama that \"His gift is the gift of oratory. That's not just the ability to speak, but the ability to connect with people.\" He also said that he would consider supporting Obama \"under the right circumstances\" but only if he made a serious attempt to \"reach across the aisle\". Cain instead endorsed [[Mitt Romney]] in the Republican primary, and eventually supported the GOP nominee, [[John McCain]].<ref name=\"cainobama\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8334-503544_162-20127194-503544/six-things-you-dont-know-about-herman-cain/?pageNum=2&tag=next|title=Cain at one point said he could envision himself supporting Barack Obama's candidacy \"under the right circumstances.\" | work=CBS News}}</ref>\n\n===Capital punishment===\nCain advocates the use of [[capital punishment in the United States]]. When asked if the death penalty should be thrown away when evidence comes into question, he replied \"No. If you do away with it, that will only brainwash people into thinking that they can do whatever they want and get away with it.\"<ref>Tolliver, Lafe. [http://www.thetoledojournal.com/news/Article/Article.asp?NewsID=111034&sID=16&ItemSource=L \"Cain\u2026.Raising Cain!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203145117/http://www.thetoledojournal.com/News/article/article.asp?NewsID=111034&sID=16&ItemSource=L |date=2012-02-03 }} ''The Toledo Journal'', October 14, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Education===\nCain opposes federal education schemes such as [[NCLB|No Child Left Behind]] and advocates \"unbundling\" education, weakening the [[United States Department of Education]] in favor of state control of education. He has argued for greater [[performance-related pay]] for teachers, as well as for vouchers and charter school systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508194027 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Education |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003145/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508194027 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Energy and the environment===\nCain favors [[offshore drilling]] and supports drilling in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] (ANWR). He favors allowing consumers to choose alternative energy sources such as solar and wind through the private market instead of the government providing funding and incentives to particular corporations and industries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174056 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Energy and the Environment |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712200528/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174056 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain's ideology on the climate represents what is termed [[climate change denial]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Evangelical Rejection of Reason |author=Karl W. Giberson and Randall J. Stephens |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 18, 2011 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/opinion/the-evangelical-rejection-of-reason.html |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316044404/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/opinion/the-evangelical-rejection-of-reason.html |archive-date=2017-03-16 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> He has made statements indicating a belief that anthropogenic global warming is a [[global warming conspiracy theory|hoax]], referring to it as \"poppycock\" and claiming that scientists were \"busted\" of having \"manipulated the data.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =Mark Levin interviews Herman Cain the day after the New Hampshire debate| url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p7YWwWF22gc&feature=player_embedded#!| date =June 16, 2011| work =[[The Mark Levin Show]]| publisher =(YouTube.com)| access-date =2016-11-30| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160427134101/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p7YWwWF22gc&feature=player_embedded#!| archive-date =2016-04-27| url-status=live| df =}}</ref>{{lopsided|date=November 2011}}\n\n===Health care===\nCain supports repeal of the 2010 [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (PPACA). Cain, a [[cancer survivor]], also has said that the PPACA would have killed him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/cancer-survivor-herman-cain-i-would-be-dead-on-obamacare/ |title=Cancer Survivor Herman Cain: \u2018I Would Be Dead\u2019 on Obamacare &#124; Video &#124; TheBlaze.com<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925193130/http://www.theblaze.com/stories/cancer-survivor-herman-cain-i-would-be-dead-on-obamacare/ |archive-date=2011-09-25 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain favors allowing the free market to play the largest role in health care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174531 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Health Care |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003249/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174531 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain supported the 2012 Ryan budget plan, which sought to privatize Medicare, describing it favorably as a \"voucher program.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-herman-cain-surge-20110526,0,3407916.story?track=rss | work=Los Angeles Times | first=James | last=Oliphant | title=Is Cain able? Herman Cain scores in latest presidential poll | date=May 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nCain believes illegal immigrants should be able to go through the traditional citizenship process but opposed what he has described as a sense of automatic \"entitlement\" by people here illegally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174404 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Immigration |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711024455/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110508174404 |archive-date=2011-07-11 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>  Cain was quoted as saying, \"America can be a nation with high fences and wide open doors.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/11/cain-gives-policy-points-gets-applause-and-high-reference-from-romney/ |title=Cain addresses controversial remarks, gets high reference from Romney &#124; Iowa Caucuses<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2011-09-29 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120709115605/http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/11/cain-gives-policy-points-gets-applause-and-high-reference-from-romney/ |archive-date=2012-07-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nCain has said he would favor erecting an [[electric fence]] on the [[Mexico \u2013 United States border|United States \u2013 Mexico border]], saying \"It's going to be 20 feet high. It's going to have barbed wire on the top. It's going to be electrified. And there's going to be a sign on the other side saying, 'It will kill you \u2014 Warning.'\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/cain-proposes-electrified-border-fence/ |title=Cain Proposes Electrified Border Fence \u2013 NY TIMES |access-date=2011-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016171208/http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/15/cain-proposes-electrified-border-fence/ |archive-date=2011-10-16 |url-status=live |df= |date=2011-10-15 }}</ref>  He later indicated his statement was an exaggeration as a joke.\n\nCain supports a constitutional amendment stating that children born to illegal immigrants in the U.S. are not U.S. citizens.<ref name=ljohnson>{{cite news |title=Herman Cain On Sharon Bialek: 'I Don't Even Know Who This Lady Is' |first=Luke |last=Johnson |work=Huffington Post |date=November 8, 2011 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/08/herman-cain-sharon-bialek-sexual-harassment_n_1082348.html |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110065405/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/08/herman-cain-sharon-bialek-sexual-harassment_n_1082348.html |archive-date=2011-11-10 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Cain has also said he does not support changing the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]], which states that all persons born in the U.S. and subject to the jurisdiction thereof are citizens of the United States.<ref name=ljohnson/>\n\n===Occupy Wall Street===\nIn October 2011, Cain described the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement as \"un-American\".  He further stated, \"I don't have facts to back this up, but I happen to believe that these demonstrations are planned and orchestrated to distract from the failed policies of the Obama administration.  Don't blame Wall Street, don't blame the big banks, if you don't have a job and you're not rich, blame yourself.\" In response, fellow Republican candidate [[Buddy Roemer]] defended the protests.<ref>[http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2011/10/05/336423/her-cain-jobless-blame-yourself/ Herman Cain On Occupy Wall Street: \u2018If You Don\u2019t Have A Job And You\u2019re Not Rich, Blame Yourself!\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020125419/http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2011/10/05/336423/her-cain-jobless-blame-yourself/ |date=2011-10-20 }} By Alex Seitz-Wald on Oct 5, 2011</ref><ref name=\"roemer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65378.html|title=Buddy Roemer: The Occupy Wall Street candidate?|access-date=2011-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008112827/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65378.html|archive-date=2011-10-08|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Second Amendment===\nCain believes that any concealed carry law must be dealt with at the state level<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144427 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 The Second Amendment |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003351/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509144427 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> and that states have the right to control gun rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.outsidethebeltway.com/herman-cain-gun-control-a-states-issue-huh/ |title=Herman Cain: Gun Control A \"States Issue.\" |publisher=OutsideTheBeltway.com |date= 2011-06-08|accessdate=September 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007170710/http://www.outsidethebeltway.com/herman-cain-gun-control-a-states-issue-huh/ |archive-date=2011-10-07 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Supreme Court justices===\nCain has expressed support for Justices [[Antonin Scalia]] and [[Clarence Thomas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193709 |title=Herman Cain \u2013 Supreme Court Justices |publisher=Thepoliticalguide.com |date=February 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 6, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009003428/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=98516477&category=views&id=20110509193709 |archive-date=2011-10-09 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment legislation===\n\nIn the early 1990s, following the Clarence Thomas hearings, Cain as the then-CEO of Godfather's Pizza expressed concern about laws making it easier for women to sue their supervisors for sexual harassment: \"This bill opens the door for opportunists who will use the legislation to make some money. ... I'm certainly for civil rights, but I don't know if this bill is fair because of what we'll have to spend to defend ourselves in unwarranted cases.\"<ref name=\"harassment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/67669.html#ixzz1cqvJdjHF|title=Under Herman Cain, NRA launched sex harassment fight|access-date=2011-11-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106115721/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/67669.html#ixzz1cqvJdjHF|archive-date=2011-11-06|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Herman Cain]]\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2012 United States presidential candidates|Cain, Herman]]\n", "name_user": "Adavidb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIraq:war is over", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_positions_of_Herman_Cain"}
