{"title_page": "30 Hudson Yards", "text_new": "{{distinguish|30 Hudson Street}}\n{{short description|Supertall skyscraper in New York City}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = 30 Hudson Yards\n| alternate_names     = Hudson Yards Tower A, Manhattan Tower, Hudson Yards North Tower\n| status              = Complete\n| image               = 30 Hudson Yards(StreetView).jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = 30 Hudson Yards in February 2019.\n| location            = 500 West 33rd Street <br/>[[Manhattan|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]] 10001<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Stephen |title=Permits Filed: 30 Hudson Yards |url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2014/07/permits-filed-30-hudson-yards.html |website=New York YIMBY |accessdate=15 February 2020 |date=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n| groundbreaking_date = December 4, 2012\n| architect           = [[Kohn Pedersen Fox]] ''(architect & master planner)''\n| floor_area          = {{convert|2,600,000|ft2|m2|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/work/30-hudson-yards/|title=30 Hudson Yards Office Space - Hudson Yards|author=|date=August 24, 2016|website=hudsonyardsnewyork.com|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| floor_count         = 101 \n| references          = <ref>{{cite web|title=30 Hudson Yards|website=Hudson Yards Center|publisher=Oxford Properties Group Inc.|accessdate=October 11, 2018|url = https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/press-releases/30-hudson-yards-tops-out-as-final-beam-is-lifted-and-completes-the-buildings-steel-crown/|date=July 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| building_type       = [[Office]], Observation, Retail\n| height              = 395 m / 1,296\nft<ref>https://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=95171</ref>\n| elevator_count      = 59\n| architectural_style = [[Neo-futurism]]\n| main_contractor     = [[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Construction]]\n| opened_date         = March 15, 2019\n| management          = [[Related Companies|The Related Companies L.P.]]<br>[[Oxford Properties|Oxford Properties Group Inc.]]\n}}\n{{Hudson Yards map}}\n}}\n'''30 Hudson Yards''' (also the '''North Tower'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chelseanow.com/2013/02/hudson-yards-set-to-alter-skyline-transform-neighborhood/|title=Hudson Yards Set to Alter Skyline, Transform Neighborhood|work=Chelsea Now|date=February 6, 2013|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref>) is a super-tall mixed use building in the [[West Side (Manhattan)|West Side]] area of [[Manhattan]]. Located near [[Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan|Hell's Kitchen]], [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]], and the [[Penn Station (New York City)|Penn Station]] area, the building is part of the [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project]], a plan to redevelop the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Metropolitan Transportation Authority's]] [[West Side Yard]].<ref>Arak, Joey (November 19, 2007). [http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2007/11/19/yardsmania_1_brookfield_properties_goes_splittsville.php \"Brookfield Properties Goes Splittsville\"]. Curbed.</ref><ref>Chaban, Matt (July 12, 2011). [http://www.observer.com/2011/07/scaling-the-towers-of-hudson-yards/ \"Scaling the Towers of Hudson Yards\"]. ''[[New York Observer]]''.</ref><ref>[https://nymag.com/homedesign/urbanliving/2012/hudson-yards/ Davidson, Justin.\"From 0 to 12 Million Square Feet\"] ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' (October 7, 2012)</ref><ref>Samtani, Hiten (August 16, 2013). [http://therealdeal.com/blog/2013/08/16/anatomy-of-a-deal-inside-relatedoxfords-unusual-hudson-yards-financing/ \"Anatomy of a deal: Inside Related/Oxford\u2019s unusual financing of Hudson Yards\"]. ''The Real Deal''.</ref><ref>Sheftell, Jason (December 4, 2012). [http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/real-estate/officials-developers-break-ground-15b-hudson-yards-article-1.1212797 \"New York City officials, developers to break ground on $15 billion mini-city Hudson Yards\"]. ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]''.</ref> Since April 2019, it has been the [[List of tallest buildings in New York City|third-tallest building in New York City]].\n\nThe building has a triangular observation deck jutting out from the 101st floor. This observation deck, at 1,100 feet, opened in March 2020 and is the highest outdoor observation deck in the Western Hemisphere.<ref>https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/discover/edge</ref> (The [[Empire State Building]]'s 102nd floor observation deck, at 1,224 feet, is enclosed.) It offers new skyline views to the south and east of Manhattan, the surrounding boroughs, and New Jersey.\n\n==History==\n[[File:30 Hudson Yards 2019.jpg|thumb|left|30 Hudson Yards from the east, with [[5 Manhattan West]] visible at left]]\n[[File:Hudson Yards May 2017 03.jpg|thumb|left|The tower's base]]\n\nThe groundbreaking ceremony took place on December 4, 2012. Early construction work focused on building a platform to cover much of the Eastern Rail Yard, for much of Phase 1 to sit upon. The platform is rested on [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]], that are drilled underground. On December 12, 2013, it was announced that [[Tutor Perini|Tutor Perini Building Corp.]] was awarded a $510 million contract to build the platform.<ref>D'Amico, Esther; Worrell, Carolina (December 19, 2013). [http://newyork.construction.com/new_york_construction_news/2013/1219-further-work-details-revealed-on-three-major-nyc-projects.asp \"Further Work Details Revealed on Three Major NYC Projects\"].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Time Warner]] announced its intentions to move most of its offices to 30 Hudson Yards, vacating its current headquarters at the [[Time Warner Center]], also owned by Related, at [[Columbus Circle]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Weiss, Lois|date=June 5, 2013|url=https://nypost.com/2013/06/05/tw-is-at-center-of-hot-attention/|title=TW is at Center of hot attention|work=[[New York Post]]}}</ref> The company will occupy half the building, below the 38th floor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2014/01/16/time-warner-inc-announces-new-york-real-estate-development-plans |title=Time Warner Press Releases |publisher=Time Warner |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/17/nyregion/time-warner-announces-a-move-from-columbus-circle-to-hudson-yards.html|title=Time Warner Is Planning a Move to Hudson Yards|date=January 16, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=April 11, 2018|via=NYTimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles V.}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2015, Related received a $690 million loan from [[Bank of America]], [[Wells Fargo]], and [[CIBC]] which allowed construction to start.<ref name=\"nyyimby 201407\">{{cite web | url=http://newyorkyimby.com/2014/07/yimby-today-505-west-19th-street-nomad-commercial-potential-and-more.html | title=Permits Filed: 30 Hudson Yards | work=NY Yimby | date=July 22, 2014 | accessdate=August 28, 2014 | author=Smith, Stephen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20151211/REAL_ESTATE/151219954/related-oxford-land-5-billion-loan-for-30-hudson-yards|title=Developers land $5 billion loan for 30 Hudson Yards, mall on far West Side|date=December 10, 2015|work=Crain's New York|last=Geiger|first=Daniel}}</ref> By January 2016, the structure's first few aboveground floors were already complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2015/12/23/hudson_yardss_tallest_tower_begins_its_1287foot_ascent.php|title=Hudson Yards's Tallest Tower Begins Its 1,287-Foot Ascent|author=|date=December 23, 2015|website=curbed.com|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> Construction of the observation deck at the top of the tower began in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/skyscraper-hudson-yards-new-york-city-observation-deck-2018-4|title=New York City is getting a 1,296-foot-tall skyscraper with the highest observation deck in the Western Hemisphere \u2014 see the incredible views|last=Garfield|first=Leanna|date=April 11, 2018|work=Business Insider|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chelseanow.com/2018/04/construction-begins-on-observation-deck-at-30-hudson-yards/|title=Construction Begins on Observation Deck at 30 Hudson Yards|last=Stiffler|first=Scott|date=April 25, 2018|website=chelseanow.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> The observation deck was nearly complete by mid-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2018/05/30-hudson-yards-observation-deck-and-parapet-nearly-complete.html|title=30 Hudson Yards' Observation Deck And Parapet Nearly Complete|last=Nelson|first=Andrew|date=May 7, 2018|publisher=New York YIMBY|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj 20140604\">{{cite web | url=https://www.6sqft.com/30-hudson-yards-officially-tops-out-at-1296-feet/|title=30 Hudson Yards officially tops out at 1,296 feet |work=[[6sqft]]|date=July 17, 2018 | access-date=October 11, 2018 |last=Gannon|first=Devin}}</ref><ref name=\"cny 20150610\">{{cite web | url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2015/06/10/hudson_yards_construction_rolls_on_as_retail_center_rises.php | title=Hudson Yards Construction Rolls On As Retail Center Rises | work=Curbed NY | date=June 10, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Jessica Dailey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/4/4/17115600/hudson-yards-construction-timeline-building-status-nyc|title=Tracking the biggest buildings taking shape at Hudson Yards|last=Walker|first=Ameena|date=April 4, 2018|website=Curbed NY|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe building opened on March 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2019/1/2/18161731/nyc-real-estate-architecture-predictions-2019|title=6 crucial ways New York City's landscape will change in 2019|last=Rosenberg|first=Zoe|date=January 2, 2019|website=Curbed NY|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/hudson-yards-rundown-major-buildings-finished-2018-10|title=Hudson Yards is the biggest New York development since Rockefeller Center. Here are all the major buildings in the $25 billion neighborhood.|last=Bendix|first=Aria|date=October 7, 2018|website=Business Insider|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> One month later, WarnerMedia executed a [[leaseback]] and sold their space to Related and [[Allianz]] for $2.2 billion after signing a 15-year lease for {{convert|1,500,000|sqft|m2}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/04/allianz-teaming-up-with-related-in-its-2-2b-acquisition-of-30-hudson-yards/|title=Allianz Teaming Up With Related in Its $2.2B Acquisition of 30 Hudson Yards|date=April 24, 2019|last=Gourarie|first=Chava}}</ref> The partners financed the purchase with a 10-year, $1.43 billion [[commercial mortgage-backed security]] [[interest-only loan]] from [[Deutsche Bank]], Wells Fargo, and [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref name=\"refi\">{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/06/30-hudson-yards-allianz/|title=Related, Allianz Office Deal at 30 Hudson Yards Funded with $1.43B Mortgage|last=Grossman|first=Matt|work=Commercial Observer|date=June 20, 2019|access-date=June 21, 2019}}</ref> In June, KKR took out a $490 million mortgage from [[Deutsche Bank]] on their office condominium space.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/06/kkr-30-hudson-yards/|title=KKR Seals $490M Financing for Commercial Condo at 30 Hudson Yards|last=Grossman|first=Matt|work=Commercial Observer|date=June 7, 2019|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tenants==\n* Lobby: [[WarnerMedia]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[The Shops & Restaurants at Hudson Yards]] (retail), [[Jack's Stir Brew Coffee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/press-releases/hudson-yards-announces-fast-casual-additions-to-dining-collection/|title=HUDSON YARDS ANNOUNCES FAST-CASUAL ADDITIONS TO DINING COLLECTION|date=December 4, 2018|publisher=Related Companies}}</ref>\n* Floors 1\u201315: [[Wells Fargo Securities]]\n* Floors 16\u201351: [[WarnerMedia]]\n* Floor 25: ([[mechanical floor]])\n* Floor 35: ([[sky lobby]])\n* Floor 52: (mechanical floor)\n* Floors 60\u201366: [[Wells Fargo Securities]]\n* Floor 67: [[Oxford Properties]] \n* Floors 68-71: [[Facebook]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://therealdeal.com/2019/11/26/heres-how-much-facebook-is-paying-at-hudson-yards/|title=Here's how much Facebook is paying at Hudson Yards|last=Sun|first=Kevin|date=November 26, 2019|work=The Real Deal}}</ref>\n* Floors 72\u201373: [[The Related Companies]] \n* Floors 74\u201383: [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]]\n* Floor 79: (mechanical floor)\n* Floors 99\u2013100: (observation deck)\n* Floor 101: (event space)\n\n==Studios==\n*17N: ''[[CNN Newsroom]]'', ''[[Early Start]]'', ''[[Reliable Sources]]''\n*19X: multi purposed studio\n*19Y: ''[[CNN Newsroom|At This Hour]]'', ''[[Cuomo Prime Time]]'', ''[[New Day (TV program)|New Day]]'', ''[[Quest Means Business]]''\n*19Z: ''[[CNN Tonight]]'', ''[[Erin Burnett OutFront]]'', ''[[Fareed Zakaria GPS]]''\n*21L: ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscaststudio.com/tag/hudson-yards/|title=30 Hudson Yards|date=August 3, 2019|publisher=NewscastStudio}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and design==\n[[Kohn Pedersen Fox]] was chosen for the design of the building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/office/30-hudson-yards |title=30 Hudson Yards Floor Plans &#124; Hudson Yards |publisher=Hudsonyardsnewyork.com |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215147/http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/office/30-hudson-yards |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Originally planned to be {{convert|1337|ft|m}} tall,<ref>Fedak, Nikolai (November 25, 2013). [http://newyorkyimby.com/2013/11/relateds-hudson-yards-towers-re-named.html \"Related's Hudson Yards Towers Re-Named\"]. New York Yimby.</ref> the building was later downsized to {{convert|1268|ft|m}} tall,<ref>{{cite web|author=CTBUH |url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/new-york-city/30-hudson-yards/13325/ |title=30 Hudson Yards Facts &#124; CTBUH Skyscraper Database |location=40.75402 -74.00083 |publisher=Skyscrapercenter.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> making it still the development's tallest building.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-19/new-york-s-hudson-yards-starts-next-phase-as-deck-begins.html | title=New York's Hudson Yards Starts Next Phase as Deck Begins | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=March 19, 2014 | accessdate=August 28, 2014 | author=David M. Levitt}}</ref> WarnerMedia's space features amenities including a cafeteria, a fitness center, a two-level auditorium and cinema and an outdoor deck.<ref name=\"refi\" />\n\nThe building features an {{convert|80|ft|0|adj=on}} observation deck that juts into the air.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hudson Yards Set to Alter Skyline, Transform Neighborhood|url=http://chelseanow.com/2013/02/hudson-yards-set-to-alter-skyline-transform-neighborhood/|website=Chelsea Now|accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref> The building's lobby will contain artwork by Spanish artist [[Jaume Plensa]] consisting of 11 stainless steel spheres hanging from the ceiling, meant to represent global unity and cultural diversity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Related And Oxford Unveil Commissioned Art Installations At Hudson Yards|work=New York Yimby|date=January 31, 2019|last=Morris|first=Sebastian|url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2019/01/related-and-oxford-unveil-commissioned-art-installations-at-hudson-yards.html}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\n30 Hudson Yards March 2017.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction in March 2017\nHudson Yards May 2017 47.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction on the left with the completed [[10 Hudson Yards]] on the right in May 2017\nHudson Yards Apr 2018 04.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction in April 2018\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in New York City]]\n* [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|30 Hudson Yards}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/work/30-hudson-yards}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150218025817/http://www.hydc.org/html/home/home.shtml New York City project website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120718082011/http://www.related.com/destinations/hudsonyards/ Related Companies project website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624075515/http://gothamist.com/2013/01/15/awesome_infrastructure_video_buildi.php#photo-1 Animation: building the platform while trains run through] Brookfield properties, via Gothamist.com\n* [http://therealdeal.com/blog/tag/hudson-yards/ Hudson Yards news and developments]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Hudson Yards}}\n{{Supertall skyscrapers |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Hudson Yards, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Kohn Pedersen Fox buildings]]\n[[Category:Oxford Properties]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 2019]]\n[[Category:Buildings developed by the Related Companies]]\n[[Category:Media company headquarters in the United States]]\n[[Category:WarnerMedia]]\n[[Category:Wells Fargo buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Supertall skyscraper in New York City}}\n{{distinguish|30 Hudson Street}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = 30 Hudson Yards\n| alternate_names     = Hudson Yards Tower A, Manhattan Tower, Hudson Yards North Tower\n| status              = Complete\n| image               = 30 Hudson Yards(StreetView).jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = 30 Hudson Yards in February 2019.\n| location            = 500 West 33rd Street <br/>[[Manhattan|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]] 10001<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Stephen |title=Permits Filed: 30 Hudson Yards |url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2014/07/permits-filed-30-hudson-yards.html |website=New York YIMBY |accessdate=15 February 2020 |date=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n| groundbreaking_date = December 4, 2012\n| architect           = [[Kohn Pedersen Fox]] ''(architect & master planner)''\n| floor_area          = {{convert|2,600,000|ft2|m2|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/work/30-hudson-yards/|title=30 Hudson Yards Office Space - Hudson Yards|author=|date=August 24, 2016|website=hudsonyardsnewyork.com|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| floor_count         = 101 \n| references          = <ref>{{cite web|title=30 Hudson Yards|website=Hudson Yards Center|publisher=Oxford Properties Group Inc.|accessdate=October 11, 2018|url = https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/press-releases/30-hudson-yards-tops-out-as-final-beam-is-lifted-and-completes-the-buildings-steel-crown/|date=July 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| building_type       = [[Office]], Observation, Retail\n| height              = 395 m / 1,296\nft<ref>https://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=95171</ref>\n| elevator_count      = 59\n| architectural_style = [[Neo-futurism]]\n| main_contractor     = [[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Construction]]\n| opened_date         = March 15, 2019\n| management          = [[Related Companies|The Related Companies L.P.]]<br>[[Oxford Properties|Oxford Properties Group Inc.]]\n}}\n{{Hudson Yards map}}\n}}\n'''30 Hudson Yards''' (also the '''North Tower'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chelseanow.com/2013/02/hudson-yards-set-to-alter-skyline-transform-neighborhood/|title=Hudson Yards Set to Alter Skyline, Transform Neighborhood|work=Chelsea Now|date=February 6, 2013|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref>) is a super-tall mixed use building in the [[West Side (Manhattan)|West Side]] area of [[Manhattan]]. Located near [[Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan|Hell's Kitchen]], [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]], and the [[Penn Station (New York City)|Penn Station]] area, the building is part of the [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project]], a plan to redevelop the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Metropolitan Transportation Authority's]] [[West Side Yard]].<ref>Arak, Joey (November 19, 2007). [http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2007/11/19/yardsmania_1_brookfield_properties_goes_splittsville.php \"Brookfield Properties Goes Splittsville\"]. Curbed.</ref><ref>Chaban, Matt (July 12, 2011). [http://www.observer.com/2011/07/scaling-the-towers-of-hudson-yards/ \"Scaling the Towers of Hudson Yards\"]. ''[[New York Observer]]''.</ref><ref>[https://nymag.com/homedesign/urbanliving/2012/hudson-yards/ Davidson, Justin.\"From 0 to 12 Million Square Feet\"] ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' (October 7, 2012)</ref><ref>Samtani, Hiten (August 16, 2013). [http://therealdeal.com/blog/2013/08/16/anatomy-of-a-deal-inside-relatedoxfords-unusual-hudson-yards-financing/ \"Anatomy of a deal: Inside Related/Oxford\u2019s unusual financing of Hudson Yards\"]. ''The Real Deal''.</ref><ref>Sheftell, Jason (December 4, 2012). [http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/real-estate/officials-developers-break-ground-15b-hudson-yards-article-1.1212797 \"New York City officials, developers to break ground on $15 billion mini-city Hudson Yards\"]. ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]''.</ref> Since April 2019, it has been the [[List of tallest buildings in New York City|third-tallest building in New York City]].\n\nThe building has a triangular observation deck jutting out from the 101st floor. This observation deck, at 1,100 feet, opened in March 2020 and is the highest outdoor observation deck in the Western Hemisphere.<ref>https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/discover/edge</ref> (The [[Empire State Building]]'s 102nd floor observation deck, at 1,224 feet, is enclosed.) It offers new skyline views to the south and east of Manhattan, the surrounding boroughs, and New Jersey.\n\n==History==\n[[File:30 Hudson Yards 2019.jpg|thumb|left|30 Hudson Yards from the east, with [[5 Manhattan West]] visible at left]]\n[[File:Hudson Yards May 2017 03.jpg|thumb|left|The tower's base]]\n\nThe groundbreaking ceremony took place on December 4, 2012. Early construction work focused on building a platform to cover much of the Eastern Rail Yard, for much of Phase 1 to sit upon. The platform is rested on [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]], that are drilled underground. On December 12, 2013, it was announced that [[Tutor Perini|Tutor Perini Building Corp.]] was awarded a $510 million contract to build the platform.<ref>D'Amico, Esther; Worrell, Carolina (December 19, 2013). [http://newyork.construction.com/new_york_construction_news/2013/1219-further-work-details-revealed-on-three-major-nyc-projects.asp \"Further Work Details Revealed on Three Major NYC Projects\"].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Time Warner]] announced its intentions to move most of its offices to 30 Hudson Yards, vacating its current headquarters at the [[Time Warner Center]], also owned by Related, at [[Columbus Circle]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Weiss, Lois|date=June 5, 2013|url=https://nypost.com/2013/06/05/tw-is-at-center-of-hot-attention/|title=TW is at Center of hot attention|work=[[New York Post]]}}</ref> The company will occupy half the building, below the 38th floor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2014/01/16/time-warner-inc-announces-new-york-real-estate-development-plans |title=Time Warner Press Releases |publisher=Time Warner |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/17/nyregion/time-warner-announces-a-move-from-columbus-circle-to-hudson-yards.html|title=Time Warner Is Planning a Move to Hudson Yards|date=January 16, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=April 11, 2018|via=NYTimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles V.}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2015, Related received a $690 million loan from [[Bank of America]], [[Wells Fargo]], and [[CIBC]] which allowed construction to start.<ref name=\"nyyimby 201407\">{{cite web | url=http://newyorkyimby.com/2014/07/yimby-today-505-west-19th-street-nomad-commercial-potential-and-more.html | title=Permits Filed: 30 Hudson Yards | work=NY Yimby | date=July 22, 2014 | accessdate=August 28, 2014 | author=Smith, Stephen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20151211/REAL_ESTATE/151219954/related-oxford-land-5-billion-loan-for-30-hudson-yards|title=Developers land $5 billion loan for 30 Hudson Yards, mall on far West Side|date=December 10, 2015|work=Crain's New York|last=Geiger|first=Daniel}}</ref> By January 2016, the structure's first few aboveground floors were already complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2015/12/23/hudson_yardss_tallest_tower_begins_its_1287foot_ascent.php|title=Hudson Yards's Tallest Tower Begins Its 1,287-Foot Ascent|author=|date=December 23, 2015|website=curbed.com|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> Construction of the observation deck at the top of the tower began in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/skyscraper-hudson-yards-new-york-city-observation-deck-2018-4|title=New York City is getting a 1,296-foot-tall skyscraper with the highest observation deck in the Western Hemisphere \u2014 see the incredible views|last=Garfield|first=Leanna|date=April 11, 2018|work=Business Insider|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chelseanow.com/2018/04/construction-begins-on-observation-deck-at-30-hudson-yards/|title=Construction Begins on Observation Deck at 30 Hudson Yards|last=Stiffler|first=Scott|date=April 25, 2018|website=chelseanow.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> The observation deck was nearly complete by mid-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2018/05/30-hudson-yards-observation-deck-and-parapet-nearly-complete.html|title=30 Hudson Yards' Observation Deck And Parapet Nearly Complete|last=Nelson|first=Andrew|date=May 7, 2018|publisher=New York YIMBY|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj 20140604\">{{cite web | url=https://www.6sqft.com/30-hudson-yards-officially-tops-out-at-1296-feet/|title=30 Hudson Yards officially tops out at 1,296 feet |work=[[6sqft]]|date=July 17, 2018 | access-date=October 11, 2018 |last=Gannon|first=Devin}}</ref><ref name=\"cny 20150610\">{{cite web | url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2015/06/10/hudson_yards_construction_rolls_on_as_retail_center_rises.php | title=Hudson Yards Construction Rolls On As Retail Center Rises | work=Curbed NY | date=June 10, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Jessica Dailey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/4/4/17115600/hudson-yards-construction-timeline-building-status-nyc|title=Tracking the biggest buildings taking shape at Hudson Yards|last=Walker|first=Ameena|date=April 4, 2018|website=Curbed NY|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe building opened on March 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2019/1/2/18161731/nyc-real-estate-architecture-predictions-2019|title=6 crucial ways New York City's landscape will change in 2019|last=Rosenberg|first=Zoe|date=January 2, 2019|website=Curbed NY|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/hudson-yards-rundown-major-buildings-finished-2018-10|title=Hudson Yards is the biggest New York development since Rockefeller Center. Here are all the major buildings in the $25 billion neighborhood.|last=Bendix|first=Aria|date=October 7, 2018|website=Business Insider|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> One month later, WarnerMedia executed a [[leaseback]] and sold their space to Related and [[Allianz]] for $2.2 billion after signing a 15-year lease for {{convert|1,500,000|sqft|m2}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/04/allianz-teaming-up-with-related-in-its-2-2b-acquisition-of-30-hudson-yards/|title=Allianz Teaming Up With Related in Its $2.2B Acquisition of 30 Hudson Yards|date=April 24, 2019|last=Gourarie|first=Chava}}</ref> The partners financed the purchase with a 10-year, $1.43 billion [[commercial mortgage-backed security]] [[interest-only loan]] from [[Deutsche Bank]], Wells Fargo, and [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref name=\"refi\">{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/06/30-hudson-yards-allianz/|title=Related, Allianz Office Deal at 30 Hudson Yards Funded with $1.43B Mortgage|last=Grossman|first=Matt|work=Commercial Observer|date=June 20, 2019|access-date=June 21, 2019}}</ref> In June, KKR took out a $490 million mortgage from [[Deutsche Bank]] on their office condominium space.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2019/06/kkr-30-hudson-yards/|title=KKR Seals $490M Financing for Commercial Condo at 30 Hudson Yards|last=Grossman|first=Matt|work=Commercial Observer|date=June 7, 2019|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tenants==\n* Lobby: [[WarnerMedia]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[The Shops & Restaurants at Hudson Yards]] (retail), [[Jack's Stir Brew Coffee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/press-releases/hudson-yards-announces-fast-casual-additions-to-dining-collection/|title=HUDSON YARDS ANNOUNCES FAST-CASUAL ADDITIONS TO DINING COLLECTION|date=December 4, 2018|publisher=Related Companies}}</ref>\n* Floors 1\u201315: [[Wells Fargo Securities]]\n* Floors 16\u201351: [[WarnerMedia]]\n* Floor 25: ([[mechanical floor]])\n* Floor 35: ([[sky lobby]])\n* Floor 52: (mechanical floor)\n* Floors 60\u201366: [[Wells Fargo Securities]]\n* Floor 67: [[Oxford Properties]] \n* Floors 68-71: [[Facebook]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://therealdeal.com/2019/11/26/heres-how-much-facebook-is-paying-at-hudson-yards/|title=Here's how much Facebook is paying at Hudson Yards|last=Sun|first=Kevin|date=November 26, 2019|work=The Real Deal}}</ref>\n* Floors 72\u201373: [[The Related Companies]] \n* Floors 74\u201383: [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]]\n* Floor 79: (mechanical floor)\n* Floors 99\u2013100: (observation deck)\n* Floor 101: (event space)\n\n==Studios==\n*17N: ''[[CNN Newsroom]]'', ''[[Early Start]]'', ''[[Reliable Sources]]''\n*19X: multi purposed studio\n*19Y: ''[[CNN Newsroom|At This Hour]]'', ''[[Cuomo Prime Time]]'', ''[[New Day (TV program)|New Day]]'', ''[[Quest Means Business]]''\n*19Z: ''[[CNN Tonight]]'', ''[[Erin Burnett OutFront]]'', ''[[Fareed Zakaria GPS]]''\n*21L: ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscaststudio.com/tag/hudson-yards/|title=30 Hudson Yards|date=August 3, 2019|publisher=NewscastStudio}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and design==\n[[Kohn Pedersen Fox]] was chosen for the design of the building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/office/30-hudson-yards |title=30 Hudson Yards Floor Plans &#124; Hudson Yards |publisher=Hudsonyardsnewyork.com |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215147/http://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/office/30-hudson-yards |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Originally planned to be {{convert|1337|ft|m}} tall,<ref>Fedak, Nikolai (November 25, 2013). [http://newyorkyimby.com/2013/11/relateds-hudson-yards-towers-re-named.html \"Related's Hudson Yards Towers Re-Named\"]. New York Yimby.</ref> the building was later downsized to {{convert|1268|ft|m}} tall,<ref>{{cite web|author=CTBUH |url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/new-york-city/30-hudson-yards/13325/ |title=30 Hudson Yards Facts &#124; CTBUH Skyscraper Database |location=40.75402 -74.00083 |publisher=Skyscrapercenter.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> making it still the development's tallest building.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-19/new-york-s-hudson-yards-starts-next-phase-as-deck-begins.html | title=New York's Hudson Yards Starts Next Phase as Deck Begins | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=March 19, 2014 | accessdate=August 28, 2014 | author=David M. Levitt}}</ref> WarnerMedia's space features amenities including a cafeteria, a fitness center, a two-level auditorium and cinema and an outdoor deck.<ref name=\"refi\" />\n\nThe building features a {{convert|80|ft|0|adj=on}} observation deck that juts into the air.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hudson Yards Set to Alter Skyline, Transform Neighborhood|url=http://chelseanow.com/2013/02/hudson-yards-set-to-alter-skyline-transform-neighborhood/|website=Chelsea Now|accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref> The building's lobby will contain artwork by Spanish artist [[Jaume Plensa]] consisting of 11 stainless steel spheres hanging from the ceiling, meant to represent global unity and cultural diversity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Related And Oxford Unveil Commissioned Art Installations At Hudson Yards|work=New York Yimby|date=January 31, 2019|last=Morris|first=Sebastian|url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2019/01/related-and-oxford-unveil-commissioned-art-installations-at-hudson-yards.html}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\n30 Hudson Yards March 2017.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction in March 2017\nHudson Yards May 2017 47.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction on the left with the completed [[10 Hudson Yards]] on the right in May 2017\nHudson Yards Apr 2018 04.jpg|30 Hudson Yards under construction in April 2018\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in New York City]]\n* [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|30 Hudson Yards}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.hudsonyardsnewyork.com/work/30-hudson-yards}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150218025817/http://www.hydc.org/html/home/home.shtml New York City project website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120718082011/http://www.related.com/destinations/hudsonyards/ Related Companies project website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130624075515/http://gothamist.com/2013/01/15/awesome_infrastructure_video_buildi.php#photo-1 Animation: building the platform while trains run through] Brookfield properties, via Gothamist.com\n* [http://therealdeal.com/blog/tag/hudson-yards/ Hudson Yards news and developments]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Hudson Yards}}\n{{Supertall skyscrapers |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Hudson Yards, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Kohn Pedersen Fox buildings]]\n[[Category:Oxford Properties]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 2019]]\n[[Category:Buildings developed by the Related Companies]]\n[[Category:Media company headquarters in the United States]]\n[[Category:WarnerMedia]]\n[[Category:Wells Fargo buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: a {{convert|8 \u2192  an {{convert|8", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/30_Hudson_Yards"}
{"title_page": "Harvard College social clubs", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n{{original research|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n\n[[Harvard College]] has several types of social clubs. These are split between gender-inclusive clubs recognized by the College, and unrecognized single-gender clubs which are subject to College sanctions. The oldest, dating to 1791, are the traditionally all-male final clubs. Fraternities were prominent in the late 19th century as well, until their initial expulsions and then eventual resurrection off Harvard's campus in the 1990s. From 1991 onwards, all-female final clubs as well as sororities began to appear. Between 1984 and 2018, no social organizations were recognized by the school due to the clubs' refusal to become gender-inclusive. \n\nBeginning with the [[Spee Club]] in 2015, a number of formerly single-gender organizations began to admit new members regardless of gender.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/11/4/spee-elects-coed-class/ |title = Spee Club Elects First Class of Men and Women &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> In 2016, Harvard announced sanctions on members of remaining single-gender clubs, aiming to push them to become coed.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/12/6/sanctions-explainer-v2/ |title = Harvard's Sanctions, Explained (Again) &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> Eventually, on September 8, 2018, Harvard announced that it would recognize an initial list of fifteen social organizations that either already were gender-inclusive or had committed to becoming gender-inclusive.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/9/8/15-groups-recognized/ |title = Fox, Delphic-Bee Clubs Among 15 Social Groups to Promise Co-Ed Status, Escaping Sanctions &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> Eleven clubs remain single-gender, and remain unrecognized by the College. \n\n== Origins ==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nThe historical basis for the name \"final clubs\" dates to the late 19th century, a time when Harvard had a variety of clubs for students of each class year.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} During that period, Harvard College freshmen could join a freshman club, then a \"waiting club,\" and eventually, as they neared completion of their studies, a \"final club.\"{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Hence, students of different years joined different clubs, and the \"final clubs\" were so named because they were the last social club a person could join before graduation.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Harvard's final clubs for women date to 1991 with the founding of the Bee Club.<ref name=CrimsonFeltonWhartonRetrosp>{{cite journal | authors = Felton, Lena K. & Wharton, Molly E. | date = October 10, 2013 | title=Female Final Clubs: A Retrospection | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2013/10/10/female-final-clubs-a-retrospection/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Francis | first=A.M. | title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America | publisher=LULU Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-312-93285-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA8 | accessdate=June 2, 2016 | page=8}}</ref>\n\nMany of the clubs were founded in the 19th century, after Harvard banned traditional fraternities in the 1850s.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Of the final clubs still in existence (see below), only the Fox was initially founded as a final club. The Phoenix SK is the amalgam of three separate clubs: the Phoenix, the Sphinx, and the Kalumet.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==The clubs==\n<!--PER WP:VERIFY, WIKILINKS ARE NOT ACCEPTABLE AS CITATIONS. EACH ENTRY MUST BE SOURCED, FROM ONE BROAD, OR SEVERAL SOURCES. IF EACH ENTRY ON THE LIST DOES NOT APPEAR IN THE GENERAL SOURCE APPEARING AT THE OPENING, IT MUST HAVE A SOURCE, INLINE AT THE BULLET.-->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}} \nRecognized coed clubs:<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://osl.fas.harvard.edu/policy |title = Recognized Social Organizations at Harvard College}}</ref>\n*[[Spee Club]] (1852)\n*[[Delphic Club]] and Bee Club Merged Group\n*Oak Club (1999)\n*Sab Club (2002)\n*The FDL (formerly [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]])\n*Pleiades Society (2002)\n*La Vie Club (2008)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lavieclub.org/what-we-do/ | title=What We do}}</ref>\n*The Aleph (formerly [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]])\n*K.S. Club (formerly [[Kappa Sigma]]) (1905)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/9/3/kappa-sigma-coed/ |title = Kappa Sigma to Become Gender Neutral &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*The Kal\u00ed Prax\u00ed (formerly [[Delta Gamma]])<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/8/7/delta-gamma-launches-new-club/ |title = Ex-Members of Shuttered Sorority Delta Gamma Launch Co-Ed Club 'Kali Praxi' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*The Ivy (formerly [[Alpha Phi]])\n*The TA (formerly [[Kappa Alpha Theta]])<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://crimson-theta.org/welcome | title=Home}}</ref>\n*IC Club (2000)<ref>https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2001/10/9/isis-debuts-as-womens-club-as/&sa=U&ved=0ahUKEwjMmaHGrIbdAhVPMd8KHdKtBy8QFggOMAM&client=internal-uds-cse&cx=018182123538720087896:jxrddb2lgiy&usg=AOvVaw0cT57qXvcPFG08cPYY_YLx</ref>\n\n{{col-3}}\nUnrecognized all-male clubs:<ref name=CrimsonMcauleyMensFCs>{{cite journal | authors = Mcauley, James K. | date = October 5, 2010 | title=The Men's Final Clubs | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/series/the-punch/article/2010/10/5/series-men-final-clubs/?page=single|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227005519/http://www.thecrimson.com/series/the-punch/article/2010/10/5/series-men-final-clubs/?page=single | archive-date = December 27, 2014  | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online blog  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> <ref name=CrimsonThorne>{{cite journal | authors = Thorne, Gabriela | date = July 16, 2015 | title=#tbt to Going Greek | url = https://college.harvard.edu/admissions/hear-our-students/student-blog/tbt-going-greek | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online blog  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kappasigma.org/kappa-sigma-returns-to-harvard/|title=Kappa Sigma Returns to Harvard - Kappa Sigma Fraternity|date=February 12, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crimsonsae.com/index.php|title=Sigma Alpha Epsilon \u2014 Mass Gamma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2001/2/23/rush-hour-greek-groups-get-popular/?page=1|title=Rush Hour: Greek Groups Get Popular - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harvarddke.org|title=Delta Kappa Epsilon Alpha|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harvardsigmachi.com/=Kappa Eta Sigma Chi|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[A.D. Club]] (1836)\n*[[Fly Club]] (1836)\n*[[Owl Club (Harvard)|Owl Club]] (1896)\n*[[Phoenix S.K. Club]] (1895)\n*[[Porcellian Club]] (1791)\n*[[Fox Club]] (1898)\n*[[Sigma Chi]] (1992)\n*[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (1893)\n\n{{col-3}}\n\nUnrecognized all-female clubs:\n*Exister Society, \"The X\" (2017)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/4/20/new-final-club-x/ |title = Students Form All-Female Final Club the 'X' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*Alpha Phi (2013)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/4/alpha-phi-back-lawsuit/ |title = Alpha Phi Returns to Campus, Joins Lawsuit Opposing Sanctions &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://cambridgealphaphi.com/about-us/ |title = About Us}}</ref>\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==History==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nThe Harvard men's final clubs trace their roots to the late 18th century, while the five formerly all-female social clubs were founded more recently.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Another women's organization, the Seneca, distinguishes itself as a \"[[501(c)#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] nonprofit women's organization that is often misidentified as a final club.\"{{cite quote|date=May 2016}} Several other clubs are also 501(c)(3) organizations and engage in some community service.  The Bee was founded in 1991,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} IC in 2000,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Pleiades in 2002,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Sab in 2002,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} and La Vie in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Commonwealth Of Massachusetts Staff |year=2008 |title=La Vie Club Incorporated Summary Screen |url=http://www.corp.sec.state.ma.us/corp/CorpSearch/CorpSearchSummary.asp?ReadFromDB=True&UpdateAllowed=&FEIN=000991056 |location=Boston, MA |publisher=The Commonwealth Of Massachusetts, William Francis Galvin, Secretary Of The Commonwealth, Corporations Division |format=government database entry |access-date=May 11, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604000459/http://www.corp.sec.state.ma.us/corp/CorpSearch/CorpSearchSummary.asp?ReadFromDB=True&UpdateAllowed=&FEIN=000991056 |archivedate=June 4, 2016 }}{{better source|date=May 2016}}</ref> (The co-ed [[Signet Society]], ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', ''[[The Harvard Advocate]]'', ''[[Hasty Pudding Theatricals]]'', and ''[[The Harvard Lampoon]]'' also have selective membership, but their charters define them as something other than social organizations, based on their literary or artistic characteristics.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}})\n\nNine of the traditionally all-male clubs own real estate in [[Harvard Square]], with the clubhouses usually including dining areas, libraries, and game rooms.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Most are staffed with chefs, stewards, and other paid personnel, and serve lunch and dinner meals at regular schedules.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The Delphic & Bee house boasts a regulation-size [[squash court]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Beam, Alex |date=May 20, 2009 |title=Harvard's Vanishing Squash Courts |journal=Vanity Fair |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2009/05/harvards-vanishing-squash-courts.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Fly Club owns additional property at 45 Dunster Street, in a building that is currently home to the [[Hasty Pudding Club]] and was previously home to the D.U. Club (the \"Duck\") and then the Bee Club (before the latter began the process of merging with the Delphic).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/9/19/hasty-pudding-clubhouse/ | title=Hasty Pudding Institute Moves into Former Bee Clubhouse &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>  The D.U. Club closed, in 1995, after an assault of a football recruit occurred at its clubhouse.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jonathan A. Lewin |date=March 18, 1995 |title=Final Club Closed After Recruit Is Beaten In Fight |journal=The Harvard Crimson |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1995/3/18/final-club-closed-after-recruit-is/}}</ref> The D.U. Club's graduate membership merged with the Fly in 1996. In a controversial move, the Fly did not allow former D.U. undergraduate members to integrate,<ref name=CrimsonGranade>{{cite journal |authors=Granade, Matthew W. |date=February 12, 1996 |title=D.U., Fly Clubs Agree to Merge |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1996/2/12/du-fly-clubs-agree-to-merge/ |journal=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |format=online article |access-date=May 11, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> and subsequently the undergraduate D.U. membership formed The [[Oak Club]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.theoakclub.org/history|publisher=The Oak Club|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> La Vie Club rents a [[colonial style]] house on Garden Street.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} <ref name=\"CHC\">{{cite web|author=CHC Staff |date=2009 |title=City of Cambridge, Landmarks and Other Protected Properties |url=http://www.cambridgema.gov/historic/landmark_11X17.pdf |access-date=May 11, 2016 |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Cambridge Historical Commission |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806144925/http://www2.cambridgema.gov/historic/landmark_11X17.pdf |archivedate=August 6, 2012}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Sanctions==\nIn the fall of 2015, Harvard President Drew Faust criticized the clubs for\u2014as stated by C. Ramsey Fahs of ''The Harvard Crimson''\u2014their \"gender exclusivity and the potential for alcohol abuse and sexual assault on the off-campus properties.\"<!--PHRASE ADDED BECAUSE AS APPEARING, IT OTHERWISE ALLEGES TO BE A QUOTE OF THE PRESIDENT (WHICH IT IS NOT).--><ref name=CrimsonFahs29Jan16>{{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = January 29, 2016 | title=Divided Fox Club Opens With New Policies | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/1/29/fox-reopens-new-rules/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> The [[Spee Club]] began admitting women in later 2015,<ref name=CrimsonDelwiche>{{cite journal | authors = Delwiche, Noah J. | date = September 11, 2015 | title=In Historic Move, Spee Club Invites Women To Punch: As final clubs face pressure, one male club moves to go co-ed | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/9/11/spee-club-punch-women/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> and the [[Fox Club]] followed suit but was then temporarily shut down as graduate board members sought to re-evaluate what it meant to be a \"member of the Fox\".{{cite quote|date=May 2016}}\n\nAs part of an effort to marginalize organizations that \"contribute to a social life and a student culture that for many on our campus is disempowering and exclusionary\", a new policy provides<ref name=policy>{{cite web | author = Khurana, Rakesh | date = May 6, 2016 | title = Untitled letter addressed \"Dear President Faust\" [Opening \"I write today to convey the College's recommendations for addressing the problems created for our community by the discriminatory membership policies of undergraduate unrecognized single-gender social organizations, including Final Clubs\".] | format = PDF, letter on stationery, from college.harvard.edu | pages = 1\u20134, esp. 1 | url=http://college.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/presidentfaust5.6.16__0.pdf | access-date = May 11, 2016 | quote = [Quoting, end of paragraph 2, p. 1:] At a time when Harvard is preparing citizens and citizen-leaders to bring people together and embrace an increasingly diverse and interconnected world, these organizations contribute to a social life and a student culture that for many on our campus is disempowering and exclusionary.}}</ref> that students entering in the fall of 2017 or later who join unrecognized single-sex organizations (such as single-sex [[final clubs]], fraternities, and sororities) will be barred from campus leadership positions such as team captaincies, and from receiving recommendation letters from Harvard requisite for scholarships and fellowships.<ref name=NYT2016>{{cite journal | author = Saul, Stephanie | date = May 7, 2016 | title = Harvard Restrictions Could Reshape Exclusive Student Clubs | journal = [[The New York Times]] | url =  https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/07/us/harvard-restrictions-could-reshape-exclusive-student-clubs.html?_r=0 | access-date =  | quote = }} Note: Date of print appearance may have been May 6, 2016.</ref>\nAt least one club has protested that the new rule infringes students' [[Freedom of association#United States Constitution|right of free association]],<ref name=NYT2016 /> and enforcement may be stymied by the difficulty of establishing who the members of each club are.<ref name=CrimsonFahs6May16>{{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = May 6, 2016 | title=A Guide to Harvard's Relationship with Final Clubs: The Crimson gives a quick primer on the final clubs, institutions unique to Harvard, and the administration's actions toward them over this tumultuous year. | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/5/6/final-clubs-explained/      | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> In 2016, the President and Vice President of the Undergraduate Council, Shaiba Rather and Daniel Banks spoke before the elected Faculty Council and the Faculty of Arts and Sciences of Harvard University to support the effort to curb gender-discrimination amongst student organizations. Their statement was the first official opinion of any elected members of the student body on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/11/2/UC-leaders-faculty-meeting/|title=UC Leaders Support Social Organization Sanctions at Faculty Meeting - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref> As administrative officials endeavored to implement and rewrite the sanctions, Rather and Banks were drafted as hardliners against any gender discrimination between Final Clubs and the Harvard student body.<ref>http://osl.fas.harvard.edu/files/osl/files/implementationcommitteefinalreport.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2016/11/social-club-sanctions-debated |title = Harvard Faculty Debate Final Club Sanctions|date = November 2, 2016}}</ref> However, in November 2016, a slight majority of undergraduate student voters  on a referendum question were in favor of repealing the sanctions (59.8%), while 30.3% were against repealing the sanctions and 9.8% abstained from voting. The vote had no immediate effect on the policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/11/22/referendum-reveal-student-opposition-college-sanctions/|title=Majority of Student Voters Oppose College Sanctions in UC Ballot - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn December 2017, the University's highest governing body, the Harvard Corporation, voted to approve the sanctions and confirm their permanence. Currently, members of the class of 2021 and beyond who are members of unrecognized (single-gender) social organizations are barred from \"holding leadership positions in recognized student organizations, becoming varsity captains, or receiving College endorsement for prestigious fellowships,\" according to the [[Harvard Crimson]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/12/6/sanctions-explainer-v2/ |title = Harvard's Sanctions, Explained (Again) &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> The University has faced questions about how it will enforce its sanctions policy, and the enforcement mechanism remains somewhat unclear. As the class of 2021 had its first opportunity to join single-gender organizations in fall of 2018 (and as members of that class will begin to seek on-campus leadership positions as juniors in 2019), it is expected that Harvard will face its first real test in enforcing the sanctions in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/5/editorial-stand-up-for-sanctions/ | title=Stand up for the Sanctions, Harvard &#124; Opinion &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the policy, the all-female [[Sabli\u00e8re Society|Sabli\u00e8re]] and [[Seneca Society|Seneca]] societies instituted gender-neutral recruitment policies in 2016. The all-male Oak Club followed suit in January 2017 after reaching a \"club-wide consensus\".<ref name=\"Xiao 2017\">{{cite web | last=Xiao | first=Derek G. | title=All-Male Oak Club to Accept Women | website=The Harvard Crimson | date=January 25, 2017 | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/1/25/oak-club-to-go-coed/ | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Former sorority [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] announced it would form a new gender-inclusive group called the Fleur-de-Lis (FDL) beginning in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/1/8/kappa-gender-neutral/ |title = Kappa Kappa Gamma Now Gender-Neutral Club 'The Fleur-de-Lis' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> \nIn September 2018, Harvard released a public list of organizations it would recognize, certifying their gender-inclusive status or their commitment to achieving gender-inclusive status. In addition to the Sab, Oak, Seneca, and FDL, this initial list included the [[Spee Club]], the [[Fox Club]], the [[Delphic Club]] and Bee Club Merged Group, the Aleph (formerly [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]]), the La Vie Club, The IC Club, the K.S. (formerly [[Kappa Sigma]], the Ivy (formerly [[Alpha Phi]], the Pleaides Society, the Kali Praxi (formerly [[Delta Gamma]]), and the TA (formerly [[Kappa Alpha Theta]]).\n\n==Proposed elimination from campus life==\nIn July 2017, a Harvard committee pointed to [[Bowdoin College]] as a model for eradicating [[final clubs]], [[sororities]], and [[fraternities]] from campus social life. This preliminary recommendation would have taken effect with the incoming class of 2021, so all currently enrolled students would be exempt. The transition period would have extended into May 2022 before all such organizations and social clubs would be abolished.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/07/30/harvard-looks-bowdoin-model-eradicating-frats-but-its-decision-had-mixed-results/1YSwSjkmUg6dPs2gxr860M/story.html |title=Harvard looks to Bowdoin as model in eradicating frats, but its decision had mixed results |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Grinberg |first=Emanuella |last2=Kaufman |first2=Ellie |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/14/us/harvard-fraternities-ban-trnd/index.html |title=Harvard mulls phasing out frats, sororities, final clubs |work=[[CNN]] |date=July 14, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 }}</ref> <br>\nAfter the committee released its 22-page report, ''The Harvard Crimson'' reported that the committee, co-chaired by Danoff Dean of the College Rakesh Khurana, had not been transparent in its deliberations or conclusions. Members of the committee, speaking anonymously, described \"a process ... marked by confusion, disagreement, and opacity, resulting in a report that did not necessarily capture the full committee's views.\" (Hannah Natanson & Derek G. Xiao.\"Seven Votes: How a Harvard Committee Came to Recommend a Social Group Ban\". ''The Harvard Crimson''. July 22, 2017.) Moreover, according to ''The Crimson'', the report misrepresented the conclusions of the committee:\n\n{{quote|According to documents reviewed by ''The Crimson'', the decision to outlaw membership in social groups at Harvard\u2014some over two centuries old\u2014received only seven votes from the 27-person committee.\n\nBy contrast, two other options\u2014one suggesting a new committee to oversee the social groups, another proposing a ban of all organizations that discriminate on the basis of sex, race, or socioeconomic status\u2014gained 12 and 11 votes, respectively. Not every member of the committee was present at the vote.\n\nThe committee never conducted another vote after May 12. At the body's last meeting 14 days later, the decision to ban membership in the groups had become a fait accompli: Committee members spent most of the meeting debating the finer points of the proposed social group prohibition, according to two members of the committee. No student members were in attendance.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Natanson |first1=Hannah |last2=Xiao |first2=Derek G. |title=Seven Votes How a Harvard Committee Came to Recommend a Social Group Ban |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/7/22/inside-social-ban-committee/ |website=The Crimson |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |language=en |date=July 22, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n==Controversy ==\nHarvard severed ties with final clubs in 1984 because of their refusal to admit women.<ref name=\"NYT2016\" />\n\nDuring the 2006 Senate hearings on the nomination of [[Samuel Alito]] to the United States Supreme Court, Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] was among those highlighting Alito's membership in [[Concerned Alumni of Princeton]], which had opposed admission of women into Princeton; when Kennedy's membership in the Owl Club was pointed out, Kennedy resigned from the club.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hemel|first1=Daniel J.|title=Kennedy Severs Final Club Ties|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/1/18/kennedy-severs-final-club-ties-a/|publisher=The Harvard Crimson|accessdate=April 27, 2017|date=January 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Massachusetts gubernatorial candidate [[Deval Patrick]]'s membership in the [[Fly Club]] was criticized as contradictory to his image as a champion of [[civil rights]]; Patrick responded that he had left the club in the early 1980s for that reason.<ref name=Boston.comPhillips>{{cite journal | author = Phillips, Frank | date = August 3, 2006 | title=Patrick says he quit The Fly Club in 1983: Nine exclusive clubs at Harvard limit membership to men. A gubernatorial candidate's link to one renews debate on elitism. | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/politics/candidates/articles/2006/08/03/patrick_says_he_quit_the_fly_club_in_1983/ | archiveurl=http://archive.boston.com/news/local/politics/candidates/articles/2006/08/03/patrick_says_he_quit_the_fly_club_in_1983/ | archive-date = August 3, 2006  | journal = [[The Boston Globe]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  | ref = Archive date unknown. Internal publication archive.  }}{{subscription required}}</ref><sup>[''Subscription required'']</sup>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nIn December 2018 separate suits were filed in federal and Massachusetts courts by national fraternities and sororities which alleged that Harvard's policies against single-sex clubs were discriminatory.{{refn|https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/harvard-sued-fraternities-sororities-over-single-sex-rule-n942961}} The lawsuits are expected to play out over the course of several years.<ref>https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/14/sanctions-lawsuit-what-to-expect/</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* ''[[The Social Network]]'' featured both [[The Phoenix \u2013 S K Club]] and the [[Porcellian Club]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qz.com/678017/harvard-is-dealing-a-huge-blow-to-its-secretive-male-only-student-clubs/|title=Harvard is dealing a huge blow to its secretive, male-only student clubs|first=Amy X.|last=Wang|publisher=}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Accidental Billionaires]]'' by [[Ben Mezrich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/flyby/article/2010/7/27/sorkin-zuckerberg-final-facebook/|title=Making a Movie? The Final Clubs Welcome You. - Flyby - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Collegiate secret societies in North America]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = May 6, 2016 | title=A Guide to Harvard's Relationship with Final Clubs: The Crimson gives a quick primer on the final clubs, institutions unique to Harvard, and the administration's actions toward them over this tumultuous year. | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/5/6/final-clubs-explained/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Harrington, Rebecca M. | date = March 2, 2006 | title=How the Final Clubbers Fool You\u2014The Trend is Nigh | url = http://www.thecrimson.harvard.edu/article/2006/3/2/how-the-final-clubbers-fool-you/  | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online arts article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Hernandez, Javier C. | date = January 17, 2006 | title=Kennedy Ends His Final Club Ties: Senator withdraws from Owl Club after conservatives criticized his membership | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/1/17/kennedy-ends-his-final-club-ties/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  |display-authors=etal}}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Hemel, Daniel J. | date = October 24, 2005 | title=E-mails Offer Glimpse of Club: Isis e-mail archives reveal details of 'punch' process, relationship with Bee Club | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=509327 | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Sachs, Stephen E. | date = October 23, 2001 | title=What's Wrong With Final Clubs: The Public Interest | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=121825 | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online opinion piece  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Final Club}}\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n{{original research|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n\n[[Harvard College]] has several types of social clubs. These are split between gender-inclusive clubs recognized by the College, and unrecognized single-gender clubs which are subject to College sanctions. The oldest, dating to 1791, are the traditionally all-male final clubs. Fraternities were prominent in the late 19th century as well, until their initial expulsions and then eventual resurrection off Harvard's campus in the 1990s. From 1991 onwards, all-female final clubs as well as sororities began to appear. Between 1984 and 2018, no social organizations were recognized by the school due to the clubs' refusal to become gender-inclusive. \n\nBeginning with the [[Spee Club]] in 2015, a number of formerly single-gender organizations began to admit new members regardless of gender.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/11/4/spee-elects-coed-class/ |title = Spee Club Elects First Class of Men and Women &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> In 2016, Harvard announced sanctions on members of remaining single-gender clubs, aiming to push them to become coed.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/12/6/sanctions-explainer-v2/ |title = Harvard's Sanctions, Explained (Again) &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> Eventually, on September 8, 2018, Harvard announced that it would recognize an initial list of fifteen social organizations that either already were gender-inclusive or had committed to becoming gender-inclusive.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/9/8/15-groups-recognized/ |title = Fox, Delphic-Bee Clubs Among 15 Social Groups to Promise Co-Ed Status, Escaping Sanctions &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> Eleven clubs remain single-gender, and remain unrecognized by the College. \n\n== Origins ==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nThe historical basis for the name \"final clubs\" dates to the late 19th century, a time when Harvard had a variety of clubs for students of each class year.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} During that period, Harvard College freshmen could join a freshman club, then a \"waiting club,\" and eventually, as they neared completion of their studies, a \"final club.\"{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Hence, students of different years joined different clubs, and the \"final clubs\" were so named because they were the last social club a person could join before graduation.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Harvard's final clubs for women date to 1991 with the founding of the Bee Club.<ref name=CrimsonFeltonWhartonRetrosp>{{cite journal | authors = Felton, Lena K. & Wharton, Molly E. | date = October 10, 2013 | title=Female Final Clubs: A Retrospection | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2013/10/10/female-final-clubs-a-retrospection/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Francis | first=A.M. | title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America | publisher=LULU Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-312-93285-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA8 | accessdate=June 2, 2016 | page=8}}</ref>\n\nMany of the clubs were founded in the 19th century, after Harvard banned traditional fraternities in the 1850s.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Of the final clubs still in existence (see below), only the Fox was initially founded as a final club. The Phoenix SK is the amalgam of three separate clubs: the Phoenix, the Sphinx, and the Kalumet.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==The clubs==\n<!--PER WP:VERIFY, WIKILINKS ARE NOT ACCEPTABLE AS CITATIONS. EACH ENTRY MUST BE SOURCED, FROM ONE BROAD, OR SEVERAL SOURCES. IF EACH ENTRY ON THE LIST DOES NOT APPEAR IN THE GENERAL SOURCE APPEARING AT THE OPENING, IT MUST HAVE A SOURCE, INLINE AT THE BULLET.-->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}} \nRecognized coed clubs:<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://osl.fas.harvard.edu/policy |title = Recognized Social Organizations at Harvard College}}</ref>\n*[[Spee Club]] (1852)\n*[[Delphic Club]] and Bee Club Merged Group\n*Oak Club (1999)\n*Sab Club (2002)\n*The FDL (formerly [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]])\n*Pleiades Society (2002)\n*La Vie Club (2008)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lavieclub.org/what-we-do/ | title=What We do}}</ref>\n*The Aleph (formerly [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]])\n*K.S. Club (formerly [[Kappa Sigma]]) (1905)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/9/3/kappa-sigma-coed/ |title = Kappa Sigma to Become Gender Neutral &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*The Kal\u00ed Prax\u00ed (formerly [[Delta Gamma]])<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/8/7/delta-gamma-launches-new-club/ |title = Ex-Members of Shuttered Sorority Delta Gamma Launch Co-Ed Club 'Kali Praxi' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*The Ivy (formerly [[Alpha Phi]])\n*The TA (formerly [[Kappa Alpha Theta]])<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://crimson-theta.org/welcome | title=Home}}</ref>\n*IC Club (2000)<ref>https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2001/10/9/isis-debuts-as-womens-club-as/&sa=U&ved=0ahUKEwjMmaHGrIbdAhVPMd8KHdKtBy8QFggOMAM&client=internal-uds-cse&cx=018182123538720087896:jxrddb2lgiy&usg=AOvVaw0cT57qXvcPFG08cPYY_YLx</ref>\n\n\n{{col-3}}\nUnrecognized all-male clubs:<ref name=CrimsonMcauleyMensFCs>{{cite journal | authors = Mcauley, James K. | date = October 5, 2010 | title=The Men's Final Clubs | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/series/the-punch/article/2010/10/5/series-men-final-clubs/?page=single|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227005519/http://www.thecrimson.com/series/the-punch/article/2010/10/5/series-men-final-clubs/?page=single | archive-date = December 27, 2014  | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online blog  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> <ref name=CrimsonThorne>{{cite journal | authors = Thorne, Gabriela | date = July 16, 2015 | title=#tbt to Going Greek | url = https://college.harvard.edu/admissions/hear-our-students/student-blog/tbt-going-greek | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online blog  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kappasigma.org/kappa-sigma-returns-to-harvard/|title=Kappa Sigma Returns to Harvard - Kappa Sigma Fraternity|date=February 12, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crimsonsae.com/index.php|title=Sigma Alpha Epsilon \u2014 Mass Gamma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2001/2/23/rush-hour-greek-groups-get-popular/?page=1|title=Rush Hour: Greek Groups Get Popular - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harvarddke.org|title=Delta Kappa Epsilon Alpha|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harvardsigmachi.com/=Kappa Eta Sigma Chi|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[A.D. Club]] (1836)\n*[[Fly Club]] (1836)\n*[[Owl Club (Harvard)|Owl Club]] (1896)\n*[[Phoenix S.K. Club]] (1895)\n*[[Porcellian Club]] (1791)\n*[[Fox Club]] (1898)\n*[[Sigma Chi]] (1992)\n*[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (1893)\n\n{{col-3}}\n\nUnrecognized all-female clubs:\n*Exister Society, \"The X\" (2017)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/4/20/new-final-club-x/ |title = Students Form All-Female Final Club the 'X' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n*Alpha Phi (2013)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/4/alpha-phi-back-lawsuit/ |title = Alpha Phi Returns to Campus, Joins Lawsuit Opposing Sanctions &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://cambridgealphaphi.com/about-us/ |title = About Us}}</ref>\n\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==History==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nThe Harvard men's final clubs trace their roots to the late 18th century, while the five formerly all-female social clubs were founded more recently.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Another women's organization, the Seneca, distinguishes itself as a \"[[501(c)#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] nonprofit women's organization that is often misidentified as a final club.\"{{cite quote|date=May 2016}} Several other clubs are also 501(c)(3) organizations and engage in some community service.  The Bee was founded in 1991,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} IC in 2000,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Pleiades in 2002,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Sab in 2002,{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} and La Vie in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Commonwealth Of Massachusetts Staff |year=2008 |title=La Vie Club Incorporated Summary Screen |url=http://www.corp.sec.state.ma.us/corp/CorpSearch/CorpSearchSummary.asp?ReadFromDB=True&UpdateAllowed=&FEIN=000991056 |location=Boston, MA |publisher=The Commonwealth Of Massachusetts, William Francis Galvin, Secretary Of The Commonwealth, Corporations Division |format=government database entry |access-date=May 11, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604000459/http://www.corp.sec.state.ma.us/corp/CorpSearch/CorpSearchSummary.asp?ReadFromDB=True&UpdateAllowed=&FEIN=000991056 |archivedate=June 4, 2016 }}{{better source|date=May 2016}}</ref> (The co-ed [[Signet Society]], ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', ''[[The Harvard Advocate]]'', ''[[Hasty Pudding Theatricals]]'', and ''[[The Harvard Lampoon]]'' also have selective membership, but their charters define them as something other than social organizations, based on their literary or artistic characteristics.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}})\n\nNine of the traditionally all-male clubs own real estate in [[Harvard Square]], with the clubhouses usually including dining areas, libraries, and game rooms.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} Most are staffed with chefs, stewards, and other paid personnel, and serve lunch and dinner meals at regular schedules.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} The Delphic & Bee house boasts a regulation-size [[squash court]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Beam, Alex |date=May 20, 2009 |title=Harvard's Vanishing Squash Courts |journal=Vanity Fair |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2009/05/harvards-vanishing-squash-courts.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Fly Club owns additional property at 45 Dunster Street, in a building that is currently home to the [[Hasty Pudding Club]] and was previously home to the D.U. Club (the \"Duck\") and then the Bee Club (before the latter began the process of merging with the Delphic).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/9/19/hasty-pudding-clubhouse/ | title=Hasty Pudding Institute Moves into Former Bee Clubhouse &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>  The D.U. Club closed, in 1995, after an assault of a football recruit occurred at its clubhouse.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jonathan A. Lewin |date=March 18, 1995 |title=Final Club Closed After Recruit Is Beaten In Fight |journal=The Harvard Crimson |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1995/3/18/final-club-closed-after-recruit-is/}}</ref> The D.U. Club's graduate membership merged with the Fly in 1996. In a controversial move, the Fly did not allow former D.U. undergraduate members to integrate,<ref name=CrimsonGranade>{{cite journal |authors=Granade, Matthew W. |date=February 12, 1996 |title=D.U., Fly Clubs Agree to Merge |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1996/2/12/du-fly-clubs-agree-to-merge/ |journal=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |format=online article |access-date=May 11, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> and subsequently the undergraduate D.U. membership formed The [[Oak Club]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.theoakclub.org/history|publisher=The Oak Club|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> La Vie Club rents a [[colonial style]] house on Garden Street.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} <ref name=\"CHC\">{{cite web|author=CHC Staff |date=2009 |title=City of Cambridge, Landmarks and Other Protected Properties |url=http://www.cambridgema.gov/historic/landmark_11X17.pdf |access-date=May 11, 2016 |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Cambridge Historical Commission |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806144925/http://www2.cambridgema.gov/historic/landmark_11X17.pdf |archivedate=August 6, 2012}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Sanctions==\nIn the fall of 2015, Harvard President Drew Faust criticized the clubs for\u2014as stated by C. Ramsey Fahs of ''The Harvard Crimson''\u2014their \"gender exclusivity and the potential for alcohol abuse and sexual assault on the off-campus properties.\"<!--PHRASE ADDED BECAUSE AS APPEARING, IT OTHERWISE ALLEGES TO BE A QUOTE OF THE PRESIDENT (WHICH IT IS NOT).--><ref name=CrimsonFahs29Jan16>{{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = January 29, 2016 | title=Divided Fox Club Opens With New Policies | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/1/29/fox-reopens-new-rules/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> The [[Spee Club]] began admitting women in later 2015,<ref name=CrimsonDelwiche>{{cite journal | authors = Delwiche, Noah J. | date = September 11, 2015 | title=In Historic Move, Spee Club Invites Women To Punch: As final clubs face pressure, one male club moves to go co-ed | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/9/11/spee-club-punch-women/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> and the [[Fox Club]] followed suit but was then temporarily shut down as graduate board members sought to re-evaluate what it meant to be a \"member of the Fox\".{{cite quote|date=May 2016}}\n\nAs part of an effort to marginalize organizations that \"contribute to a social life and a student culture that for many on our campus is disempowering and exclusionary\", a new policy provides<ref name=policy>{{cite web | author = Khurana, Rakesh | date = May 6, 2016 | title = Untitled letter addressed \"Dear President Faust\" [Opening \"I write today to convey the College's recommendations for addressing the problems created for our community by the discriminatory membership policies of undergraduate unrecognized single-gender social organizations, including Final Clubs\".] | format = PDF, letter on stationery, from college.harvard.edu | pages = 1\u20134, esp. 1 | url=http://college.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/presidentfaust5.6.16__0.pdf | access-date = May 11, 2016 | quote = [Quoting, end of paragraph 2, p. 1:] At a time when Harvard is preparing citizens and citizen-leaders to bring people together and embrace an increasingly diverse and interconnected world, these organizations contribute to a social life and a student culture that for many on our campus is disempowering and exclusionary.}}</ref> that students entering in the fall of 2017 or later who join unrecognized single-sex organizations (such as single-sex [[final clubs]], fraternities, and sororities) will be barred from campus leadership positions such as team captaincies, and from receiving recommendation letters from Harvard requisite for scholarships and fellowships.<ref name=NYT2016>{{cite journal | author = Saul, Stephanie | date = May 7, 2016 | title = Harvard Restrictions Could Reshape Exclusive Student Clubs | journal = [[The New York Times]] | url =  https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/07/us/harvard-restrictions-could-reshape-exclusive-student-clubs.html?_r=0 | access-date =  | quote = }} Note: Date of print appearance may have been May 6, 2016.</ref>\nAt least one club has protested that the new rule infringes students' [[Freedom of association#United States Constitution|right of free association]],<ref name=NYT2016 /> and enforcement may be stymied by the difficulty of establishing who the members of each club are.<ref name=CrimsonFahs6May16>{{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = May 6, 2016 | title=A Guide to Harvard's Relationship with Final Clubs: The Crimson gives a quick primer on the final clubs, institutions unique to Harvard, and the administration's actions toward them over this tumultuous year. | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/5/6/final-clubs-explained/      | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}</ref> In 2016, the President and Vice President of the Undergraduate Council, Shaiba Rather and Daniel Banks spoke before the elected Faculty Council and the Faculty of Arts and Sciences of Harvard University to support the effort to curb gender-discrimination amongst student organizations. Their statement was the first official opinion of any elected members of the student body on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/11/2/UC-leaders-faculty-meeting/|title=UC Leaders Support Social Organization Sanctions at Faculty Meeting - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref> As administrative officials endeavored to implement and rewrite the sanctions, Rather and Banks were drafted as hardliners against any gender discrimination between Final Clubs and the Harvard student body.<ref>http://osl.fas.harvard.edu/files/osl/files/implementationcommitteefinalreport.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2016/11/social-club-sanctions-debated |title = Harvard Faculty Debate Final Club Sanctions|date = November 2, 2016}}</ref> However, in November 2016, a slight majority of undergraduate student voters  on a referendum question were in favor of repealing the sanctions (59.8%), while 30.3% were against repealing the sanctions and 9.8% abstained from voting. The vote had no immediate effect on the policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/11/22/referendum-reveal-student-opposition-college-sanctions/|title=Majority of Student Voters Oppose College Sanctions in UC Ballot - News - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn December 2017, the University's highest governing body, the Harvard Corporation, voted to approve the sanctions and confirm their permanence. Currently, members of the class of 2021 and beyond who are members of unrecognized (single-gender) social organizations are barred from \"holding leadership positions in recognized student organizations, becoming varsity captains, or receiving College endorsement for prestigious fellowships,\" according to the [[Harvard Crimson]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/12/6/sanctions-explainer-v2/ |title = Harvard's Sanctions, Explained (Again) &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> The University has faced questions about how it will enforce its sanctions policy, and the enforcement mechanism remains somewhat unclear. As the class of 2021 had its first opportunity to join single-gender organizations in fall of 2018 (and as members of that class will begin to seek on-campus leadership positions as juniors in 2019), it is expected that Harvard will face its first real test in enforcing the sanctions in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/5/editorial-stand-up-for-sanctions/ | title=Stand up for the Sanctions, Harvard &#124; Opinion &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the policy, the all-female [[Sabli\u00e8re Society|Sabli\u00e8re]] and [[Seneca Society|Seneca]] societies instituted gender-neutral recruitment policies in 2016. The all-male Oak Club followed suit in January 2017 after reaching a \"club-wide consensus\".<ref name=\"Xiao 2017\">{{cite web | last=Xiao | first=Derek G. | title=All-Male Oak Club to Accept Women | website=The Harvard Crimson | date=January 25, 2017 | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/1/25/oak-club-to-go-coed/ | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Former sorority [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] announced it would form a new gender-inclusive group called the Fleur-de-Lis (FDL) beginning in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/1/8/kappa-gender-neutral/ |title = Kappa Kappa Gamma Now Gender-Neutral Club 'The Fleur-de-Lis' &#124; News &#124; the Harvard Crimson}}</ref> \nIn September 2018, Harvard released a public list of organizations it would recognize, certifying their gender-inclusive status or their commitment to achieving gender-inclusive status. In addition to the Sab, Oak, Seneca, and FDL, this initial list included the [[Spee Club]], the [[Fox Club]], the [[Delphic Club]] and Bee Club Merged Group, the Aleph (formerly [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]]), the La Vie Club, The IC Club, the K.S. (formerly [[Kappa Sigma]], the Ivy (formerly [[Alpha Phi]], the Pleaides Society, the Kali Praxi (formerly [[Delta Gamma]]), and the TA (formerly [[Kappa Alpha Theta]]).\n\n==Proposed elimination from campus life==\nIn July 2017, a Harvard committee pointed to [[Bowdoin College]] as a model for eradicating [[final clubs]], [[sororities]], and [[fraternities]] from campus social life. This preliminary recommendation would have taken effect with the incoming class of 2021, so all currently enrolled students would be exempt. The transition period would have extended into May 2022 before all such organizations and social clubs would be abolished.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krantz |first=Laura |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/07/30/harvard-looks-bowdoin-model-eradicating-frats-but-its-decision-had-mixed-results/1YSwSjkmUg6dPs2gxr860M/story.html |title=Harvard looks to Bowdoin as model in eradicating frats, but its decision had mixed results |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Grinberg |first=Emanuella |last2=Kaufman |first2=Ellie |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/14/us/harvard-fraternities-ban-trnd/index.html |title=Harvard mulls phasing out frats, sororities, final clubs |work=[[CNN]] |date=July 14, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 }}</ref> <br>\nAfter the committee released its 22-page report, ''The Harvard Crimson'' reported that the committee, co-chaired by Danoff Dean of the College Rakesh Khurana, had not been transparent in its deliberations or conclusions. Members of the committee, speaking anonymously, described \"a process ... marked by confusion, disagreement, and opacity, resulting in a report that did not necessarily capture the full committee's views.\" (Hannah Natanson & Derek G. Xiao.\"Seven Votes: How a Harvard Committee Came to Recommend a Social Group Ban\". ''The Harvard Crimson''. July 22, 2017.) Moreover, according to ''The Crimson'', the report misrepresented the conclusions of the committee:\n\n{{quote|According to documents reviewed by ''The Crimson'', the decision to outlaw membership in social groups at Harvard\u2014some over two centuries old\u2014received only seven votes from the 27-person committee.\n\nBy contrast, two other options\u2014one suggesting a new committee to oversee the social groups, another proposing a ban of all organizations that discriminate on the basis of sex, race, or socioeconomic status\u2014gained 12 and 11 votes, respectively. Not every member of the committee was present at the vote.\n\nThe committee never conducted another vote after May 12. At the body's last meeting 14 days later, the decision to ban membership in the groups had become a fait accompli: Committee members spent most of the meeting debating the finer points of the proposed social group prohibition, according to two members of the committee. No student members were in attendance.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Natanson |first1=Hannah |last2=Xiao |first2=Derek G. |title=Seven Votes How a Harvard Committee Came to Recommend a Social Group Ban |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/7/22/inside-social-ban-committee/ |website=The Crimson |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |language=en |date=July 22, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n==Controversy ==\nHarvard severed ties with final clubs in 1984 because of their refusal to admit women.<ref name=\"NYT2016\" />\n\nDuring the 2006 Senate hearings on the nomination of [[Samuel Alito]] to the United States Supreme Court, Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] was among those highlighting Alito's membership in [[Concerned Alumni of Princeton]], which had opposed admission of women into Princeton; when Kennedy's membership in the Owl Club was pointed out, Kennedy resigned from the club.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hemel|first1=Daniel J.|title=Kennedy Severs Final Club Ties|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/1/18/kennedy-severs-final-club-ties-a/|publisher=The Harvard Crimson|accessdate=April 27, 2017|date=January 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Massachusetts gubernatorial candidate [[Deval Patrick]]'s membership in the [[Fly Club]] was criticized as contradictory to his image as a champion of [[civil rights]]; Patrick responded that he had left the club in the early 1980s for that reason.<ref name=Boston.comPhillips>{{cite journal | author = Phillips, Frank | date = August 3, 2006 | title=Patrick says he quit The Fly Club in 1983: Nine exclusive clubs at Harvard limit membership to men. A gubernatorial candidate's link to one renews debate on elitism. | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/politics/candidates/articles/2006/08/03/patrick_says_he_quit_the_fly_club_in_1983/ | archiveurl=http://archive.boston.com/news/local/politics/candidates/articles/2006/08/03/patrick_says_he_quit_the_fly_club_in_1983/ | archive-date = August 3, 2006  | journal = [[The Boston Globe]] | format = online article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  | ref = Archive date unknown. Internal publication archive.  }}{{subscription required}}</ref><sup>[''Subscription required'']</sup>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nIn December 2018 separate suits were filed in federal and Massachusetts courts by national fraternities and sororities which alleged that Harvard's policies against single-sex clubs were discriminatory.{{refn|https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/harvard-sued-fraternities-sororities-over-single-sex-rule-n942961}} The lawsuits are expected to play out over the course of several years.<ref>https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2018/12/14/sanctions-lawsuit-what-to-expect/</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* ''[[The Social Network]]'' featured both [[The Phoenix \u2013 S K Club]] and the [[Porcellian Club]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qz.com/678017/harvard-is-dealing-a-huge-blow-to-its-secretive-male-only-student-clubs/|title=Harvard is dealing a huge blow to its secretive, male-only student clubs|first=Amy X.|last=Wang|publisher=}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Accidental Billionaires]]'' by [[Ben Mezrich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/flyby/article/2010/7/27/sorkin-zuckerberg-final-facebook/|title=Making a Movie? The Final Clubs Welcome You. - Flyby - The Harvard Crimson|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Collegiate secret societies in North America]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | authors = Fahs, C. Ramsey | date = May 6, 2016 | title=A Guide to Harvard's Relationship with Final Clubs: The Crimson gives a quick primer on the final clubs, institutions unique to Harvard, and the administration's actions toward them over this tumultuous year. | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2016/5/6/final-clubs-explained/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Harrington, Rebecca M. | date = March 2, 2006 | title=How the Final Clubbers Fool You\u2014The Trend is Nigh | url = http://www.thecrimson.harvard.edu/article/2006/3/2/how-the-final-clubbers-fool-you/  | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online arts article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Hernandez, Javier C. | date = January 17, 2006 | title=Kennedy Ends His Final Club Ties: Senator withdraws from Owl Club after conservatives criticized his membership | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/1/17/kennedy-ends-his-final-club-ties/ | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  |display-authors=etal}}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Hemel, Daniel J. | date = October 24, 2005 | title=E-mails Offer Glimpse of Club: Isis e-mail archives reveal details of 'punch' process, relationship with Bee Club | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=509327 | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online news article  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n* {{cite journal | authors = Sachs, Stephen E. | date = October 23, 2001 | title=What's Wrong With Final Clubs: The Public Interest | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=121825 | journal = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | format = online opinion piece  | access-date=May 11, 2016 | quote =  }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Final Club}}\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard University]]\n", "name_user": "RedHotPear", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe clubs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard_College_social_clubs"}
{"title_page": "Haitian Vodou", "text_new": "{{mergefrom|Haitian mythology|discuss=Talk:Haitian Vodou#Merge proposal|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Syncretic religion practised chiefly in Haiti and among the Haitian diaspora}}\n{{Haitian Vodou}}\n\n'''Haitian Vodou'''{{sfn|Cosentino|1995a|p=xiii-xiv}}{{sfn|Brown|1991|}}{{sfn|Fandrich|2007|p=775}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0}}, {{IPA-fr|vodu|lang}}, also written as '''Vaudou''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0}};<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1189105 |title= Of Worlds Seen and Unseen: The Educational Character of Haitian Vodou|journal=Comparative Education Review |volume=40 |issue=3 |author=Michel, Claudine |pages=280\u2013294 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press |year=1996 |doi=10.1086/447386 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=41715143 |title= R\u00e9flexion: Vaudou et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 en Ha\u00efti|journal=Journal of Haitian Studies |volume=8 |issue=2 |author=Piquion, Ren\u00e9 |pages=167\u2013176 |publisher=Center for Black Studies Research |year=2002}}</ref> known commonly as '''Voodoo'''<ref name=\"Corbett\">[http://faculty.webster.edu/corbetre/haiti/voodoo/spelling.htm Corbett, Bob, ''The Spelling of Voodoo'', 1998]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/saumya-arya-haas/what-is-vodou_b_827947.html |title=What is Voodoo? Understanding a Misunderstood Religion |editor=Haas, Saumya Arya |date=25 May 2011 |publisher=Huffington Post |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|u\u02d0|d|u\u02d0}}, sometimes as '''Vodun'''{{sfn|Courlander|1988|p=88}}{{sfn|Thompson|1983|p=163\u2013191}} {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0}}, '''Vodoun'''{{sfn|Courlander|1988|p=88}}{{sfn|Cosentino|1995a|p=xiv}} {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0|n}}, '''Vodu'''<ref name=\"Corbett\"/> {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0}}, or '''Vaudoux'''<ref name=\"Corbett\"/> {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|o\u028a|d|u\u02d0}}) is a [[syncretic]]{{sfn|Stevens-Arroyo|2002|p=37-58}} [[religion]] based on [[West African Vodun]], practiced chiefly in [[Haiti]] and the [[Haitian diaspora]]. Practitioners are called \"vodouists\" ([[French language|French]]: ''vodouisants'' {{IPA-fr|voduiz\u0251\u0303|}}) or \"servants of the spirits\" ([[Haitian Creole language|Haitian Creole]]: ''s\u00e8vit\u00e8'').{{sfn|Cosentino|1995b|p=25}}\n\nVodouists believe in a distant and unknowable [[Creator deity|Supreme Creator]], ''Bondye'' (derived from the French ''Bon Dieu'', meaning \"good [[God]]\"). According to Vodouists, Bondye does not intercede in human affairs, and thus they direct their worship toward spirits subservient to Bondye, called [[loa]].{{sfn|Gordon|2000|p=48}} Every loa is responsible for a particular aspect of life, with the dynamic and changing personalities of each loa reflecting the many possibilities inherent to the aspects of life over which they preside.{{sfn|Brown|1991|p=6}} To navigate daily life, vodouists cultivate personal relationships with the loa through the presentation of offerings, the creation of personal altars and devotional objects, and participation in elaborate ceremonies of music, dance, and [[spirit possession]].{{sfn|Brown|1991|p=4\u20137}}\n\nVodou originated in what is now [[Benin]] and developed in the [[French colonial empire]] in the 18th century among West African peoples who were enslaved, when African religious practice was actively suppressed, and enslaved Africans were [[Forced conversion|forced to convert]] to [[Christianity]].{{sfn|Gordon|2000|p=10}}{{sfn|Desmangles|1990|p=475}} Religious practices of contemporary Vodou are descended from, and closely related to, [[West African Vodun]] as practiced by the [[Fon people|Fon]] and [[Ewe people|Ewe]]. Vodou also incorporates elements and symbolism from other African peoples including the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] and [[Kongo people|Kongo]]; as well as [[Ta\u00edno people|Ta\u00edno]] religious beliefs, [[Roman Catholicism]], and European spirituality including [[mysticism]] and other influences.{{sfn|Cosentino|1995b|p=25-55}}\n\nIn Haiti, some Catholics combine aspects of Catholicism with aspects of Vodou, a practice forbidden by the Church and denounced as diabolical by [[Protestantism in Haiti|Haitian Protestants]].<ref>{{Cite book|URL = https://books.google.com/books?id=40SIdXeUEhUC|title = Crossing the Water and Keeping the Faith:Haitian Religion in Miami|last = Rey|first = Terry|last2 = Stepick|first2 = Alex|date = 2013-08-19|publisher = NYU Press|ISBN = 9781479820771|language = en}}</ref>\n\n==Names and etymology==\n''Vodou'' is a [[Haitian Creole language|Haitian Creole]] word that formerly referred to only a small subset of Haitian rituals.{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=205}} The word derives from an [[Ayizo language|Ayizo]] word referring to mysterious forces or powers that govern the world and the lives of those who reside within it, but also a range of artistic forms that function in conjunction with these ''vodun'' energies.{{sfn|Blier|1995|p=61}} Two of the major speaking populations of Ayizo are the [[Ewe people|Ewe]] and the [[Fon people|Fon]]\u2014European slavers called both the Arada. These two peoples composed a sizable number of the early enslaved population in [[St. Dominigue]]. In Haiti, practitioners occasionally use \"Vodou\" to refer to Haitian religion generically, but it is more common for practitioners to refer to themselves as those who \"serve the spirits\" (''s\u00e8vit\u00e8'') by participating in ritual ceremonies, usually called a \"service to the loa\" (''s\u00e8vis lwa'') or an \"African service\" (''s\u00e8vis gine'').{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=205}} These terms also refer to the religion as a whole.\n\nOutside of Haiti, the term ''Vodou'' refers to the entirety of traditional Haitian religious practice.{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=205}} \nOriginally written as ''vodun'', it is first recorded in ''[[Doctrina Christiana]]'', a 1658 document written by the King of [[Allada]]'s ambassador to the court of [[Philip IV of Spain]].{{sfn|Blier|1995|p=61}} In the following centuries, ''Vodou'' was eventually taken up by non-Haitians as a generic descriptive term for traditional Haitian religion.{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=205}} There are many used orthographies for this word. Today, the spelling ''Vodou'' is the most commonly accepted orthography in English.{{sfn|Cosentino|1995a|p=xiv}} Other potential spellings include ''Vodoun'', ''vaudou'', and ''voodoo'', with ''vau-'' or ''vou-'' prefix variants reflecting French orthography, and a final ''-n'' reflecting the nasal vowel in West African or older, non-urbanized, Haitian Creole pronunciations.\n\nThe spelling ''voodoo'', once very common, is now generally avoided by Haitian practitioners and scholars when referring to the Haitian religion.{{sfn|Courlander|1988|p=88}}{{sfn|Lane|1949|p=1162}}{{sfn|Thompson|1983|p=163}}{{sfn|Cosentino|1988|p=77}} This is both to avoid confusion with [[Louisiana Voodoo]],{{sfn|Fandrich|2007|p=780}} a related but distinct set of religious practices, as well as to separate Haitian Vodou from the negative connotations and misconceptions the term \"voodoo\" has acquired in popular culture.{{sfn|Fandrich|2007|p=775}}{{sfn|Hurbon|1995|p=181-197}} Over the years, practitioners and their supporters have called on various institutions including the [[Associated Press]] to redress this misrepresentation by adopting \"Vodou\" in reference to the Haitian religion. In October 2012, the [[Library of Congress]] decided to change their [[subject heading]] from \"Voodooism\" to Vodou in response to a petition by a group of scholars and practitioners in collaboration with [[KOSANBA]], the scholarly association for the study of Haitian Vodou based at University of California Santa Barbara.<ref>For a fuller description of transitions in spelling, see: [http://www.bulldozia.com/projects/index.php?id=583 From Voodoo to Vodou]</ref>\n\n==Beliefs==\n{{Voodoo sidebar| Beliefs}}\n[[File:PortAuPrinceMarche.jpg|right|thumb|Vodou paraphernalia, [[Port-au-Prince]], Haiti.]]\nVodou is popularly described as not simply a religion, but rather an experience that ties body and soul together. The concept of tying that exists in Haitian religious culture is derived from the Congolese tradition of ''kanga'', the practice of tying one's soul to something tangible. This \"tying of soul\" is evident in many Haitian Vodou practices that are still exercised today.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rey|first=Terry|author2=Karen Richman|title=The Somatics of Syncretism: Tying Body and Soul in Haitian Religion|journal=Studies in Religion/Sciences Religieuses|year=2010|volume=39|issue=3|pages=279\u2013403|doi=10.1177/0008429810373321|url=http://sir.sagepub.com/content/41/2/231.full.pdf+html|accessdate=2013-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Spirits===\nVodouisants believe in a Supreme God called Bondye, from the [[French language|French]] (''Bon Dieu'' = Good God).<ref>Haitian Vodouisants believe in Damballah. In her book \"Tell My Horse\", [[Zora Neale Hurston]] writes that \"Damballah is the highest and most powerful of all the gods, but never is he referred to as the father of the gods as was Jupiter, Odin, and great Zeus...whenever any of the gods meet him they bow themselves and sing, \"Ohe', Ohe'! Ce Papa nous qui pe' passe'!\" (It is our papa who passes.)\" (Hurston, pg. 118</ref> When it came in contact with Roman Catholicism, the Supreme Creator was associated with the [[Christianity|Christian]] God, and the ''loa'' associated with the [[saints]].\n\n====Loa====\n[[File:VoodooValris.jpg|right|thumbnail|A large sequined Vodou \"drapo\" or flag by the artist George Valris, depicting the [[veve]], or symbol, of the loa [[Loko Atison]].]]\nSince Bondye (God) is considered unreachable, Vodouisants aim their prayers to lesser entities, the spirits known as [[loa]], or ''mist\u00e8''. The most notable loa include [[Papa Legba]] (guardian of the crossroads), [[Erzulie#Ma\u00eetresse Mambo Erzulie Fr\u00e9da Dahomey|Erzulie Freda]] (the spirit of love), [[Simbi]] (the spirit of rain and magicians), [[Azaka Medeh|Kouzin Zaka]] (the spirit of agriculture), and [[Marassa Jumeaux|The Marasa]], divine twins considered to be the first children of Bondye.{{sfn|Gordon|2000|p=54}}\n\nThese loa can be divided into 21 nations, which include the Petro, Rada, Congo, and Nago.{{sfn|Alvarado|2011}}\n\nEach of the loa is associated with a particular Roman Catholic saint. For example, Legba is associated with [[Anthony the Hermit|St. Anthony the Hermit]], and [[Damballa]] is associated with [[Saint Patrick|St. Patrick]].<ref>Simpson, George (1978). Black Religions in the New World. New York: Columbia University Press. p. 66.</ref>\n\nThe loa also fall into family groups who share a surname, such as [[Ogou]], [[Erzulie|Ezili]], [[Azaka (disambiguation)|Azaka]]<!-- NOTE: This DAB link is intentional, as the page just disambiguates two loa with the same surname: Azaka Medeh (loa of harvest) and Azaka-Tonnerre (loa of thunder). --> \nor [[Ghede]]. For instance, \"Ezili\" is a family, [[Erzulie#Erzulie Dantor|Ezili Danto]] and [[Erzulie#Ma\u00eetresse Mambo Erzulie Fr\u00e9da Dahomey|Ezili Freda]] are two individual spirits in that family. Each family is associated with a specific aspect, for instance the Ogou family are soldiers, the Ezili govern the feminine spheres of life, the Azaka govern agriculture, the Ghede govern the sphere of death and fertility.\n\nA [[Simbi]] is a Loa which represents magic. A Simbi is portrayed as a green snake. This Loa (Simbi) is used to contact the dead.<ref name=\"MDM\">{{cite web |title=Voodoo History Basic Principles \n |url=https://www.white-magic-help.net/About_White_Magic/Voodoo_History_Basic_Principles_Background.html |website=white-magic |publisher=Marion Daghan-Malenky |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Morality===\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2010}}\n{{See also|Haitian Vodou and sexual orientation}}\nVodou's moral code focuses on the vices of dishonor and greed. There is also a notion of relative propriety\u2014and what is appropriate to someone with [[Damballah|Dambala Wedo]]  as their head may be different from someone with [[Ogoun|Ogou Feray]] as their head. For example, one spirit is very cool and the other is very hot. Coolness overall is valued, and so is the ability and inclination to protect oneself and one's own if necessary. Love and support within the family of the Vodou society seem to be the most important considerations. Generosity in giving to the community and to the poor is also an important value. One's blessings come through the community, and one should be willing to give back. There are no \"solitaries\" in Vodou\u2014only people separated geographically from their elders and house. A person without a relationship of some kind with elders does not practice Vodou as it is understood in Haiti and among Haitians; additionally, Haitian Vodou emphasizes the 'wholeness of being' not just with elders and the material world, but also unity with the interconnected forces of nature.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Michel|first1=Claudine|title=Women's Moral and Spiritual Leadership in Haitian Vodou: The Voice of Mama Lola and Karen McCarthy Brown|journal=Journal of Feminist Studies in Religion|date=September 1, 2001|volume=17|issue=2}}</ref>\n\nThere is a diversity of practice in Vodou across the country of Haiti and the Haitian diaspora. For instance, in the north of Haiti, the ''lave t\u00e8t'' (\"head washing\")<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Daniels|first1=Kyrah Malika|title=The Coolness of Cleansing: Sacred Waters, Medicinal Plants and Ritual Baths of Haiti and Peru|journal=Revista: Harvard Review of Latin America|date=Fall 2016|volume=16|issue=1|pages=21\u201324}}</ref> or ''kanzwe'' may be the only initiation, as it is in the Dominican Republic, Cuba and Puerto Rico,  whereas in Port-au-Prince and the south they practice the ''kanzo'' rites<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Richman|first1=Karen E.|title=Peasants, Migrants and the Discovery of African Traditions: Ritual and Social Change in Lowland Haiti|journal=Journal of Religion in Africa|date=August 1, 2007|volume=37|issue=3|pages=383\u2013387}}</ref> with three grades of initiation{{spaced ndash}}kanzo senp, si pwen, and asogwe{{spaced ndash}}and the latter is the most familiar mode of practice outside Haiti. Some lineages combine both, as [[Mambo (Vodou)|Mambo]] [[Katherine Dunham]] reports from her personal experience in her book ''Island Possessed''.\n\nWhile the overall tendency in Vodou is conservative in accord with its African roots, there is no singular, definitive form, only what is right in a particular house or lineage. Small details of service and the spirits served vary from house to house, and information in books or on the internet therefore may seem contradictory. There is no central authority or  \"[[pope]]\" in Haitian Vodou, since \"every [[Mambo (Vodou)|mambo]] and houngan is the head of their own house\", as a popular Haitian saying goes. Another consideration in terms of Haitian diversity are the many sects besides the S\u00e8vi Gine in Haiti such as the Makaya, Rara, and other secret societies, each of which has its own distinct pantheon of spirits.\n\n===Soul===\nAccording to Vodou, the soul consists of two aspects, in a type of [[soul dualism]]: the ''gros bon ange'' (big good angel) and the ''ti bon ange'' (little good angel). The ''gros bon ange'' is the part of the soul that is essentially responsible for the basic biological functions, such as the flow of blood through the body and breathing. On the other hand, the ''ti bon ange'' is the source of personality, character and willpower. \"As the ''gros bon ange'' provides each person with the power to act, it is the ''ti bon ange'' that molds the individual sentiment within each act\".<ref>Thomas, Kette. \"Haitian Zombie, Myth, and Modern Identity.\" CLCWeb: Comparative Literature and Culture 12.2 (2010): n. pag. Web. 29 Oct. 2013.</ref> While the latter is an essential element for the survival of one's individual identity, it is not necessary to keep the body functioning properly in biological terms, and therefore a person can continue to exist without it.\n\n==Practices==\n\n===Liturgy and practice===\n[[File:JacmelVodou.jpg|right|thumb|Vodou ceremony, [[Jacmel]], [[Haiti]].]]\nA Haitian Vodou temple is called a [[Peristil]].{{sfn|Kilson|Rotberg|1976|p=345}} After a day or two of preparation setting up altars at an Hounfour, and ritually preparing and cooking fowl and other foods, a Haitian Vodou service begins with a series of prayers and songs in French, then a litany in [[Haitian Creole]] and [[Haitian Vodoun Culture Language|Langaj]] that goes through all the European and African saints and loa honored by the house, and then a series of verses for all the main spirits of the house. This is called the \"Priy\u00e8 Gine\" or the African Prayer. After more introductory songs, beginning with saluting Hounto, the spirit of the drums, the songs for all the individual spirits are sung, starting with the [[Legba]] family through all the Rada spirits, then there is a break and the Petro part of the service begins, which ends with the songs for the [[Gu\u00e9d\u00e9|Gede]] family.\n\nAs the songs are sung, participants believe that spirits come to visit the ceremony, by taking [[Spirit possession#In Haitian Vodou and African traditions|possession]] of individuals and speaking and acting through them. When a ceremony is made, only the family of those possessed is benefited.  At this time it is believed that devious mambo or houngan can take away the luck of the worshippers through particular actions. For instance, if a priest asks for a drink of champagne, a wise participant refuses. Sometimes these ceremonies may include dispute among the singers as to how a hymn is to be sung. In Haiti, these Vodou ceremonies, depending on the Priest or Priestess, may be more organized.  But in the United States, many vodouists and clergy take it as a sort of non-serious party or \"folly\". In a serious rite, each spirit is saluted and greeted by the initiates present and gives readings, advice, and cures to those who ask for help. Many hours later, as morning dawns, the last song is sung, the guests leave, and the exhausted hounsis, houngans, and mambos can go to sleep.[[File:VOODOO PERISTILE Croix des Mission, Haiti 1980.jpg|thumb|VOODOO PERISTILE Croix des Mission, Haiti 1980]]\n\nVodou practitioners believe that if one follows all taboos imposed by their particular loa and is punctilious about all offerings and ceremonies, the loa will aid them. Vodou practitioners also believe that if someone ignores their loa it can result in sickness, the failure of crops, the death of relatives, and other misfortunes.<ref>Simpson, George (1978). ''Black Religions in the New World''. New York: Columbia University Press. p. 86.</ref>\nAnimals are sometimes sacrificed in Haitian Vodou. A variety of animals are sacrificed, such as pigs, goats, chickens, and bulls.\n\"The intent and emphasis of sacrifice is not upon the death of the animal, it is upon the transfusion of its life to the loa; for the understanding is that flesh and blood are of the essence of life and vigor, and these will restore the divine energy of the god.\"<ref>[[Deren, Maya]] (1953). ''[[Divine Horsemen: The Living Gods of Haiti]]''. New York: Thames and Hudson. p. 216.</ref>\n\nOn the individual's household level, a Vodouisant or \"s\u00e8vit\u00e8\"/\"serviteur\" may have one or more tables set out for their ancestors and the spirit or spirits that they serve with pictures or statues of the spirits, perfumes, foods, and other things favored by their spirits. The most basic set up is just a white candle and a clear glass of water and perhaps flowers. On a particular spirit's day, one lights a candle and says an [[Lord's Prayer|Our Father]] and [[Hail Mary]], salutes Papa Legba and asks him to open the gate, and then one salutes and speaks to the particular spirit as an elder family member. Ancestors are approached directly, without the mediating of Papa Legba, since they are said to be \"in the blood\".\n\nIn a Vodou home, the only recognizable religious items are often images of saints and candles with a rosary. In other homes, where people may more openly show their devotion to the spirits, noticeable items may include an altar with Catholic saints and iconographies, rosaries, bottles, jars, rattles, perfumes, oils, and dolls. Some Vodou devotees have less paraphernalia in their homes because they had no option but to hide their beliefs. Haiti is a rural society and the cult of ancestors guard the traditional values of the peasant class.  The ancestors are linked to family life and the land. Haitian peasants serve the spirits daily and sometime gather with their extended family on special occasions for ceremonies, which may celebrate the birthday of a spirit or a particular event. In very remote areas, people may walk for days to partake in ceremonies that take place as often as several times a month. Vodou is closely tied to the division and administration of land as well as to the residential economy. The cemeteries and many crossroads are meaningful places for worship: the cemetery acts as a repository of spirits and the crossroads acts as points of access to the world of the invisible.<ref>Michel, Claudine (Aug 1996). \"Of Worlds Seen and Unseen: The Educational Character of Haitian Vodou\". Comparative Education Review (The University of Chicago Press on behalf of the Comparative and International Education) 40. Retrieved Dec 5, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Priests===\n[[File:Antique ceremonial suit for Haitian Vodou Voudun rites.jpg|thumb|Ceremonial suit for Haitian Vodou rites, [[Ethnological Museum of Berlin]], Germany.]]\n[[Houngan]]s (priest) or [[Mambo (Vodou)|Mambo]]s (priestess) are usually people who were chosen by the dead ancestors and received the divination from the deities while he or she was possessed. His or her tendency is to do good by helping and protecting others from spells, however they sometimes use their supernatural power to hurt or kill people. They also conduct ceremonies that usually take place \"amba peristil\" (under a Vodou temple). However, non-Houngan or non-Mambo as Vodouisants are not [[Initiation|initiated]], and are referred to as being \"bossale\"; it is not a requirement to be an initiate to serve one's spirits. There are clergy in Haitian vodou whose responsibility it is to preserve the rituals and songs and maintain the relationship between the spirits and the community as a whole (though some of this is the responsibility of the whole community as well). They are entrusted with leading the service of all of the spirits of their lineage. Sometimes they are \"called\" to serve in a process called ''being reclaimed'', which they may resist at first.{{sfn|McAlister|1993|pp=10\u201327}} Below the houngans and mambos are the hounsis, who are initiates who act as assistants during ceremonies and who are dedicated to their own personal mysteries.\n\nThe ''asson'' (calabash rattle) is the symbol for one who has acquired the status of houngan or mambo (priest or priestess) in Haitian Vodou. The calabash is taken from the calabasse courante or calabasse ordinaire tree, which is associated with Danbhalah-W\u00e9do. A houngan or mambo traditionally holds the asson in their hand, along with a clochette (bell). The asson contains stones and snake vertebrae that give it its sound. The asson is covered with a web of porcelain beads.<ref>Rigaud, Milo (2001). Secrets of Voodoo. New York: City Lights Publishers. pp. 35\u201336.</ref>\n\nA ''bokor'' is a sorcerer or magician who casts spells on request. They are not necessarily priests, and may be practitioners of \"darker\" things, and are often not accepted by the mambo or the houngan.\n \n''Bokor'' can also be a Haitian term for a Vodou priest or other practitioner who works with both the light and dark arts of magic.<ref>[[Bokor]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=December 2017}} The bokor, in that sense, deals in ''baka' (malevolent spirits contained in the form of various animals).<ref>Deren, Maya (1953). Divine Horsemen: The Living Gods of Haiti. New York: Thames and Hudson. p. 75.</ref>\n\n===Death and the afterlife===\nPractitioners of Vodou revere death, and believe it is a great transition from one life to another, or to the afterlife. Some Vodou families believe that a person's spirit leaves the body, but is trapped in water, over mountains, in grottoes\u2014or anywhere else a voice may call out and echo\u2014for one year and one day. After then, a ceremonial celebration commemorates the deceased for being released into the world to live again. In the words of Edwidge Danticat, author of \"A Year and a Day\"\u2014an article about death in Haitian society published in the New Yorker\u2014and a Vodou practitioner, \"The year-and-a-day commemoration is seen, in families that believe in it and practice it, as a tremendous obligation, an honorable duty, in part because it assures a transcendental continuity of the kind that has kept us Haitians, no matter where we live, linked to our ancestors for generations.\" After the soul of the deceased leaves its resting place, it can occupy trees, and even become a hushed voice on the wind. Though other Haitian and West African families believe there is an afterlife in paradise in the realm of God.<ref>Danticat, Edwidge. \"A Year And A Day.\" The New Yorker 17 Jan. 2011: 19. Popular Culture Collection.\nWeb. 26 September. 2013.\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Before 1685: From Africa to the Caribbean===\n[[File:Gbe languages.png|thumb|Area of [[West African Vodun]] practice, the religion with the greatest influence on Haitian Vodou.]]\n\nThe cultural area of the [[Fon people|Fon]], [[Ewe people|Ewe]], and [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] peoples share a common [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]] conception of a dual [[Cosmology|cosmological]] divine principle consisting of [[Nana Buluku]], the [[God]]-Creator, and the voduns(s) or God-Actor(s), daughters and sons of the Creator's twin children [[Mawu]] (goddess of the moon) and [[Lisa (mythology)|Lisa]] (god of the sun). The God-Creator is the [[cosmogonical]] principle and does not trifle with the mundane; the voduns(s) are the God-Actor(s) who actually govern earthly issues. The [[Dahomey mythology|pantheon of vodoun]] is quite large and complex.\n\nWest African Vodun has its primary emphasis on ancestors, with each family of spirits having its own specialized priest and priestess, which are often hereditary. In many African clans, deities might include [[Mami Wata]], who are gods and goddesses of the waters; [[Legba]], who in some clans is virile and young in contrast to the old man form he takes in Haiti and in many parts of Togo; [[Ogoun|Gu]] (or Ogoun), ruling iron and smithcraft; [[Sakpata]], who rules diseases; and many other spirits distinct in their own way to West Africa.\n\nA significant portion of Haitian Vodou often overlooked by scholars until recently is the input from the [[Kingdom of Kongo|Kongo]]. The entire northern area of Haiti is heavily influenced by [[Kongo people|Kongo practices]]. In northern Haiti, it is often called the [[Kongo Rite]] or Lemba, from the Lemba rituals of the [[Kingdom of Loango|Loango]] area and [[Mayombe]]. In the south, Kongo influence is called [[Petwo]] (Petro). Many loa (a Kikongo term) are of Kongo origin such as Basimba belonging to the [[Basimba people]] and the Lemba.<ref>{{citation |title= The Book of Life, Knowledge and Confidence| publisher= Pacific Press|year=2012| url= https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1471734633|pp=112}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the Vodun religion (distinct from Haitian Vodou) already existed in the United States previously to Haitian immigration, having been brought by enslaved West Africans, specifically from the Ewe, Fon, Mina, Kabaye, and Nago groups. Some of the more enduring forms survive in the [[Gullah|Gullah Islands]].\n\nEuropean [[colonialism]], followed by totalitarian regimes in West Africa, suppressed Vodun as well as other forms of the religion. However, because the Vodun deities are born to each African clan-group, and its clergy is central to maintaining the moral, social, and political order and ancestral foundation of its villagers, it proved to be impossible to eradicate the religion.\n\n===1685-1791: Vodou in colonial Saint-Domingue===\nThe majority of the Africans who were brought as slaves to Haiti were from Western and Central Africa. The survival of the belief systems in the [[New World]] is remarkable, although the traditions have changed with time and have even taken on some Catholic forms of worship.{{sfn|Stevens-Arroyo|2002|}} Two important factors, however, characterize the uniqueness of Haitian Vodou as compared to African Vodun; the transplanted Africans of Haiti, similar to those of [[Cuba]] and Brazil, were obliged to disguise their loa or spirits as [[Roman Catholic]] [[saint]]s, an element of a process called [[syncretism]].\n\nTwo keys provisions of the [[Code Noir]] by King [[Louis XIV of France]] in 1685 severely limited the ability of enslaved Africans in Saint-Domingue to practice African religions. First, the Code Noir explicitly forbade the open practice of all African religions.{{sfn|Desmangles|1990|p=475}} Second, it forced all slaveholders to convert their slaves to Catholicism within eight days of their arrival in Saint-Domingue.{{sfn|Desmangles|1990|p=475}} Despite French efforts, enslaved Africans in Saint-Domingue were able to cultivate their own religious practices.  Enslaved Africans spent their Sunday and holiday nights expressing themselves. While bodily autonomy was strictly controlled during the day at night, the enslaved Africans wielded a degree of agency. They began to continue their religious practices but also used the time to cultivate community and reconnect the fragmented pieces of their various heritages. These late night reprieves were a form of resistance against white domination and also created community cohesion between people from vastly different ethnic groups.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Slavery and Slave Society,\" in the Making of Haiti|last=Fick|first=Carolyn|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=39}}</ref> While Catholicism was used as a tool for suppression, enslaved Haitians, partly out of necessity, would go on to incorporate aspects of Christianity into their Vodou.{{sfn|Desmangles|1990|p=475}} [[M\u00e9d\u00e9ric Louis \u00c9lie Moreau de Saint-M\u00e9ry]], a French observer writing in 1797, noted this religious [[syncretism]], commenting that the Catholic-style altars and votive candles used by Africans in Haiti were meant to conceal the Africanness of the religion,{{sfn|Moreau de Saint-M\u00e9ry|1797}} but the connection goes much further than that. Vodounists superimposed Catholic saints and figures onto the Iwa/Ioa, major spirits that work as agents of the Grand Met.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Caribbean Religious History: An Introduction|last=Edmonds|first=Ennis Barrington|publisher=New York Univ. Press|year=2010|isbn=|location=New York City|pages=112}}</ref> Some examples of major Catholic idols re-imagined as Iwa are the Virgin Mary being seen as Ezili. Saint Jacques as Ogou, and Saint Patrick as Dambala.<ref name=\":0\" /> Vodou ceremonies and rituals also incorporated some Catholic elements such as the adoption of the Catholic calendar, the use of holy water in purification rituals, singing hymns, and the introduction of Latin loanwords into Vodou lexicon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===1791\u20131804: The Haitian Revolution===\nVodou was a powerful political and cultural force in Haiti.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Squint|first=Kirsten L.|date=2007|title=Vodou and Revolt in Literature of the Haitian Revolution|url=|journal=CLA Journal|volume=2|pages=170|via=JSTOR}}</ref>The most historically iconic Vodou ceremony in Haitian history was the [[Bois Ca\u00efman]] ceremony of August 1791  that took place on the eve of a slave rebellion that predated the Haitian Revolution.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Haitian Revolutionary Studies|last=Geggus|first=David|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2002|isbn=|location=|pages=84\u201385}}</ref> During the ceremony the spirit [[Ezili Dantor]] possessed a priestess and received a [[Creole Pig|black pig]] as an offering, and all those present pledged themselves to the fight for freedom.{{sfn|Markel|2009|}} While there is debate on whether or not Bois Caiman was truly a Vodou ritual, the ceremony also served as a covert meeting to iron out details regarding the revolt.<ref name=\":1\" /> Vodou ceremonies often held a political secondary function that strengthened bonds between enslaved people while providing space for organizing within the community. Vodou thus gave slaves a way both a symbolic and physical space of subversion against their French masters.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nPolitical leaders such as [[Boukman Dutty]], a slave who helped plan the 1791 revolt, also served as religious leader, connecting Vodou spirituality with political action.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Avengers of the New World: The Story of the Haitian Revolution|last=Dubois|first=Laurent|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=99}}</ref> Bois Caiman has often been cited as the start of the [[Haitian Revolution]] but the slave uprising had already been planned weeks in advance,<ref name=\":1\" /> proving that the thirst for freedom had always been present. The revolution would free the Haitian people from French [[French colonial empires|colonial]] rule in 1804 and establish the first black people's [[republic]] in the history of the world and the second independent nation in the Americas. Haitian nationalists have frequently drawn inspiration by imagining their ancestors' gathering of unity and courage. Since the 1990s, some neo-evangelicals have interpreted the politico-religious ceremony at Bois Ca\u00efman to have been a pact with demons. This extremist view is not considered credible by mainstream Protestants, however conservatives such as Pat Robertson repeat the idea.<ref>{{cite journal|last=McAlister|first=Elizabeth|title=From Slave Revolt to a Blood Pact with Satan: The Evangelical Rewriting of Haitian History|journal=Studies in Religion/Sciences Religieuses|date=June 2012|volume=41|issue=2|pages=187\u2013215|url=http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1047&context=elizabeth_mcalister|doi=10.1177/0008429812441310}}</ref>\n\n===Vodou in 19th-century Haiti===\n\n====1804: Liberty, Isolation, Boycott====\nOn 1 January 1804 the former slave Jean-Jaqcues Dessalines (as [[Jacques I]]) declared the independence of St. Domingue as the First Black Empire; two years later, after his assassination, it became the Republic of Haiti. This was the second nation to gain independence from European rule (after the United States), and the only state to have arisen from the liberation of slaves. No nation recognized the new state, which was instead met with isolation and boycotts. This exclusion from the global market led to major economic difficulties for the new state.\n\nMany of the leaders of the revolt disassociated themselves from Vodou. They strived to be accepted as Frenchmen and good Catholics rather than as free Haitians. Yet most practitioners of Vodou saw, and still see, no contradiction between Vodou and Catholicism, and also take part in Catholic masses.\n\n====1835: Vodou made punishable, secret societies====\nThe new Haitian state did not recognize Vodou as an official religion. In 1835, the government made practising Vodou punishable. Secret Vodou societies therefore continued to be important. These societies also provided the poor with protection and solidarity against the exercising of power by the elite. They had their own symbols and codes.\n\n===20th century to the present===\nToday, Vodou is practiced not only by Haitians but by Americans and people of many other nations who have been exposed to Haitian culture. Related forms of Vodou exist in other countries in the forms of [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] [[Dominican Vud\u00fa|Vud\u00fa]], Cuban [[Cuban Vod\u00fa|Vod\u00fa]],{{sfn|Stevens-Arroyo|2002|pp=37\u201358}}, [[Brazil|Brazilian]] [[Candombl\u00e9 Jej\u00e9|Vodum]], and also in places to which Haitians have immigrated. There has been a re-emergence of the Vodun traditions in the United States, maintaining the same ritual and cosmological elements as in West Africa.\n\nFormer president of Haiti [[Fran\u00e7ois Duvalier]] (also known as Papa Doc) played a role in elevating the status of Vodou into a national doctrine. Duvalier was involved in the noirisme movement and hoped to re-value cultural practices that had their origins in Africa. Duvalier manipulated Vodou to suit his purposes throughout his Reign of Terror. He organized the Vodou priests in the countryside and had them advance his agenda, instilling fear through promoting the belief that he had supernatural powers playing into the religion's mysticism.<ref>Time Magazine (Jan 17, 2011). \"The Death and Legacy of Papa Doc Duvalier\" Retrieved May 13, 2015.</ref><ref>Apter, Andrew (May 2002). \"On African Origins: Creolization and Connaissance in Haitian Vodou\". American Ethnologist (Wiley on behalf of the American Anthropological Association) 29. Retrieved Dec 8, 2013.</ref>\n\nMany Haitians involved in the practice of Vodou have been initiated as Houngans or Mambos. In January 2010, after the [[2010 Haiti earthquake|Haiti earthquake]] traditional ceremonies were organized to appease the spirits and seek the blessing of ancestors for the Haitians. Also a ''\"purification ceremony\"'' was planned for Haiti.\n\n=== Controversy after the 2010 earthquake ===\nFollowing the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]], there were verbal and physical attacks against vodou practitioners in Haiti perpetrated by those who felt that vodouists were partially responsible for the natural disaster. Furthermore, during a [[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak|Cholera outbreak in 2010]] several Vodou priests were lynched by mobs who believed them to be spreading the disease.{{sfn|Valme|2010|}}\n\n==Demographics and geographic distribution==\nBecause of the religious syncretism between Catholicism and Vodou, it is difficult to estimate the number of Vodouists in Haiti. The CIA currently estimates that approximately 50% of Haiti's population practices Vodou, with nearly all Vodouists participating in one of Haiti's Christian denominations.{{sfn|CIA World Factbook}}hi\n\n==Gallery of Haitian Vodou objects==\n<gallery>\nFile:Antique ceremonial suit for Haitian Vodou.jpg|Ceremonial suit\nFile:Haitian Vodou fetish statue devil with twelve eyes.jpg|Statue of a [[djab]], a quick-working wild spirit.\nFile:Antique Haitian Vodou ceremonial drum.jpg|Ceremonial drum\nFile:Trop Pou Te Haitian Vodou banners.jpg|Banner reading \"Trop Pou Te\" in the [[Haitian Creole language]]\nFile:Vodou mirror museum exhibit.jpg|Mirrors represent doorways to the world of the dead.\n</gallery>\n\n==Misconceptions==\n[[File:Affaire de Bizoton 1864.png|thumb|The ''Affaire de Bizoton'' of 1864. The murder and alleged canibalization of a woman's body by eight voodoo devotees caused a scandal worldwide and was taken as proof of the evil nature of voodoo.]]\n\nVodou has often been associated in popular culture with [[Satanism]], [[witchcraft]], [[zombie]]s and \"voodoo dolls\". Zombie creation has been referenced within rural Haitian culture,{{sfn|Davis|1988|}} but is not a part of Vodou. Such manifestations fall under the auspices of the ''[[bokor]]'' or sorcerer, rather than the priest of the loa. The practice of sticking pins in voodoo dolls has history in folk magic. \"Voodoo dolls\" are often associated with [[Louisiana Voodoo|New Orleans Voodoo]] and [[Hoodoo (folk magic)|Hoodoo]] as well the magical devices of the [[poppet]] and the ''[[nkisi]]'' or ''bocio'' of West and Central Africa.\n\nThe general fear of Vodou in the US can be traced back to the end of the [[Haitian Revolution]] (1791-1804). There is a legend that Haitians were able to beat the French during the Haitian Revolution because their Vodou deities made them invincible. The US, seeing the tremendous potential Vodou had for rallying its followers and inciting them to action, feared the events at [[Bois Ca\u00efman]] could spill over onto American soil. After the Haitian Revolution many Haitians fled as refugees to New Orleans. Free and enslaved Haitians who moved to New Orleans brought their religious beliefs with them and reinvigorated the Voodoo practices that were already present in the city. Eventually, Voodoo in New Orleans became hidden and the magical components were left present in the public sphere. This created what is called hoodoo in the southern part of the United States. Because hoodoo is folk magic, Voodoo and Afro-diasporic religions in the U.S. became synonymous with fraud. This is one origin of the stereotype that Haitian Vodou, New Orleans Voodoo, and hoodoo are all tricks used to make money off the gullible.<ref>Long, Carolyn Morrow (Oct 2002). \"Perceptions of New Orleans Voodoo: Sin, Fraud, Entertainment and Religion\". Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions (University of California Pres) 6. Retrieved Dec 5, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe elites preferred to view it as folklore in an attempt to render it relatively harmless as a curiosity that might continue to inspire music and dance.<ref>Bellegarde-Smith, P. (2006). ''Haitian Vodou: Spirit, Myth and Reality''. (p. 25).  Bloomington, IN: Indiana University Press</ref>\n\nFearing an uprising in opposition to the [[US occupation of Haiti]] (1915-1934), political and religious elites, along with Hollywood and the film industry, sought to trivialize the practice of Vodou. Hollywood often depicts Vodou as evil and having ties to Satanic practices in movies such as ''[[White Zombie (film)|White Zombie]]'', ''[[The Devil's Advocate (1997 film)|The Devil's Advocate]]'', ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]'', ''[[The Serpent and the Rainbow (film)|The Serpent and the Rainbow]]'', ''[[Child's Play (1988 film)|Child's Play]]'', ''[[Live and Let Die (film)|Live and Let Die]]'', and in children's movies like ''[[The Princess and the Frog]]'', though this last example countered this trope with a kindly voodoo priestess who helps the main characters.\n\nIn 2010, a [[2010 Haiti earthquake|7.0 earthquake]] that devastated Haiti brought negative attention to Vodou. [[Televangelist]] [[Pat Robertson]] stated that the country had cursed itself after the events at Bois Ca\u00efman, because he claimed they had engaged in Satanic practices in the ceremony preceding the Haitian Revolution. \"They were under the heel of the French, you know, Napoleon the third and whatever. And they got together and swore a pact to the devil. They said 'We will serve you if you will get us free from the prince.' True story. And so the devil said, 'Ok it's a deal.' And they kicked the French out. The Haitians revolted and got something themselves free. But ever since they have been cursed by one thing after another.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-12017-504083.html|title=Pat Robertson: Haiti \"Cursed\" After \"Pact to the Devil\" - Crimesider - CBS News|date=6 November 2012|accessdate=2 August 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106024225/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-12017-504083.html|archivedate=6 November 2012}}</ref><ref>See also (or, instead) this [[CBS News]] (\"\u00a9 2010 CBS Interactive Inc.\") web page: {{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cbsnews.com/news/pat-robertson-haiti-cursed-after-pact-to-the-devil/\n |title       = Pat Robertson: Haiti \"Cursed\" After \"Pact to the Devil\"\n |author      = Smith, Ryan\n |date        = January 13, 2010\n |accessdate  = January 7, 2015\n |archivedate = January 7, 2015\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6VPecOTR3?url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/pat-robertson-haiti-cursed-after-pact-to-the-devil/\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref>\n\n==KOSANBA==\nScholarly research on Vodou and other African spiritual retentions in Haiti started in the early 20th century with chronicles such as [[Zora Neale Hurston]]'s \"Tell My Horse\", amongst others. Other notable early scholars of Haitian Vodou one could cite are Milo Rigaud, [[Alfred Metraux]] and [[Maya Deren]], for example. In April 1997, thirteen scholars gathered at the University of California Santa Barbara for a colloquium on Haitian Vodou.  From that meeting the ''Congress of Santa Barbara'' was created, also known as [[KOSANBA]].{{sfn|KOSANBA|}}  These scholars felt there was a need for access to scholarly resources and course offerings studying Haitian Vodou, and pledged, \"...to create a space where scholarship on Vodou can be augmented.\"<ref name=\"ucsb.edu\">{{Cite web | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613040659/http://research.ucsb.edu/cbs/projects/haiti/kosanba/declaration.html |title = KOSANBA: A Scholarly Association for the Study of Haitian Vodou}}</ref> As further described in the Congress\u2019 declaration:\n\n\"The presence, role, and importance of Vodou in Haitian history, society, and culture are unarguable, and recognizably a part of the national ethos. The impact of the religion qua spiritual and intellectual disciplines on popular national institutions, human and gender relations, the family, that plastic arts, philosophy and ethics, oral and written literature, language, popular and sacred music, science and technology and the healing arts, is indisputable. It is the belief of the Congress that Vodou plays, and shall continue to play, a major role in the grand scheme of Haitian development and in the socio-economic, political, and cultural arenas.  Development, when real and successful, always comes from the modernization of ancestral traditions, anchored in the rich cultural expressions of a people.\"<ref name=\"ucsb.edu\"/>\n\nIn the fall of 2012, KOSANBA successfully petitioned the Library of Congress to change the terms \"voodoo\" and \"voodooism\" to the correct spelling \"Vodou\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100611173100/http://research.ucsb.edu/cbs/projects/haiti/kosanba/index.html]</ref>\n\n==Organizations==\nIn the aftermath of the [[Fran\u00e7ois Duvalier]] dictatorship, a number of individuals, including many houngan, sought to organize means of defense for Haitian Vodou from defamation by Christian missionaries and congregations. One of the first leading houngan to formally organize other houngan in solidarity was [[Wesner Morency]] (1959\u20132007), who established the Vodou Church of Haiti in 1998 (registered in 2001 by the Ministry of Justice) and the Commission Nationale pour la Structuration de Vodou (CONAVO). Another individual who has pursued the organization of houngan is the late [[Max Beauvoir]], who established and heads the [[National Confederation of Haitian Vodou]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Afro-American religion]]\n** [[Santer\u00eda]]\n** [[Candombl\u00e9]]\n** [[Umbanda]]\n* [[Haitian mythology]]\n* [[Haitian Vodou art]]\n* [[Hoodoo (folk magic)|Hoodoo]]\n* [[Juju]]\n* [[Louisiana Voodoo]]\n* [[West African Vodun]]\n* [[Witch doctor]]\n* [[Simbi]]\n{{Portal|Traditional African religion}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Alvarado\n  | first1 = Denise\n  | year = 2011\n  | title = The Voodoo Hoodoo Spellbook\n  | publisher = Weiser Books\n  | location =\n  | isbn = 978-1-57863-513-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book | last = Blier\n  | first = Suzanne Preston\n  | editor-first = Cosentino\n  | editor-last = Donald J.\n  | title = Sacred Arts of Haitian Vodou\n  | publisher = Los Angeles: UCLA Fowler Museum of Cultural History\n  | year = 1995\n  | pages = 61\u201387\n  | chapter = Vodun: West African