s, 1955.\n* Anderson, Jeffrey. 2005. ''Conjure In African American Society''. Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press.\n* ''Angels in the Mirror:  Vodou Musics of Haiti.''  Roslyn, New York:  Ellipsis Arts.  1997. Compact Disc and small book.\n* Argyle, W.J., The Fon of Dahomey: A History and Ethnography of the Old Kingdom, Oxford, Oxford University Press, 1966.\n* Bellegarde-Smith and Claudine, Michel. ''Haitian Vodou: Spirit, Myth & Reality.'' Indiana University Press, 2006.\n* Broussalis, Mart\u00edn and Joseph Senatus Ti Wouj:\"Voodoo percussion\", 2007. A CD with text containing the ritual drumming.\n* Chesi, Gert, Voodoo: Africa's Secret Power, Austria, Perliner, 1980.\n* Chireau, Yvonne. 2003. ''Black Magic: Religion and the African American Conjuring Tradition''. Berkeley: University of California Press.\n* Cosentino, Donald. 1995. \"Imagine Heaven\" in ''Sacred Arts of Haitian Vodou''. Edited by Cosentino, Donald et al. Berkeley: University of California Press.\n* Decalo, Samuel, Historical Dictionary of Dahomey, (People's Republic of Benin), N.J., The Scarecrow Press, Inc., 1976.\n* Deren, Maya, ''[[Divine Horsemen: The Living Gods of Haiti (film)]]''. 1985 (Black and white documentary, 52 minutes).\n* Deren, Maya, ''The Voodoo Gods''. Thames & Hudson, 1953.\n* [[Alfred Burdon Ellis|Ellis, A.B.]], The Ewe Speaking Peoples of the Slave Coast of West Africa, Chicago, Benin Press Ldt, 1965.\n* Fandrich, Ina J. 2005. ''The Mysterious Voodoo Queen, Marie Laveaux: A Study of Powerful Female Leadership in Nineteenth-Century New Orleans''. New York: Routledge.\n* Filan, Kinaz. ''The Haitian Vodou Handbook''. Destiny Books (of Inner Traditions International), 2007.\n* Herskovits, Melville J. (1971). Life in a Haitian Valley: Garden CITY, NEW YORK: DOUBLEDAY & COMPANY, INC.\n* Le Herisee, A. & Rivet, P., The Royanume d'Ardra et son evangelisation au XVIIIe siecle, Travaux et Memories de Institut d'Enthnologie, no. 7, Paris, 1929.\n* Long, Carolyn. 2001. ''Spiritual Merchants: Magic, Religion and Commerce''. Knoxville: University of Tennessee Press.\n* McAlister, Elizabeth.  2002.  ''Rara!  Vodou, Power, and Performance in Haiti and its Diaspora''.  Berkeley:  University of California Press.\n* McAlister, Elizabeth.  1995.  \"[http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=elizabeth_mcalister A Sorcerer's Bottle: The Visual Art of Magic in Haiti]\".  In Donald J. Cosentino, ed., ''Sacred Arts of Haitian Vodou''.  UCLA Fowler Museum, 1995.\n* McAlister, Elizabeth. 2000  \"[http://wesscholar.wesleyan.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1013&context=div2facpubs Love, Sex, and Gender Embodied:  The Spirits of Haitian Vodou.]\"  In J. Runzo and N. Martin, eds, Love, Sex, and Gender in the World Religions.  Oxford:  Oneworld Press.\n* Malefijt, Annemarie de Waal (1989). Religion and Culture: An introduction to Anthropology of Religion. Long Groove, Illinois: Waveland Press, Inc.\n* McAlister, Elizabeth.  1998.  \"[http://wesscholar.wesleyan.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1015&context=div2facpubs The Madonna of 115th St. Revisited:  Vodou and Haitian Catholicism in the Age of Transnationalism.]\"  In S. Warner, ed., Gatherings in Diaspora.  Philadelphia:  Temple Univ. Press.\n* Rhythms of Rapture:  Sacred Musics of Haitian Vodou.  Smithsonian Folkways, 1005.  Compact Disc and Liner Notes\n* Saint-Lot, Marie-Jos\u00e9 Alcide. 2003. ''Vodou: A Sacred Theatre''. Coconut Grove: Educa Vision, Inc.\n* Tallant, Robert. \"Reference materials on voodoo, folklore, spirituals, etc. 6\u20131 to 6\u20135 -Published references on folklore and spiritualism.\" ''The Robert Tallant Papers''. New Orleans Public Library.  fiche 7 and 8, grids 1\u201322. Accessed 5 May 2005.\n* Thornton, John K. 1988. \"On the trail of Voodoo: African Christianity in Africa and the Americas\" ''The Americas'' Vol: 44.3 Pp 261\u2013278.\n* Vanhee, Hein. 2002. \"Central African Popular Christianity and the Making of Haitian Vodou Religion.\" in ''Central Africans and Cultural Transformations in the American Diaspora'' Edited by: L. M. Heywood. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 243\u201364.\n* Verger, Pierre F\u00e1t\u00famb\u00ed, Dieux d'Afrique: Culte des Orishas et Vodouns \u00e0 l'ancienne C\u00f4te des Esclaves en Afrique et \u00e0 Bahia, la Baie de Tous Les Saints au Br\u00e9sil. 1954.\n* Ward, Martha. 2004. ''Voodoo Queen: The Spirited Lives of Marie Laveau'' Jackson: University of Mississippi Press.\n* Warren, Dennis, D., The Akan of Ghana, Accra, Pointer Limited, 1973. 9.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Haitian Vodou}}\n* [http://www.havanatimes.org/?p=9966 Haiti in Cuba: Vodou, Racism & Domination] by Dimitri Prieto, ''Havana Times'', June 8, 2009.\n* [http://rara.wesleyan.edu Rara: Vodou, Power and Performance in Haiti and Its Diaspora].\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122770590&ps=cprs Voodoo Brings Solace To Grieving Haitians]\u2014''[[All Things Considered]]'' from [[NPR]]. Audio and transcript. January 20, 2010.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100210185240/http://speakingoffaith.publicradio.org/programs/2010/vodou/ Living Vodou]. ''[[Speaking of Faith]]'' from [[American Public Media]]. Audio and [https://archive.is/20130113043734/http://speakingoffaith.publicradio.org/programs/2010/vodou/transcript.shtml transcript]. February 4, 2010\n* [http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/60418,in-pictures,news-in-pictures,in-pictures-haiti-voodoo-christian-attack-earthquake-aid-earthquake Voodoo Alive and Well in Haiti]\u2014slideshow by ''[[The First Post]]''\n* [http://www.life.com/gallery/62471/inside-haitian-vodou#index/0 Inside Haitian Vodou]\u2014slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]''\n\n{{Afro-American Religions}}\n{{Haiti topics}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n[[Category:Haitian Vodou| ]]\n[[Category:Afro-Caribbean religion]]\n[[Category:Afro-Haitian culture]]\n[[Category:Afro-American religion]]\n[[Category:Christianity and religious syncretism]]\n[[Category:Religion in Haiti]]\n", "name_user": "73.252.148.161", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDemographics and geographic distribution)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_Vodou"}
{"title_page": "History of the Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)", "text_new": "{{for|the current Washington Nationals|Washington Nationals}}\n{{for|the American Association Washington Senators|Washington Senators (1891\u20131899)}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|2=Talk:History of the Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)#Requested move 6 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>\n{| class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:27em; font-size:88%; text-align:left; line-height:1.5em\"\n! colspan=2 class=\"fn org\" style=\"font-size:125%; text-align:center; {{Baseball primary style|Washington Senators|border=2}}; margin-bottom:3px;\"|Washington Senators\n|-\n! [[File:Washington Senators.svg|center|frameless|100px]]\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"|First franchise [[Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|Washington Senators]] jersey logo\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"|Years [[1901 in baseball|1901]]\u2013[[1960 in baseball|1960]]\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"| Based in Washington, D.C.\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Other Names\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n* The Washington Senators\n* The Nats\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Major league affiliations\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[American League]]\n*\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Ballpark\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[American League Park]]\n* [[Boundary Field]]\n* [[Griffith Stadium]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Owners \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| \n* [[Clark Griffith]]\n* [[Calvin Griffith]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Notable managers \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[Clark Griffith]]\n* [[Bucky Harris]]\n* [[Joe Cronin]]\n*\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color: #dcdcdc; text-align: center\"|Major league titles\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|\n* 1924: World Champions\n* 1925: American League Champions\n* 1933: American League Champions\n|}\n\nThe '''Washington Senators''' [[baseball]] team was one of the [[American League]]'s eight charter franchises. Now known as the '''[[Minnesota Twins]]''', the club was founded in [[Washington, D.C.]] in {{mlby|1901}} as the Washington Senators.  In {{mlby|1905}}, the team changed its official name to the '''Washington Nationals'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/|title=Minnesota Twins Team History & Encyclopedia|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2008-09-24}}</ref> The name \"Nationals\" appeared on the uniforms for only two seasons, and was then replaced with the \"W\" logo for the next 52 years. However, the names \"Senators\", \"Nationals\" and shorter \"Nats\" were used interchangeably by fans and media for the next 60 years; in {{mlby|2005}}, the latter two names were revived for [[Washington Nationals|the current National League franchise]] that had previously played in [[Montreal Expos|Montreal]]. For a time, from 1911 to 1933, the Senators were one of the more successful franchises in [[Major League Baseball]]. The team's rosters included [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Baseball Hall of Fame members]] [[Goose Goslin]], [[Sam Rice]], [[Joe Cronin]], [[Bucky Harris]], [[Heinie Manush]] and one of the greatest players and pitchers of all time, [[Walter Johnson]]. But the Senators are remembered more for their many years of mediocrity and futility, including six last-place finishes in the 1940s and 1950s. [[Joe Judge (baseball)|Joe Judge]], [[Cecil Travis]], [[Buddy Myer]], [[Roy Sievers]] and [[Eddie Yost]] were other notable Senators players whose careers were spent in obscurity due to the team's lack of success.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rDQDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA48&dq=spud%20davis%20baseball%20digest&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=13 Most Forgotten Stars In Major League History|author=Grosshandler, Stan|publisher=Books.Google.com|date=February 1981|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zCoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44&dq=eddie+yost+baseball+digest&hl=en&ei=EH3GTOUch4LhBqS36dsP&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=20th Century All-Overlooked Stars|author=Vass, George|publisher=Books.Google.com|date=August 1999|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===A losing start for a charter franchise===\nWhen the [[American League]] declared itself a major league in {{baseball year|1901}}, the new league moved the previous minor league circuit  [[Western League (original)|Western League]]'s Kansas City franchise to Washington, a city that had been abandoned by the older [[National League]] a year earlier. The new Washington club, like the old one, was called the \"Senators\" (the second of three franchises to hold the name).\n\nThe Senators began their history as a consistently losing team, at times so inept that ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' columnist Charley Dryden famously joked, \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and last in the American League,\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dryden|first=Charles|title=untitled|newspaper=Washington Post|date=June 27, 1904}}</ref> a play on the famous line in [[Henry Lee III]]'s eulogy for President [[George Washington]] as \"First in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen\". The [[1904 Washington Senators season|1904 Senators]] lost 113 games, and the next season the team's owners, trying for a fresh start, changed the team's name to the \"Nationals\" (and occasionally nicknamed the \"Nats\"). However, the \"Senators\" name remained widely used by fans and journalists \u2014 in fact, the two names were used interchangeably<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/senators-nationals-nats-whats-in-a-name/2012/10/05/75e95352-0ef9-11e2-bd1a-b868e65d57eb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|first=John|last=Kelly|title=Picking the National's team name all by design|date=6 October 2012}}</ref> \u2014 although \"Nats\" remained the team's nickname.<ref name=\"ap19400616\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=T41hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QU0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6992%2C4002266|title=Tigers Climb Into Second Place - Defeat Nats Twice, A's Upset Tribe|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=1940-06-16|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=September 6, 2012|pages=19}}</ref> The Senators name was officially restored in {{mlby|1956}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsecyclopedia.com/al/wasdc/nats.html|title=Washington Senators (Nationals) (1901-1960)|website=www.sportsecyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n\n===A new era===\nThe club continued to lose, despite the addition of a talented 19-year-old pitcher named [[Walter Johnson]] in {{mlby|1907}}. Raised in rural [[Kansas]], Johnson was a tall, lanky man with long arms who, using a leisurely windup and unusual sidearm delivery, threw the ball faster than anyone had ever seen. Johnson's breakout year was {{mlby|1910}}, when he struck out 313 batters, posted an [[earned-run average]] of 1.36 and won 25 games for a losing ball club. Over his 21-year Hall of Fame career, Johnson, nicknamed the \"Big Train\", won 417 games and struck out 3,508 batters, a major-league record that stood for more than 50 years.\n\nIn {{mlby|1911}}, the Senators' wooden ballpark burned to the ground, and they replaced it with a modern concrete-and-steel structure on the same location. First called National Park, it later was renamed [[Griffith Stadium]], after the man who was named Washington manager in {{mlby|1912}} and whose name became almost synonymous with the ball club: [[Clark Griffith]]. A star pitcher with the National League's [[Chicago Colts]] in the 1890s, Griffith jumped to the AL in 1901 and became a successful manager with the [[Chicago White Sox]] and [[New York Highlanders]]. Walter Johnson blossomed in [[1911 Washington Senators season|1911]] with 25 victories, although the Senators still finished the season in seventh place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/WSH/1911.shtml|title=1911 Washington Senators|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> In [[1912 Washington Senators season|1912]], the Senators improved dramatically, as their pitching staff led the league in team [[earned run average]] and in [[strikeout]]s. Johnson won 33 games while teammate [[Bob Groom]] added another 24 wins to help the Senators finish the season in second place behind the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/WSH/1912.shtml|title=1912 Washington Senators|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> The Senators continued to perform respectably in [[1913 Washington Senators season|1913]] with Johnson posting a career-high 35 victories, as the team once again finished in second place, this time to the [[Philadelphia Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1913.shtml|title=1913 American League Team Statistics and Standings|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> Starting in [[1916 Washington Senators season|1916]], the Senators settled back into mediocrity. Griffith, frustrated with the owners' penny-pinching, bought a controlling interest in the team in {{mlby|1920}} and stepped down as field manager a year later to focus on his duties as team president.\n\n===1924: World champions===\n[[File:1924worldseries.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Washington's [[Bucky Harris]] scores on his home run in the fourth inning of Game 7 of the 1924 World Series.]]\n\nIn [[1924 Washington Senators season|1924]], Griffith named 27-year-old second baseman [[Bucky Harris]] player-manager. Led by the hitting of [[Goose Goslin]] and [[Sam Rice]], and a solid pitching staff headlined by the 36-year-old Johnson, the Senators captured their first American League pennant, two games ahead of [[Babe Ruth]] and the New York Yankees.\n\nThe Senators faced [[John McGraw]]'s heavily favored [[1924 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] in the [[1924 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1924_WS.shtml|title=1924 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> Despite Johnson losing both of his starts, the Senators kept pace to tie the Series at three games apiece and force Game 7. The Senators trailed the Giants 3\u20131 in the eighth inning of Game 7, when Bucky Harris hit a routine ground ball to third which hit a pebble and took a bad hop over Giants third baseman [[Freddie Lindstrom]]. Two runners scored on the play, tying the score at three.<ref name=\"1924 World Series Game 7 box score at Baseball Reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS1/WS1192410100.shtml|title=1924 World Series Game 7 box score|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> In the ninth inning with the game tied, 3\u20133, Harris brought in an aging Johnson to pitch on just one day of rest \u2013 he had been the losing pitcher in Game 5. Johnson held the Giants scoreless into extra innings. In the bottom of the 12th inning, [[Muddy Ruel]] hit a high [[foul ball]] near [[home plate]].<ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=muddy+ruel+baseball+digest&cd=1#v=onepage&q=muddy%20ruel%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson|author=Ruel, Muddy|date=October 1964|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> The Giants' catcher, [[Hank Gowdy]], dropped his protective face mask to field the ball but, failing to toss the mask aside, stumbled over it and dropped the ball, thus giving Ruel another chance to bat.<ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\" /> On the next [[Pitch (baseball)|pitch]], Ruel hit a [[Double (baseball)|double]] and, then proceeded to score the winning [[Run (baseball)|run]] when [[Earl McNeely]] hit a [[ground ball]] that took another bad hop over Lindstrom's head.<ref name=\"1924 World Series Game 7 box score at Baseball Reference\" /><ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\" /> It was the only [[World Series]] triumph for the franchise during their 60-year tenure in Washington.\n\n===Building a winning tradition===\n[[File:Joe_Judge_flowers_(cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|On behalf of the [[Elks]] of Washington, [[Joe Judge (baseball)|Joe Judge]] (front left), captain of the Senators, was presented with a floral tribute for the team before the start of a game in 1929]]\nThe Senators repeated as American League champions in {{mlby|1925}} but lost the [[1925 World Series|World Series]] to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. After Johnson's retirement in {{mlby|1927}}, the Senators endured a few losing seasons until returning to contention in {{mlby|1930}}, this time with Johnson as manager. But after the Senators finished third in {{mlby|1931}} and {{mlby|1932}}, behind powerful Philadelphia and New York, Griffith fired Johnson, a victim of high expectations.<ref>Thomas, Henry W.: \"Walter Johnson: Baseball's Big Train\", page 319. Bison Books, 1998</ref>\n\nFor his new manager in {{mlby|1933}}, Griffith returned to the formula that worked for him in 1924, and 26-year-old shortstop [[Joe Cronin]] became player-manager. The change worked, as Washington posted a 99\u201353 record and swept to the pennant seven games ahead of the Yankees. But the Senators lost the [[1933 World Series|World Series]] to the Giants in five games, and after that, the city would not host another World Series until {{mlby|2019}}, when the [[Washington Nationals]], its current National League team, defeated the [[Houston Astros]].\n\n===Fading fortunes===\nThe Senators sank all the way to seventh in {{mlby|1934}}. Attendance plunged as well, and after the season Griffith traded Cronin to the Red Sox for journeyman shortstop [[Lyn Lary]] and $225,000 in cash (even though Cronin was married to Griffith's niece, Mildred). Despite the return of Harris as manager in 1935\u201342 and 1950\u201354, Washington remained mostly a losing ball club for the next 25 years, contending for the pennant only in the talent-thin war years of {{mlby|1943}} and {{mlby|1945}}.\n\nIn the fall of {{mlby|1953}}, the second major baseball franchise shift of the mid-20th century took place (after the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] moved to [[Milwaukee]] in 1952), with long suffering [[Baltimore]] civic and business interests purchasing the perennially cellar-dwelling [[St. Louis Browns]] from controversial but enterprising owner [[Bill Veeck]] and moving them {{convert|40|mi}} northeast of Washington to the [[Chesapeake Bay]] port city. In the spring of {{mlby|1954}}, the Browns moved to a newly renovated and modernized [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]] on the site of their former northeastern city collegiate football bowl, and replacing the earlier [[minor league baseball|minor league]] level \"Triple A\" \"Orioles\" (also sometimes nicknamed the \"Birds\") of the [[International League]] where they had been consistent champions since the 1910s. The additional competition in the same League for [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]] area baseball fans added to the complexion around the nation's capital for the rest of the 1950s as the new \"[[Baltimore Orioles]]\" swiftly built their team prospects with astute trades and farm system output during the rest of the decade, finally becoming pennant contenders by {{mlby|1960}}. They continued their winning ways as one of the most dominant teams in professional baseball for the next two decades overpowering even the hapless third Senators franchise in 1961\u20131971.\n\nThe Senators were also the butt of many nationwide jokes during the 1950s, with the debut and running of a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical play in 1955 in [[New York City]] called ''\"[[Damn Yankees]]\"'' (based on an earlier best-selling novel and later movie in 1958), which followed a hapless elderly D.C. fan being given a \"Faustian\" or \"devil's bargain,\" selling his soul to transform the team by becoming a young powerful new Senators player (played in the movie version by heart-throb leading-man actor [[Tab Hunter]]) and lead the lowly team to a pennant versus the Yankees.\n\nIn 1954, Senators scout [[Ossie Bluege]], with help from longtime third base coach Alan Rupprecht, signed a 17-year-old [[Harmon Killebrew]]. Because of his $30,000 signing bonus, an enormous amount for that time, baseball rules required Killebrew to spend the rest of 1954 with the Senators as a \"bonus baby.\" Killebrew bounced between the Senators and the minor leagues for the next few years. He became the Senators' regular third baseman in {{mlby|1959}}, leading the League with 42 home runs and earning a starting spot on the American League [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|All-Star]] team.\n\n===Relocation===\nClark Griffith died in {{mlby|1955}}, and his nephew and adopted son [[Calvin Griffith|Calvin]] took over the team presidency. He sold Griffith Stadium to the city of Washington and leased it back, leading to speculation that the team was planning to move, as the [[Atlanta Braves|Braves]], [[Baltimore Orioles|Browns]] and [[Oakland Athletics|Athletics]] had done in the early 1950s, and the [[San Francisco Giants|Giants]] and [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]] would do later in the decade. After an early flirtation with San Francisco (with a \"Triple A\" [[Pacific Coast League]] team, the [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]]), by {{mlby|1957}} Griffith was courting [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul|Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul]] in the [[Upper Midwest]] state of [[Minnesota]], a prolonged process that resulted in his rejecting the Twin Cities' first offer<ref>{{cite news|title=Senators Reject Bids to Move to Minneapolis or St. Paul|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/10/22/archives/senators-reject-bids-to-move-to-minneapolis-or-st-paul-two-other.html?sq=giants+relocate+minneapolis&scp=2&st=p|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|agency=Associated Press|date=October 27, 1957|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref> before agreeing to relocate. The American League opposed the move at first, but in {{mlby|1960}}, in the face of the [[Continental League]]'s proposed Minnesota franchise, a deal was reached. The Senators moved and were replaced with an expansion [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Senators]] team for {{mlby|1961}}. The old Washington Senators became the new [[Minnesota Twins]]; the expansion Senators would become the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in {{mlby|1972}}, and baseball would not return to the city until {{mlby|2005}}, when the former Montreal Expos became the [[Washington Nationals]].\n\n==Photos==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Washington baseball LCCN2016894152 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators around 1925\nFile:Baseball LCCN2016887984 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators in the 1920s\nFile:Washington baseball LCCN2016890155 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators Team Picture in the early 1930s\n</gallery>\n\n==The Washington Senators in popular culture==\nThe longtime competitive struggles of the team were fictionalized in the 1954 book ''[[The Year the Yankees Lost the Pennant]]'', which became the 1955 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Damn Yankees]]'' and [[Damn Yankees (film)|the 1958 film]] starring then \"heart-throb\" leading-man actor [[Tab Hunter]]). The plot centers on Joe Boyd, a middle-aged real estate salesman and long-suffering fan of the Washington Senators baseball club. In this musical comedy-drama of the [[Faust|Faust legend]], Boyd sells his soul to the [[Devil]] and becomes slugger Joe Hardy, the \"long ball hitter the Senators need that he'd sell his soul for\" (as spoken by him in a throwaway line near the beginning of the drama). His hitting prowess enables the Senators to win the American League [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]] over the then-dominant Yankees. One of the songs from the musical, \"You Gotta Have Heart\", is frequently played at baseball games.\n\nThe (expansion) Washington Senators were mentioned several times in Tom Clancy's book ''Without Remorse''. As they performed even worse than the team they replaced, they were the subject of an updated joke: \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and ''still'' last in the American League.\" When the current Nationals had their own struggles, the joke was updated once again, this time to \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and last in the National League.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{1924 Washington Senators}}\n{{Minnesota Twins}}\n{{MLBHistory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History of the Washington Senators (1901-60)}}\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360)]]\n[[Category:History of Major League Baseball by team|Washington Senators]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the current Washington Nationals|Washington Nationals}}\n{{for|the American Association Washington Senators|Washington Senators (1891\u20131899)}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|2=Talk:History of the Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)#Requested move 6 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>\n{| class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:27em; font-size:88%; text-align:left; line-height:1.5em\"\n! colspan=2 class=\"fn org\" style=\"font-size:125%; text-align:center; {{Baseball primary style|Washington Senators|border=2}}; margin-bottom:3px;\"|Washington Senators\n|-\n! [[File:Washington Senators.svg|center|frameless|100px]]\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"|First franchise [[Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|Washington Senators]] jersey logo\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"|Years [[1901 in baseball|1901]]\u2013[[1960 in baseball|1960]]\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"2\"| Based in Washington, D.C.\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Other Names\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n* The Washington Senators\n* The Nats\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Major league affiliations\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[American League]]\n*\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Ballpark\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[American League Park]]\n* [[Boundary Field]]\n* [[Griffith Stadium]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Owners \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"| \n* [[Clark Griffith]]\n* [[Calvin Griffith]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"|Notable managers \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|\n* [[Clark Griffith]]\n* [[Bucky Harris]]\n* [[Joe Cronin]]\n*\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"background-color: #dcdcdc; text-align: center\"|Major league titles\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|\n* 1924: World Champions\n* 1925: American League Champions\n* 1933: American League Champions\n|}\n\nThe '''Washington Senators''' [[baseball]] team was one of the [[American League]]'s eight charter franchises. Now known as the '''[[Minnesota Twins]]''', the club was founded in [[Washington, D.C.]] in {{mlby|1901}} as the Washington Senators.  In {{mlby|1905}}, the team changed its official name to the '''Washington Nationals'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/|title=Minnesota Twins Team History & Encyclopedia|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2008-09-24}}</ref> The name \"Nationals\" appeared on the uniforms for only two seasons, and was then replaced with the \"W\" logo for the next 52 years. However, the names \"Senators\", \"Nationals\" and shorter \"Nats\" were used interchangeably by fans and media for the next 60 years; in {{mlby|2005}}, the latter two names were revived for [[Washington Nationals|the current National League franchise]] that had previously played in [[Montreal Expos|Montreal]]. For a time, from 1911 to 1933, the Senators were one of the more successful franchises in [[Major League Baseball]]. The team's rosters included [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Baseball Hall of Fame members]] [[Goose Goslin]], [[Sam Rice]], [[Joe Cronin]], [[Bucky Harris]], [[Heinie Manush]] and one of the greatest players and pitchers of all time, [[Walter Johnson]]. But the Senators are remembered more for their many years of mediocrity and futility, including six last-place finishes in the 1940s and 1950s. [[Joe Judge (baseball)|Joe Judge]], [[Cecil Travis]], [[Buddy Myer]], [[Roy Sievers]] and [[Eddie Yost]] were other notable Senators players whose careers were spent in obscurity due to the team's lack of success.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rDQDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA48&dq=spud%20davis%20baseball%20digest&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=13 Most Forgotten Stars In Major League History|author=Grosshandler, Stan|publisher=Books.Google.com|date=February 1981|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zCoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44&dq=eddie+yost+baseball+digest&hl=en&ei=EH3GTOUch4LhBqS36dsP&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=20th Century All-Overlooked Stars|author=Vass, George|publisher=Books.Google.com|date=August 1999|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===A losing start for a charter franchise===\nWhen the [[American League]] declared itself a major league in {{baseball year|1901}}, the new league moved the previous minor league circuit  [[Western League (original)|Western League]]'s Kansas City franchise to Washington, a city that had been abandoned by the older [[National League]] a year earlier. The new Washington club, like the old one, was called the \"Senators\" (the second of three franchises to hold the name).\n\nThe Senators began their history as a consistently losing team, at times so inept that ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' columnist Charley Dryden famously joked, \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and last in the American League,\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dryden|first=Charles|title=untitled|newspaper=Washington Post|date=June 27, 1904}}</ref> a play on the famous line in [[Henry Lee III]]'s eulogy for President [[George Washington]] as \"First in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen\". The [[1904 Washington Senators season|1904 Senators]] lost 113 games, and the next season the team's owners, trying for a fresh start, changed the team's name to the \"Nationals\" (and occasionally nicknamed the \"Nats\"). However, the \"Senators\" name remained widely used by fans and journalists \u2014 in fact, the two names were used interchangeably<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/senators-nationals-nats-whats-in-a-name/2012/10/05/75e95352-0ef9-11e2-bd1a-b868e65d57eb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|first=John|last=Kelly|title=Picking the National's team name all by design|date=6 October 2012}}</ref> \u2014 although \"Nats\" remained the team's nickname.<ref name=\"ap19400616\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=T41hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QU0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6992%2C4002266|title=Tigers Climb Into Second Place - Defeat Nats Twice, A's Upset Tribe|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=1940-06-16|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=September 6, 2012|pages=19}}</ref> The Senators name was officially restored in {{mlby|1956}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsecyclopedia.com/al/wasdc/nats.html|title=Washington Senators (Nationals) (1901-1960)|website=www.sportsecyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n\n===A new era===\nThe club continued to lose, despite the addition of a talented 19-year-old pitcher named [[Walter Johnson]] in {{mlby|1907}}. Raised in rural [[Kansas]], Johnson was a tall, lanky man with long arms who, using a leisurely windup and unusual sidearm delivery, threw the ball faster than anyone had ever seen. Johnson's breakout year was {{mlby|1910}}, when he struck out 313 batters, posted an [[earned-run average]] of 1.36 and won 25 games for a losing ball club. Over his 21-year Hall of Fame career, Johnson, nicknamed the \"Big Train\", won 417 games and struck out 3,508 batters, a major-league record that stood for more than 50 years.\n\nIn {{mlby|1911}}, the Senators' wooden ballpark burned to the ground, and they replaced it with a modern concrete-and-steel structure on the same location. First called National Park, it later was renamed [[Griffith Stadium]], after the man who was named Washington manager in {{mlby|1912}} and whose name became almost synonymous with the ball club: [[Clark Griffith]]. A star pitcher with the National League's [[Chicago Colts]] in the 1890s, Griffith jumped to the AL in 1901 and became a successful manager with the [[Chicago White Sox]] and [[New York Highlanders]]. Walter Johnson blossomed in [[1911 Washington Senators season|1911]] with 25 victories, although the Senators still finished the season in seventh place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/WSH/1911.shtml|title=1911 Washington Senators|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> In [[1912 Washington Senators season|1912]], the Senators improved dramatically, as their pitching staff led the league in team [[earned run average]] and in [[strikeout]]s. Johnson won 33 games while teammate [[Bob Groom]] added another 24 wins to help the Senators finish the season in second place behind the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/WSH/1912.shtml|title=1912 Washington Senators|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> The Senators continued to perform respectably in [[1913 Washington Senators season|1913]] with Johnson posting a career-high 35 victories, as the team once again finished in second place, this time to the [[Philadelphia Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1913.shtml|title=1913 American League Team Statistics and Standings|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref> Starting in [[1916 Washington Senators season|1916]], the Senators settled back into mediocrity. Griffith, frustrated with the owners' penny-pinching, bought a controlling interest in the team in {{mlby|1920}} and stepped down as field manager a year later to focus on his duties as team president.\n\n===1924: World champions===\n[[File:1924worldseries.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Washington's [[Bucky Harris]] scores on his home run in the fourth inning of Game 7 of the 1924 World Series.]]\n\nIn [[1924 Washington Senators season|1924]], Griffith named 27-year-old second baseman [[Bucky Harris]] player-manager. Led by the hitting of [[Goose Goslin]] and [[Sam Rice]], and a solid pitching staff headlined by the 36-year-old Johnson, the Senators captured their first American League pennant, two games ahead of [[Babe Ruth]] and the New York Yankees.\n\nThe Senators faced [[John McGraw]]'s heavily favored [[1924 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] in the [[1924 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1924_WS.shtml|title=1924 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> Despite Johnson losing both of his starts, the Senators kept pace to tie the Series at three games apiece and force Game 7. The Senators trailed the Giants 3-1 in the eighth inning of Game 7, when Bucky Harris hit a routine ground ball to third which hit a pebble and took a bad hop over Giants third baseman [[Freddie Lindstrom]]. Two runners scored on the play, tying the score at three.<ref name=\"1924 World Series Game 7 box score at Baseball Reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS1/WS1192410100.shtml|title=1924 World Series Game 7 box score|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> In the ninth inning with the game tied, 3\u20133, Harris brought in an aging Johnson to pitch on just one day of rest \u2013 he had been the losing pitcher in Game 5. Johnson held the Giants scoreless into extra innings. In the bottom of the 12th inning, [[Muddy Ruel]] hit a high [[foul ball]] near [[home plate]].<ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZzIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=muddy+ruel+baseball+digest&cd=1#v=onepage&q=muddy%20ruel%20baseball%20digest&f=false|title=How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson|author=Ruel, Muddy|date=October 1964|magazine=Baseball Digest|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> The Giants' catcher, [[Hank Gowdy]], dropped his protective face mask to field the ball but, failing to toss the mask aside, stumbled over it and dropped the ball, thus giving Ruel another chance to bat.<ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\" /> On the next [[Pitch (baseball)|pitch]], Ruel hit a [[Double (baseball)|double]] and, then proceeded to score the winning [[Run (baseball)|run]] when [[Earl McNeely]] hit a [[ground ball]] that took another bad hop over Lindstrom's head.<ref name=\"1924 World Series Game 7 box score at Baseball Reference\" /><ref name=\"How Senators' Strategy Won for Johnson\" /> It was the only [[World Series]] triumph for the franchise during their 60-year tenure in Washington.\n\n===Building a winning tradition===\n[[File:Joe_Judge_flowers_(cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|On behalf of the [[Elks]] of Washington, [[Joe Judge (baseball)|Joe Judge]] (front left), captain of the Senators, was presented with a floral tribute for the team before the start of a game in 1929]]\nThe Senators repeated as American League champions in {{mlby|1925}} but lost the [[1925 World Series|World Series]] to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. After Johnson's retirement in {{mlby|1927}}, the Senators endured a few losing seasons until returning to contention in {{mlby|1930}}, this time with Johnson as manager. But after the Senators finished third in {{mlby|1931}} and {{mlby|1932}}, behind powerful Philadelphia and New York, Griffith fired Johnson, a victim of high expectations.<ref>Thomas, Henry W.: \"Walter Johnson: Baseball's Big Train\", page 319. Bison Books, 1998</ref>\n\nFor his new manager in {{mlby|1933}}, Griffith returned to the formula that worked for him in 1924, and 26-year-old shortstop [[Joe Cronin]] became player-manager. The change worked, as Washington posted a 99\u201353 record and swept to the pennant seven games ahead of the Yankees. But the Senators lost the [[1933 World Series|World Series]] to the Giants in five games, and after that, the city would not host another World Series until {{mlby|2019}}, when the [[Washington Nationals]], its current National League team, defeated the [[Houston Astros]].\n\n===Fading fortunes===\nThe Senators sank all the way to seventh in {{mlby|1934}}. Attendance plunged as well, and after the season Griffith traded Cronin to the Red Sox for journeyman shortstop [[Lyn Lary]] and $225,000 in cash (even though Cronin was married to Griffith's niece, Mildred). Despite the return of Harris as manager in 1935\u201342 and 1950\u201354, Washington remained mostly a losing ball club for the next 25 years, contending for the pennant only in the talent-thin war years of {{mlby|1943}} and {{mlby|1945}}.\n\nIn the fall of {{mlby|1953}}, the second major baseball franchise shift of the mid-20th century took place (after the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] moved to [[Milwaukee]] in 1952), with long suffering [[Baltimore]] civic and business interests purchasing the perennially cellar-dwelling [[St. Louis Browns]] from controversial but enterprising owner [[Bill Veeck]] and moving them {{convert|40|mi}} northeast of Washington to the [[Chesapeake Bay]] port city. In the spring of {{mlby|1954}}, the Browns moved to a newly renovated and modernized [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]] on the site of their former northeastern city collegiate football bowl, and replacing the earlier [[minor league baseball|minor league]] level \"Triple A\" \"Orioles\" (also sometimes nicknamed the \"Birds\") of the [[International League]] where they had been consistent champions since the 1910s. The additional competition in the same League for [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]] area baseball fans added to the complexion around the nation's capital for the rest of the 1950s as the new \"[[Baltimore Orioles]]\" swiftly built their team prospects with astute trades and farm system output during the rest of the decade, finally becoming pennant contenders by {{mlby|1960}}. They continued their winning ways as one of the most dominant teams in professional baseball for the next two decades overpowering even the hapless third Senators franchise in 1961\u20131971.\n\nThe Senators were also the butt of many nationwide jokes during the 1950s, with the debut and running of a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical play in 1955 in [[New York City]] called ''\"[[Damn Yankees]]\"'' (based on an earlier best-selling novel and later movie in 1958), which followed a hapless elderly D.C. fan being given a \"Faustian\" or \"devil's bargain,\" selling his soul to transform the team by becoming a young powerful new Senators player (played in the movie version by heart-throb leading-man actor [[Tab Hunter]]) and lead the lowly team to a pennant versus the Yankees.\n\nIn 1954, Senators scout [[Ossie Bluege]], with help from longtime third base coach Alan Rupprecht, signed a 17-year-old [[Harmon Killebrew]]. Because of his $30,000 signing bonus, an enormous amount for that time, baseball rules required Killebrew to spend the rest of 1954 with the Senators as a \"bonus baby.\" Killebrew bounced between the Senators and the minor leagues for the next few years. He became the Senators' regular third baseman in {{mlby|1959}}, leading the League with 42 home runs and earning a starting spot on the American League [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|All-Star]] team.\n\n===Relocation===\nClark Griffith died in {{mlby|1955}}, and his nephew and adopted son [[Calvin Griffith|Calvin]] took over the team presidency. He sold Griffith Stadium to the city of Washington and leased it back, leading to speculation that the team was planning to move, as the [[Atlanta Braves|Braves]], [[Baltimore Orioles|Browns]] and [[Oakland Athletics|Athletics]] had done in the early 1950s, and the [[San Francisco Giants|Giants]] and [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]] would do later in the decade. After an early flirtation with San Francisco (with a \"Triple A\" [[Pacific Coast League]] team, the [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]]), by {{mlby|1957}} Griffith was courting [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul|Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul]] in the [[Upper Midwest]] state of [[Minnesota]], a prolonged process that resulted in his rejecting the Twin Cities' first offer<ref>{{cite news|title=Senators Reject Bids to Move to Minneapolis or St. Paul|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/10/22/archives/senators-reject-bids-to-move-to-minneapolis-or-st-paul-two-other.html?sq=giants+relocate+minneapolis&scp=2&st=p|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|agency=Associated Press|date=October 27, 1957|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref> before agreeing to relocate. The American League opposed the move at first, but in {{mlby|1960}}, in the face of the [[Continental League]]'s proposed Minnesota franchise, a deal was reached. The Senators moved and were replaced with an expansion [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Senators]] team for {{mlby|1961}}. The old Washington Senators became the new [[Minnesota Twins]]; the expansion Senators would become the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in {{mlby|1972}}, and baseball would not return to the city until {{mlby|2005}}, when the former Montreal Expos became the [[Washington Nationals]].\n\n==Photos==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Washington baseball LCCN2016894152 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators around 1925\nFile:Baseball LCCN2016887984 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators in the 1920s\nFile:Washington baseball LCCN2016890155 (cropped).jpg|Washington Senators Team Picture in the early 1930s\n</gallery>\n\n==The Washington Senators in popular culture==\nThe longtime competitive struggles of the team were fictionalized in the 1954 book ''[[The Year the Yankees Lost the Pennant]]'', which became the 1955 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Damn Yankees]]'' and [[Damn Yankees (film)|the 1958 film]] starring then \"heart-throb\" leading-man actor [[Tab Hunter]]). The plot centers on Joe Boyd, a middle-aged real estate salesman and long-suffering fan of the Washington Senators baseball club. In this musical comedy-drama of the [[Faust|Faust legend]], Boyd sells his soul to the [[Devil]] and becomes slugger Joe Hardy, the \"long ball hitter the Senators need that he'd sell his soul for\" (as spoken by him in a throwaway line near the beginning of the drama). His hitting prowess enables the Senators to win the American League [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]] over the then-dominant Yankees. One of the songs from the musical, \"You Gotta Have Heart\", is frequently played at baseball games.\n\nThe (expansion) Washington Senators were mentioned several times in Tom Clancy's book ''Without Remorse''. As they performed even worse than the team they replaced, they were the subject of an updated joke: \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and ''still'' last in the American League.\" When the current Nationals had their own struggles, the joke was updated once again, this time to \"Washington: First in war, first in peace, and last in the National League.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{1924 Washington Senators}}\n{{Minnesota Twins}}\n{{MLBHistory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History of the Washington Senators (1901-60)}}\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360)]]\n[[Category:History of Major League Baseball by team|Washington Senators]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1924: World champions:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 3-1 \u2192 3\u20131", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Washington_Senators_(1901%E2%80%931960)"}
{"title_page": "Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| based_on             = ''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree'' by Robert Barry\n| writer               = [[Mitchell Kriegman]]\n| story                = \n| director             = [[Jon Stone]]\n| narrated             = [[Kermit the Frog]]\n| starring             = [[Robert Downey Jr.]]<br>[[Stockard Channing]]<br>[[Leslie Nielsen]]\n| music                = [[Silversher & Silversher|Michael & Patty Silversher]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = [[Michael K. Frith]]\n| producer             = Ritamarie Peruggi\n| editor               = Jason Bielski<br>David Gumpel<br>Mark Oberthaler\n| cinematography       = Tony Cutrono\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[The Jim Henson Company|Jim Henson Productions]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1995|12|6}}\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree''''' is a 1995 [[Christmas by medium|Christmas]] [[television special]] starring [[Robert Downey Jr.]], [[Stockard Channing]] and [[Leslie Nielsen]], featuring [[Kermit the Frog]] as a [[narration|narrator]] and various other [[The Muppets|Muppets]] created exclusively for the special. It was sponsored by [[Nabisco]] and originally aired December 6, 1995 on [[CBS]].\n\nThe special was based on a 1963 book of the same name, by Robert Barry. In 2005, ''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree'' was adapted into a children's theater stage production by the [[Way Off Broadway Dinner Theatre]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe special begins with the song \u201cThe Perfect Tree,\u201d which features both Mr. Willowby ([[Robert Downey Jr.]]) singing about his desire to find the perfect [[Christmas tree]] and, within Willowby\u2019s house, a father [[mouse]] singing that he will go out to get a tree for his family (his two children, Beverly and Ned, decide to come with him). After the song is finished, Willowby asks his [[butler]], Baxter ([[Leslie Nielsen]]) where his tree is.\n\nThe special then follows the family of mice out in the woods looking for a tree. Eventually, the father mouse spots \u201cthe perfect tree,\u201d but it is far too large to fit into their tiny living quarters, so the family climbs the tree so that he can chop off the very top. Right when they reach the top, however, Willowby\u2019s [[lumberjack]]s arrive at the scene and cut the entire tree down (as they sing the song \u201cWe\u2019re Lumberjacks\u201d). The family of mice hold on to the tree as it is brought to Willowby\u2019s house.\n\nThe tree is set up in the house, and Willowby notices it is slightly too tall. He has Baxter cut off the very top, and then tells him to bring up the top part of the tree (which the mouse family is in) to one of his staff, Swedish maid Miss Adelaide (Channing), whom Willowby describes as being a very lonely person who doesn\u2019t even come down for Christmas. However, this is part of Mr. Willowby's hidden agenda of getting Baxter and Adelaide to admit their secret love for each other.\n\nBaxter does so, and while he is meeting with Adelaide, she describes her family\u2019s traditions at Christmas time. While they are talking, a romantic interest between the two of them is insinuated. At one point, Baxter notices the father mouse on the floor, but Adelaide says it is Christmastime and thus would be wrong to kill the mouse at this time. She places the mouse up on a banister, and he returns to the top of the tree with his children.\n\nAfter Baxter leaves, Adelaide notices that the tree in her room is slightly too tall, so she cuts off the top and throws it out the window (with the mouse family in it). Before the father mouse can cut off the top, a [[bear]] picks up the tree and brings it home to her den and family to use as his own Christmas tree.\n\nThe bears engage in their Christmas festivities, and eventually notice that the tree is too tall. They cut off the top (which once again has the mice in it) and throw it outside. The family of mice laugh at all they\u2019ve been through that evening, only to then be picked up (along with the remnants of the tree) by an [[owl]].\n\nMeanwhile back at the manor, Mr. Willowby is piling gifts around the tree, but notices he doesn't hear Baxter anywhere. To his great satisfaction, he quickly finds the butler standing in the snow underneath Miss Adelaide's window, listening to her sing.\n\nThe owls set up the tree in their own den, and then engage in an angelic chorus (the mouse family speculates that they never knew owls could be so musical). Eventually, they too notice that the tree they have is too tall, and so they cut off the top and throw it (along with the mice) outside.\n\nThe father mouse then raises his axe to cut off a tree from the remnants that have been thrown outside, but then realizes that the tree as it is actually the perfect size for his own home. He and the other mice return to the manor. But Baxter catches Beverly by the tail, grousing over the possible mouse infestation. Fortunately at that moment, Willowby\u2019s Christmas Ball is about to begin, and as the guests arrive, he hears Miss Adelaide leaving her room. Knowing how she would feel, he releases Beverly and tells her to \"Hurry home for Christmas.\" The mice race into their den with the tree, cheering that their Christmas can begin.\n\nMeanwhile, Mr. Willowby's Christmas party is in full swing. Adelaide comes down this time, and begins to dance with Baxter. With Mr. Willowby joining their dance for a moment, he turns to gaze upon the tree, and launches into a final rendition of \"The Perfect Tree\".\n\nThe show ends with our narrarator Kermit The Frog leaving the darkened manor at party's end, wishing the audience Happy Holidays and good night. As the credits roll, Ned and Beverly begin relating their adventure to their mother while father dozes by the fireplace.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]] as Mr. Willowby\n* [[Stockard Channing]] as Miss Adelaide\n* [[Leslie Nielsen]] as Baxter the Butler\n\n===Muppet performers===\n* [[Bill Barretta]] as Bear\n* [[Julianne Buescher]] as Beverly Mouse\n* [[Steve Whitmire]] as Bear, [[Kermit the Frog]], Owl\n* [[Kevin Clash]] as Father Mouse, Owl\n* [[Bruce Lanoil]] as Owl, Bear\n* [[David Rudman]] as Ned Mouse\n\n==Accolades==\nScore- and songwriters Patty and Michael Silversher were nominated for an Emmy for the song \u201cThe Perfect Tree.\u201d The special also won a [[Casting Society of America]] award for \u201cBest Casting for TV Nighttime Special\u201d.<ref>http://imdb.com/title/tt0124013/awards</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{muppets}}\n* {{imdb title|0124013|Mr. Willowby\u2019s Christmas Tree}}\n\n{{The Jim Henson Company}}\n{{The Muppets}}\n\n[[Category:1995 television specials]]\n[[Category:1990s American television specials]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Christmas television specials]]\n[[Category:The Muppets television specials]]\n[[Category:1995 television films]]\n[[Category:CBS television specials]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| based_on             = ''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree'' by Robert Barry\n| writer               = [[Mitchell Kriegman]]\n| story                = \n| director             = [[Jon Stone]]\n| narrated             = [[Kermit the Frog]]\n| starring             = [[Robert Downey Jr.]]<br>[[Stockard Channing]]<br>[[Leslie Nielsen]]\n| music                = [[Silversher & Silversher|Michael & Patty Silversher]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| executive_producer   = [[Michael K. Frith]]\n| producer             = Ritamarie Peruggi\n| editor               = Jason Bielski<br>David Gumpel<br>Mark Oberthaler\n| cinematography       = Tony Cutrono\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[The Jim Henson Company|Jim Henson Productions]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1995|12|6}}\n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree''''' is a 1995 [[Christmas by medium|Christmas]] [[television special]] starring [[Robert Downey Jr.]], [[Stockard Channing]] and [[Leslie Nielsen]], featuring [[Kermit the Frog]] as a [[narration|narrator]] and various other [[The Muppets|Muppets]] created exclusively for the special. It was sponsored by [[Nabisco]] and originally aired December 6, 1995 on [[CBS]].\n\nThe special was based on a 1963 book of the same name, by Robert Barry. In 2005, ''Mr. Willowby's Christmas Tree'' was adapted into a children's theater stage production by the [[Way Off Broadway Dinner Theatre]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe special begins with the song \u201cThe Perfect Tree,\u201d which features both Mr. Willowby ([[Robert Downey Jr.]]) singing about his desire to find the perfect [[Christmas tree]] and, within Willowby\u2019s house, a father [[mouse]] singing that he will go out to get a tree for his family (his two children, Beverly and Ned, decide to come with him). After the song is finished, Willowby asks his [[butler]], Baxter ([[Leslie Nielsen]]) where his tree is.\n\nThe special then follows the family of mice out in the woods looking for a tree. Eventually, the father mouse spots \u201cthe perfect tree,\u201d but it is far too large to fit into their tiny living quarters, so the family climbs the tree so that he can chop off the very top. Right when they reach the top, however, Willowby\u2019s [[lumberjack]]s arrive at the scene and cut the entire tree down (as they sing the song \u201cWe\u2019re Lumberjacks\u201d). The family of mice hold on to the tree as it is brought to Willowby\u2019s house.\n\nThe tree is set up in the house, and Willowby notices it is slightly too tall. He has Baxter cut off the very top, and then tells him to bring up the top part of the tree (which the mouse family is in) to one of his staff, Swedish maid Miss Adelaide (Channing), whom Willowby describes as being a very lonely person who doesn\u2019t even come down for Christmas. However, this is part of Mr. Willowby's hidden agenda of getting Baxter and Adelaide to admit their secret love for each other.\n\nBaxter does so, and while he is meeting with Adelaide, she describes her family\u2019s traditions at Christmas time. While they are talking, a romantic interest between the two of them is insinuated. At one point, Baxter notices the father mouse on the floor, but Adelaide says it is Christmastime and thus would be wrong to kill the mouse at this time. She places the mouse up on a banister, and he returns to the top of the tree with his children.\n\nAfter Baxter leaves, Adelaide notices that the tree in her room is slightly too tall, so she cuts off the top and throws it out the window (with the mouse family in it). Before the father mouse can cut off the top, a [[bear]] picks up the tree and brings it home to her den and family to use as his own Christmas tree.\n\nThe bears engage in their Christmas festivities, and eventually notice that the tree is too tall. They cut off the top (which once again has the mice in it) and throw it outside. The family of mice laugh at all they\u2019ve been through that evening, only to then be picked up (along with the remnants of the tree) by an [[owl]].\n\nMeanwhile back at the manor, Mr. Willowby is piling gifts around the tree, but notices he doesn't hear Baxter anywhere. To his great satisfaction, he quickly finds the butler standing in the snow underneath Miss Adelaide's window, listening to her sing.\n\nThe owls set up the tree in their own den, and then engage in an angelic chorus (the mouse family speculates that they never knew owls could be so musical). Eventually, they too notice that the tree they have is too tall, and so they cut off the top and throw it (along with the mice) outside.\n\nThe father mouse then raises his axe to cut off a tree from the remnants that have been thrown outside, but then realizes that the tree as it is actually the perfect size for his own home. He and the other mice return to the manor. But Baxter catches Beverly by the tail, grousing over the possible mouse infestation. Fortunately at that moment, Willowby\u2019s Christmas Ball is about to begin, and as the guests arrive, he hears Miss Adelaide leaving her room. Knowing how she would feel, he releases Beverly and tells her to \"Hurry home for Christmas.\" The mice race into their den with the tree, cheering that their Christmas can begin.\n\nMeanwhile, Mr. Willowby's Christmas party is in full swing. Adelaide comes down this time, and begins to dance with Baxter. With Mr. Willowby joining their dance for a moment, he turns to gaze upon the tree, and launches into a final rendition of \"The Perfect Tree\".\n\nThe show ends with our narrarator Kermit The Frog leaving the darkened manor at party's end, wishing the audience Happy Holidays and good night. As the credits roll, Ned and Beverly begin relating their adventure to their mother while father dozes by the fireplace.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Robert Downey Jr.]] as Mr. Willowby\n* [[Stockard Channing]] as Miss Adelaide\n* [[Leslie Nielsen]] as Baxter the Butler\n\n===Muppet performers===\n* [[Bill Barretta]] as Bear\n* [[Julianne Buescher]] as Beverly Mouse\n* [[Steve Whitmire]] as Bear, [[Kermit the Frog]], Owl\n* [[Kevin Clash]] as Father Mouse, Owl\n* [[Bruce Lanoil]] as Owl, Bear\n* [[David Rudman]] as Ned Mouse\n\n==Accolades==\nScore- and songwriters Patty and Michael Silversher were nominated for an Emmy for the song \u201cThe Perfect Tree.\u201d The special also won a [[Casting Society of America]] award for \u201cBest Casting for TV Nighttime Special\u201d.<ref>http://imdb.com/title/tt0124013/awards</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{muppets}}\n* {{imdb title|0124013|Mr. Willowby\u2019s Christmas Tree}}\n\n{{The Jim Henson Company}}\n{{The Muppets}}\n\n[[Category:Christmas television specials]]\n[[Category:The Muppets television specials]]\n[[Category:1995 television films]]\n[[Category:1995 television specials]]\n[[Category:CBS television specials]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mr._Willowby%27s_Christmas_Tree"}
{"title_page": "Employer student loan contributions", "text_new": "'''Employer student loan contributions''' are a type of employee benefit in the United States. With this benefit, employers pay back [[student loan]]s on behalf of employees, at certain amount per month as decided by the employer. Companies are using this benefit as a way to attract and retain employees, especially millennial workers.<ref>{{Cite web|first= Deirdre |last= Fernandes |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2016/03/15/fidelity-student-loan-debt-repayment-benefit-draws-workers/YgdrOElKnqqCR1tjKcvbnM/story.html|title=Fidelity\u2019s student loan debt repayment benefit draws 5,000 workers |work= The Boston Globe |access-date=April 21, 2016 |date= March 15, 2016 }}</ref> This benefit has grown as education debt has increased. According to the Washington Post, student debt has nearly tripled since the early 1990s and averaged $35,000 in 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/on-leadership/wp/2016/03/15/the-popular-new-perk-companies-are-using-to-attract-millennials/|title=The popular new perk companies are using to attract millennials|last=McGregor|first=Jena|date=March 15, 2016 |work=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=April 21, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOnly about 3% of companies currently offer employer student loan contributions, according to a survey by the Society for Human Resources Management from June 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /> Prominent companies that have announced this benefit include [[Fidelity Investments]], [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]], [[Natixis Global Asset Management]], [[Kronos Incorporated|Kronos]], [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]] and law firm [[Orrick, Herrington & Sutcliffe]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/26/your-money/medical-dental-401-k-now-add-school-loan-aid-to-job-benefits.html|title=Medical, Dental, 401(k)? Now Add School Loan Aid to Job Benefits|last=Bernard|first=Tara Siegel|date=March 25, 2016 |work =The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date= April 21, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/07/employer-benefits-student-loans/491942/|title=When Employers Pay Student Loans, Those Who Most Need Help Are Left Out|last=White|first=Gillian B.|work=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2016 |date= July 10, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/15/business/dealbook/firms-offer-cash-to-help-new-lawyers-pay-student-debt.html|title=Firms Offer Cash to Help New Lawyers Pay Student Debt|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=July 15, 2016 |work =The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date= October 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCompanies may work with a vendor to administer these payments. The main vendors are [https://www.iontuition.com IonTuition], [http://peoplejoy.com/ PeopleJoy], [https://www.leafbenefits.com/ Leaf Education Benefits], [[CommonBond]], [http://getpeanutbutter.com Peanut Butter],        [[Tuition.io]], [[SoFi]], Gradifi, and EdAssist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEmployer student loan contributions used to be taxable as regular income in the U.S.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]], payments of student loan principal and interest by an employer to either an employee or a lender is not taxable to the employee if paid on or before December 31, 2020.<ref>\"[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hr748/text Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2206]\". ''United States Congress''. [[govtrack]].  March 27, 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Employee benefits]]\n[[Category:Employers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Employer student loan contributions''' are a type of employee benefit in the United States. With this benefit, employers pay back [[student loan]]s on behalf of employees, at certain amount per month as decided by the employer. Companies are using this benefit as a way to attract and retain employees, especially millennial workers.<ref>{{Cite web|first= Deirdre |last= Fernandes |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2016/03/15/fidelity-student-loan-debt-repayment-benefit-draws-workers/YgdrOElKnqqCR1tjKcvbnM/story.html|title=Fidelity\u2019s student loan debt repayment benefit draws 5,000 workers |work= The Boston Globe |access-date=April 21, 2016 |date= March 15, 2016 }}</ref> This benefit has grown as education debt has increased. According to the Washington Post, student debt has nearly tripled since the early 1990s and averaged $35,000 in 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/on-leadership/wp/2016/03/15/the-popular-new-perk-companies-are-using-to-attract-millennials/|title=The popular new perk companies are using to attract millennials|last=McGregor|first=Jena|date=March 15, 2016 |work=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=April 21, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOnly about 3% of companies currently offer employer student loan contributions, according to a survey by the Society for Human Resources Management from June 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /> Prominent companies that have announced this benefit include [[Fidelity Investments]], [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]], [[Natixis Global Asset Management]], [[Kronos Incorporated|Kronos]], [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]] and law firm [[Orrick, Herrington & Sutcliffe]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/26/your-money/medical-dental-401-k-now-add-school-loan-aid-to-job-benefits.html|title=Medical, Dental, 401(k)? Now Add School Loan Aid to Job Benefits|last=Bernard|first=Tara Siegel|date=March 25, 2016 |work =The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date= April 21, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/07/employer-benefits-student-loans/491942/|title=When Employers Pay Student Loans, Those Who Most Need Help Are Left Out|last=White|first=Gillian B.|work=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2016 |date= July 10, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/15/business/dealbook/firms-offer-cash-to-help-new-lawyers-pay-student-debt.html|title=Firms Offer Cash to Help New Lawyers Pay Student Debt|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=July 15, 2016 |work =The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date= October 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCompanies may work with a vendor to administer these payments. The main vendors are [http://peoplejoy.com/ PeopleJoy], [https://www.leafbenefits.com/ Leaf Education Benefits], [[CommonBond]], [http://getpeanutbutter.com Peanut Butter],        [[Tuition.io]], [[SoFi]], Gradifi, and EdAssist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEmployer student loan contributions used to be taxable as regular income in the U.S.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]], payments of student loan principal and interest by an employer to either an employee or a lender is not taxable to the employee if paid on or before December 31, 2020.<ref>\"[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hr748/text Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2206]\". ''United States Congress''. [[govtrack]].  March 27, 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Employee benefits]]\n[[Category:Employers]]\n", "name_user": "Spacenerd9", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Employer_student_loan_contributions"}
{"title_page": "Nicol\u00e1s del Ca\u00f1o", "text_new": "{{expand Spanish|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| office = [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|National Deputy]]<br /><small>[[Province of Buenos Aires|for the Province of Buenos Aires]]</small>\n| term_start = December 10, 2017\n| term_end = \n| office2 = [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|National Deputy]]<br /><small>[[Mendoza Province|for Mendoza]]</small>\n| term_start2 = December 10, 2013\n| term_end2 = December 4, 2015\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = [[Soledad Sosa]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|02|06|}}\n| birth_place = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina)|Socialist Workers' Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Workers' Left Front]] {{small|(since 2011)}}\n| alma_mater = [[National University of Cuyo]]\n| profession = Politician\n| spouse = \n}}\n\n'''Nicol\u00e1s del Ca\u00f1o''' (born 6 February 1980) is a member of the Argentinian [[Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina)|Socialist Workers' Party]]<ref name=\"report\">http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Nicolas-Del-Cao-compartira-la-banca-con-Soledad-Sosa-Empezamos-a-escribir-otra-historia-dijo--20131028-0009.html report on his election with photo (Spanish)</ref> and presidential candidate of the [[Workers' Left Front]] (FIT).\n\n== Political career ==\nIn 2006 he moved to [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] to help build the PTS in that province. He later entered to the [[National University of Cuyo]], where he studied [[sociology]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Este-es-Nicolas-Del-Cao-el-candidato-revelacion-de-las-PASO-en-Mendoza-20130813-0017.html|title=Este es Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o, el candidato revelaci\u00f3n de las PASO en Mendoza|author=|authorlink=|date=|language=|publisher=|accessdate=13  August 2013}}</ref> while he had several jobs, such as selling ties or working in a [[Call centre|call center]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Conoc\u00e9 los candidatos y las boletas que encontrar\u00e1s en el cuarto oscuro|url=http://elsolonline.com/noticias/ver/1110/112920/conoce-los-candidatos-y-las-boletas-que-encontraras-en-el-cuarto-oscuro|publisher=El Sol|date=20  October 2011|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"lpo\">{{cite news|title=Qui\u00e9n es Nicol\u00e1s del Ca\u00f1o, la gran sorpresa de las PASO en Mendoza|url=http://www.lapoliticaonline.com/nota/71854/|publisher=La Pol\u00edtica Online|date=12  August 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Perfil|url=http://www.pts.org.ar/Nicolas-del-Cano|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laizquierdadiario.com/elecciones2015/?team_members=nicolas-del-cano|title=NICOL\u00c1S DEL CA\u00d1O|author=|authorlink=|date=|language=|publisher=|accessdate=8  May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe won a seat for the [[Workers' Left Front]] in the Argentine Chamber of Deputies for [[Mendoza Province]] at the [[2013 Argentine legislative election]].<ref name=report/>  This post was rotated with [[Soledad Sosa]].<ref name=report/>\n\nDuring the [[2011 Argentine provincial elections|2011 elections]] he was candidate for [[Governor of Mendoza Province]], managing 1.6% of votes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=ELECCIONES NACIONALES - 13 DISTRITO MENDOZA - 23 de octubre de 2011|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/estadistica/archivos/2011_nacionales/resultados_nacionales_2011_mendoza.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref>  However, it was a surprise when, during the primary elections for the [[2013 Argentine legislative election|2013 Argentinian legislative elections]] he managed to obtain 7.6% of votes,<ref name=\"lpo\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=Resultados Definitivos PASO 2013|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/resultados_definitivos_PASO_2013_distritos.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref> which caused his rivals in the [[Democratic Party (Mendoza)|Democrat Party]] to accuse him in a video of aiming to \"[[Expropriation|expropriate]]\" citizens and to try and convert Mendoza into \"[[Fidel Castro]]'s [[Cuba]]\". The video was quickly parodied<ref>{{cite news|title=El PD le pega duro a Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o en un video pero r\u00e1pidamente apareci\u00f3 una parodia|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/El-PD-le-pega-duro-a-Nicolas-Del-Cao-en-un-video-pero-rapidamente-aparecio-una-parodia--20130924-0021.html|publisher=[[Diario Uno (Mendoza)|Diario UNO]]|date=24  September 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref> and was even compared to [[Herminio Iglesias#Cardboard coffin controversy|Herminio Iglesias' coffin controversy]] by a Democrat Party leader.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Calivares|title=Crisis en el PD: \"El video que le hicieron a Del Ca\u00f1o es el caj\u00f3n de Herminio Iglesias del \u00b483\"|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Crisis-en-el-PD-El-video-que-le-hicieron-a-Del-Cao-es-el-cajon-de-Herminio-Iglesias-del-83-20131030-0065.html|publisher=Diario UNO|date=30  October 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== As deputy ==\n[[File:22.50 Habla del Ca\u00f1o. \"Hemos superado el mill\u00f3n de votos\" (21910070523).jpg|250px|left|thumb|Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o during a press conference (2015).]]\nIn 2013, Del Ca\u00f1o was elected as national deputy, obtaining 14% of votes in the [[2013 Argentine legislative election|elections]], positioning the PTS in the third place and sending the traditional [[Democratic Party (Mendoza)|Democratic Party of Mendoza]] to fourth place.<ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=Mendoza \u2013 Diputados Nacionales|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/escrutinios-definitivos/Mendoza.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.unidiversidad.com.ar/cobos-gano-y-la-izquierda-se-consolido-como-tercera-fuerza</ref> During his political campaign, he questioned the high salaries of politicians and proposed that minimum wage be equivalent to a teacher's, which he later presented as a bill and he himself lowered his own salary by donating the better part of it to striking workers, which, according to himself, was inspired by the members of the [[Paris Commune]] of 1871.<ref>http://www.mdzol.com/nota/493638-del-cano-explico-como-cobrar-lo-mismo-que-un-docente-siendo-diputado/</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El \u00faltimo rom\u00e1ntico|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbbDFGZynT0|publisher=TvPTS|date=22  January 2014|accessdate=2  February 2014|author=Telenoche|authorlink=Telenoche (Argentina)}}</ref><ref>http://www.pts.org.ar/Rendicion-de-cuentas-de-Nicolas-del-Cano</ref>\n\nOnce he took office as deputy, he challenged the fact that his fellow deputy Diego Mestre from the [[Radical Civic Union]] was allowed to take office too, arguing he had usurped his seat and had taken it from the FIT through [[Electoral fraud|fraud]]. Unlike the rest of the coalitions in Congress, Del Ca\u00f1o and the FIT refused to vote [[Juli\u00e1n Dom\u00ednguez]] as president of the [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|Chamber of Deputies]]. Such was the case too with the Deputies' vice-president.<ref>{{cite news|title=La izquierda record\u00f3 a Mariano Ferreyra y prometi\u00f3 legislar para \"la clase obrera\"|url=http://noticias.terra.com.ar/politica/la-izquierda-recordo-a-mariano-ferreyra-y-prometio-legislar-para-la-clase-obrera,055b6350c0eb2410VgnCLD2000000ec6eb0aRCRD.html|publisher=Terra|date=4  December 2013|accessdate=3  February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs deputy, he presented several bills proposing the nationalization of oil, prohibiting outsourcing, dismantling the State's repressive forces, including government espionage and the criminalization of social protests, demanding the declassification of files ranging from times of the [[National Reorganization Process|Dictatorship]] to the current government, and questioning the existence of a political caste with higher salaries, proposing they be reduced to that of a teacher or a qualified worker. Most of his electoral propositions became bills once he took office as deputy.<ref>http://www.sitioandino.com/nota/133096/</ref><ref>http://opinion.infobae.com/nicolas-del-cano/2014/05/27/prohibir-ya-los-despidos-y-suspensiones/</ref><ref>http://www.parlamentario.com/noticia-76844.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impulsan un proyecto de ley para que legisladores y ministros ganen igual que los docentes|url=https://www.infobae.com/2014/03/18/1551070-impulsan-un-proyecto-ley-que-legisladores-y-ministros-ganen-igual-que-los-docentes/|work=Infobae|date=18  March 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref>\n\nDuring a strike of laid-off workers of [[Lear Corporation]] in 2014 at their factory in [[General Pacheco]], within [[Greater Buenos Aires]]; Del Ca\u00f1o was attacked with [[rubber bullet]]s from the [[Argentine National Gendarmerie|National Gendarmerie]] while he was supporting a picket line in the [[Pan-American Highway]]. Later, as he was attending a session in the chamber of deputies, he was harassed by bureaucrats of the Mechanics and Allied Automotive Transport Trade Union (SMATA from its Spanish acronym), a union that has publicly supported the layoffs of delegates and dissident activists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Diputados de todos los partidos se solidarizaron con Del Ca\u00f1o tras la represi\u00f3n de Gendarmer\u00eda|url=https://losandes.com.ar/article/diputados-de-todos-los-partidos-se-solidarizaron-con-del-cano-tras-la-represion-de-gendarmeria|work=[[Diario Los Andes]]|date=29  October 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Militantes de SMATA abuchean a diputados opositores.|url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/diputados-smata-deuda-opositores_0_B1GdzTK9DXx.html|last=Ortelli|first=Ignacio|work=[[Clarin (Argentina)|Clarin]]|date=10  September 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> After Del Ca\u00f1o's complaint, judge Sandra Arroyo Salgado ordered that the National Gendarmerie could no longer make operations within the highway.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gendarmer\u00eda no podr\u00e1 intervenir m\u00e1s en los cortes de ruta en la Panamericana|url=https://www.infobae.com/2014/11/04/1606561-gendarmeria-no-podra-intervenir-mas-los-cortes-ruta-la-panamericana/|work=Infobae|date=4  November 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref>\n\n== Presidential candidate ==\n{{Main|2015 Argentine general election}}\n[[File:Montagem dos candidatos \u00e0 presid\u00eancia da Argentina em 2015.jpg|200px|thumb|Above: [[Adolfo Rodr\u00edguez Sa\u00e1]], [[Daniel Scioli]], [[Margarita Stolbizer]]. Below: [[Mauricio Macri]], Del Ca\u00f1o and [[Sergio Massa]]. 2015 presidential candidates.]]\nIn 2015 he was the FIT's candidate for mayor of Mendoza, managing to obtain 16,9% of votes in second place, surpassing the official candidate Carlos Aranda of the [[Front for Victory]], a result never before seen for any leftist force to an executive position in the country.<ref>http://www.ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar/padron</ref><ref>http://www.mendozapost.com/nota/9751/</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=El FIT qued\u00f3 segundo, desplaz\u00f3 al PJ y gan\u00f3 un edil.|url=https://losandes.com.ar/article/el-fit-quedo-segundo-desplazo-al-pj-y-gano-un-edil|work=Diario Los Andes|last=Olivera|first=Cinthia|date=4  May 2015|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> Later that year he was the FIT's presidential candidate, managing to win the primary election against [[Jorge Altamira]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Ruiz|first=Iv\u00e1n|title=Del Ca\u00f1o rompi\u00f3 todos los pron\u00f3sticos y super\u00f3 a Altamira en la interna de la izquierda|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1817973-del-cano-rompio-todos-los-pronosticos-y-supero-a-altamira-en-la-interna-de-la-izquierda|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n (Argentina)|La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=10  August 2015|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> and getting fourth place in the presidential elections in October with 3,27% of votes.\n\n== 2017 elections ==\nIn March 2017, the PTS announced Del Ca\u00f1o as pre-candidate to deputy for the Province of Buenos Aires to represent the FIT in the [[2017 Argentine legislative election|legislative elections]]. This had negative repercussions from the rest of the FIT's member parties, since they argued that they should have presented common lists to prevent quarrels within the FIT. [[N\u00e9stor Pitrola]] ([[Workers' Party (Argentina)|PO]]) was especially emphatic about Del Ca\u00f1o appearing as pre-candidate for the Province of Buenos Aires when the previous election he had already contended as deputy for Mendoza. He said: \"they bring Del Ca\u00f1o as candidate for the province where he has no relation. This is parachuting him in the same style as the other parties and will undoubtedly affect the FIT in Mendoza\". [[Juan Carlos Giordano]] ([[Socialist Left (Argentina)|IS]]) declared: \"We do not agree with the PTS in presenting their electoral campaign one-sidedly when the right thing to do is that all three parties do so and present a unified list\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Soria Guadalupe |first1=Alan |last2=Silva da Sousa |first2=Marcelo |title=El PTS ya present\u00f3 candidatos y hay enojos en el Frente de Izquierda |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1993319-el-pts-ya-presento-candidatos-y-hay-enojos-en-el-frente-de-izquierda |newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n (Argentina)|La Naci\u00f3n]] |date=14 March 2017 |access-date=22 May 2017}}.</ref> In that sense, Giordano himself, representing his party, made a proposition to prevent inner squarrels in the FIT, consisting in presenting Pitrola as heading the list for deputies and Del Ca\u00f1o heading the list for senators<ref>{{cite web |title=Propuesta para lista \u00fanica del FIT en las PASO: Del Ca\u00f1o (PTS) Senador - Pitrola (PO) Diputado |url=http://www.izquierdasocialista.org.ar/index.php/elecciones-2013-fit/5648-propuesta-para-lista-unica-del-fit-en-las-paso-del-cano-pts-senador-pitrola-po-diputado |newspaper=Izquierda Socialista |date=21 May 2017 |access-date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, the FIT agreed in unified lists for all districts where they contended, with Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o as candidate for the Province of Buenos Aires and N\u00e9stor Pitrola as candidate for senator.<ref>{{cite web |title=El Frente de Izquierda se adelant\u00f3 y acord\u00f3 listas de unidad |url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/frente-izquierda-adelanto-acordo-listas-unidad_0_BJcOqBTf-.html |newspaper=[[Clarin (Argentina)|Clarin]] |date=13 June 2017 |access-date=30 October 2018}}.</ref> Del Ca\u00f1o received 5,54% of votes and since December 2017 heads the bloc PTS-FIT along his comrade Nathalia Gonz\u00e1lez Seligra.<ref>{{cite web |title=Argentina: asumieron los diputados obreros y socialistas del Frente de Izquierda |url=https://www.laizquierdadiario.com/Argentina-asumieron-los-diputados-obreros-y-socialistas-del-Frente-de-Izquierda |newspaper=La Izquierda Diario |date=6 December 2017|access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2019 elections==\nHe will be the FIT-U's candidate for president, running with [[Romina Del Pl\u00e1]] for vice-president.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cano, Nicolas del}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Argentine Chamber of Deputies]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina]]\n[[Category:Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina) politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{expand Spanish|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| office = [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|National Deputy]]<br /><small>[[Province of Buenos Aires|for the Province of Buenos Aires]]</small>\n| term_start = December 10, 2017\n| term_end = \n| office2 = [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|National Deputy]]<br /><small>[[Mendoza Province|for Mendoza]]</small>\n| term_start2 = December 10, 2013\n| term_end2 = December 4, 2015\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = [[Soledad Sosa]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|02|06|}}\n| birth_place = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina)|Socialist Workers' Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Workers' Left Front]] {{small|(since 2011)}}\n| alma_mater = [[National University of Cuyo]]\n| profession = Politician\n| spouse = \n}}\n\n'''Nicol\u00e1s del Ca\u00f1o''' (born 6 February 1980) is a member of the Argentinian [[Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina)|Socialist Workers' Party]]<ref name=\"report\">http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Nicolas-Del-Cao-compartira-la-banca-con-Soledad-Sosa-Empezamos-a-escribir-otra-historia-dijo--20131028-0009.html report on his election with photo (Spanish)</ref> and presidential candidate of the [[Workers' Left Front]] (FIT).\n\n== Political career ==\nIn 2006 he moved to [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] to help build the PTS in that province. He later entered to the [[National University of Cuyo]], where he studied [[sociology]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Este-es-Nicolas-Del-Cao-el-candidato-revelacion-de-las-PASO-en-Mendoza-20130813-0017.html|title=Este es Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o, el candidato revelaci\u00f3n de las PASO en Mendoza|author=|authorlink=|date=|language=|publisher=|accessdate=13  August 2013}}</ref> while he had several jobs, such as selling ties or working in a [[Call centre|call center]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Conoc\u00e9 los candidatos y las boletas que encontrar\u00e1s en el cuarto oscuro|url=http://elsolonline.com/noticias/ver/1110/112920/conoce-los-candidatos-y-las-boletas-que-encontraras-en-el-cuarto-oscuro|publisher=El Sol|date=20  October 2011|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"lpo\">{{cite news|title=Qui\u00e9n es Nicol\u00e1s del Ca\u00f1o, la gran sorpresa de las PASO en Mendoza|url=http://www.lapoliticaonline.com/nota/71854/|publisher=La Pol\u00edtica Online|date=12  August 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Perfil|url=http://www.pts.org.ar/Nicolas-del-Cano|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laizquierdadiario.com/elecciones2015/?team_members=nicolas-del-cano|title=NICOL\u00c1S DEL CA\u00d1O|author=|authorlink=|date=|language=|publisher=|accessdate=8  May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe won a seat for the [[Workers' Left Front]] in the Argentine Chamber of Deputies for [[Mendoza Province]] at the [[2013 Argentine legislative election]].<ref name=report/>  This post was rotated with [[Soledad Sosa]].<ref name=report/>\n\nDuring the [[2011 Argentine provincial elections|2011 elections]] he was candidate for [[Governor of Mendoza Province]], managing 1.6% of votes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=ELECCIONES NACIONALES - 13 DISTRITO MENDOZA - 23 de octubre de 2011|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/estadistica/archivos/2011_nacionales/resultados_nacionales_2011_mendoza.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref>  However, it was a surprise when, during the primary elections for the [[2013 Argentine legislative election|2013 Argentinian legislative elections]] he managed to obtain 7.6% of votes,<ref name=\"lpo\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=Resultados Definitivos PASO 2013|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/resultados_definitivos_PASO_2013_distritos.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref> which caused his rivals in the [[Democratic Party (Mendoza)|Democrat Party]] to accuse him in a video of aiming to \"[[Expropriation|expropriate]]\" citizens and to try and convert Mendoza into \"[[Fidel Castro]]'s [[Cuba]]\". The video was quickly parodied<ref>{{cite news|title=El PD le pega duro a Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o en un video pero r\u00e1pidamente apareci\u00f3 una parodia|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/El-PD-le-pega-duro-a-Nicolas-Del-Cao-en-un-video-pero-rapidamente-aparecio-una-parodia--20130924-0021.html|publisher=[[Diario Uno (Mendoza)|Diario UNO]]|date=24  September 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref> and was even compared to [[Herminio Iglesias#Cardboard coffin controversy|Herminio Iglesias' coffin controversy]] by a Democrat Party leader.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Calivares|title=Crisis en el PD: \"El video que le hicieron a Del Ca\u00f1o es el caj\u00f3n de Herminio Iglesias del \u00b483\"|url=http://www.diariouno.com.ar/mendoza/Crisis-en-el-PD-El-video-que-le-hicieron-a-Del-Cao-es-el-cajon-de-Herminio-Iglesias-del-83-20131030-0065.html|publisher=Diario UNO|date=30  October 2013|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== As deputy ==\n[[File:22.50 Habla del Ca\u00f1o. \"Hemos superado el mill\u00f3n de votos\" (21910070523).jpg|250px|left|thumb|Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o during a press conference (2015).]]\nIn 2013, Del Ca\u00f1o was elected as national deputy, obtaining 14% of votes in the [[2013 Argentine legislative election|elections]], positioning the PTS in the third place and sending the traditional [[Democratic Party (Mendoza)|Democratic Party of Mendoza]] to fourth place.<ref>{{cite web|author=Direcci\u00f3n Nacional Electoral|title=Mendoza \u2013 Diputados Nacionales|url=http://www.elecciones.gov.ar/escrutinios-definitivos/Mendoza.pdf|accessdate=2  February 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.unidiversidad.com.ar/cobos-gano-y-la-izquierda-se-consolido-como-tercera-fuerza</ref> During his political campaign, he questioned the high salaries of politicians and proposed that minimum wage be equivalent to a teacher's, which he later presented as a bill and he himself lowered his own salary by donating the better part of it to striking workers, which, according to himself, was inspired by the members of the [[Paris Commune]] of 1871.<ref>http://www.mdzol.com/nota/493638-del-cano-explico-como-cobrar-lo-mismo-que-un-docente-siendo-diputado/</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El \u00faltimo rom\u00e1ntico|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbbDFGZynT0|publisher=TvPTS|date=22  January 2014|accessdate=2  February 2014|author=Telenoche|authorlink=Telenoche (Argentina)}}</ref><ref>http://www.pts.org.ar/Rendicion-de-cuentas-de-Nicolas-del-Cano</ref>\n\nOnce he took office as deputy, he challenged the fact that his fellow deputy Diego Mestre from the [[Radical Civic Union]] was allowed to take office too, arguing he had usurped his seat and had taken it from the FIT through [[Electoral fraud|fraud]]. Unlike the rest of the coalitions in Congress, Del Ca\u00f1o and the FIT refused to vote [[Juli\u00e1n Dom\u00ednguez]] as president of the [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|Chamber of Deputies]]. Such was the case too with the Deputies' vice-president.<ref>{{cite news|title=La izquierda record\u00f3 a Mariano Ferreyra y prometi\u00f3 legislar para \"la clase obrera\"|url=http://noticias.terra.com.ar/politica/la-izquierda-recordo-a-mariano-ferreyra-y-prometio-legislar-para-la-clase-obrera,055b6350c0eb2410VgnCLD2000000ec6eb0aRCRD.html|publisher=Terra|date=4  December 2013|accessdate=3  February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs deputy, he presented several bills proposing the nationalization of oil, prohibiting outsourcing, dismantling the State's repressive forces, including government espionage and the criminalization of social protests, demanding the declassification of files ranging from times of the [[National Reorganization Process|Dictatorship]] to the current government, and questioning the existence of a political caste with higher salaries, proposing they be reduced to that of a teacher or a qualified worker. Most of his electoral propositions became bills once he took office as deputy.<ref>http://www.sitioandino.com/nota/133096/</ref><ref>http://opinion.infobae.com/nicolas-del-cano/2014/05/27/prohibir-ya-los-despidos-y-suspensiones/</ref><ref>http://www.parlamentario.com/noticia-76844.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impulsan un proyecto de ley para que legisladores y ministros ganen igual que los docentes|url=https://www.infobae.com/2014/03/18/1551070-impulsan-un-proyecto-ley-que-legisladores-y-ministros-ganen-igual-que-los-docentes/|work=Infobae|date=18  March 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref>\n\nDuring a strike of laid-off workers of [[Lear Corporation]] in 2014 at their factory in [[General Pacheco]], within [[Greater Buenos Aires]]; Del Ca\u00f1o was attacked with [[rubber bullet]]s from the [[Argentine National Gendarmerie|National Gendarmerie]] while he was supporting a picket line in the [[Pan-American Highway]]. Later, as he was attending a session in the chamber of deputies, he was harassed by bureaucrats of the Mechanics and Allied Automotive Transport Trade Union (SMATA from its Spanish acronym), a union that has publicly supported the layoffs of delegates and dissident activists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Diputados de todos los partidos se solidarizaron con Del Ca\u00f1o tras la represi\u00f3n de Gendarmer\u00eda|url=https://losandes.com.ar/article/diputados-de-todos-los-partidos-se-solidarizaron-con-del-cano-tras-la-represion-de-gendarmeria|work=[[Diario Los Andes]]|date=29  October 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Militantes de SMATA abuchean a diputados opositores.|url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/diputados-smata-deuda-opositores_0_B1GdzTK9DXx.html|last=Ortelli|first=Ignacio|work=[[Clarin (Argentina)|Clarin]]|date=10  September 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> After Del Ca\u00f1o's complaint, judge Sandra Arroyo Salgado ordered that the National Gendarmerie could no longer make operations within the highway.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gendarmer\u00eda no podr\u00e1 intervenir m\u00e1s en los cortes de ruta en la Panamericana|url=https://www.infobae.com/2014/11/04/1606561-gendarmeria-no-podra-intervenir-mas-los-cortes-ruta-la-panamericana/|work=Infobae|date=4  November 2014|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref>\n\n== Presidential candidate ==\n{{Main|2015 Argentine general election}}\n[[File:Montagem dos candidatos \u00e0 presid\u00eancia da Argentina em 2015.jpg|200px|thumb|Above: [[Adolfo Rodr\u00edguez Sa\u00e1]], [[Daniel Scioli]], [[Margarita Stolbizer]]. Below: [[Mauricio Macri]], Del Ca\u00f1o and [[Sergio Massa]]. 2015 presidential candidates.]]\nIn 2015 he was the FIT's candidate for mayor of Mendoza, managing to obtain 16,9% of votes in second place, surpassing the official candidate Carlos Aranda of the [[Front for Victory]], a result never before seen for any leftist force to an executive position in the country.<ref>http://www.ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar/padron</ref><ref>http://www.mendozapost.com/nota/9751/</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=El FIT qued\u00f3 segundo, desplaz\u00f3 al PJ y gan\u00f3 un edil.|url=https://losandes.com.ar/article/el-fit-quedo-segundo-desplazo-al-pj-y-gano-un-edil|work=Diario Los Andes|last=Olivera|first=Cinthia|date=4  May 2015|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> Later that year he was the FIT's presidential candidate, managing to win the primary election against [[Jorge Altamira]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Ruiz|first=Iv\u00e1n|title=Del Ca\u00f1o rompi\u00f3 todos los pron\u00f3sticos y super\u00f3 a Altamira en la interna de la izquierda|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/1817973-del-cano-rompio-todos-los-pronosticos-y-supero-a-altamira-en-la-interna-de-la-izquierda|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n (Argentina)|La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=10  August 2015|accessdate=30  October 2018}}.</ref> and getting fourth place in the presidential elections in October with 3,27% of votes.\n\n== 2017 elections ==\nIn March 2017, the PTS announced Del Ca\u00f1o as pre-candidate to deputy for the Province of Buenos Aires to represent the FIT in the [[2017 Argentine legislative election|legislative elections]]. This had negative repercussions from the rest of the FIT's member parties, since they argued that they should have presented common lists to prevent quarrels within the FIT. [[N\u00e9stor Pitrola]] ([[Workers' Party (Argentina)|PO]]) was especially emphatic about Del Ca\u00f1o appearing as pre-candidate for the Province of Buenos Aires when the previous election he had already contended as deputy for Mendoza. He said: \"they bring Del Ca\u00f1o as candidate for the province where he has no relation. This is parachuting him in the same style as the other parties and will undoubtedly affect the FIT in Mendoza\". [[Juan Carlos Giordano]] ([[Socialist Left (Argentina)|IS]]) declared: \"We do not agree with the PTS in presenting their electoral campaign one-sidedly when the right thing to do is that all three parties do so and present a unified list\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Soria Guadalupe |first1=Alan |last2=Silva da Sousa |first2=Marcelo |title=El PTS ya present\u00f3 candidatos y hay enojos en el Frente de Izquierda |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1993319-el-pts-ya-presento-candidatos-y-hay-enojos-en-el-frente-de-izquierda |newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n (Argentina)|La Naci\u00f3n]] |date=14 March 2017 |access-date=22 May 2017}}.</ref> In that sense, Giordano himself, representing his party, made a proposition to prevent inner squarrels in the FIT, consisting in presenting Pitrola as heading the list for deputies and Del Ca\u00f1o heading the list for senators<ref>{{cite web |title=Propuesta para lista \u00fanica del FIT en las PASO: Del Ca\u00f1o (PTS) Senador - Pitrola (PO) Diputado |url=http://www.izquierdasocialista.org.ar/index.php/elecciones-2013-fit/5648-propuesta-para-lista-unica-del-fit-en-las-paso-del-cano-pts-senador-pitrola-po-diputado |newspaper=Izquierda Socialista |date=21 May 2017 |access-date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, the FIT agreed in unified lists for all districts where they contended, with Nicol\u00e1s Del Ca\u00f1o as candidate for the Province of Buenos Aires and N\u00e9stor Pitrola as candidate for senator.<ref>{{cite web |title=El Frente de Izquierda se adelant\u00f3 y acord\u00f3 listas de unidad |url=https://www.clarin.com/politica/frente-izquierda-adelanto-acordo-listas-unidad_0_BJcOqBTf-.html |newspaper=[[Clarin (Argentina)|Clarin]] |date=13 June 2017 |access-date=30 October 2018}}.</ref> Del Ca\u00f1o received 5,54% of votes and since December 2017 heads the bloc PTS-FIT along his comrade Nathalia Gonz\u00e1lez Seligra.<ref>{{cite web |title=Argentina: asumieron los diputados obreros y socialistas del Frente de Izquierda |url=https://www.laizquierdadiario.com/Argentina-asumieron-los-diputados-obreros-y-socialistas-del-Frente-de-Izquierda |newspaper=La Izquierda Diario |date=6 December 2017|access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2019 elections==\nHe will be the FIT-U's candidate for president, running with [[Romina Del Pl\u00e1]] for vice-president.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cano, Nicolas del}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Argentine Chamber of Deputies]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00f3rdoba Province, Argentina]]\n[[Category:Socialist Workers' Party (Argentina) politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicol%C3%A1s_del_Ca%C3%B1o"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Rochester\n| latin             = Dioecesis Roffensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = SacredHeartCathedralRochesterNewYorkWestView.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| caption           = Sacred Heart Cathedral\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n| image_alt         = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| metropolitan      = [[Timothy M. Dolan]]\n| territory         = [[Monroe County, New York|Counties of Monroe]], [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]], [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]], [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]], [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]], [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]], [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]], [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]], [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]], [[Yates County, New York|Yates]], [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] and [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of New York]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 8,772 \n| population        = 1,570,000\n| population_as_of  = 2014\n| catholics         = 350,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 23\n| parishes          = <!-- Number of parishes in the diocese --> 106\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese --> 172\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese --> 172\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese --> 27 \n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = March 3, 1868\n| cathedral         = [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[St. John Fisher]] \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese --> 251\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]\n| apostolic_admin   = \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = Very Rev. Paul J. Tomasso\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Matthew H. Clark]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Rochester map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = {{URL|http://www.dor.org}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester''' is a [[diocese]] of the [[Catholic Church]] in the Greater [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] region of [[New York State]] in the [[United States]]. The region that the Diocese comprises extends from its northern border on the south shore of [[Lake Ontario]] through the [[Finger Lakes]] region to its southern border at the [[New York (state)|New York]]-[[Pennsylvania]] border. \n\nThe Diocese of Rochester comprises 12 counties in New York, with approximately 350,000 Catholics and over 125 faith communities (parishes and chapels), 22 diocesan elementary schools and 7 independent parochial high schools. The bishop of the diocese is currently [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]. The metropolitan for the diocese is the Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York]], currently Cardinal [[Timothy Dolan]]. The [[cathedral]] [[parish]] for the diocese is [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:St. Patrick's Cathedral - Rochester, New York.jpg|thumb|right|St. Patrick's Cathedral in Rochester (1868-1937)]]\nThe Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester began on March 3, 1868, when [[Pope Pius IX]] entrusted eight counties (Monroe, Livingston, Wayne, Ontario, Seneca, Cayuga, Yates, and Tompkins) within the Diocese of Buffalo to [[Bernard J. McQuaid]], the first bishop of Rochester. The new diocese had about 54,500 Catholics in 35 parish churches and 29 mission churches.\n\nIn 1896, the counties of Schuyler, Tioga, Chemung, and Steuben were added to the Diocese of Rochester from the Diocese of Buffalo, forming the current boundaries.\n\nThe diocese grew as Catholic immigrants came to western New York, peaking in the 1960s. Since then, the Catholic population has stabilized while the numbers of ordained presbyters (priests) and women religious (sisters) has fallen.<ref>[http://www.dor.org/dorhomepage/history.htm Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester - Diocesan History]</ref>\n*In 1909, there were 121,000 Catholics in 93 parishes, 36 missions and 53 parish schools with 18,000 pupils. There were 164 priests and more than 500 sisters.\n*In 1938, there were 223,657 Catholics in 129 parishes, 36 missions and 72 parish schools serving 23,796 pupils. There were 289 active diocesan priests.\n*In 1966, there were 361,790 Catholics in 155 parishes, 36 mission churches and 99 elementary parish schools serving 45,540 pupils. There were 371 active diocesan priests and 1,549 sisters.\n*In 1978, there were 358,850 Catholics in 161 parishes, 29 mission churches and 75 schools serving 19,526 pupils. There were 311 active diocesan priests and 1,095 women religious.\n*In 1992, there were 361,384 Catholics in 162 parishes and 58 elementary schools serving 11,992 pupils. There were 208 active diocesan priests and 842 sisters.\n\nOn September 22nd 2017 the Diocese of Rochester inaugurated its sesquicentennial anniversary marked by a solemn mass at Sacred Heart Cathedral. This event marks a year long celebration celebrating one hundred and fifty years and the year of the Eucharist which was proclaimed by Bishop Salvatore Matano on the Feast of Corpus Christi.\n\n==Reports of sex abuse and bankruptcy==\n\nIn June 2018, it was revealed that the Diocese had secretly paid $1.6 million since 1950 in compensation to 20 sex abuse victims.<ref>https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/local/columnists/andreatta/2018/06/09/andreatta-diocese-rochester-has-paid-1-6-m-20-sex-abuse-victims/686390002/</ref> Most of the payments occurred after the eruption of the 2002 clergy sex abuse scandal, although some are decades old. On June 10, 2019, a man claiming that he had been molested between 1969 and 1971 by local priest Rev. Francis Vogt filed a lawsuit against the Diocese of Rochester and several other local Catholic organizations affiliated the Diocese, claiming that they shielded Vogt from potential prosecution.<ref name=grownnot>https://13wham.com/news/local/victim-sues-diocese-of-rochester-over-claims-of-sexual-abuse-by-priest</ref> On September 12, 2019, the Diocese filed for [[Chapter 11 Bankruptcy]] in the wake of lawsuits against priests and other ministers who served in the Diocese.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2019/09/12/rochester-ny-catholic-diocese-bankruptcy-sex-abuse-lawsuits-child-victims-act-cva-chapter-11/2297878001/|title=Diocese bankruptcy: Matano says it was 'a very difficult and painful decision'|last=Orr|first=Steve|date=September 12, 2019|work=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> <ref name=protectionnotgood /> The Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester is the first Catholic diocese in the state of New York to file for bankruptcy and also the 20th Catholic diocese in the U.S. to do so.<ref name=protectionnotgood>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/09/12/catholic-sex-abuse-rochester-diocese-files-bankruptcy-protection/2308133001/</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\nThe following are lists of bishops and their years of service:\n\n===Bishops of Rochester===\n# [[Bernard J. McQuaid]] (1868-1909)\n# [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1909-1928), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[John Francis O'Hern]] (1929-1933)\n# [[Edward Aloysius Mooney|Edward A. Mooney]] (1933-1937), Archbishop (ad personam), appointed [[Archdiocese of Detroit|Archbishop of Detroit]] ([[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] in 1946)\n# [[James E. Kearney]] (1937-1966)\n# Venerable [[Fulton J. Sheen]] (1966-1969), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[Joseph Lloyd Hogan]] (1969-1978) \n# [[Matthew H. Clark]] (1979-2012) \n# [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]] (2014-present)\n\n===Coadjutor Bishop===\n* [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1905-1909)\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n* [[Lawrence B. Casey]] (1953-1966), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Paterson|Bishop of Paterson]]\n* [[John Edgar McCafferty]] (1968-1980)\n* [[Dennis Walter Hickey]] (1968-1990)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Edward Joseph Hanna]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Auxiliary Bishop of San Francisco]] in 1912 and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Archbishop of San Francisco]]\n*[[Walter Andrew Foery]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1937\n*[[James Michael Moynihan]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1995\n\n==Schools==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Superintendents of the Monroe County Catholic School System'''\n|-\n! Name !! Tenure\n|-\n|  Sr. Roberta Tierney, [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|SSND]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sr. Roberta Tierney; directed education - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/obituaries/sr-roberta-tierney-directed-education/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n||  1976 \u2013 1978 \n|-\n|Timothy Leahy\n|1978 - 1979\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/in-depth/back-to-school/previous-stories/siena-principal-taught-responsibility/?keywords=Timothy%20Leahy&tag=&searc