mily School, Dansville, Livingston County\n*All Saints Catholic Academy, Gates\n*Catherine McAuley, Greece\n*Corpus Christi, Rochester\n*Good Shepherd, Henrietta\n*Holy Cross, Rochester (reopened in 2011)\n*Holy Family, Rochester\n*Holy Trinity, Webster\n*St. Andrews, Rochester\n*St. Boniface, Rochester\n*St. John of Rochester, Fairport\n*St. John the Evangelist, Spencerport\n*St. Margaret Mary, Irondequoit\n*St. Monica, Rochester\n\n===High schools===\nThere remain five traditionally Catholic high schools (or combined junior/senior high schools) in the diocese.  These schools were founded by various [[Religious institute (Catholic)|Roman Catholic religious orders]] and operate independently of the diocese itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''\n|-\n! School !! Founding Religious Order !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| [[Aquinas Institute]] || [[Congregation of St. Basil|Basilian]] || [[Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 1902 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Bishop Kearney High School (Irondequoit, New York)|Bishop Kearney High School]] || [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]], [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|Sisters of Notre Dame]] || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || 1962 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] || [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1954 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Notre Dame High School (Elmira, New York)|Notre Dame High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || 1955 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of Mercy High School (New York)|Our Lady of Mercy High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1928 || Grades 6 through 12\n|}\n<gallery>\nFile:Aquinas Institute front entrance.JPG|Aquinas Institute\nFile:Bishop Kearney High School.JPG|Bishop Kearney High School\nFile:McQuaidJesuitHighSchoolFrontEntranceB.JPG|McQuaid Jesuit High School\nFile:GreeceOdysseyAcademyFrontEntrance.JPG|The former Cardinal Mooney High School\n</gallery>\n\n====Former high schools====\n*Academy of the Sacred Heart, Rochester, Monroe County, 1855\u20131969\n*[[Cardinal Mooney High School (Greece, New York)|Cardinal Mooney High School]], Greece, Monroe County, 1962\u20131989\n*[[DeSales High School (Geneva, New York)|DeSales High School]], Geneva, Ontario County, 1912\u20132012\n*[[Nazareth Academy (Rochester, New York)|Nazareth Academy]], Rochester, Monroe County, 1871\u20132010\n*St. Agnes High School, Rochester, Monroe County, 1954\u20131982\n*King's Preparatory, Rochester, Monroe County, 1967-1970\n*St. Anthony of Padua College Prep School, Watkins Glen, Schuyler County, 1949-1970\n\n===Former seminaries===\n*St. Andrew's Preparatory Seminary, 1870\u20131967\n*[[Saint Bernard's Seminary]], 1893\u20131981\n\n===Former liberal arts colleges===\n*[[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College for Women]], became independent in the 1970s\n*[[St. John Fisher College|St. John Fisher College for Men]], became independent in 1968\n\n==Former charitable institutions==\n*St. Ann's Home (now St. Ann's Community)\n*St. Joseph's Orphan Asylum (later St. Joseph's Villa, now Villa of Hope)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://villaofhope.org/About-Us/History | title = Villa of Hope History | year = 2020 | work = Organization website | publisher = Villa of Hope | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2020-02-28}}</ref>\n*St. Mary's Boys' Home\n*St. Mary's Hospital, Rochester, Monroe County\n*St. Patrick's Girls' Home\n\n==Counties==\nThis is a list of the counties in [[New York State]] that fall into the Diocese of Rochester:\n* [[Monroe County, New York|Monroe]]\n* [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]]\n* [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]]\n* [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]]\n* [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]]\n* [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]]\n* [[Yates County, New York|Yates]]\n* [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]]\n* [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] (added in 1896)\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = CoA_Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester.svg\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Arms was designed and adopted when the diocese was erected. It was designed in the 1930s by Pierre LaRose\n|year_adopted      = 1868\n|crest             =\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        =  The arms of the diocese are composed of a [[saltire]] with a crescent in the center.\n|supporters        =\n|compartment       =\n|motto             = \n|orders            =\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         =  The St. Andrew's Cross (saltire) was taken from the coat of arms of the original [[Diocese of Rochester]] in England (now an Anglican diocese). The new design is distinguished from the original, by changing a scallop shell in the center to the crescent symbol of the Immaculate Conception. The cross emphasizes the bishop as the successor to the apostles, and the bishop's charge to preach and live the Word of God faithfully and to witness to the Resurrection. \n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dor.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester Official Site]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Diocese of Rochester}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of New York}}\n{{coord|43|09|56|N|77|36|41|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester|*]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Rochester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Rochester\n| latin             = Dioecesis Roffensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = SacredHeartCathedralRochesterNewYorkWestView.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| caption           = Sacred Heart Cathedral\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n| image_alt         = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| metropolitan      = [[Timothy M. Dolan]]\n| territory         = [[Monroe County, New York|Counties of Monroe]], [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]], [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]], [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]], [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]], [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]], [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]], [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]], [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]], [[Yates County, New York|Yates]], [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] and [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of New York]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 8,772 \n| population        = 1,570,000\n| population_as_of  = 2014\n| catholics         = 350,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 23\n| parishes          = <!-- Number of parishes in the diocese --> 106\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese --> 172\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese --> 172\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese --> 27 \n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = March 3, 1868\n| cathedral         = [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[St. John Fisher]] \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese --> 251\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]\n| apostolic_admin   = \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = Very Rev. Paul J. Tomasso\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Matthew H. Clark]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Rochester map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = {{URL|http://www.dor.org}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester''' is a [[diocese]] of the [[Catholic Church]] in the Greater [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] region of [[New York State]] in the [[United States]]. The region that the Diocese comprises extends from its northern border on the south shore of [[Lake Ontario]] through the [[Finger Lakes]] region to its southern border at the [[New York (state)|New York]]-[[Pennsylvania]] border. \n\nThe Diocese of Rochester comprises 12 counties in New York, with approximately 350,000 Catholics and over 125 faith communities (parishes and chapels), 22 diocesan elementary schools and 7 independent parochial high schools. The bishop of the diocese is currently [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]. The metropolitan for the diocese is the Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York]], currently Cardinal [[Timothy Dolan]]. The [[cathedral]] [[parish]] for the diocese is [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:St. Patrick's Cathedral - Rochester, New York.jpg|thumb|left|St. Patrick's Cathedral in Rochester (1868-1937)]]\nThe Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester began on March 3, 1868, when [[Pope Pius IX]] entrusted eight counties (Monroe, Livingston, Wayne, Ontario, Seneca, Cayuga, Yates, and Tompkins) within the Diocese of Buffalo to [[Bernard J. McQuaid]], the first bishop of Rochester. The new diocese had about 54,500 Catholics in 35 parish churches and 29 mission churches.\n\nIn 1896, the counties of Schuyler, Tioga, Chemung, and Steuben were added to the Diocese of Rochester from the Diocese of Buffalo, forming the current boundaries.\n\nThe diocese grew as Catholic immigrants came to western New York, peaking in the 1960s. Since then, the Catholic population has stabilized while the numbers of ordained presbyters (priests) and women religious (sisters) has fallen.<ref>[http://www.dor.org/dorhomepage/history.htm Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester - Diocesan History]</ref>\n*In 1909, there were 121,000 Catholics in 93 parishes, 36 missions and 53 parish schools with 18,000 pupils. There were 164 priests and more than 500 sisters.\n*In 1938, there were 223,657 Catholics in 129 parishes, 36 missions and 72 parish schools serving 23,796 pupils. There were 289 active diocesan priests.\n*In 1966, there were 361,790 Catholics in 155 parishes, 36 mission churches and 99 elementary parish schools serving 45,540 pupils. There were 371 active diocesan priests and 1,549 sisters.\n*In 1978, there were 358,850 Catholics in 161 parishes, 29 mission churches and 75 schools serving 19,526 pupils. There were 311 active diocesan priests and 1,095 women religious.\n*In 1992, there were 361,384 Catholics in 162 parishes and 58 elementary schools serving 11,992 pupils. There were 208 active diocesan priests and 842 sisters.\n\nOn September 22nd 2017 the Diocese of Rochester inaugurated its sesquicentennial anniversary marked by a solemn mass at Sacred Heart Cathedral. This event marks a year long celebration celebrating one hundred and fifty years and the year of the Eucharist which was proclaimed by Bishop Salvatore Matano on the Feast of Corpus Christi.\n\n==Reports of sex abuse and bankruptcy==\n\nIn June 2018, it was revealed that the Diocese had secretly paid $1.6 million since 1950 in compensation to 20 sex abuse victims.<ref>https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/local/columnists/andreatta/2018/06/09/andreatta-diocese-rochester-has-paid-1-6-m-20-sex-abuse-victims/686390002/</ref> Most of the payments occurred after the eruption of the 2002 clergy sex abuse scandal, although some are decades old. On June 10, 2019, a man claiming that he had been molested between 1969 and 1971 by local priest Rev. Francis Vogt filed a lawsuit against the Diocese of Rochester and several other local Catholic organizations affiliated the Diocese, claiming that they shielded Vogt from potential prosecution.<ref name=grownnot>https://13wham.com/news/local/victim-sues-diocese-of-rochester-over-claims-of-sexual-abuse-by-priest</ref> On September 12, 2019, the Diocese filed for [[Chapter 11 Bankruptcy]] in the wake of lawsuits against priests and other ministers who served in the Diocese.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2019/09/12/rochester-ny-catholic-diocese-bankruptcy-sex-abuse-lawsuits-child-victims-act-cva-chapter-11/2297878001/|title=Diocese bankruptcy: Matano says it was 'a very difficult and painful decision'|last=Orr|first=Steve|date=September 12, 2019|work=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> <ref name=protectionnotgood /> The Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester is the first Catholic diocese in the state of New York to file for bankruptcy and also the 20th Catholic diocese in the U.S. to do so.<ref name=protectionnotgood>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/09/12/catholic-sex-abuse-rochester-diocese-files-bankruptcy-protection/2308133001/</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\nThe following are lists of bishops and their years of service:\n\n===Bishops of Rochester===\n# [[Bernard J. McQuaid]] (1868-1909)\n# [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1909-1928), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[John Francis O'Hern]] (1929-1933)\n# [[Edward Aloysius Mooney|Edward A. Mooney]] (1933-1937), Archbishop (ad personam), appointed [[Archdiocese of Detroit|Archbishop of Detroit]] ([[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] in 1946)\n# [[James E. Kearney]] (1937-1966)\n# Venerable [[Fulton J. Sheen]] (1966-1969), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[Joseph Lloyd Hogan]] (1969-1978) \n# [[Matthew H. Clark]] (1979-2012) \n# [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]] (2014-present)\n\n===Coadjutor Bishop===\n* [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1905-1909)\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n* [[Lawrence B. Casey]] (1953-1966), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Paterson|Bishop of Paterson]]\n* [[John Edgar McCafferty]] (1968-1980)\n* [[Dennis Walter Hickey]] (1968-1990)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Edward Joseph Hanna]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Auxiliary Bishop of San Francisco]] in 1912 and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Archbishop of San Francisco]]\n*[[Walter Andrew Foery]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1937\n*[[James Michael Moynihan]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1995\n\n==Schools==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Superintendents of the Monroe County Catholic School System'''\n|-\n! Name !! Tenure\n|-\n|  Sr. Roberta Tierney, [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|SSND]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sr. Roberta Tierney; directed education - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/obituaries/sr-roberta-tierney-directed-education/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n||  1976 \u2013 1978 \n|-\n|Timothy Leahy\n|1978 - 1979\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/in-depth/back-to-school/previous-stories/siena-principal-taught-responsibility/?keywords=Timothy%20Leahy&tag=&searchSectionID=\n|Rev. Richard C. Kinsky, CSB\n|1979 - 1981\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/news/obituaries/father-richard-c-kinsky-csb-76/\n|Sr. Edwardine Weaver, RSM\n|1981 - 1986\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/in-depth/milestonesvocations/milestones-vocations-2013/sisters-of-mercy-mark-a-total-of-955-years-of-service/?keywords=Edwardine%20Weaver,%20RSM&tag=&searchSectionID=\n|Br. Brian Walsh, [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|CFC]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = New schools head brings fresh ideas - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/local-news/new-schools-head-brings-fresh-ideas/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n|July 1986 \u2013 1 July 1991\n|-\n|Sr. Mary Ann Binsack, [[Religious Sisters of Mercy|RSM]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://lib.catholiccourier.com/1992-catholic-courier/catholic-courier-1992%20-%200447.pdf|title = Schools superintendent to stress long view|last = Cullivan|first = Rob|date = May 28, 1992|work = Catholic Courier|access-date = November 25, 2015|via = }}</ref>\n|1991 \u2013 1992\n|-\n| Timothy W. Dwyer<ref name=\":0\" /> || 1992 \u2013 2001\n|-\n| Sr. Elizabeth Meegan, [[Dominican Order|OP]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = New schools head brings fresh ideas - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/local-news/new-schools-head-brings-fresh-ideas/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> || 2001 \u2013 2006\n|-\n| Sr. Elaine Poitras, CSC<ref name=\":1\" /> || 2006 \u2013 January 2008\n|-\n| Sr. Janice Morgan, [[Sisters of St. Joseph|CSJ]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = DOR Catholic: Update on Sister Janice Morgan|url = http://dorcatholic.blogspot.com/2009/02/update-on-sister-janice-morgan.html|website = DOR Catholic|date = 2009-02-27|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> || January 2008 \u2013 August 2008\n|-\n| Anne Willkens Leach || August 2008 \u2013 July 2013\n|-\n| Anthony S. Cook III<ref>http://www.dor.org/index.cfm/news/news-docs/new-schools-superintendent-named/</ref> || 1 July 2013 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n===Primary schools===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dorschools.org/discover-our-schools | title = Discover Our Schools | year = 2012 | work = Catholic Schools Diocese of Rochester | publisher = Diocese of Rochester | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2013-01-02}}</ref>\n|-\n! School !! Parish !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| All Saints Academy || St. Mary || [[Corning (city), New York|Corning, Steuben County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 8\n|-\n| Holy Cross School || Holy Cross || [[Charlotte, Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 2011 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| Holy Family Primary School || St. Mary || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Agnes School || St. Agnes || [[Avon (village), New York|Avon, Livingston County]] || 1878 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Francis de Sales - St. Stephen School || Our Lady of Peace || [[Geneva, New York|Geneva, Ontario County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 8\n|-\n| St. John Neumann School || St. John the Evangelist || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Joseph Elementary School || St. Joseph || [[Auburn, New York|Auburn, Cayuga County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 5\n|-\n| St. Joseph School || St. Joseph || [[Penfield, New York|Penfield, Monroe County]] || 1960 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Kateri School || Christ the King || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Lawrence School || St. Lawrence || [[Greece (town), New York|Greece, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Louis School || St. Louis || [[Pittsford, New York|Pittsford, Monroe County]] || || Pre-School through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Mary School || St. Mary || [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua, Ontario County]] || 1849 || K through Grade 8\n|-\n| St. Mary Our Mother School || St. Mary Our Mother || [[Horseheads, New York|Horseheads, Chemung County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Michael School || St. Michael || [[Penn Yan, New York|Penn Yan, Yates County]] || 1882 || Pre-K through Grade 5\n|-\n| [[Saint Pius X School|St. Pius X School]] || St. Pius X || [[Chili, New York|Chili, Monroe County]] || 1954 || Pre-K through Grade 5\n|-\n| St. Rita School || St. Rita || [[Webster, New York|Webster, Monroe County]] || |1957|| Pre-K through Grade 5\n|-\n| Seton Catholic School || Our Lady of Lourdes/St. Anne || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1948 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| Siena Catholic Academy || St. Thomas More || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1993 || Grades 6, 7, and 8\n|-\n|}\n\n\n====Former primary schools====\nOver the years, as Catholic populations moved to the suburbs, the Diocese has closed parishes and their schools.  These include the former Holy Apostles, Holy Redeemer, Holy Rosary, Immaculate Conception, Our Lady of Mt. Carmel, Our Lady of Perpetual Help, Our Lady of Victory, Sacred Heart, St. Anthony of Padua, St. Augustine, St. Casimir, St. Francis Xavier, St. Helen, St. John the Evangelist, St. Joseph, St. Lucy, St. Mary, St. Michael, St. Patrick, Ss. Peter and Paul, St. Stanislaus, and St. Theresa.\n\nIn 2008, facing growing deficits and declining enrollments, the Diocese closed the following schools:<ref>{{Citation | publication-date = 2008-01-19 | title = As Bishop Announces Closures, Catholic High Schools Plan to Expand | newspaper = Rochester [[Democrat and Chronicle]] | publication-place = [[Rochester, New York]] | page = | issn = 1088-5153 | url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080119/NEWS01/801190326/1002/NEWS | accessdate = 2013-01-02 | archiveurl = http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news2008/01_02/2008_01_19_Bryant_AsBishop.htm | archivedate = 2008}}</ref>\n*Holy Family School, Dansville, Livingston County\n*All Saints Catholic Academy, Gates\n*Catherine McAuley, Greece\n*Corpus Christi, Rochester\n*Good Shepherd, Henrietta\n*Holy Cross, Rochester (reopened in 2011)\n*Holy Family, Rochester\n*Holy Trinity, Webster\n*St. Andrews, Rochester\n*St. Boniface, Rochester\n*St. John of Rochester, Fairport\n*St. John the Evangelist, Spencerport\n*St. Margaret Mary, Irondequoit\n*St. Monica, Rochester\n\n===High schools===\nThere remain five traditionally Catholic high schools (or combined junior/senior high schools) in the diocese.  These schools were founded by various [[Religious institute (Catholic)|Roman Catholic religious orders]] and operate independently of the diocese itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''\n|-\n! School !! Founding Religious Order !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| [[Aquinas Institute]] || [[Congregation of St. Basil|Basilian]] || [[Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 1902 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Bishop Kearney High School (Irondequoit, New York)|Bishop Kearney High School]] || [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]], [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|Sisters of Notre Dame]] || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || 1962 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] || [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1954 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Notre Dame High School (Elmira, New York)|Notre Dame High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || 1955 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of Mercy High School (New York)|Our Lady of Mercy High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1928 || Grades 6 through 12\n|}\n<gallery>\nFile:Aquinas Institute front entrance.JPG|Aquinas Institute\nFile:Bishop Kearney High School.JPG|Bishop Kearney High School\nFile:McQuaidJesuitHighSchoolFrontEntranceB.JPG|McQuaid Jesuit High School\nFile:GreeceOdysseyAcademyFrontEntrance.JPG|The former Cardinal Mooney High School\n</gallery>\n\n====Former high schools====\n*Academy of the Sacred Heart, Rochester, Monroe County, 1855\u20131969\n*[[Cardinal Mooney High School (Greece, New York)|Cardinal Mooney High School]], Greece, Monroe County, 1962\u20131989\n*[[DeSales High School (Geneva, New York)|DeSales High School]], Geneva, Ontario County, 1912\u20132012\n*[[Nazareth Academy (Rochester, New York)|Nazareth Academy]], Rochester, Monroe County, 1871\u20132010\n*St. Agnes High School, Rochester, Monroe County, 1954\u20131982\n*King's Preparatory, Rochester, Monroe County, 1967-1970\n*St. Anthony of Padua College Prep School, Watkins Glen, Schuyler County, 1949-1970\n\n===Former seminaries===\n*St. Andrew's Preparatory Seminary, 1870\u20131967\n*[[Saint Bernard's Seminary]], 1893\u20131981\n\n===Former liberal arts colleges===\n*[[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College for Women]], became independent in the 1970s\n*[[St. John Fisher College|St. John Fisher College for Men]], became independent in 1968\n\n==Former charitable institutions==\n*St. Ann's Home (now St. Ann's Community)\n*St. Joseph's Orphan Asylum (later St. Joseph's Villa, now Villa of Hope)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://villaofhope.org/About-Us/History | title = Villa of Hope History | year = 2020 | work = Organization website | publisher = Villa of Hope | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2020-02-28}}</ref>\n*St. Mary's Boys' Home\n*St. Mary's Hospital, Rochester, Monroe County\n*St. Patrick's Girls' Home\n\n==Counties==\nThis is a list of the counties in [[New York State]] that fall into the Diocese of Rochester:\n* [[Monroe County, New York|Monroe]]\n* [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]]\n* [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]]\n* [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]]\n* [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]]\n* [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]]\n* [[Yates County, New York|Yates]]\n* [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]]\n* [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] (added in 1896)\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = CoA_Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester.svg\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Arms was designed and adopted when the diocese was erected. It was designed in the 1930s by Pierre LaRose\n|year_adopted      = 1868\n|crest             =\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        =  The arms of the diocese are composed of a [[saltire]] with a crescent in the center.\n|supporters        =\n|compartment       =\n|motto             = \n|orders            =\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         =  The St. Andrew's Cross (saltire) was taken from the coat of arms of the original [[Diocese of Rochester]] in England (now an Anglican diocese). The new design is distinguished from the original, by changing a scallop shell in the center to the crescent symbol of the Immaculate Conception. The cross emphasizes the bishop as the successor to the apostles, and the bishop's charge to preach and live the Word of God faithfully and to witness to the Resurrection. \n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dor.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester Official Site]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Diocese of Rochester}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of New York}}\n{{coord|43|09|56|N|77|36|41|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester|*]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Rochester]]\n", "name_user": "Freddiem", "label": "safe", "comment": "moved image so as not to obstruct bullets", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester"}
{"title_page": "History of the Washington Nationals", "text_new": "The [[Washington Nationals]] are a [[Major League Baseball]] team formed in 1969 as the [[Montreal Expos]]. In 2005, the Expos moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] and were renamed the Nationals. The franchise won the [[List of National League pennant winners|National League pennant]] in 2019, and has won its division five times. They won the [[World Series]] in 2019 against the [[Astros]] in game 7.\n\n==History==\n\n===Montreal Expos===\n{{Main|Montreal Expos}}\nThe Montreal Expos joined the [[National League]] in [[1969 Major League Baseball season|1969]], along with the [[San Diego Padres]], with a majority share held by [[Charles Bronfman]], a major shareholder in [[Seagram]]. Named after the [[Expo 67]] [[World's Fair]], the Expos' initial home was [[Jarry Park Stadium|Jarry Park]]. Managed by [[Gene Mauch]], the team lost 110 games in their first season, coincidentally matching the Padres inaugural win-loss record, and continued to struggle during their first decade with sub-.500 seasons.\n\nStarting in [[1977 Major League Baseball season|1977]], the team's home venue was Montreal's [[Olympic Stadium (Montreal)|Olympic Stadium]], built for the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. Two years later, the team won a franchise-high 95 games, finishing second in the National League East. The Expos began the 1980s with a core group of young players, including catcher [[Gary Carter]], outfielders [[Tim Raines]] and [[Andre Dawson]], third baseman [[Tim Wallach]], and pitchers [[Steve Rogers (baseball)|Steve Rogers]] and [[Bill Gullickson]]. The team won its only division championship in the strike-shortened split season of [[1981 in baseball|1981]], ending its season with a three games to two loss to the [[1981 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the [[1981 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]].\n\nThe team spent most of the 1980s in the middle of the NL East pack, finishing in third or fourth place in eight out of nine seasons from 1982 to 1990. [[Buck Rodgers]] was hired as manager before the [[1985 Major League Baseball season|1985 season]] and guided the Expos to a .500 or better record five times in six years, with the highlight coming in [[1987 Major League Baseball season|1987]], when they won 91 games. They finished third, but were just four games behind the division-winning [[1987 St. Louis Cardinals|Cardinals]].\n\nBronfman sold the team to a consortium of owners in 1991, with [[Claude Brochu]] as the managing general partner.<ref name=\"ExposGuide1996\">{{Cite book\n| author=Montreal Expos\n| authorlink=Montreal Expos\n| title=Expos Media Guide 1996\n| year=1996 }}</ref><ref name=\"1991June-Gazette\">{{Cite news\n  | last=Blair\n  | first=Jeff\n  | title=Brochu group goes to bat for baseball survival here; Expos sale official as Bronfman era ends\n  | newspaper=Montreal Gazette\n  | pages=C.1\n  | date=1991-06-15 }}</ref>\nRodgers, at that time second only to Gene Mauch in number of Expos games managed, was replaced partway through the [[1991 Major League Baseball season|1991 season]]. In May [[1992 Major League Baseball season|1992]], [[Felipe Alou]], a member of the Expos organization since 1976, was promoted to field manager, becoming the first Dominican-born manager in MLB history.<ref name=\"ExposGuide1996\"/> Alou would become the leader in Expos games managed, while guiding the team to winning records, including [[1994 Major League Baseball season|1994]], when the Expos, led by a talented group of players including [[Larry Walker]], [[Mois\u00e9s Alou]], [[Marquis Grissom]] and [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]], had the best record in the major leagues until the [[1994\u201395 Major League Baseball strike]] forced the cancellation of the remainder of the season. After the disappointment of 1994, Expos management began shedding its key players, and the team's fan support dwindled.\n\nBrochu sold control of the team to [[Jeffrey Loria]] in [[1999 Major League Baseball season|1999]],<ref name=\"ExposGuide2000\">{{Cite book\n| author=Montreal Expos\n| authorlink=Montreal Expos\n| title=Expos Media Guide 2000\n| year=2000\n| publisher=\n| location=\n| id=\n}}</ref><ref name=\"GlobeAndMail-LoriaPurchase\">{{Cite news\n  | last=Blair\n  | first=Jeff\n  | title=Expos to field better team, Loria says Ebullient new chairman vows to increase salary limit, build new ballpark for 2002 season\n  | newspaper=The Globe and Mail\n  | pages=S.1\n  | publisher=The Globe and Mail\n  | date=1999-12-10 }}\n</ref>\nbut Loria failed to close on a plan to build a new downtown ballpark, and did not reach an agreement on television and English radio broadcast contracts for the [[2000 Major League Baseball season|2000 season]], reducing the team's media coverage.\n\n====2001 contraction====\n{{main|2001 Major League Baseball contraction plan}}\nIn November 2001, Major League Baseball's owners voted 28\u20132 to contract the league by two teams \u2014 according to various sources, the Expos and the Minnesota Twins, both of which reportedly voted against contraction.<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\">{{cite web\n  | last=Schoenfield\n  | first=David\n  | title=Still 30 teams: Contraction timeline\n  | publisher=ESPN.com\n  | date=2002-02-05\n  | url=http://assets.espn.go.com/mlb/s/2002/0205/1323230.html\n  | accessdate=2009-02-19 }}</ref>\nSubsequently, the [[Boston Red Sox]] were sold to a partnership led by [[John W. Henry]], owner of the [[Florida Marlins]].<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/><ref>{{Cite book\n  | last=Mnookin\n  | first=Seth\n  | title=Feeding the Monster. How Money, Smarts, and Nerve Took a Team to the Top.\n  | publisher=Simon & Schuster\n  | year=2006\n  | location=New York\n  | isbn=0-7432-8681-2 }}\n</ref>\nIn order to clear the way for Henry's group to assume ownership of the Red Sox, Henry sold the Marlins to Loria, and baseball purchased the Expos from Loria.<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/>\nHowever, as the [[Metropolitan Sports Facilities Commission]], operator of the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome|Metrodome]], won an injunction requiring the Twins to play there in [[2002 Major League Baseball season|2002]],<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/> MLB was unable to revoke the Twins franchise, and so had to keep the Twins and Expos as part of the [[Major League Baseball schedule|regular season schedule]]. In the collective bargaining agreement signed with the [[Major League Baseball Players Association]] (MLBPA) in August 2002, contraction was prohibited through to the end of the contract in 2006.<ref>{{cite press release\n  | title=Deal in place, games go on\n  | publisher=MLB.com\n  | date=2002-08-30\n  | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/mlb/news/mlb_news.jsp?ymd=20020830&content_id=116907&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp\n  | accessdate=2006-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Creation of the Nationals===\nWith contraction no longer an option for the immediate term, MLB began looking for a relocation site for the Expos. Some of the choices included [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]]; Washington, D.C.; [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]; [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]]; [[Portland, Oregon]]; somewhere in [[Northern Virginia]] such as [[Arlington, Virginia|Arlington]] or [[Dulles, Virginia|Dulles]]; [[Norfolk, Virginia]]; [[Las Vegas]]; and [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].  Washington and Virginia emerged as the front-runners.\n\nIn both [[2003 Major League Baseball season|2003]] and [[2004 Major League Baseball season|2004]], the Expos played 22 of their home games in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] at the [[Hiram Bithorn Stadium]], and the remaining 59 in Montreal.\n\nOn September 29, 2004, MLB announced that the Expos would move to Washington, D.C. in [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005]].<ref name=\"Myles-Gazette-2004-09-30\">{{cite news |last=Myles |first=Stephanie |title=31,395 say goodbye |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |pages=C1 | date=2004-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bloom |first=Barry M. |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20040929&content_id=875100&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=MLB selects D.C. for Expos |work=[[MLB.com]] |date=2004-09-29 |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Expos played their final game on October 3 at [[Shea Stadium]], losing by a score of 8\u20131 against the [[2004 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], the same opponent that the Expos first faced at its start, 35 years earlier. On November 15, a lawsuit by the former team owners against MLB and former majority owner Jeffrey Loria was struck down by arbitrators, bringing to an end all legal actions that would impede a move. The owners of the other MLB teams approved the move to Washington in a 28\u20131 vote on December 3 ([[Baltimore Orioles]] owner [[Peter Angelos]] cast the sole dissenting vote).\n\n===Washington baseball history revived===\n{{Main|History of Washington, D.C. professional baseball}}\n\nNumerous professional baseball teams have called Washington, D.C. home. The [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]], a founding member of the [[American League]], played in the nation's capital from 1901 to 1960 before moving to Minnesota and becoming the [[Minnesota Twins|Twins]]. These Senators were owned by [[Clark Griffith]] and played in [[Griffith Stadium]]. With notable stars including [[Walter Johnson]] and [[Joe Cronin]], the Senators won the [[1924 World Series]] and pennants in [[1925 World Series|1925]] and [[1933 World Series|1933]], but were more often unsuccessful and moved to Minnesota for the [[1961 Major League Baseball season|1961 season]] where the team was renamed the Minnesota Twins. A second [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] team (1961\u20131971) had a winning record only once in their 11 years, though bright spots, such as slugger [[Frank Howard (baseball)|Frank Howard]], earned the love of fans. The second Senators team moved to Arlington, Texas, for the [[1972 Major League Baseball season|1972 season]] and changed their name to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], and Washington spent the next 33 years without a baseball team.\n\nAlthough there was some sentiment to revive the name Senators, political considerations factored into the choice of Nationals, a revival of the first American League franchise's \"official\" nickname used from [[1905 Major League Baseball season|1905]] to [[1956 Major League Baseball season|1956]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dcvote.org/media/media.cfm?mediaID=1098&year=2005 | work=DCVote.org | title=Media Center | accessdate=September 24, 2010}}</ref> Politicians and others in the District of Columbia objected to the name Senators because the District of Columbia does not have [[District of Columbia voting rights|voting representation in Congress]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A1767-2004Oct1?language=printer | work=The Washington Post | title=The District's Senators Shouldn't Wear Cleats| date=October 3, 2004}}</ref> In addition, the Rangers still owned the rights to the Senators name,<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/expos/2004-11-19-nats-nickname_x.htm?loc=interstitialskip | work=USA Today | title=In Washington, it'll be \"Let's go Nats\"|date=November 22, 2004}}</ref> although the\nNationals were able to acquire the rights to the curly \"W\" from the Rangers.\n\nWashington, D.C., mayor [[Anthony A. Williams]] supported the name \"Washington Grays\", in honor of the Negro-league team the [[Homestead Grays]] (1929\u20131950), which had been based in [[Pittsburgh]], but played many of their home games in Washington. In the end, the team owners chose the name \"Washington Nationals\", which had been the official name of the American League's Washington Senators from 1905\u20131956.\n\n===Opposition from the Orioles===\nThe move was announced despite opposition from Peter Angelos, owner of the nearby Baltimore Orioles, who infamously announced \"There are no baseball fans in Washington, D.C. That's a fiction.\" Since 1972, the Orioles had been the only MLB franchise in the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Metropolitan Area]], which he considered a single market. Angelos contended that the Orioles would suffer financially if another team were allowed to enter the market, although the Orioles and the Washington Senators had shared the market successfully from 1954 through 1971, and four other major metropolitan areas ([[New York metropolitan area|New York]], [[Los Angeles metropolitan area|Los Angeles]], [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicago]], and [[San Francisco Bay Area]]) of roughly comparable size to Baltimore-Washington each have two MLB teams (in all cases, one each in the National and American Leagues). This reasoning disturbed many in Washington who recalled that it was the Griffith family, owners of the Washington Senators, who allowed the [[History of the St. Louis Browns|St. Louis Browns]] to move to Baltimore and become the Orioles in {{mlby|1954}} in the first place.\n\nOn March 31, 2005, Angelos and Major League Baseball struck a deal to protect the Orioles against any financial harm the Nationals might present.\n\nUnder the terms of the deal, [[List of Washington Nationals broadcasters|television and radio broadcast rights]] to Nationals games are handled by the Orioles franchise, which formed a new network (the [[Mid-Atlantic Sports Network]]) to produce and distribute the games for both franchises on both local affiliates and cable/satellite systems. MASN was not, however, immediately available on all cable providers, adding to the frustration of Nationals fans. In fact, most in the DC area missed almost the entirety of the Nationals' first two seasons. The deal with Angelos makes the Nationals the only major league baseball team that does not own its own broadcast rights.\n\n===The ballpark controversy===\n[[File:Nationals at bat.JPG|right|thumb|300px|Nationals at bat against the [[San Diego Padres]] in [[RFK Stadium]], 8 July 2006.]]\nThe team's relocation to Washington was contingent on a financing plan for the [[Nationals Park|Nationals' new stadium]]\u2014this plan quickly became the subject of much debate on the [[Council of the District of Columbia]].\n\nThree Council members who supported Mayor [[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams's]] plan were ousted in September 2004's Democratic party primary. In addition, an opinion poll conducted by ''[[The Washington Post]]'' during the peak of the controversy found that approximately two-thirds of District residents opposed the mayor's stadium plan.\n\nMuch of the controversy centered on the fact that the city would be helping finance a $581 million stadium without support from [[Maryland]] or [[Virginia]] or their counties, from which a large portion of the team's fan base would be drawn.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=3930510 | work=The Economist | title=Letters | date=April 29, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, the move to Washington itself was called into doubt when the D.C. Council sought to change details of the stadium's financing. When the Council voted on December 14, 2004 to require 50 percent private financing for any new stadium, MLB ceased promotional activities for the Nationals and announced that they would consider looking for a new market.\n\nEventually, the council passed an amended plan on December 21, 2004 that proved slightly more financially favorable to the city, while remaining acceptable to MLB. Mayor Williams signed the stadium financing package on December 30.\n\nDuring the [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005 season]], a private financing plan for construction of the stadium was negotiated between the city and a syndicate of bankers led by [[Deutsche Bank]]. The negotiations of the details ran into another problem in November 2005. The bankers requested a [[letter of credit]] or other financial guarantee of $24 million, $6 million for each of four years, insuring payment of lease revenues against various risks including poor attendance and terrorism. The city requested that Major League Baseball provide this guarantee, which they were unwilling to do.\n\nOn December 22, 2005, the ''Washington Post'' reported that Major League Baseball had specifically instructed prospective owners not to offer to pay cost overruns on the stadium if they were selected as the owners. Bidders were also told not to communicate with the press about these issues.\n\nIn February 2006, the DC City Council imposed a $611 million cap on the stadium.\n\nFinally, on March 5, Major League Baseball signed a lease for a new ballpark, agreeing to the city's $611 million cap. MLB also agreed to contribute $20 million toward the cost of the stadium, although it did not agree to cover stadium overruns. Further, MLB added the condition that excess ballpark tax revenue earmarked for debt service for the bonds be available for cost overruns. Two days later, on March 7 the DC City Council, by a vote of 9\u20134, approved a construction contract for a state-of-the-art stadium with a contemporary glass-and-stone facade, seats for 41,000 fans and a view of the U.S. Capitol, and affirmed its demand that public spending on the project be limited to $611 million. The votes were the final actions needed to satisfy the terms of the deal struck in September 2004, paving the way for the sale of the team.\n\nMajor League Baseball had agreed at the time that the franchise was moved to Washington to sell the team to an owner or ownership syndicate. Several dates for sale of the team were set and missed due to the legal wrangling regarding the building of the stadium. The delay was harshly criticized by city residents and leaders as reported in ''The Washington Post''.\n\nSelecting from a finalized group of three potential ownership syndicates, Major League Baseball announced in July 2006 that it had chosen the [[Lerner Enterprises]] group, led by billionaire [[real estate developer]] [[Theodore N. Lerner]]. The final sale price of the team was $450 million and the transfer of ownership was completed July 24, 2006. In late September 2006, [[Comcast]] finally agreed to broadcast the Nationals games.\n\n====New ownership and \"The Plan\"====\n[[File:Nationals Game - 2009 - Stierch.jpg|thumb|right|Washington Nationals versus the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in 2009 at [[Nationals Park]]]]\nWhen Ted Lerner took over the club in mid-{{MLBy|2006}}, he hired [[Stan Kasten]] as team president. Kasten was widely known as the architect of the [[Atlanta Braves]] before and during their run of 14 division titles (a streak only interrupted by the strike season of 1994, when the Braves ended the season behind the Montreal Expos \u2013 ironically, the Nationals' predecessor). Kasten was also the general manager or president of many other [[Atlanta]]-area sports teams, including the [[Atlanta Hawks]] and [[Atlanta Thrashers]]. \"The Plan\", as it became known, was a long-range rebuilding and restructuring of the team from the ground up. This plan included investing in the farm system and the draft, and having a suitable team to go along with their new stadium.\n\nIn the front office, the Nationals hired the well-respected former Arizona scouting director [[Mike Rizzo (baseball)|Mike Rizzo]] to be the vice president of baseball operations, second in charge under then-general manager Jim Bowden.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nationals Counting on Draft-Day Payoff | author=Barry Svrluga | work=Washington Post | date=June 5, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/04/AR2007060401755.html}}</ref>\n\n=====2006-07=====\nAt the end of the [[2006 Major League Baseball season|2006 season]], the Nationals did not re-sign free agent and star OF [[Alfonso Soriano]]. Soriano signed a $136 million contract with the Cubs, and Washington received two draft picks in return. OF [[Jos\u00e9 Guill\u00e9n]] was also allowed to depart via free agency, and another high draft pick was obtained. Another high priced player, 2B/DH [[Jos\u00e9 Vidro]], was traded to the [[Seattle Mariners]] for prospects OF [[Chris Snelling]] and RHP [[Emiliano Fruto]]. In mid-2006, the Nationals received OF [[Austin Kearns]], 2B/SS [[Felipe L\u00f3pez (baseball)|Felipe L\u00f3pez]], and RHP [[Ryan Wagner]] from the [[Cincinnati Reds]], giving up LHP [[Gary Majewski]], LHP [[Bill Bray]], SS [[Royce Clayton]], 2B [[Brendan Harris]] and RHP [[Daryl Thompson]]. In August, they traded RHP [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] for prospects LHP [[Matt Chico]] and RHP [[Garrett Mock]]. Other players traded or let go from the [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005 season]] were OF [[Preston Wilson]], RHP [[H\u00e9ctor Carrasco]], IF [[Jamey Carroll]], and OF [[Terrmel Sledge]]. The team also acquired pitching prospects [[Luis Atilano]] from Atlanta, [[Shairon Martis]] from [[List of San Francisco Giants seasons|San Francisco]] and [[Jhonny N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] from the [[Los Angeles Dodgers seasons|Dodgers]]. In [[2006 Major League Baseball season|2006]], they had two first-round draft picks, OF [[Chris Marrero]], and RHP [[Colten Williams]], and signed them both to developmental contracts. The Nationals also signed a 16-year-old Dominican shortstop, [[Esmailyn Gonzalez]], for $1.4 million.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Top 10 Prospects: Washington Nationals | author=Aaron Fitt | date=January 12, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/263086.html}}</ref> Gonzalez was later revealed to be 20 years old at the time of his signing.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3916960 | work=ESPN.com | title=Dominican prospect faked age, name | date=February 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs for their farm system, the Nationals had a lot of work to do. By the spring of [[2007 Major League Baseball season|2007]], ''Baseball America'' had ranked the Nationals organization as dead last twice in four years in terms of minor league talent.<ref name=WT-20070907>{{Cite news | title=From worst to ... not quite first | first=Mark |last=Zuckerman | date=September 7, 2007 | work=[[Washington Times]] | url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/sep/7/from-worst-to-not-quite-first/ | access-date=April 7, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407124102/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/sep/7/from-worst-to-not-quite-first/ | archive-date=April 7, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Nationals had five of the first seventy picks in the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]]: their own two, and three compensation picks (two from losing Soriano, and one for Guillen). The team selected players that many considered to be four of the top 30 players available.<ref name=WT-20070907/> Overall, the Nationals signed all of their top twenty draft picks.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070816&content_id=2151632&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb | work=MLB.com | author=Bill Ladson | title=Nats agree to terms with McGeary | date=August 16, 2007}}</ref>  One of them, a first-round supplemental pick, Michael Burgess, was, by the end of the year, picked by ''Baseball America'' as the top prospect for the entire [[Gulf Coast League]].<ref>{{Cite news| title=Gulf Coast League Top 20 Prospects List: Young talent proves tough to gauge | author=Chris Kline | date=September 20, 2007 | publisher=Baseball America | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264872.html}}</ref>  Their rookie team, [[Vermont Lake Monsters|Vermont]], sent three starting pitchers [[Colton Willems]], [[Glenn Gibson]], and [[Adrian Alaniz]], and two position players, [[first baseman]] [[Bill Rhinehart]], and [[outfielder]] [[Aaron Seuss]] to the [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star Game.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Experienced Former College Players Fill NYPL All-Star Rosters | date=August 9, 2007 | author=Ben Badler | publisher=Baseball America | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/blog/prospects/?p=525}}</ref>  By the end of the season, three Vermont pitchers landed in the Top 20 prospects for the New York\u2013Penn League:\n*2007 second-round Jordan Zimmermann was ranked #5\n*2006 fourth round LHP Glenn Gibson (later traded to the Tampa Bay Rays for Elijah Dukes) was ranked #9\n*2006 first round RHP Colton Willems was ranked #11.<ref>{{Cite news| title=New York\u2013Penn League Top 20 Prospects List | author=Aaron Fitt | date=September 26, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264923.html | publisher=Baseball America}}</ref>\nIn the low-A [[South Atlantic League]] Top 20, two players made the list:\n*Chris Marrero was ranked #5\n*[[Justin Maxwell]], who played a few games with the Nationals during September, was ranked at #18.<ref>{{Cite news| title=South Atlantic League Top 20 Prospects List | author=Bill Ballew | date=October 1, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264942.html | publisher=Baseball America}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, after having no teams in the Dominican Summer League, the Nationals fielded two clubs in 2007, one of which won the DSL Championships.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Notes | author=Bill Ladson | date=September 7, 2007 | publisher=MLB.com | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070907&content_id=2194744&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb}}</ref>\n\n=====\"The Plan\" reloaded=====\nIn March 2009, just prior to Spring training, members of the Nationals' front office were implicated in a scandal involving the skimming of bonus money from the signing of Latin American players. [[Jos\u00e9 Rijo]], a key adviser to Jim Bowden, was thought to be at the heart of this. As a result of this scandal, General Manager Jim Bowden resigned in Spring training of 2009, though he maintained he had done nothing wrong.<ref name=\"laTimes2March2009\">{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Washington Nationals general manager Jim Bowden resigns|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/02/sports/sp-newswire2|accessdate=June 23, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nMike Rizzo, the man serving as assistant G.M. for the previous two seasons, became the acting GM. Rizzo began to shape the team in a way that was contrary to Bowden's previous methods. While Bowden was known for \"dumpster-diving\", that is attempting to find serviceable players among the less-than-desired, Mike Rizzo sought players who achieved results. Bowden took risks on players with poor reputations (such as outfielders [[Elijah Dukes]] and [[Lastings Milledge]]), while Rizzo made a point out of making certain his players possessed \"character\" and would contribute to a cohesive clubhouse.\n\nDespite the failures of Bowden's tenure, his last trade appeared to have been extremely beneficial to the Nationals, as he traded infielder [[Emilio Bonifacio]] and two minor-leaguers to the Marlins for starting pitcher Scott Olsen and outfielder [[Josh Willingham]].\n\nRizzo's first major trade during the [[2008 Major League Baseball season|2009 season]] as General Manager of the Nationals was to trade Lastings Milledge along with control-challenged reliever [[Joel Hanrahan]] to the Pirates in exchange for speedy outfielder [[Nyjer Morgan]] and left-handed relief pitcher [[Sean Burnett]]. Morgan was thought to be a great clubhouse presence as well as a slick fielder on the outfield grass.\n\n[[File:MG 6582 Jason Marquis.jpg|150px |thumb|[[Jason Marquis]]]]\nMike Rizzo's new philosophy continued to show in the 2009\u20132010 offseason. He was able to acquire second baseman [[Adam Kennedy]], All Star starting pitcher [[Jason Marquis]] (who began the [[2010 Major League Baseball season|2010 season]] very poorly, though it was later revealed that he had bone chips in his throwing elbow, his ERA was over 13 at one point), and catcher Ivan \"Pudge\" Rodriguez. All three men had reputations as being great teammates. Collectively, they had extensive experience playing for successful teams. This was a contrast to the Nationals' roster at the time, which had some talented players who lacked experience playing for winning teams.\n\n===Seasons===\n{{prose|date=October 2014}}\n\n====2005====\n{{main|2005 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[Image:BushAsAPitcher.jpg|thumb|Then President [[George W. Bush]] throws out a ceremonial first pitch in 2005.]]\n*On April 4, 2005, [[Brad Wilkerson]] (after being the last player to ever wear a Montreal Expo jersey) had the honor of being the first batter for the Washington Nationals and he promptly responded with the first [[Hit (baseball)|hit]] for the new Washington incarnation of the team.  Outfielder [[Terrmel Sledge]] hit the Nationals' first home run in the April 4 contest.\n*On April 6, 2005, the Nationals recorded their first-ever regular season win by beating the [[2005 Philadelphia Phillies season|Phillies]], 7\u20133. The win came in their second game of the season and was highlighted by Wilkerson [[hit for the cycle|hitting for the cycle]].\n*On April 14, 2005, the Washington Nationals won their first regular season home game at RFK Stadium in Washington, D.C, by a score of 5\u20133 against the [[2005 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]]. President [[George W. Bush]] kept up a tradition of sitting U.S. Presidents by throwing out the [[ceremonial first pitch]] on opening day in Washington, exactly 95 years after [[William Howard Taft]] started the tradition at Griffith Stadium. There were 45,596 fans in attendance, including former Senators players and [[Baseball Commissioner]] [[Bud Selig]]. [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] threw eight shutout innings, and [[Vinny Castilla]] was denied the chance to [[Hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] when Diamondback reliever [[Lance Cormier]] hit him with a pitch in the bottom of the eighth; Castilla needed only a single to complete the cycle. [[Chad Cordero]] recorded the save for Washington.\n*Between May 29 and June 15, 2005, the Nationals compiled a 15\u20132 record including a franchise record 10-game win streak (June 2\u201312).  Ten of those games were decided by 1 run.\n*On August 4, 2005, Brad Wilkerson became the first Washington Nationals player to ever hit a [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], against then [[2005 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] relief pitcher [[Duaner S\u00e1nchez]]. The Nationals won the game 7\u20130 on a four-hit complete game shutout by [[John Patterson (pitcher)|John Patterson]].\n*During his August\u2013September callup, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] recorded 23 hits in 58 at-bats. He thus became the first member of the Washington Nationals to complete the season with a batting average of at least .300 in at least 50 at-bats.\n*The Nationals led all National League teams in interleague play in 2005, recording 12 wins.\n*At the halfway mark of the season, the Nationals were in first place in the National League East division, with a record of 50\u201331. However, they went 31\u201350 in the second half of the season, finishing at 81-81.\n\n====2006====\n{{main|2006 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n*On May 19, 2006, the Nationals opened their first-ever regular season interleague series against the [[2006 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]. Although the Orioles won the first game of what would become known as the [[Beltway Series]] (which consisted of three games in Washington and three in Baltimore), the two teams split the season series, with the home team winning twice and the visitors once. These games marked the Orioles' first matchup with a Washington-based team in 35 years, as they played against [[Minnesota Twins|the original Senators]] from 1954 to 1960, and against [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|a new Senators team]] from 1961 to 1971.<ref group=note>Prior to 2006, the Nationals' natural rival was the [[Toronto Blue Jays]], dating back to their time in Montreal, and because the 2005 schedule was set with the Expos in mind, the two teams had to play another series that year.</ref>\n*On Father's Day, June 18, 2006, against the [[2006 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]], the paid attendance was 45,157, the third-largest ever to see a single baseball game in the history of RFK Stadium. In that game, the Nationals beat the Yankees 3\u20132 on a two-run walk-off home run by rookie Ryan Zimmerman. (A [[1962 Major League Baseball season|1962]] doubleheader drew more spectators, as did the Nationals' first-ever home game with Arizona.)\n*On September 2, 2006, the Nationals rallied from three runs down in the first game and from five runs down in the second game to take a day\u2013night doubleheader sweep from the [[2006 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]], the first day-night doubleheader as part of the team's history in Washington.\n*On Labor Day, September 4, 2006, [[Ram\u00f3n Ortiz]] took a no-hitter into the ninth inning vs. the [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]], but gave up a single to Aaron Miles on his second pitch in the 9th to break up the bid. Then he gave up a home run to [[Albert Pujols]], ending his chance to get his second career shutout. Ortiz himself also hit a home run in the 8th inning. The Nationals won 5\u20132.\n*On September 16, 2006, [[Alfonso Soriano]] became the fourth player to [[40\u201340 club|hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a season]] when he stole his 40th base in the first inning of a game against the [[2006 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee Brewers]]. Soriano followed that feat on September 22 by hitting his 40th double, becoming the first member of the \"40\u201340 Club\" to also hit 40 doubles in the same season.\n\n====2007====\n{{Main|2007 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[File:IMG 9332 Ryan Zimmerman.jpg|thumb|[[Ryan Zimmerman]]]]\nAfter losing four starters (Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez, Tony Armas, Ram\u00f3n Ortiz and Pedro Astacio) from the prior year, the Nationals invited an extraordinary 36 pitchers to spring training.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nats' Starting Pitching Could Be a Real Problem | author=Thomas Boswell | date=March 7, 2007 | page=E03 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/06/AR2007030602143_pf.html | work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title=Nats' St. Claire Knows the Task at Hand | author=Barry Svrluga | work=Washington Post | date=February 26, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/25/AR2007022501373.html}}</ref>\n\nOn Opening Day, the Nationals lost their starting shortstop [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]] and center fielder [[Nook Logan]] for five weeks due to injuries. At the end of April, starting pitcher [[Jerome Williams (baseball)|Jerome Williams]] hurt his ankle while batting and was placed on the 15-day disabled list. Then, in the space of just 10 days in May, [[Shawn Hill]], [[John Patterson (pitcher)|John Patterson]], and [[Jason Bergmann]] went on the disabled list. Jerome Williams returned, pitched one game, and went back on the DL with a shoulder injury. The Washington Post's wrote: \"Almost everything that could sink a team's attitude has befallen the Nationals. They started the year 1\u20138, then they lost eight in a row to drop to 9\u201325.\"<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nationals Are Managing Just Fine With Acta | author=Thomas Boswell | date=June 4, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060301428.html | work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nThey put journeymen [[Mike Bacsik (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Bacsik]], [[Micah Bowie]], [[Tim Redding]], and [[Jason Simontacchi]], along with rookie reliever [[Levale Speigner]] into the starting rotation, amidst predictions that the 2007 Nationals might equal the [[1962 New York Mets season|1962 Mets']] record of futility of 120 losses in one season.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Baseball Most Foul: The Nats Reinvent Bad | author=Linton Weeks | work=Washington Post | date=May 8, 2007 | page=C01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/07/AR2007050701636.html}}</ref> But the Nationals bounced back, going 24\u201318 in their next 42 games through June 25. But on that day, a day in which Bergman made his first start off the DL, the Nationals received the news that shortstop [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]], their leadoff hitter (and second on the team with a .329 batting average) was lost for the rest of the season due to a thumb injury he had received the day before tagging out a runner.\n\nThe Nationals finished the [[2007 Major League Baseball season|2007 season]] 73\u201389, improving their record by two more wins than in 2006.\n\n*On April 17, 2007, one day after the shootings on the campus of [[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University|Virginia Tech]] where 33 faculty and students were murdered in the [[Virginia Tech massacre|largest mass shooting in US history]], the Nationals wore Virginia Tech baseball hats as they hosted the [[2007 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]].<ref name= post>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/04/17/AR2007041702068.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Nats Show Their Support | first=Marc | last=Carig | date=April 18, 2007 | accessdate=May 27, 2010}}</ref> The idea was e-mailed to team President Stan Kasten by Nationals fan Dave Lanham following the shootings. One of these hats was sent to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]] to be displayed.<ref name= sports>{{cite web| url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/sports/baseball/20070417-2028-bbn-nationals-virginiatech.html | work=SignOnSanDiego.com | title=Nationals don Virginia Tech baseball caps during game | date=April 17, 2007}}</ref>\n*On May 12, 2007, the Nationals hosted the [[2007 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]]. Tied 3\u20133 in the bottom of the ninth, Marlins pitcher Jorge Julio faced Ryan Zimmerman with the bases loaded and two outs. Zimmerman hit the 2\u20132 pitch over the right-center field wall for a walk-off grand slam.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270512120 | work=ESPN.com | title=Zimmerman's walk-off grand slam ends rain-delayed game | date=May 12, 2007}}</ref> Also during this game, right fielder [[Austin Kearns]] hit the Nationals' first inside-the-park home run. The game ended at 1:42AM after two separate extended rain delays.\n*On August 7, 2007, while on the road against the [[2007 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]], Nationals pitcher [[Mike Bacsik (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Bacsik]] allowed [[Barry Bonds]]' 756th career home run, giving him first place on the career home run list. However, the Nationals won the game 8\u20136.\n*On September 23, 2007, the Nationals played their final game at RFK Stadium, a 5\u20133 victory over the [[2007 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\n====2008====\n{{Main|2008 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[Image:Washingtonnational2008steam.JPG|thumb|right|270px|Nationals 2008 team during warm up]]\n*On March 30, 2008, the Nationals held the grand opening of their new ballpark, [[Nationals Park]], with a rare one game series against the [[2008 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]]. Continuing the tradition, President [[George W. Bush]] threw out the ceremonial first pitch to Nationals manager [[Manny Acta]]. The Nationals beat the Braves in dramatic fashion when, with two out in the bottom of the 9th inning, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] hit a solo [[walk-off home run]] off of pitcher [[Peter Moylan]]. This gave the Nationals a 3\u20132 victory. The first hit was recorded by [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]], the first RBI was recorded by [[Nick Johnson (baseball)|Nick Johnson]], the first run scored was recorded by Cristian Guzm\u00e1n, the first home run was recorded by the Braves' [[Chipper Jones]], and the first starting pitchers were [[Odalis P\u00e9rez]] for the Nationals and [[Tim Hudson]] for the Braves. President Bush was in the [[ESPN]] [[Sunday Night Baseball|television booth]] at the time of Jones' homer and was the one who called it.\n\n====2009====\n{{Main|2009 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n*In April 2009, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] and [[Adam Dunn]] wore jerseys that improperly spelled the team's name as \"Natinals\". They later switched to properly spelled jerseys in the 3rd inning. [[Majestic Athletic]], the uniform supplier for MLB later apologized. This spawned a rash of jokes both on the internet and on television regarding Nationals and futility. The jersey worn by Dunn was later auctioned for $8000 to benefit the Washington Nationals Dream foundation.\n*On July 27, 2009, [[Josh Willingham]] hit two [[Grand Slam (baseball)|grand slams]] in a game against the [[2009 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee Brewers]]. The first grand slam was hit against [[Jeff Suppan]] and the second against [[Mark DiFelice]]. Willingham became the 13th player in MLB history to accomplish the feat.\n*On September 30, 2009, [[Justin Maxwell]] hit a two-out full count walk-off grand slam off of [[Francisco Rodr\u00edguez (Venezuelan pitcher)|Francisco Rodr\u00edguez]] of the [[2009 New York Mets]] on Fan Appreciation Day, the Nationals' last home game of the season.\n*On October 4, 2009, the Nationals' last game of the season, the Nationals won after 15 innings, the longest game for the team as part of its Washington history. The Nationals also became the first team in MLB history to start the season losing seven in a row and close the season winning seven in a row.\n\n====2010====\n{{Main|2010 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n* On April 5, 2010, President Barack Obama kept up a tradition of sitting U.S. Presidents by throwing out the ceremonial first pitch on opening day in Washington.\n[[File:Stephen Strasburg MLB debut.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Stephen Strasburg]] during his major league debut.]]\n*On June 7, 2010 the Nationals selected [[Bryce Harper]] of [[College of Southern Nevada|Southern Nevada]]. Harper was expected to break the contract record set by [[Stephen Strasburg]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-07/nationals-take-chosen-one-bryce-harper-with-top-pick-in-baseball-s-draft.html|work=Bloomberg|title=Nationals Draft `Chosen One' Bryce Harper as No. 1 a Year After Strasburg|date=June 7, 2010|first=Erik|last=Matuszewski}}</ref> Harper is also a client of Strasburg's agent [[Scott Boras]]. With 26 seconds left to sign, Harper and Boras agreed to a $9.9 million, five-year contract,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5468993 | work=ESPN.com | title=Nationals sign Bryce Harper for $9.9M | date=August 17, 2010}}</ref> falling short of Strasburg's 15.5 million over four years.\n*On June 8, 2010, the first overall pick, [[Stephen Strasburg]] had his major league debut, attracting a sellout crowd of 40,315. Strasburg struck out 14 batters in seven innings, giving up just 2 earned runs in a win over the [[2010 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]]. The 14 strikeouts were a record for the Nationals\u2014the most in a single game by a National since the franchise moved to D.C.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/08/AR2010060805223.html?sid=ST2010060900179 | work=Washington Post | date=June 9, 2010 | title=Pitcher Stephen Strasburg makes his major league debut for Washington Nationals | first=Dave | last=Sheinin}}</ref>\n*On July 29, 2010, the Nationals traded [[Matt Capps]] to the [[Minnesota Twins]] for [[Wilson Ramos]].  Ramos was considered to be the top catching prospect in the American League.\n*On July 30, 2010, the Nationals traded infielder [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]] to the Texas Rangers for two minor league pitchers. Guzm\u00e1n had to approve the deal because he has 10-and-5 rights (players with 10 years in the major league and five consecutive years with their current team cannot be traded without their consent).<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20100730/bbo-nationals-guzman/ | work=Huffington Post | title=Guzman OKs trade from Nationals to Rangers | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref>\n*On September 6, 2010, the Nationals won their 60th game of the season, eclipsing their win totals from the 2008 and 2009 season (finishing with 59 wins each time). September call-up Danny Espinosa hit two home runs including a grand slam in the Nationals' 13\u20133 win over the [[2010 New York Mets season|Mets]] at Nationals Park.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/06/AR2010090602312.html | work=Washington Post | title=Danny Espinosa hits 2 homers, drives in 6 in Nats' win over Mets | date=September 6, 2010 | first=Adam | last=Kilgore}}</ref>\n*On September 20, 2010, the Nationals recorded their lowest attendance ever since they came to Washington, with just 10,999 in attendance for a game against the [[2010 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/09/the_nationals_are_having_troub.html | title=The Nationals are having trouble drawing a crowd | work=Washington Post | date=September 21, 2010}}</ref> The poor attendance continued during the whole series, with fewer than 12,000 on September 21, fewer than 13,000 on September 22, and 14,633 on September 23.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer.com\">{{Cite news | url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/breaking/nationals-president-stan-kasten-leaving-club-103648344.html | title=Losses mounting, attendance low, Stan Kasten resigning as president of Washington Nationals | work=Washington Examiner | date=September 23, 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/sportsdata/baseball/mlb/game/Astros_Nationals/2010/09/23 | work=USA Today | title= MLB Box Score 9/23/2010 | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n*On September 23, 2010, team president [[Stan Kasten]] announced he would resign at the end of the season.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer.com\"/> Kasten did not explain in detail his reason for resigning and said, \"It's just time to be doing something else.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=5607926 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |title=Nats president Kasten to resign at season's end |date=September 24, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2019 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*On November 10, 2010, the Nationals unveiled a new logo and uniforms.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101110&content_id=16055222&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb | title=Nationals unveil new jerseys in fashion show | work=MLB.com | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2010/11/about_the_nats_new_uniforms_an.html | work=Washington Post DC Sports Blog | title=About the Nats new uniforms and the Curly W | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n*On December 5, 2010, the Nationals signed [[Jayson Werth]] to a seven-year deal worth $126 million.\n[[File:Jayson Werth (28).jpg|thumb|[[Jayson Werth]] playing for the Nationals against the Orioles in May 2011]]\n\n====2011====\n{{Main|2011 Washington Nationals season}}\n\nOn June 23, 2011, the Nationals won a 1\u20130 game to put them above .500 with a record of 38-37 (.507), the latest point in the season the team had been above .500 since 2005. Immediately after the game, manager [[Jim Riggleman]] resigned, citing the team's refusal to discuss extending his contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110623&content_id=20914078&vkey=news_was&c_id=mlb|title=Riggleman steps down as Nationals manager|work=Major League Baseball|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Bench coach [[John McLaren (baseball)|John McLaren]] was named the interim manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/john-mclaren-will-manage-nationals.html|title=Rizzo: John McLaren will manage Nationals in Chicago|publisher=|access-date=2014-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206203141/http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/john-mclaren-will-manage-nationals.html|archive-date=2013-02-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>  It was later reported that [[Davey Johnson]] was signed through the end of the 2011 season, with an option for 2012 (as a candidate in a search that would include minority candidates), and a contract as a front office consultant through 2013.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ben Goessling |url=http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/davey-johnsons-deal-with-the-nationals.html |title=The Goessling Game: Davey Johnson's deal with the Nationals |publisher=Masnsports.com |date=2011-06-26 |accessdate=2013-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206203132/http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/davey-johnsons-deal-with-the-nationals.html |archive-date=2013-02-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Nationals finished the [[2011 Major League Baseball season|2011 season]] in third place with a record of 80\u201381, their second-best record since they moved to Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://washington.nationals.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2011_09_28_wasmlb_flomlb_1&mode=box&c_id=was#gid=2011_09_28_wasmlb_flomlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=was|title=Strasburg fans 10, wins season finale|work=Washington Nationals|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> They only played 161 games because a home game against the [[2011 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]] was cancelled due to rain. The game was not made up because it was inconsequential to the playoffs with no room on the schedule to play it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/how-the-nationals-final-two-games-will-affect-their-draft-status-and-offseason/2011/09/27/gIQAJy7O2K_blog.html|title=How the Nationals\u2019 final two games will affect their draft status and offseason|work=Washington Post|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, Washington traded prospects [[A.J. Cole]], [[Derek Norris]], [[Tom Milone]] and [[Brad Peacock]] for All-Star Pitcher [[Gio Gonz\u00e1lez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/7385033/oakland-trade-gio-gonzalez-washington-nationals |title=Oakland A's trade Gio Gonz\u00e1lez to Washington Nationals \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=2011-12-23 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2011 season, the last remaining member of the Expos \u2013 [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] \u2013 departed the Nationals, although his association with the team was non-continuous.\n\n====2012====\n{{Main|2012 Washington Nationals season}}\nOn September 20, the Nationals beat the [[2012 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] to clinch a spot in the playoffs and became the first Washington-based baseball team to advance to the postseason in 79 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Kilgore |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/washington-nationals-clinch-mlb-playoff-spot-with-4-1-win-over-los-angeles-dodgers/2012/09/20/847bf182-038b-11e2-91e7-2962c74e7738_story.html?hpid=z2 |title=Washington Nationals clinch MLB playoff spot with 4-1 win over Los Angeles Dodgers |work=The Washington Post |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> On October 1, the Nationals clinched the National League East division<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=321001120 |title=Philadelphia Phillies vs. Washington Nationals \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 01, 2012 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=2012-10-01 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> and later clinched the best record in Major League Baseball at 98\u201364.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=321003120 |title=Philadelphia Phillies vs. Washington Nationals \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 03, 2012 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=2012-10-03 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> However, the team lost to the [[2012 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] in the [[2012 National League Division Series|NLDS]] 3 games to 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=CARDS SCORE 4 IN 9TH, BEAT NATS 9-7, REACH NLCS|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/harper-nationals-lead-cards-6-0-after-3-game-5|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\n{{Main|2013 Washington Nationals season}}\nIn November 2012, manager Davey Johnson signed a contract to return for the [[2013 Major League Baseball season|2013 season]], and announced that he would retire from managing at the end of that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2012/11/10/davey-johnson-nationals-officially-agree-to-deal-for-return-in-2013-season/ |title=Davey Johnson, Nationals officially agree to deal for return in 2013 season |work=The Washington Post |first=James |last=Wagner |date=November 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed that the Nationals will likely leave the team's current spring training home at [[Space Coast Stadium]] in [[Viera, Florida]] once the lease expires in 2017 (although an early exit is possible in 2015).<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Nationals moving out of Brevard County|url=http://www.cfnews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/sports/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2013/5/14/washington_nationals.html|publisher=CFN13|accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Main|2014 Washington Nationals season}}\nOn October 31, 2013, the Nationals announced the hiring of [[Matt Williams (third baseman)|Matt Williams]] to replace Davey Johnson as the team's manager for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://curlyw.mlblogs.com/2013/10/31/nationals-name-matt-williams-manager/ |title=Nationals Name Matt Williams Manager |last=Comak |first=Amanda |work=Curly W Live |publisher=MLBlogs Network |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2013/11/01/matt-williams-introduced-as-nationals-manager-live-updates/ |title=Matt Williams introduced as Nationals manager |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Wagner |first=James |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> The Nationals clinched the NL East on September 16, 2014, after beating the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>White, Paul (September 17, 2014) [https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/09/16/washington-nationals-clinch-nl-east/15750151/ \"Nationals clinch NL East with win in Atlanta\"], ''[[USA Today]]''. Retrieved September 24, 2014.</ref>  Jordan Zimmermann pitched the Nationals' first no-hitter (since moving from Montreal in 2005) on the last day of the 2014 regular season, September 28, 2014, against the Miami Marlins.\n\n====2015====\n{{Main|2015 Washington Nationals season}}\nThe Nationals started their season in a skid, falling to the bottom of their division. On April 28, 2015, after a seven-game losing streak, with rookie starting pitcher [[A. J. Cole]] on the mound, the Nationals found themselves in at a nine-run deficit against their archrival, the [[Atlanta Braves]]. But the team clawed back to win the game 13\u201312, overcoming their largest run deficit ever.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baynews9.com/content/news/baynews9/sports/article.html/content/news/articles/bhsn/2015/4/28/oviedo_s_a_j_cole_ge.html|title=Oviedo's A.J. Cole gets no-decision in wild 13-12 Nationals win|date=April 28, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> Over the coming weeks, the Nationals rebounded from their poor start to the season, rising to the top of the division behind a career-best season for outfielder [[Bryce Harper]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.h4-entertainment.com/2015/05/bryce-harper-continues-to-lead-the-surging-nationals/|title=Bryce Harper Continues to Lead the Surging Nationals|date=May 29, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|work=Sports Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/20/bryce-harper-sets-new-career-high-with-his-23rd-home-run/|title=Bryce Harper sets new career-high with his 23rd home run|first=D.J.|last=Short|agency=NBC Sports|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> On June 20, 2015, the Nationals shut out the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], with [[Max Scherzer]] throwing a [[no-hitter]] that was [[List of Major League Baseball perfect games#Perfect games spoiled by the 27th batter|nearly perfect]]. The game was the second no-hitter in Nationals history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/2015/06/20/a83b59fe-1761-11e5-9ddc-e3353542100c_story.html|title=Nationals Max Scherzer throws no-hitter after hit-by-pitch spoils perfect game|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|work=The Washington Post|first=James|last=Wagner}}</ref> Scherzer became the first pitcher since [[Nolan Ryan]] in 1973 to throw two no-hitters in the regular season, shutting down the [[New York Mets]] on October 3, 2015, in a performance that also equaled Ryan's historic mark of 17 strikeouts in a no-hitter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://screengrabber.deadspin.com/max-scherzer-becomes-first-pitcher-since-nolan-ryan-in-1734520688|agency=Deadspin|title=Max Scherzer Becomes First Pitcher Since Nolan Ryan In 1973 To Throw Two No-Hitters In Same Regular Season|first=Timothy|last=Burke|date=October 3, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/10/max-scherzer-no-hitter-washington-nationals-new-york-mets|title=Max Scherzer hurls second no-hitter of season with dominating 17-strikeout performance|work=USA Today|date=October 3, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> However, the Mets won the division, clinching it in late September.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2015/09/26/mets-clinch-1st-playoff-spot-since-06-by-beating-reds-10-2/72900938/|title=Amazin' Mets clinch 1st playoff spot since 2006|date=September 26, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015|work=USA Today}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u20132017====\n{{Main|2016 Washington Nationals season|2017 Washington Nationals season}}\nIn 2016, the Nationals won the East division but lost in the NLDS to the Dodgers. In 2017, the Nationals again won the East division but lost in the NLDS to the Cubs, marking the fourth time out of four playoff appearances since 2012 in which the team has been eliminated in the NLDS.\n\n====2017\u20132018====\n{{Main|2017 Washington Nationals season|2018 Washington Nationals season}}\nThe 2017 season saw the Nationals earn another NL East title with a 97\u201365, but lost to the Cubs in five games. 2018 saw the Nationals host the MLB All-Star Game, but the team would regress and miss out on the playoffs, barely cracking .500 with an 82\u201380 record. Bryce Harper left the team after the season, signing with the Philadelphia Phillies as a free agent.\n\n====2019====\n{{Main|2019 Washington Nationals season}}\nEven without Harper, the Nationals would excel in 2019, earning a Wild Card berth with a 93\u201369 record, defeating the Milwaukee Brewers in the Wild Card play-in game, and winning their first playoff series since their arrival in Washington, D.C., upsetting the Los Angeles Dodgers in 5 games in their NLDS. They went on to sweep the St. Louis Cardinals in the NLCS to win the National League pennant, their first in team history dating back to their days in Montreal. When they faced the Houston Astros in the World Series, it was also the first appearance for a Washington-based team since [[History of the Washington Senators (1901-1960)|the first AL Senators]] lost to the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] in {{wsy|1933}}.  The Nationals went on to win their first World Series title 4 games to 3, becoming the second Washington D.C.-based professional sports team to win their first championship in the same year, following the [[WNBA]]'s [[Washington Mystics]] a few weeks earlier, and also became the third men's professional sports team to win their first title, following the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[St. Louis Blues]] and the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Toronto Raptors]]. Following the season, [[Anthony Rendon]] departed to the [[Los Angeles Angels]] in free agency.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of baseball team nicknames#Washington Nationals|Washington Nationals nicknames]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{ref list|group=note}}\n\n\n{{MLBHistory}}\n{{Washington Nationals}}\n\n[[Category:History of Major League Baseball by team|Washington Nationals]]\n[[Category:Washington Nationals]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Washington Nationals]] are a [[Major League Baseball]] team formed in 1969 as the [[Montreal Expos]]. In 2005, the Expos moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] and were renamed the Nationals. The franchise won the [[List of National League pennant winners|National League pennant]] in 2019, and has won its division five times. They won the [[World Series]] in 2019 against the [[Astros]] in game 7.\n\n==History==\n\n===Montreal Expos===\n{{Main|Montreal Expos}}\nThe Montreal Expos joined the [[National League]] in [[1969 Major League Baseball season|1969]], along with the [[San Diego Padres]], with a majority share held by [[Charles Bronfman]], a major shareholder in [[Seagram]]. Named after the [[Expo 67]] [[World's Fair]], the Expos' initial home was [[Jarry Park Stadium|Jarry Park]]. Managed by [[Gene Mauch]], the team lost 110 games in their first season, coincidentally matching the Padres inaugural win-loss record, and continued to struggle during their first decade with sub-.500 seasons.\n\nStarting in [[1977 Major League Baseball season|1977]], the team's home venue was Montreal's [[Olympic Stadium (Montreal)|Olympic Stadium]], built for the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. Two years later, the team won a franchise-high 95 games, finishing second in the National League East. The Expos began the 1980s with a core group of young players, including catcher [[Gary Carter]], outfielders [[Tim Raines]] and [[Andre Dawson]], third baseman [[Tim Wallach]], and pitchers [[Steve Rogers (baseball)|Steve Rogers]] and [[Bill Gullickson]]. The team won its only division championship in the strike-shortened split season of [[1981 in baseball|1981]], ending its season with a three games to two loss to the [[1981 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the [[1981 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]].\n\nThe team spent most of the 1980s in the middle of the NL East pack, finishing in third or fourth place in eight out of nine seasons from 1982 to 1990. [[Buck Rodgers]] was hired as manager before the [[1985 Major League Baseball season|1985 season]] and guided the Expos to a .500 or better record five times in six years, with the highlight coming in [[1987 Major League Baseball season|1987]], when they won 91 games. They finished third, but were just four games behind the division-winning [[1987 St. Louis Cardinals|Cardinals]].\n\nBronfman sold the team to a consortium of owners in 1991, with [[Claude Brochu]] as the managing general partner.<ref name=\"ExposGuide1996\">{{Cite book\n| author=Montreal Expos\n| authorlink=Montreal Expos\n| title=Expos Media Guide 1996\n| year=1996 }}</ref><ref name=\"1991June-Gazette\">{{Cite news\n  | last=Blair\n  | first=Jeff\n  | title=Brochu group goes to bat for baseball survival here; Expos sale official as Bronfman era ends\n  | newspaper=Montreal Gazette\n  | pages=C.1\n  | date=1991-06-15 }}</ref>\nRodgers, at that time second only to Gene Mauch in number of Expos games managed, was replaced partway through the [[1991 Major League Baseball season|1991 season]]. In May [[1992 Major League Baseball season|1992]], [[Felipe Alou]], a member of the Expos organization since 1976, was promoted to field manager, becoming the first Dominican-born manager in MLB history.<ref name=\"ExposGuide1996\"/> Alou would become the leader in Expos games managed, while guiding the team to winning records, including [[1994 Major League Baseball season|1994]], when the Expos, led by a talented group of players including [[Larry Walker]], [[Mois\u00e9s Alou]], [[Marquis Grissom]] and [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]], had the best record in the major leagues until the [[1994\u201395 Major League Baseball strike]] forced the cancellation of the remainder of the season. After the disappointment of 1994, Expos management began shedding its key players, and the team's fan support dwindled.\n\nBrochu sold control of the team to [[Jeffrey Loria]] in [[1999 Major League Baseball season|1999]],<ref name=\"ExposGuide2000\">{{Cite book\n| author=Montreal Expos\n| authorlink=Montreal Expos\n| title=Expos Media Guide 2000\n| year=2000\n| publisher=\n| location=\n| id=\n}}</ref><ref name=\"GlobeAndMail-LoriaPurchase\">{{Cite news\n  | last=Blair\n  | first=Jeff\n  | title=Expos to field better team, Loria says Ebullient new chairman vows to increase salary limit, build new ballpark for 2002 season\n  | newspaper=The Globe and Mail\n  | pages=S.1\n  | publisher=The Globe and Mail\n  | date=1999-12-10 }}\n</ref>\nbut Loria failed to close on a plan to build a new downtown ballpark, and did not reach an agreement on television and English radio broadcast contracts for the [[2000 Major League Baseball season|2000 season]], reducing the team's media coverage.\n\n====2001 contraction====\n{{main|2001 Major League Baseball contraction plan}}\nIn November 2001, Major League Baseball's owners voted 28\u20132 to contract the league by two teams \u2014 according to various sources, the Expos and the Minnesota Twins, both of which reportedly voted against contraction.<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\">{{cite web\n  | last=Schoenfield\n  | first=David\n  | title=Still 30 teams: Contraction timeline\n  | publisher=ESPN.com\n  | date=2002-02-05\n  | url=http://assets.espn.go.com/mlb/s/2002/0205/1323230.html\n  | accessdate=2009-02-19 }}</ref>\nSubsequently, the [[Boston Red Sox]] were sold to a partnership led by [[John W. Henry]], owner of the [[Florida Marlins]].<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/><ref>{{Cite book\n  | last=Mnookin\n  | first=Seth\n  | title=Feeding the Monster. How Money, Smarts, and Nerve Took a Team to the Top.\n  | publisher=Simon & Schuster\n  | year=2006\n  | location=New York\n  | isbn=0-7432-8681-2 }}\n</ref>\nIn order to clear the way for Henry's group to assume ownership of the Red Sox, Henry sold the Marlins to Loria, and baseball purchased the Expos from Loria.<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/>\nHowever, as the [[Metropolitan Sports Facilities Commission]], operator of the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome|Metrodome]], won an injunction requiring the Twins to play there in [[2002 Major League Baseball season|2002]],<ref name=\"ESPN-contraction\"/> MLB was unable to revoke the Twins franchise, and so had to keep the Twins and Expos as part of the [[Major League Baseball schedule|regular season schedule]]. In the collective bargaining agreement signed with the [[Major League Baseball Players Association]] (MLBPA) in August 2002, contraction was prohibited through to the end of the contract in 2006.<ref>{{cite press release\n  | title=Deal in place, games go on\n  | publisher=MLB.com\n  | date=2002-08-30\n  | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/mlb/news/mlb_news.jsp?ymd=20020830&content_id=116907&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp\n  | accessdate=2006-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n===Creation of the Nationals===\nWith contraction no longer an option for the immediate term, MLB began looking for a relocation site for the Expos. Some of the choices included [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]]; Washington, D.C.; [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]; [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]]; [[Portland, Oregon]]; somewhere in [[Northern Virginia]] such as [[Arlington, Virginia|Arlington]] or [[Dulles, Virginia|Dulles]]; [[Norfolk, Virginia]]; [[Las Vegas]]; and [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].  Washington and Virginia emerged as the front-runners.\n\nIn both [[2003 Major League Baseball season|2003]] and [[2004 Major League Baseball season|2004]], the Expos played 22 of their home games in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] at the [[Hiram Bithorn Stadium]], and the remaining 59 in Montreal.\n\nOn September 29, 2004, MLB announced that the Expos would move to Washington, D.C. in [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005]].<ref name=\"Myles-Gazette-2004-09-30\">{{cite news |last=Myles |first=Stephanie |title=31,395 say goodbye |newspaper=Montreal Gazette |pages=C1 | date=2004-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bloom |first=Barry M. |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20040929&content_id=875100&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=MLB selects D.C. for Expos |work=[[MLB.com]] |date=2004-09-29 |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Expos played their final game on October 3 at [[Shea Stadium]], losing by a score of 8\u20131 against the [[2004 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], the same opponent that the Expos first faced at its start, 35 years earlier. On November 15, a lawsuit by the former team owners against MLB and former majority owner Jeffrey Loria was struck down by arbitrators, bringing to an end all legal actions that would impede a move. The owners of the other MLB teams approved the move to Washington in a 28\u20131 vote on December 3 ([[Baltimore Orioles]] owner [[Peter Angelos]] cast the sole dissenting vote).\n\n===Washington baseball history revived===\n{{Main|History of Washington, D.C. professional baseball}}\n\nNumerous professional baseball teams have called Washington, D.C. home. The [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]], a founding member of the [[American League]], played in the nation's capital from 1901 to 1960 before moving to Minnesota and becoming the [[Minnesota Twins|Twins]]. These Senators were owned by [[Clark Griffith]] and played in [[Griffith Stadium]]. With notable stars including [[Walter Johnson]] and [[Joe Cronin]], the Senators won the [[1924 World Series]] and pennants in [[1925 World Series|1925]] and [[1933 World Series|1933]], but were more often unsuccessful and moved to Minnesota for the [[1961 Major League Baseball season|1961 season]] where the team was renamed the Minnesota Twins. A second [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] team (1961\u20131971) had a winning record only once in their 11 years, though bright spots, such as slugger [[Frank Howard (baseball)|Frank Howard]], earned the love of fans. The second Senators team moved to Arlington, Texas, for the [[1972 Major League Baseball season|1972 season]] and changed their name to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], and Washington spent the next 33 years without a baseball team.\n\nAlthough there was some sentiment to revive the name Senators, political considerations factored into the choice of Nationals, a revival of the first American League franchise's \"official\" nickname used from [[1905 Major League Baseball season|1905]] to [[1956 Major League Baseball season|1956]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dcvote.org/media/media.cfm?mediaID=1098&year=2005 | work=DCVote.org | title=Media Center | accessdate=September 24, 2010}}</ref> Politicians and others in the District of Columbia objected to the name Senators because the District of Columbia does not have [[District of Columbia voting rights|voting representation in Congress]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A1767-2004Oct1?language=printer | work=The Washington Post | title=The District's Senators Shouldn't Wear Cleats| date=October 3, 2004}}</ref> In addition, the Rangers still owned the rights to the Senators name,<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/expos/2004-11-19-nats-nickname_x.htm?loc=interstitialskip | work=USA Today | title=In Washington, it'll be \"Let's go Nats\"|date=November 22, 2004}}</ref> although the\nNationals were able to acquire the rights to the curly \"W\" from the Rangers.\n\nWashington, D.C., mayor [[Anthony A. Williams]] supported the name \"Washington Grays\", in honor of the Negro-league team the [[Homestead Grays]] (1929\u20131950), which had been based in [[Pittsburgh]], but played many of their home games in Washington. In the end, the team owners chose the name \"Washington Nationals\", which had been the official name of the American League's Washington Senators from 1905\u20131956.\n\n===Opposition from the Orioles===\nThe move was announced despite opposition from Peter Angelos, owner of the nearby Baltimore Orioles, who infamously announced \"There are no baseball fans in Washington, D.C. That's a fiction.\" Since 1972, the Orioles had been the only MLB franchise in the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington Metropolitan Area]], which he considered a single market. Angelos contended that the Orioles would suffer financially if another team were allowed to enter the market, although the Orioles and the Washington Senators had shared the market successfully from 1954 through 1971, and four other major metropolitan areas ([[New York metropolitan area|New York]], [[Los Angeles metropolitan area|Los Angeles]], [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicago]], and [[San Francisco Bay Area]]) of roughly comparable size to Baltimore-Washington each have two MLB teams (in all cases, one each in the National and American Leagues). This reasoning disturbed many in Washington who recalled that it was the Griffith family, owners of the Washington Senators, who allowed the [[History of the St. Louis Browns|St. Louis Browns]] to move to Baltimore and become the Orioles in {{mlby|1954}} in the first place.\n\nOn March 31, 2005, Angelos and Major League Baseball struck a deal to protect the Orioles against any financial harm the Nationals might present.\n\nUnder the terms of the deal, [[List of Washington Nationals broadcasters|television and radio broadcast rights]] to Nationals games are handled by the Orioles franchise, which formed a new network (the [[Mid-Atlantic Sports Network]]) to produce and distribute the games for both franchises on both local affiliates and cable/satellite systems. MASN was not, however, immediately available on all cable providers, adding to the frustration of Nationals fans. In fact, most in the DC area missed almost the entirety of the Nationals' first two seasons. The deal with Angelos makes the Nationals the only major league baseball team that does not own its own broadcast rights.\n\n===The ballpark controversy===\n[[File:Nationals at bat.JPG|right|thumb|300px|Nationals at bat against the [[San Diego Padres]] in [[RFK Stadium]], 8 July 2006.]]\nThe team's relocation to Washington was contingent on a financing plan for the [[Nationals Park|Nationals' new stadium]]\u2014this plan quickly became the subject of much debate on the [[Council of the District of Columbia]].\n\nThree Council members who supported Mayor [[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams's]] plan were ousted in September 2004's Democratic party primary. In addition, an opinion poll conducted by ''[[The Washington Post]]'' during the peak of the controversy found that approximately two-thirds of District residents opposed the mayor's stadium plan.\n\nMuch of the controversy centered on the fact that the city would be helping finance a $581 million stadium without support from [[Maryland]] or [[Virginia]] or their counties, from which a large portion of the team's fan base would be drawn.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=3930510 | work=The Economist | title=Letters | date=April 29, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, the move to Washington itself was called into doubt when the D.C. Council sought to change details of the stadium's financing. When the Council voted on December 14, 2004 to require 50 percent private financing for any new stadium, MLB ceased promotional activities for the Nationals and announced that they would consider looking for a new market.\n\nEventually, the council passed an amended plan on December 21, 2004 that proved slightly more financially favorable to the city, while remaining acceptable to MLB. Mayor Williams signed the stadium financing package on December 30.\n\nDuring the [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005 season]], a private financing plan for construction of the stadium was negotiated between the city and a syndicate of bankers led by [[Deutsche Bank]]. The negotiations of the details ran into another problem in November 2005. The bankers requested a [[letter of credit]] or other financial guarantee of $24 million, $6 million for each of four years, insuring payment of lease revenues against various risks including poor attendance and terrorism. The city requested that Major League Baseball provide this guarantee, which they were unwilling to do.\n\nOn December 22, 2005, the ''Washington Post'' reported that Major League Baseball had specifically instructed prospective owners not to offer to pay cost overruns on the stadium if they were selected as the owners. Bidders were also told not to communicate with the press about these issues.\n\nIn February 2006, the DC City Council imposed a $611 million cap on the stadium.\n\nFinally, on March 5, Major League Baseball signed a lease for a new ballpark, agreeing to the city's $611 million cap. MLB also agreed to contribute $20 million toward the cost of the stadium, although it did not agree to cover stadium overruns. Further, MLB added the condition that excess ballpark tax revenue earmarked for debt service for the bonds be available for cost overruns. Two days later, on March 7 the DC City Council, by a vote of 9\u20134, approved a construction contract for a state-of-the-art stadium with a contemporary glass-and-stone facade, seats for 41,000 fans and a view of the U.S. Capitol, and affirmed its demand that public spending on the project be limited to $611 million. The votes were the final actions needed to satisfy the terms of the deal struck in September 2004, paving the way for the sale of the team.\n\nMajor League Baseball had agreed at the time that the franchise was moved to Washington to sell the team to an owner or ownership syndicate. Several dates for sale of the team were set and missed due to the legal wrangling regarding the building of the stadium. The delay was harshly criticized by city residents and leaders as reported in ''The Washington Post''.\n\nSelecting from a finalized group of three potential ownership syndicates, Major League Baseball announced in July 2006 that it had chosen the [[Lerner Enterprises]] group, led by billionaire [[real estate developer]] [[Theodore N. Lerner]]. The final sale price of the team was $450 million and the transfer of ownership was completed July 24, 2006. In late September 2006, [[Comcast]] finally agreed to broadcast the Nationals games.\n\n====New ownership and \"The Plan\"====\n[[File:Nationals Game - 2009 - Stierch.jpg|thumb|right|Washington Nationals versus the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in 2009 at [[Nationals Park]]]]\nWhen Ted Lerner took over the club in mid-{{MLBy|2006}}, he hired [[Stan Kasten]] as team president. Kasten was widely known as the architect of the [[Atlanta Braves]] before and during their run of 14 division titles (a streak only interrupted by the strike season of 1994, when the Braves ended the season behind the Montreal Expos \u2013 ironically, the Nationals' predecessor). Kasten was also the general manager or president of many other [[Atlanta]]-area sports teams, including the [[Atlanta Hawks]] and [[Atlanta Thrashers]]. \"The Plan\", as it became known, was a long-range rebuilding and restructuring of the team from the ground up. This plan included investing in the farm system and the draft, and having a suitable team to go along with their new stadium.\n\nIn the front office, the Nationals hired the well-respected former Arizona scouting director [[Mike Rizzo (baseball)|Mike Rizzo]] to be the vice president of baseball operations, second in charge under then-general manager Jim Bowden.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nationals Counting on Draft-Day Payoff | author=Barry Svrluga | work=Washington Post | date=June 5, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/04/AR2007060401755.html}}</ref>\n\n=====2006-07=====\nAt the end of the [[2006 Major League Baseball season|2006 season]], the Nationals did not re-sign free agent and star OF [[Alfonso Soriano]]. Soriano signed a $136 million contract with the Cubs, and Washington received two draft picks in return. OF [[Jos\u00e9 Guill\u00e9n]] was also allowed to depart via free agency, and another high draft pick was obtained. Another high priced player, 2B/DH [[Jos\u00e9 Vidro]], was traded to the [[Seattle Mariners]] for prospects OF [[Chris Snelling]] and RHP [[Emiliano Fruto]]. In mid-2006, the Nationals received OF [[Austin Kearns]], 2B/SS [[Felipe L\u00f3pez (baseball)|Felipe L\u00f3pez]], and RHP [[Ryan Wagner]] from the [[Cincinnati Reds]], giving up LHP [[Gary Majewski]], LHP [[Bill Bray]], SS [[Royce Clayton]], 2B [[Brendan Harris]] and RHP [[Daryl Thompson]]. In August, they traded RHP [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] for prospects LHP [[Matt Chico]] and RHP [[Garrett Mock]]. Other players traded or let go from the [[2005 Major League Baseball season|2005 season]] were OF [[Preston Wilson]], RHP [[H\u00e9ctor Carrasco]], IF [[Jamey Carroll]], and OF [[Terrmel Sledge]]. The team also acquired pitching prospects [[Luis Atilano]] from Atlanta, [[Shairon Martis]] from [[List of San Francisco Giants seasons|San Francisco]] and [[Jhonny N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] from the [[Los Angeles Dodgers seasons|Dodgers]]. In [[2006 Major League Baseball season|2006]], they had two first-round draft picks, OF [[Chris Marrero]], and RHP [[Colten Williams]], and signed them both to developmental contracts. The Nationals also signed a 16-year-old Dominican shortstop, [[Esmailyn Gonzalez]], for $1.4 million.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Top 10 Prospects: Washington Nationals | author=Aaron Fitt | date=January 12, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/263086.html}}</ref> Gonzalez was later revealed to be 20 years old at the time of his signing.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3916960 | work=ESPN.com | title=Dominican prospect faked age, name | date=February 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs for their farm system, the Nationals had a lot of work to do. By the spring of [[2007 Major League Baseball season|2007]], ''Baseball America'' had ranked the Nationals organization as dead last twice in four years in terms of minor league talent.<ref name=WT-20070907>{{Cite news | title=From worst to ... not quite first | first=Mark |last=Zuckerman | date=September 7, 2007 | work=[[Washington Times]] | url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/sep/7/from-worst-to-not-quite-first/ | access-date=April 7, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407124102/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/sep/7/from-worst-to-not-quite-first/ | archive-date=April 7, 2019 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Nationals had five of the first seventy picks in the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]]: their own two, and three compensation picks (two from losing Soriano, and one for Guillen). The team selected players that many considered to be four of the top 30 players available.<ref name=WT-20070907/> Overall, the Nationals signed all of their top twenty draft picks.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070816&content_id=2151632&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb | work=MLB.com | author=Bill Ladson | title=Nats agree to terms with McGeary | date=August 16, 2007}}</ref>  One of them, a first-round supplemental pick, Michael Burgess, was, by the end of the year, picked by ''Baseball America'' as the top prospect for the entire [[Gulf Coast League]].<ref>{{Cite news| title=Gulf Coast League Top 20 Prospects List: Young talent proves tough to gauge | author=Chris Kline | date=September 20, 2007 | publisher=Baseball America | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264872.html}}</ref>  Their rookie team, [[Vermont Lake Monsters|Vermont]], sent three starting pitchers [[Colton Willems]], [[Glenn Gibson]], and [[Adrian Alaniz]], and two position players, [[first baseman]] [[Bill Rhinehart]], and [[outfielder]] [[Aaron Seuss]] to the [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star Game.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Experienced Former College Players Fill NYPL All-Star Rosters | date=August 9, 2007 | author=Ben Badler | publisher=Baseball America | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/blog/prospects/?p=525}}</ref>  By the end of the season, three Vermont pitchers landed in the Top 20 prospects for the New York\u2013Penn League:\n*2007 second-round Jordan Zimmermann was ranked #5\n*2006 fourth round LHP Glenn Gibson (later traded to the Tampa Bay Rays for Elijah Dukes) was ranked #9\n*2006 first round RHP Colton Willems was ranked #11.<ref>{{Cite news| title=New York\u2013Penn League Top 20 Prospects List | author=Aaron Fitt | date=September 26, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264923.html | publisher=Baseball America}}</ref>\nIn the low-A [[South Atlantic League]] Top 20, two players made the list:\n*Chris Marrero was ranked #5\n*[[Justin Maxwell]], who played a few games with the Nationals during September, was ranked at #18.<ref>{{Cite news| title=South Atlantic League Top 20 Prospects List | author=Bill Ballew | date=October 1, 2007 | url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/features/264942.html | publisher=Baseball America}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, after having no teams in the Dominican Summer League, the Nationals fielded two clubs in 2007, one of which won the DSL Championships.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Notes | author=Bill Ladson | date=September 7, 2007 | publisher=MLB.com | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070907&content_id=2194744&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb}}</ref>\n\n=====\"The Plan\" reloaded=====\nIn March 2009, just prior to Spring training, members of the Nationals' front office were implicated in a scandal involving the skimming of bonus money from the signing of Latin American players. [[Jos\u00e9 Rijo]], a key adviser to Jim Bowden, was thought to be at the heart of this. As a result of this scandal, General Manager Jim Bowden resigned in Spring training of 2009, though he maintained he had done nothing wrong.<ref name=\"laTimes2March2009\">{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Washington Nationals general manager Jim Bowden resigns|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/02/sports/sp-newswire2|accessdate=June 23, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nMike Rizzo, the man serving as assistant G.M. for the previous two seasons, became the acting GM. Rizzo began to shape the team in a way that was contrary to Bowden's previous methods. While Bowden was known for \"dumpster-diving\", that is attempting to find serviceable players among the less-than-desired, Mike Rizzo sought players who achieved results. Bowden took risks on players with poor reputations (such as outfielders [[Elijah Dukes]] and [[Lastings Milledge]]), while Rizzo made a point out of making certain his players possessed \"character\" and would contribute to a cohesive clubhouse.\n\nDespite the failures of Bowden's tenure, his last trade appeared to have been extremely beneficial to the Nationals, as he traded infielder [[Emilio Bonifacio]] and two minor-leaguers to the Marlins for starting pitcher Scott Olsen and outfielder [[Josh Willingham]].\n\nRizzo's first major trade during the [[2008 Major League Baseball season|2009 season]] as General Manager of the Nationals was to trade Lastings Milledge along with control-challenged reliever [[Joel Hanrahan]] to the Pirates in exchange for speedy outfielder [[Nyjer Morgan]] and left-handed relief pitcher [[Sean Burnett]]. Morgan was thought to be a great clubhouse presence as well as a slick fielder on the outfield grass.\n\n[[File:MG 6582 Jason Marquis.jpg|150px |thumb|[[Jason Marquis]]]]\nMike Rizzo's new philosophy continued to show in the 2009\u20132010 offseason. He was able to acquire second baseman [[Adam Kennedy]], All Star starting pitcher [[Jason Marquis]] (who began the [[2010 Major League Baseball season|2010 season]] very poorly, though it was later revealed that he had bone chips in his throwing elbow, his ERA was over 13 at one point), and catcher Ivan \"Pudge\" Rodriguez. All three men had reputations as being great teammates. Collectively, they had extensive experience playing for successful teams. This was a contrast to the Nationals' roster at the time, which had some talented players who lacked experience playing for winning teams.\n\n===Seasons===\n{{prose|date=October 2014}}\n\n====2005====\n{{main|2005 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[Image:BushAsAPitcher.jpg|thumb|Then President [[George W. Bush]] throws out a ceremonial first pitch in 2005.]]\n*On April 4, 2005, [[Brad Wilkerson]] (after being the last player to ever wear a Montreal Expo jersey) had the honor of being the first batter for the Washington Nationals and he promptly responded with the first [[Hit (baseball)|hit]] for the new Washington incarnation of the team.  Outfielder [[Terrmel Sledge]] hit the Nationals' first home run in the April 4 contest.\n*On April 6, 2005, the Nationals recorded their first-ever regular season win by beating the [[2005 Philadelphia Phillies season|Phillies]], 7\u20133. The win came in their second game of the season and was highlighted by Wilkerson [[hit for the cycle|hitting for the cycle]].\n*On April 14, 2005, the Washington Nationals won their first regular season home game at RFK Stadium in Washington, D.C, by a score of 5\u20133 against the [[2005 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]]. President [[George W. Bush]] kept up a tradition of sitting U.S. Presidents by throwing out the [[ceremonial first pitch]] on opening day in Washington, exactly 95 years after [[William Howard Taft]] started the tradition at Griffith Stadium. There were 45,596 fans in attendance, including former Senators players and [[Baseball Commissioner]] [[Bud Selig]]. [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] threw eight shutout innings, and [[Vinny Castilla]] was denied the chance to [[Hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] when Diamondback reliever [[Lance Cormier]] hit him with a pitch in the bottom of the eighth; Castilla needed only a single to complete the cycle. [[Chad Cordero]] recorded the save for Washington.\n*Between May 29 and June 15, 2005, the Nationals compiled a 15-2 record including a franchise record 10-game win streak (June 2\u201312).  Ten of those games were decided by 1 run.\n*On August 4, 2005, Brad Wilkerson became the first Washington Nationals player to ever hit a [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], against then [[2005 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] relief pitcher [[Duaner S\u00e1nchez]]. The Nationals won the game 7\u20130 on a four-hit complete game shutout by [[John Patterson (pitcher)|John Patterson]].\n*During his August\u2013September callup, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] recorded 23 hits in 58 at-bats. He thus became the first member of the Washington Nationals to complete the season with a batting average of at least .300 in at least 50 at-bats.\n*The Nationals led all National League teams in interleague play in 2005, recording 12 wins.\n*At the halfway mark of the season, the Nationals were in first place in the National League East division, with a record of 50\u201331. However, they went 31-50 in the second half of the season, finishing at 81-81.\n\n====2006====\n{{main|2006 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n*On May 19, 2006, the Nationals opened their first-ever regular season interleague series against the [[2006 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]. Although the Orioles won the first game of what would become known as the [[Beltway Series]] (which consisted of three games in Washington and three in Baltimore), the two teams split the season series, with the home team winning twice and the visitors once. These games marked the Orioles' first matchup with a Washington-based team in 35 years, as they played against [[Minnesota Twins|the original Senators]] from 1954 to 1960, and against [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|a new Senators team]] from 1961 to 1971.<ref group=note>Prior to 2006, the Nationals' natural rival was the [[Toronto Blue Jays]], dating back to their time in Montreal, and because the 2005 schedule was set with the Expos in mind, the two teams had to play another series that year.</ref>\n*On Father's Day, June 18, 2006, against the [[2006 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]], the paid attendance was 45,157, the third-largest ever to see a single baseball game in the history of RFK Stadium. In that game, the Nationals beat the Yankees 3-2 on a two-run walk-off home run by rookie Ryan Zimmerman. (A [[1962 Major League Baseball season|1962]] doubleheader drew more spectators, as did the Nationals' first-ever home game with Arizona.)\n*On September 2, 2006, the Nationals rallied from three runs down in the first game and from five runs down in the second game to take a day\u2013night doubleheader sweep from the [[2006 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]], the first day-night doubleheader as part of the team's history in Washington.\n*On Labor Day, September 4, 2006, [[Ram\u00f3n Ortiz]] took a no-hitter into the ninth inning vs. the [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]], but gave up a single to Aaron Miles on his second pitch in the 9th to break up the bid. Then he gave up a home run to [[Albert Pujols]], ending his chance to get his second career shutout. Ortiz himself also hit a home run in the 8th inning. The Nationals won 5\u20132.\n*On September 16, 2006, [[Alfonso Soriano]] became the fourth player to [[40\u201340 club|hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a season]] when he stole his 40th base in the first inning of a game against the [[2006 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee Brewers]]. Soriano followed that feat on September 22 by hitting his 40th double, becoming the first member of the \"40\u201340 Club\" to also hit 40 doubles in the same season.\n\n====2007====\n{{Main|2007 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[File:IMG 9332 Ryan Zimmerman.jpg|thumb|[[Ryan Zimmerman]]]]\nAfter losing four starters (Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez, Tony Armas, Ram\u00f3n Ortiz and Pedro Astacio) from the prior year, the Nationals invited an extraordinary 36 pitchers to spring training.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nats' Starting Pitching Could Be a Real Problem | author=Thomas Boswell | date=March 7, 2007 | page=E03 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/06/AR2007030602143_pf.html | work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title=Nats' St. Claire Knows the Task at Hand | author=Barry Svrluga | work=Washington Post | date=February 26, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/25/AR2007022501373.html}}</ref>\n\nOn Opening Day, the Nationals lost their starting shortstop [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]] and center fielder [[Nook Logan]] for five weeks due to injuries. At the end of April, starting pitcher [[Jerome Williams (baseball)|Jerome Williams]] hurt his ankle while batting and was placed on the 15-day disabled list. Then, in the space of just 10 days in May, [[Shawn Hill]], [[John Patterson (pitcher)|John Patterson]], and [[Jason Bergmann]] went on the disabled list. Jerome Williams returned, pitched one game, and went back on the DL with a shoulder injury. The Washington Post's wrote: \"Almost everything that could sink a team's attitude has befallen the Nationals. They started the year 1\u20138, then they lost eight in a row to drop to 9\u201325.\"<ref>{{Cite news| title=Nationals Are Managing Just Fine With Acta | author=Thomas Boswell | date=June 4, 2007 | page=E01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060301428.html | work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nThey put journeymen [[Mike Bacsik (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Bacsik]], [[Micah Bowie]], [[Tim Redding]], and [[Jason Simontacchi]], along with rookie reliever [[Levale Speigner]] into the starting rotation, amidst predictions that the 2007 Nationals might equal the [[1962 New York Mets season|1962 Mets']] record of futility of 120 losses in one season.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Baseball Most Foul: The Nats Reinvent Bad | author=Linton Weeks | work=Washington Post | date=May 8, 2007 | page=C01 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/07/AR2007050701636.html}}</ref> But the Nationals bounced back, going 24\u201318 in their next 42 games through June 25. But on that day, a day in which Bergman made his first start off the DL, the Nationals received the news that shortstop [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]], their leadoff hitter (and second on the team with a .329 batting average) was lost for the rest of the season due to a thumb injury he had received the day before tagging out a runner.\n\nThe Nationals finished the [[2007 Major League Baseball season|2007 season]] 73\u201389, improving their record by two more wins than in 2006.\n\n*On April 17, 2007, one day after the shootings on the campus of [[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University|Virginia Tech]] where 33 faculty and students were murdered in the [[Virginia Tech massacre|largest mass shooting in US history]], the Nationals wore Virginia Tech baseball hats as they hosted the [[2007 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]].<ref name= post>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/04/17/AR2007041702068.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Nats Show Their Support | first=Marc | last=Carig | date=April 18, 2007 | accessdate=May 27, 2010}}</ref> The idea was e-mailed to team President Stan Kasten by Nationals fan Dave Lanham following the shootings. One of these hats was sent to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]] to be displayed.<ref name= sports>{{cite web| url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/sports/baseball/20070417-2028-bbn-nationals-virginiatech.html | work=SignOnSanDiego.com | title=Nationals don Virginia Tech baseball caps during game | date=April 17, 2007}}</ref>\n*On May 12, 2007, the Nationals hosted the [[2007 Florida Marlins season|Florida Marlins]]. Tied 3\u20133 in the bottom of the ninth, Marlins pitcher Jorge Julio faced Ryan Zimmerman with the bases loaded and two outs. Zimmerman hit the 2\u20132 pitch over the right-center field wall for a walk-off grand slam.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270512120 | work=ESPN.com | title=Zimmerman's walk-off grand slam ends rain-delayed game | date=May 12, 2007}}</ref> Also during this game, right fielder [[Austin Kearns]] hit the Nationals' first inside-the-park home run. The game ended at 1:42AM after two separate extended rain delays.\n*On August 7, 2007, while on the road against the [[2007 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]], Nationals pitcher [[Mike Bacsik (left-handed pitcher)|Mike Bacsik]] allowed [[Barry Bonds]]' 756th career home run, giving him first place on the career home run list. However, the Nationals won the game 8\u20136.\n*On September 23, 2007, the Nationals played their final game at RFK Stadium, a 5\u20133 victory over the [[2007 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\n====2008====\n{{Main|2008 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n[[Image:Washingtonnational2008steam.JPG|thumb|right|270px|Nationals 2008 team during warm up]]\n*On March 30, 2008, the Nationals held the grand opening of their new ballpark, [[Nationals Park]], with a rare one game series against the [[2008 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]]. Continuing the tradition, President [[George W. Bush]] threw out the ceremonial first pitch to Nationals manager [[Manny Acta]]. The Nationals beat the Braves in dramatic fashion when, with two out in the bottom of the 9th inning, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] hit a solo [[walk-off home run]] off of pitcher [[Peter Moylan]]. This gave the Nationals a 3\u20132 victory. The first hit was recorded by [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]], the first RBI was recorded by [[Nick Johnson (baseball)|Nick Johnson]], the first run scored was recorded by Cristian Guzm\u00e1n, the first home run was recorded by the Braves' [[Chipper Jones]], and the first starting pitchers were [[Odalis P\u00e9rez]] for the Nationals and [[Tim Hudson]] for the Braves. President Bush was in the [[ESPN]] [[Sunday Night Baseball|television booth]] at the time of Jones' homer and was the one who called it.\n\n====2009====\n{{Main|2009 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n*In April 2009, [[Ryan Zimmerman]] and [[Adam Dunn]] wore jerseys that improperly spelled the team's name as \"Natinals\". They later switched to properly spelled jerseys in the 3rd inning. [[Majestic Athletic]], the uniform supplier for MLB later apologized. This spawned a rash of jokes both on the internet and on television regarding Nationals and futility. The jersey worn by Dunn was later auctioned for $8000 to benefit the Washington Nationals Dream foundation.\n*On July 27, 2009, [[Josh Willingham]] hit two [[Grand Slam (baseball)|grand slams]] in a game against the [[2009 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee Brewers]]. The first grand slam was hit against [[Jeff Suppan]] and the second against [[Mark DiFelice]]. Willingham became the 13th player in MLB history to accomplish the feat.\n*On September 30, 2009, [[Justin Maxwell]] hit a two-out full count walk-off grand slam off of [[Francisco Rodr\u00edguez (Venezuelan pitcher)|Francisco Rodr\u00edguez]] of the [[2009 New York Mets]] on Fan Appreciation Day, the Nationals' last home game of the season.\n*On October 4, 2009, the Nationals' last game of the season, the Nationals won after 15 innings, the longest game for the team as part of its Washington history. The Nationals also became the first team in MLB history to start the season losing seven in a row and close the season winning seven in a row.\n\n====2010====\n{{Main|2010 Washington Nationals season}}\n\n* On April 5, 2010, President Barack Obama kept up a tradition of sitting U.S. Presidents by throwing out the ceremonial first pitch on opening day in Washington.\n[[File:Stephen Strasburg MLB debut.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Stephen Strasburg]] during his major league debut.]]\n*On June 7, 2010 the Nationals selected [[Bryce Harper]] of [[College of Southern Nevada|Southern Nevada]]. Harper was expected to break the contract record set by [[Stephen Strasburg]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-07/nationals-take-chosen-one-bryce-harper-with-top-pick-in-baseball-s-draft.html|work=Bloomberg|title=Nationals Draft `Chosen One' Bryce Harper as No. 1 a Year After Strasburg|date=June 7, 2010|first=Erik|last=Matuszewski}}</ref> Harper is also a client of Strasburg's agent [[Scott Boras]]. With 26 seconds left to sign, Harper and Boras agreed to a $9.9 million, five-year contract,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5468993 | work=ESPN.com | title=Nationals sign Bryce Harper for $9.9M | date=August 17, 2010}}</ref> falling short of Strasburg's 15.5 million over four years.\n*On June 8, 2010, the first overall pick, [[Stephen Strasburg]] had his major league debut, attracting a sellout crowd of 40,315. Strasburg struck out 14 batters in seven innings, giving up just 2 earned runs in a win over the [[2010 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]]. The 14 strikeouts were a record for the Nationals\u2014the most in a single game by a National since the franchise moved to D.C.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/08/AR2010060805223.html?sid=ST2010060900179 | work=Washington Post | date=June 9, 2010 | title=Pitcher Stephen Strasburg makes his major league debut for Washington Nationals | first=Dave | last=Sheinin}}</ref>\n*On July 29, 2010, the Nationals traded [[Matt Capps]] to the [[Minnesota Twins]] for [[Wilson Ramos]].  Ramos was considered to be the top catching prospect in the American League.\n*On July 30, 2010, the Nationals traded infielder [[Cristian Guzm\u00e1n]] to the Texas Rangers for two minor league pitchers. Guzm\u00e1n had to approve the deal because he has 10-and-5 rights (players with 10 years in the major league and five consecutive years with their current team cannot be traded without their consent).<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20100730/bbo-nationals-guzman/ | work=Huffington Post | title=Guzman OKs trade from Nationals to Rangers | date=July 30, 2010}}</ref>\n*On September 6, 2010, the Nationals won their 60th game of the season, eclipsing their win totals from the 2008 and 2009 season (finishing with 59 wins each time). September call-up Danny Espinosa hit two home runs including a grand slam in the Nationals' 13\u20133 win over the [[2010 New York Mets season|Mets]] at Nationals Park.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/06/AR2010090602312.html | work=Washington Post | title=Danny Espinosa hits 2 homers, drives in 6 in Nats' win over Mets | date=September 6, 2010 | first=Adam | last=Kilgore}}</ref>\n*On September 20, 2010, the Nationals recorded their lowest attendance ever since they came to Washington, with just 10,999 in attendance for a game against the [[2010 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/09/the_nationals_are_having_troub.html | title=The Nationals are having trouble drawing a crowd | work=Washington Post | date=September 21, 2010}}</ref> The poor attendance continued during the whole series, with fewer than 12,000 on September 21, fewer than 13,000 on September 22, and 14,633 on September 23.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer.com\">{{Cite news | url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/breaking/nationals-president-stan-kasten-leaving-club-103648344.html | title=Losses mounting, attendance low, Stan Kasten resigning as president of Washington Nationals | work=Washington Examiner | date=September 23, 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/sportsdata/baseball/mlb/game/Astros_Nationals/2010/09/23 | work=USA Today | title= MLB Box Score 9/23/2010 | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n*On September 23, 2010, team president [[Stan Kasten]] announced he would resign at the end of the season.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer.com\"/> Kasten did not explain in detail his reason for resigning and said, \"It's just time to be doing something else.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=5607926 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |title=Nats president Kasten to resign at season's end |date=September 24, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2019 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*On November 10, 2010, the Nationals unveiled a new logo and uniforms.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101110&content_id=16055222&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb | title=Nationals unveil new jerseys in fashion show | work=MLB.com | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dcsportsbog/2010/11/about_the_nats_new_uniforms_an.html | work=Washington Post DC Sports Blog | title=About the Nats new uniforms and the Curly W | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n*On December 5, 2010, the Nationals signed [[Jayson Werth]] to a seven-year deal worth $126 million.\n[[File:Jayson Werth (28).jpg|thumb|[[Jayson Werth]] playing for the Nationals against the Orioles in May 2011]]\n\n====2011====\n{{Main|2011 Washington Nationals season}}\n\nOn June 23, 2011, the Nationals won a 1-0 game to put them above .500 with a record of 38-37 (.507), the latest point in the season the team had been above .500 since 2005. Immediately after the game, manager [[Jim Riggleman]] resigned, citing the team's refusal to discuss extending his contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110623&content_id=20914078&vkey=news_was&c_id=mlb|title=Riggleman steps down as Nationals manager|work=Major League Baseball|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Bench coach [[John McLaren (baseball)|John McLaren]] was named the interim manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/john-mclaren-will-manage-nationals.html|title=Rizzo: John McLaren will manage Nationals in Chicago|publisher=|access-date=2014-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206203141/http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/john-mclaren-will-manage-nationals.html|archive-date=2013-02-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>  It was later reported that [[Davey Johnson]] was signed through the end of the 2011 season, with an option for 2012 (as a candidate in a search that would include minority candidates), and a contract as a front office consultant through 2013.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ben Goessling |url=http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/davey-johnsons-deal-with-the-nationals.html |title=The Goessling Game: Davey Johnson's deal with the Nationals |publisher=Masnsports.com |date=2011-06-26 |accessdate=2013-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206203132/http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/06/davey-johnsons-deal-with-the-nationals.html |archive-date=2013-02-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Nationals finished the [[2011 Major League Baseball season|2011 season]] in third place with a record of 80-81, their second-best record since they moved to Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://washington.nationals.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2011_09_28_wasmlb_flomlb_1&mode=box&c_id=was#gid=2011_09_28_wasmlb_flomlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=was|title=Strasburg fans 10, wins season finale|work=Washington Nationals|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> They only played 161 games because a home game against the [[2011 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]] was cancelled due to rain. The game was not made up because it was inconsequential to the playoffs with no room on the schedule to play it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/how-the-nationals-final-two-games-will-affect-their-draft-status-and-offseason/2011/09/27/gIQAJy7O2K_blog.html|title=How the Nationals\u2019 final two games will affect their draft status and offseason|work=Washington Post|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, Washington traded prospects [[A.J. Cole]], [[Derek Norris]], [[Tom Milone]] and [[Brad Peacock]] for All-Star Pitcher [[Gio Gonz\u00e1lez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/7385033/oakland-trade-gio-gonzalez-washington-nationals |title=Oakland A's trade Gio Gonz\u00e1lez to Washington Nationals \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=2011-12-23 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2011 season, the last remaining member of the Expos \u2013 [[Liv\u00e1n Hern\u00e1ndez]] \u2013 departed the Nationals, although his association with the team was non-continuous.\n\n====2012====\n{{Main|2012 Washington Nationals season}}\nOn September 20, the Nationals beat the [[2012 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] to clinch a spot in the playoffs and became the first Washington-based baseball team to advance to the postseason in 79 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Kilgore |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/washington-nationals-clinch-mlb-playoff-spot-with-4-1-win-over-los-angeles-dodgers/2012/09/20/847bf182-038b-11e2-91e7-2962c74e7738_story.html?hpid=z2 |title=Washington Nationals clinch MLB playoff spot with 4-1 win over Los Angeles Dodgers |work=The Washington Post |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> On October 1, the Nationals clinched the National League East division<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=321001120 |title=Philadelphia Phillies vs. Washington Nationals \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 01, 2012 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=2012-10-01 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> and later clinched the best record in Major League Baseball at 98-64.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=321003120 |title=Philadelphia Phillies vs. Washington Nationals \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 03, 2012 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=2012-10-03 |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> However, the team lost to the [[2012 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] in the [[2012 National League Division Series|NLDS]] 3 games to 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=CARDS SCORE 4 IN 9TH, BEAT NATS 9-7, REACH NLCS|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/harper-nationals-lead-cards-6-0-after-3-game-5|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\n{{Main|2013 Washington Nationals season}}\nIn November 2012, manager Davey Johnson signed a contract to return for the [[2013 Major League Baseball season|2013 season]], and announced that he would retire from managing at the end of that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2012/11/10/davey-johnson-nationals-officially-agree-to-deal-for-return-in-2013-season/ |title=Davey Johnson, Nationals officially agree to deal for return in 2013 season |work=The Washington Post |first=James |last=Wagner |date=November 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed that the Nationals will likely leave the team's current spring training home at [[Space Coast Stadium]] in [[Viera, Florida]] once the lease expires in 2017 (although an early exit is possible in 2015).<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Nationals moving out of Brevard County|url=http://www.cfnews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/sports/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2013/5/14/washington_nationals.html|publisher=CFN13|accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Main|2014 Washington Nationals season}}\nOn October 31, 2013, the Nationals announced the hiring of [[Matt Williams (third baseman)|Matt Williams]] to replace Davey Johnson as the team's manager for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://curlyw.mlblogs.com/2013/10/31/nationals-name-matt-williams-manager/ |title=Nationals Name Matt Williams Manager |last=Comak |first=Amanda |work=Curly W Live |publisher=MLBlogs Network |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2013/11/01/matt-williams-introduced-as-nationals-manager-live-updates/ |title=Matt Williams introduced as Nationals manager |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Wagner |first=James |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> The Nationals clinched the NL East on September 16, 2014, after beating the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>White, Paul (September 17, 2014) [https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/09/16/washington-nationals-clinch-nl-east/15750151/ \"Nationals clinch NL East with win in Atlanta\"], ''[[USA Today]]''. Retrieved September 24, 2014.</ref>  Jordan Zimmermann pitched the Nationals' first no-hitter (since moving from Montreal in 2005) on the last day of the 2014 regular season, September 28, 2014, against the Miami Marlins.\n\n====2015====\n{{Main|2015 Washington Nationals season}}\nThe Nationals started their season in a skid, falling to the bottom of their division. On April 28, 2015, after a seven-game losing streak, with rookie starting pitcher [[A. J. Cole]] on the mound, the Nationals found themselves in at a nine-run deficit against their archrival, the [[Atlanta Braves]]. But the team clawed back to win the game 13-12, overcoming their largest run deficit ever.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baynews9.com/content/news/baynews9/sports/article.html/content/news/articles/bhsn/2015/4/28/oviedo_s_a_j_cole_ge.html|title=Oviedo's A.J. Cole gets no-decision in wild 13-12 Nationals win|date=April 28, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> Over the coming weeks, the Nationals rebounded from their poor start to the season, rising to the top of the division behind a career-best season for outfielder [[Bryce Harper]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.h4-entertainment.com/2015/05/bryce-harper-continues-to-lead-the-surging-nationals/|title=Bryce Harper Continues to Lead the Surging Nationals|date=May 29, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|work=Sports Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/20/bryce-harper-sets-new-career-high-with-his-23rd-home-run/|title=Bryce Harper sets new career-high with his 23rd home run|first=D.J.|last=Short|agency=NBC Sports|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> On June 20, 2015, the Nationals shut out the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], with [[Max Scherzer]] throwing a [[no-hitter]] that was [[List of Major League Baseball perfect games#Perfect games spoiled by the 27th batter|nearly perfect]]. The game was the second no-hitter in Nationals history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/nationals/2015/06/20/a83b59fe-1761-11e5-9ddc-e3353542100c_story.html|title=Nationals Max Scherzer throws no-hitter after hit-by-pitch spoils perfect game|date=June 20, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2015|work=The Washington Post|first=James|last=Wagner}}</ref> Scherzer became the first pitcher since [[Nolan Ryan]] in 1973 to throw two no-hitters in the regular season, shutting down the [[New York Mets]] on October 3, 2015, in a performance that also equaled Ryan's historic mark of 17 strikeouts in a no-hitter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://screengrabber.deadspin.com/max-scherzer-becomes-first-pitcher-since-nolan-ryan-in-1734520688|agency=Deadspin|title=Max Scherzer Becomes First Pitcher Since Nolan Ryan In 1973 To Throw Two No-Hitters In Same Regular Season|first=Timothy|last=Burke|date=October 3, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/10/max-scherzer-no-hitter-washington-nationals-new-york-mets|title=Max Scherzer hurls second no-hitter of season with dominating 17-strikeout performance|work=USA Today|date=October 3, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> However, the Mets won the division, clinching it in late September.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2015/09/26/mets-clinch-1st-playoff-spot-since-06-by-beating-reds-10-2/72900938/|title=Amazin' Mets clinch 1st playoff spot since 2006|date=September 26, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015|work=USA Today}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u20132017====\n{{Main|2016 Washington Nationals season|2017 Washington Nationals season}}\nIn 2016, the Nationals won the East division but lost in the NLDS to the Dodgers. In 2017, the Nationals again won the East division but lost in the NLDS to the Cubs, marking the fourth time out of four playoff appearances since 2012 in which the team has been eliminated in the NLDS.\n\n====2017\u20132018====\n{{Main|2017 Washington Nationals season|2018 Washington Nationals season}}\nThe 2017 season saw the Nationals earn another NL East title with a 97-65, but lost to the Cubs in five games. 2018 saw the Nationals host the MLB All-Star Game, but the team would regress and miss out on the playoffs, barely cracking .500 with an 82-80 record. Bryce Harper left the team after the season, signing with the Philadelphia Phillies as a free agent.\n\n====2019====\n{{Main|2019 Washington Nationals season}}\nEven without Harper, the Nationals would excel in 2019, earning a Wild Card berth with a 93-69 record, defeating the Milwaukee Brewers in the Wild Card play-in game, and winning their first playoff series since their arrival in Washington, D.C., upsetting the Los Angeles Dodgers in 5 games in their NLDS. They went on to sweep the St. Louis Cardinals in the NLCS to win the National League pennant, their first in team history dating back to their days in Montreal. When they faced the Houston Astros in the World Series, it was also the first appearance for a Washington-based team since [[History of the Washington Senators (1901-1960)|the first AL Senators]] lost to the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] in {{wsy|1933}}.  The Nationals went on to win their first World Series title 4 games to 3, becoming the second Washington D.C.-based professional sports team to win their first championship in the same year, following the [[WNBA]]'s [[Washington Mystics]] a few weeks earlier, and also became the third men's professional sports team to win their first title, following the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[St. Louis Blues]] and the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Toronto Raptors]]. Following the season, [[Anthony Rendon]] departed to the [[Los Angeles Angels]] in free agency.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of baseball team nicknames#Washington Nationals|Washington Nationals nicknames]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{ref list|group=note}}\n\n\n{{MLBHistory}}\n{{Washington Nationals}}\n\n[[Category:History of Major League Baseball by team|Washington Nationals]]\n[[Category:Washington Nationals]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 15-2 \u2192 15\u20132 (6), 80-81 \u2192 80\u201381 (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Washington_Nationals"}
